<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8242 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-RUNAWAY-AZR &LR;      09-11 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNAWAY-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right now, 134 kids _ including a 10-year-old _ are missing from
state foster homes, all runaways. But little is being done to find
them.
</P>
<P>
   Child welfare officials and police say scouring the streets for
these children _ who don't want to be found anyway _ is mostly
futile. They either turn up or get picked up for other reasons _
curfew, trespassing, stealing, drinking or drugs, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Others say more should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our kids. They belong to the state of Arizona,''
says Carol Kamin, director of the Children's Action Alliance, a
non-profit advocacy group. ``If one of your children was missing,
you would be out looking for them _ driving around, calling their
friends, doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old Glendale girl in foster care who recently made
headlines for having a late-term abortion in Kansas was a chronic
runaway. But no one ever chased her down, either, family members
say.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials think the girl became pregnant while she was on
the run. She told the court that she also used alcohol and illegal
drugs while on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep an eye on her 24 hours a day, seven days a
week,'' says Bob Harkins, the girl's maternal uncle. ``And the
state didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   When a kid runs from foster care, child welfare officials file a
report with police and contact parents and school authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go looking for the child because we know that that
can be like looking for a needle in a haystack,'' especially in
urban areas, says Mary Ault, a Child Protective Services
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   If they get word about where a runaway might be _ at the home of
a friend or relative _ they will go look for the kid. But Ault says
the agency simply doesn't have enough staff to spend hours looking
for these kids. There are almost 7,000 kids in state foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Even the police don't search for known runaways, particularly
teenagers, Mesa Police Det. Jose Martinez says. Officers will
follow up on any initial leads and then put information on a
national computerized list of missing juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they run across these kids while on patrol, but they
don't hunt them down or go door-to-door as they would for a missing
child.
</P>
<P>
   Police do look for runaways if they suspect they could be in
danger or are suicidal, Martinez says. The younger the kid, the
more likely they are to look.
</P>
<P>
   Of the kids currently on ``runaway status,'' the youngest is 10,
the oldest is 18. The state may continue to supervise 18-year-olds
for many reasons, including if the teens are disabled or pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority of runaways are 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can become victims for all kinds of predatory types of
people,'' says Rick Lenz, director of therapeutic group home
services for Arizona Baptist Children's Services.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit agency runs two Phoenix group homes.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, a 12-year-old boy ran away from one of the
agency's homes just before bedtime wearing only boxer shorts and a
T-shirt. He was barefoot and spent the night huddled in an alley,
hiding himself with debris.
</P>
<P>
   The boy came back the next morning, much like he had the dozen
or so other times he ran away during his 18 months in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   For this boy, it is his way of coping with anger, stress or
sadness, Lenz says. He simply runs from it.
</P>
<P>
   Some foster kids run without much thought, walking out the door
with only the clothes on their backs. Others plan it, storing food
and other supplies before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Some run because they don't like where they live or the people
they live with, officials say. Some run because they miss their
families and think things will be better if they can just get home
again.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, they run because they were told they
couldn't attend some great party in the desert on Saturday night,
say those who work with the kids. Or, they sneak out to see a
forbidden friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that kids don't just run away from foster care,'' Ault
says. ``They run away from their own parents, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of them don't know why they are running.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Kroll, who has worked for CPS since 1990, has seen
plenty of foster kids run. She is an independent living specialist,
working with teenage foster children.
</P>
<P>
   One 16-year-old girl she knew ran away 68 times in two and a
half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so frustrated,'' Kroll said. ``I felt like all I did was
chase her from place to place.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl turned 18 while on the run and never came back. Kroll
often wonders what happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   Foster homes and group homes cannot be locked, according to
federal law. These children are in the state's care because of
something their parents did, not because they did anything wrong.
So, it is up to staff to make sure no kid leaves when they are not
supposed to, though state law prohibits them from physically
restraining children.
</P>
<P>
   And, like other children, these kids often go to public schools
and can take off easily from there, simply never showing up back at
the group home in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't have the manpower to send staff out looking for
them,'' Lenz says.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer kids run from foster homes where they get the full
attention of foster parents instead of a rotating staff and where
there are not as many children, Lenz says.
</P>
<P>
   It is easiest to find kids who are habitual runners, Kroll says.
They usually turn up at the same places and with the same people.
It's the kids who run less frequently or for the first time that
are the hardest to track.
</P>
<P>
   These are children who typically are self sufficient, having
been part of families who gave them lots of responsibility _
running a household, getting themselves off to school or caring for
younger siblings. But Kroll still worries about the condition they
are in when they come back, particularly the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for someone to love them, so people take
advantage of them in that way,'' she says. ``I talk about that with
my girls a lot. I tell them that sex is not love.''
</P>
<P>
   What irks Ault is that these kids can't get far alone.
Unfailingly, someone gives them a ride _ sometimes out of state _
food and a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez says anyone who knowingly helps runaways could be
charged criminally, either with hindering prosecution or harboring
a fugitive. Both are Class 1 misdemeanors, punishable by up to six
months in jail or fines up to $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old who took off a few days ago from Lenz's group
home now is in juvenile detention, waiting to be transferred to a
more secure residential center where doors can be locked.
</P>
<P>
   It will be harder for him to run from there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
