To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RELIGION (Jerusalem) _ Reform and Conservative Jews are
mounting a huge campaign, tied to the holidays, to attract
Israelis. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WIS-FATHERS (Milwaukee) _ Across the country, policymakers are
pondering ways to make better fathers of down-on-their-luck men.
There are tougher new laws to make them pay child support. There
are new job-training programs to help them get skills. Now once a
week, in a strip mall on the outskirts of town, a Milwaukee program
adds an unusual twist: an obituary-writing session to force the
absent fathers to see themselves through their children's eyes. By
Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 24, 26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-GORE (Washington) _ The nation's labor movement is sharply
divided over how to handle its endorsement in next year's
presidential race and election, with a bloc of powerful unions _
the auto workers, steel workers and teamsters _ expressing deep
dissatisfaction over the labor positions of Vice President Al Gore.
The divide pits service-sector and government-employee unions,
which want to issue an endorsement of Gore as soon as possible,
against industrial unions, which complain that the Clinton
administration has done too little to prevent expanded trade from
wiping out thousands of jobs. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ Rep. Baron Hill, a moderate Democrat
from Indiana, spent a good part of August walking across his
district and talking with constituents about what to do with the
federal budget surplus. Perhaps not surprisingly for a Democrat, he
says he heard little enthusiasm for the $792 billion Republican tax
cutting plan, which President Clinton has pledged to veto. But he
heard a remarkably consistent call for Congress and the
administration to use the surplus for a purpose long supported by
economists but seen as a political yawner by both parties: reducing
the $3.6 trillion national debt, the financial hangover from
decades of deficit spending. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   PBS-DONOR-LISTS (Washington) _ More public television stations
than previously thought swapped donor and member lists with
political organizations, the inspector general for public
broadcasting finds. By Katharine Q. Seeley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
