<P>
   BRAIN-SIDES (Undated) _ Twenty years ago, psychologists had a
field day ascribing various functions to either the left or right
side of the human brain. Language was on the left. Drawing skills
stemmed from the right. The left was a whiz at logic but not at
intuition. The right could conjure up poetry but not arithmetic.
Eventually things got so silly and inconsistent that the whole
endeavor was dismissed as ``dichotomania.'' Careful researchers
abandoned the enterprise. Today many of those same researchers say
that hemispheric lateralization is undergoing a renaissance. By
Sandra Blakeslee. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSTON-BOOK (New York) _ The Canadian novelist Wayne Johnston
talks about ``The Colony of Unrequited Dreams,'' his Newfoundland
saga. By Mel Gussow.
