<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANAPOLIS KNOWS HOW TO PRIVATIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ City officials debating whether Kansas City
needs a year or more to forge a privatization plan should read
``The Seven Habits of Effective Mayors,'' in the Sept. 13 Weekly
Standard. They should then go to Indianapolis for an expert
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The article, by Eric S. Cohen, assistant editor of Public
Interest, chronicles how Indianapolis Mayor Stephen Goldsmith has
made privatization a critical component of one of the country's
most successful city administrations during the '90s. Since
Goldsmith's election in 1992, Cohen says, ``(he) has cut the budget
every year, cut taxes four times, opened nearly 80 city services to
competitive bidding, and reduced the city work force by 40
percent.'' Meanwhile, crime is down and homebuilding is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith's record, in other words, offers a model that those
searching for similar solutions would do well to study. Its
components, however, go far beyond mere privatization:
</P>
<P>
   - Encourage competition: Although contracting out some of the
city's services to private firms has saved the city $400 million,
management reforms also have enabled the city's union workers to
win ``a fair number'' of city contracts. The competitive way,
Goldsmith says, is both cheaper and better.
</P>
<P>
   - Eliminate cronyism: Goldsmith fired enough of the political
hacks larding the management bureaucracy to make city departments
competitive with private sector companies. Many of those axed were
the mayor's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   - Cut taxes: Both Goldsmith and other big-city mayors are
finding that tax relief is a key to reversing the outflow of
residents and businesses to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   - Emphasize fundamentals: Goldsmith believes cities should stick
to their knitting. Focus on roads, sewers, water systems and other
such infrastructure needs. More than $1 billion has been spent on a
Building Better Neighborhoods initiative, and law enforcement
outlays have been increased by $160 million even while taxes were
being reduced.
</P>
<P>
   - Support ``little platoons'': City hall nurtures neighborhood
leaders who undertake projects to improve their areas. An example
is the creation of a community center that has helped neutralize a
tough neighborhood's gang and drug influence.
</P>
<P>
   - Enlist institutions: Goldsmith's ``Front Porch Alliance''
encourages faith-based and community-based efforts ``to rebuild the
city's social capital.'' Examples include churches getting city
assistance to help transform abandoned parking lots into parks and
playgrounds, and community groups being supplied with city trucks
and trash collection bins for neighborhood cleanup projects.
</P>
<P>
   - Acknowledge government's limits: City government concentrates
on providing public services, while leaving job creation to
business and encouraging churches and families to maintain the
social fabric and instill civic virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here, it seems, is twofold. Privatization's process
is well understood, but success depends on decisive political
leadership that understands it's only one building block in the
quest to improve city government. The overall plan must include the
grass-roots involvement of citizens, churches, charities, civic
groups and businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
