<HEADER>
A8260 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SUPERVOTER-AZR &LR;      09-11 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERVOTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORE GROUP DECIDES ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call them Phoenix's supervoters, the priority voters.
</P>
<P>
   They're mostly older, educated Anglos, half of whom live in
north-central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   And they are the ones, political professionals say, on whom
campaigning politicians lavish the most attention.
</P>
<P>
   Despite campaign rhetoric to the contrary, most citywide
elections _ including Tuesday's _ are decided by pretty much the
same 96,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The professionals know this exclusive clique well and have even
given it a name: &UR; supervoters, priority voters, even high-efficacy
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Win their hearts, and you win the election.
</P>
<P>
   The other 400,000 registered Phoenix voters are largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Even the political parties' get-out-the vote drives are aimed
mainly at the regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice thought, that it would be on an even keel,'' said
Cortland Coleman, political director of the Arizona Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not the case. Resources and energy are focused on
priority voters.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervoters club isn't difficult to join. Just vote in city
elections year after year and you're in.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pollock is a member. So are many of her neighbors who live
in City Council District 4, a central Phoenix community rich in
supervoters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When elections roll around, we are blitzkrieged with
candidates and fliers and tons of phone calls,'' said Pollock, a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians woo supervoters with mailers and phone calls, leave
fliers at their houses, even make personal visits _ or at least
send a volunteer. In his first mayoral race, for example, Skip
Rimsza left potted plants at the homes of 50,000 to 60,000
supervoters.
</P>
<P>
   And they are more likely to pick up the phone when you call.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock is convinced that being a supervoter means getting more
attention once politicians are in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a doubt in my mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Political researchers agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians will skew values, beliefs and programs to people
who vote all the time,'' said Arizona State University Professor
David Berman, author of ``Arizona Government and Politics''.``''
</P>
<P>
   ``So it becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who make their living in the political trenches say
targeting supervoters is a purely practical decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best world, I'd advocate communicating to every
registered household,'' said political strategist Michael Crusa.
Communicating with a household can cost a candidate $1 to $2, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do the math,'' Crusa said. ``Candidates can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Crusa advocates seven contacts _ phone, mailer, visit,
flier _ with supervoters and, if a candidate can afford it, at
least two contacts with those voters who make it to half the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthier candidates, especially non-incumbents, may reach out
to semidependable voters _ those who vote in special elections,
Crusa said. He calls them ``the-two-out-of-fours.''
</P>
<P>
   Although supervoters live throughout Phoenix, more than half of
the members of the club live in three of eight council districts _
Districts 3, 4 and 6.
</P>
<P>
   In all three of these central Phoenix districts, 20 percent of
registered voters cast a ballot Tuesday, compared with 17 percent
citywide.
</P>
<P>
   Even more noteworthy was that only one of these three districts
had a race for a council seat _ and that was a race in name only.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with southeast Phoenix's District 7, where a tight
three-way race for a council seat drew only 14 percent of
registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Central Phoenix's District 4 had Tuesday's highest rate of of
voter turnout, 20.92 percent. In 1997, when District 4 voters chose
a new council member, nearly 27 percent of registered voters cast
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Within District 4 are a handful of precincts that can turn out a
voting rate as high as 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   District 4 resident Posey Moore Nash is appalled by the city's
low voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``People died for the right to vote,'' Nash said. Yet when Nash
ran for the council seat in 1997, she couldn't afford to reach out
to new and unreliable voters, but concentrated her efforts in
supervoter precincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pepper those areas with literature and you walk them,''
Nash said. ``You want to get those people. The other ones are
hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   District 4 resident G.G. George ran for mayor in 1994 and said
she should have spent more time and energy capturing the attention
of the city's known voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I concentrated on everyone; that was my downfall,'' George
said. ``I spoke to everybody I could. The political strategists are
absolutely correct. That's not the right way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Democratic and Republican parties admit that what they
called their get-out-the-vote efforts are most often confined to
people who already vote regularly.
</P>
<P>
   They will, on occasion, reach out to new residents or make a
foray into a new neighborhood; but those are not efficient uses of
scarce resources.
</P>
<P>
   But that must be done carefully, Crusa said. In Scottsdale on
Tuesday, he said, the Canals Project went down to defeat because
the controversy ``encouraged too high a turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists took their message to the most logical place _ the
people who always vote, Crusa said. What they failed to do was get
their message to the rare voter motivated by this particular issue.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for catering exclusively to a small group of
known voters is that it's often to an incumbent's or
well-established candidate's benefit to keep turnout low, Berman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get supporters out to vote,'' he said, ``and hope others
don't know it's an election.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the American system was designed from the beginning to
prevent mass voting, keep turnout low and establish a small,
controllable group of like-minded voters, political researcher and
ASU Professor Bruce Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed, Merrill said, to maintain power in the hands of
``the White, male, Christian elite.'' It's done through
registration rules, one-day voting, and minimal attempts at voter
outreach, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill and others are expecting significant changes in
traditional American voting patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Women, minorities, and younger people have the potential to
carry sway at the ballot box; and the growing vote-by-mail movement
could begin developing a new set of supervoters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These great pressures will eventually lead to mass voting,''
Merrill said. For example, he said, with more education and more
money, more of Phoenix's Hispanics will move into the supervoter
profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll begin to understand they can not only join the game,
they can write the rules of the game,'' Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the power continues in the hands of those who have
always understood the game, get involved and vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the voters in Tuesday's race voted early and by mail.
Mail-in ballots aren't counted by precinct, making it difficult to
track precinct-by-precinct voter counts.
</P>
<P>
   But the city's ``permanent list of early voters'' contains the
names of residents who vote and request early ballots, and usually
return them.
</P>
<P>
   That list _ now a favorite with candidates seeking supervoters _
shows that in 13 of 41 District 4 precincts, more than 25 percent
of voters requested early ballots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
