<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHT-RAIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY TO STUDY LIGHT RAIL ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Seventeen months after light-rail planning
stalled, the city has launched a new study to answer _ possibly
once and for all _ the question of light rail's future in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Perry, an architect and planner hired by the city, will
oversee a team of experts charged with reaching consensus on a
practical public transit system in the city's central business
corridor.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which is expected to take 12 to 18 months, could cost
between $600,000 and $700,000 and will be paid for by the Federal
Transit Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said the business community, neighborhoods and others
would be included as the city tried to develop the consensus that
eluded area transportation officials and froze the planning process
in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure we not only speak to the public but have
a conversation with the public about this issue,'' Perry said. ``It
won't be us deciding something and then going out to test the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for the latest study, coming from both the city and
business leaders, began almost a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The intent is to complete work halted by the Kansas City Area
Transportation Authority, focusing on the central business
corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Several key questions the city must answer are whether light
rail is the right technology, what the starter route should be, and
how to coordinate with the commuter rail system _ passenger trains
on existing heavy rail tracks from Johnson County, Kan. _ that has
received funding authorization from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   When the ATA started drafting driveway and intersection changes
in early 1997, high-profile business leaders and politicians
protested that they had not been consulted.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce then tried to find a
route that business interests could support, but gave up in April
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber officials worked with U.S. Sen. Kit Bond to free up
about $1.5 million remaining from the ATA's preliminary engineering
grant.
</P>
<P>
   The city will direct the study, with the ATA providing technical
support. If the city arrives at an agreed-upon strategy, the rest
of the $1.5 million grant can be used to complete preliminary
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Mann, chairman of the chamber's Metropolitan Initiative
Committee, urged that the consulting team make a point of working
with the newly formed Regional Transit Alliance, a group of
residents supporting quality metropolitan area transit.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will be asked on Nov. 2 to consider a light-rail proposal
developed by transportation activist Clay Chastain and his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain's initiative asks voters to extend two half-cent sales
taxes _ due to expire in December 2000 _ for 15 years. One
half-cent tax would pay for improvements to roads, sewers, bridges
and sidewalks. The other would pay the city's share of a $1.5
billion light-rail line from Kansas City International Airport to
south Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said that the competition among cities for federal
transit dollars was fierce and that time was running out for Kansas
City to identify its local match and get in line for those
dwindling federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's imperative that we get this thing approved now,''
Chastain said, ``and let the city deal with the details after it's
approved.''
</P>
<P>
   But city, chamber and transportation officials say that is the
wrong approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Transit Administration, they argued, has strict
guidelines and wants detailed plans and ridership and cost
estimates before it will consider funding. Those are questions the
city's study will explore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
