r a BC-ARTIST'S-SECLUSION-2N     09-11 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIST'S-SECLUSION-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ flowing, dancing notes.
</P>
<P>
   Each new painting created a distinctive melody in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He reduced his color range to a muted bronzish-olive tone. He
cut out all backgrounds so that his sculptural ``objects'' would
appear to float in space.
</P>
<P>
   His work became larger and larger. He dreamed of a triumphant
one-man exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``...but several times readying myself for a show, seemingly
only a few months away, I stopped, discarded everything and began
again, knowing I had just given myself a year or two more of solid
painting.''
</P>
<P>
   In June of this year, exhausted and nearly overwhelmed by an
internal exploration that had, he said, ``lasted a bit too long,''
he found a space downtown, framed and hung 15 huge paintings, and
sent out invitations for a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I was thinking of such great crowds,'' he said. ``I had
such expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   But hardly anyone came, hardly anyone at all. He received no
critical attention. He sold nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet for me,'' he said, ``it was the most glorious of defeats,
finally seeing it all hung, all framed, my task complete.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien came to the show and thought the paintings ``very
interesting'' but problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding a market will be difficult,'' he said. ``But selling
is not the true end result for an artist. Physically making art is
the true end result. Sean is a born maker of art. He has to create.
What he does now will tell us what he got from those seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bovinett said recently that he is undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay with it,'' he said, ``simplify the work,
return to a normal life, and see where it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my grandfather would smile at that. He would
appreciate the cheekiness of going on with this adventure no matter
what the consequences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
