<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ARTIST'S-SECLUSION-KA     09-11 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIST'S-SECLUSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECLUSION AIDS ARTIST'S CREATIVE DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Seven years ago a local painter named Sean
Bovinett, well known in Kansas City's small arts community,
closeted himself in his Valentine neighborhood apartment and
essentially disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shut out the world so I could devote myself to a monumental
task,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his self-imposed exile he remained secretive, sharing
his thoughts with almost no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if he'd vanished,'' said John O'Brien, owner of the
Dolphin Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean became an enigma,'' said Tom Gomersall, a former
instructor at the Kansas City Art Institute who taught Bovinett 26
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him then as a tough, outgoing ex-Marine _
disciplined, aggressive, full of life and creativity. He embraced
the world,'' Gomersall said. ``I don't think I ever understood his
decision to isolate himself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bovinett, now 48, saw his choice as a necessary step on a
``long journey'' that had begun in the tiny English village of
Marlow Bottom, 30 miles southwest of London.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that he and his twin brother were raised by their
maternal grandparents. His divorced mother had married a U.S. Air
Force officer and moved to America.
</P>
<P>
   Bovinett's grandparents, Ivy and Douglas Gregory, were lay
ministers in the Methodist Church and staunch, radical supporters
of the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were artistic as well,'' Bovinett said. ``We were the odd
folks on the street, so to speak. It was a delightful way to grow
up.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 13, his mother returned. Her second husband adopted
the boys, gave them his name, and several years later they all
moved to America _ to Montgomery, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from culture shock, eager to escape Montgomery, Bovinett
joined the Marines shortly after graduating high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Marines,'' he said, ``I developed a strong feeling
about doing things right, no matter what the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   He also discovered that his drawing, begun when he was 3 years
old, was considered unusually good by his colleagues. Encouraged,
he decided to try a career in art.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the Art Institute, Bovinett worked for
seven years as a process artist at Hallmark Cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent every day hunched over a light table, duplicating and
enhancing other artists' original work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while I felt as though I were locked in an arts
factory, a velvet prison. It's a horrible place to be when you feel
you have something original to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to England he found a small watercolor painting
his grandfather had made in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``He painted it in my grandmother's autograph book,'' Bovinett
said. ``It was a simple landscape, but a truly lovely thing. My
grandfather could have been a great painter if he hadn't had to
work in a factory. That painting nudged me toward quitting Hallmark
and trying to make it on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   When the owners of a New England-based printing company
expressed interest in using Bovinett's work for limited-edition
posters, he was ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I packed everything in my '74 Land Rover, including my dog,
and moved to Boston,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The move was a disaster. The poster contract fell through. The
Land Rover threw a rod. And Bovinett, nearly broke, had to give
away his golden retriever.
</P>
<P>
   He flew back to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to feel that I didn't fit in anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 he had his own show at the old Athena Restaurant on
Broadway. He sold three paintings.
</P>
<P>
   But he was feeling lost, empty, without purpose.
</P>
<P>
   To reinvigorate himself he began to work on still-life
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to create my own simple still life, a traditional
vase of five tulips,'' he wrote in his journal. ``But after several
weeks I found myself working on over 30 still lifes at the same
time...there seemed to be no end in sight....''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing he had become obsessed with the work, he destroyed all
but seven of the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean was clearly placing a terrible burden on himself,'' said
O'Brien of the Dolphin Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, to pay his rent, Bovinett took a job at the Boulevard
Brewery, cleaning vats. He could no longer afford flowers to paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forced to consider using my imagination to begin
creating my own vases...I felt I needed serious hours to pursue
this lead. Began going to bed at 7:30 in the evening and waking
around 2:30 in the morning to work (before going to brewery).''
</P>
<P>
   He painted with new fervor, sensing that his ``lead,'' a journey
deep into his imagination, would result in something important.
</P>
<P>
   He quit his brewery job. He cut off his relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put my social life on hold for the indefinite future. I
suppose it can be described as an obsession, but I prefer `complete
immersion.' The very withering away from the world is that which is
sustaining...Socializing is just letting the pressure out of the
cooker. I needed to keep the fire stoked.'
</P>
<P>
   He left his apartment only to shop. Living off a profit-sharing
plan from a previous job, he bought nothing but groceries, art
supplies, and an occasional shirt from a thrift shop.
</P>
<P>
   He painted seven days a week, 12 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time doesn't matter. I had come a long way and had found
myself inside a kind of cathedral of the imagination...anything was
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Influenced by the work of Belgian surrealist Rene Magritte, he
painted imaginary vases with billowing opera curtains extending
magically from their sides. He struggled to create sculptures on
canvas. He painted undulating musical instruments extending skyward
with flowing, dancing notes. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
