<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONE NIGHT, DODGERS DELIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the spring-training war room, as clear as if it
were yesterday, it's easy to remember the Dodgers brass talking
about these types of games. The Dodgers wouldn't need to score
much, which wasn't expected anyway, because the pitching would do
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The runs, or even run, would come either from the long ball or,
unlike past teams, the manufactured route.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days, when dreaming of such wins seemed like so
much more than a dream. They were supposed to come more than once
every 100 or so games.
</P>
<P>
   But there it was, in all its splendor, Friday against the Mets.
The Dodgers won 3-1 behind a strong start from surging right-hander
Darren Dreifort and a pair of manufactured runs.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi hit his 29th homer and the Dodgers ended a
four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   For a night, you started to get the idea this group knows how to
play the game together instead of as individuals. The Dodgers
actually scored a run without a hit. They did what winning teams
did, only winning teams do this more than once every few months.
</P>
<P>
   It began with Eric Young leading off with a walk against Al
Leiter. Mark Grudzielanek's grounder with Young trying to steal got
the Dodgers a man on second with one out. Young, who used his legs
to create mayhem during the first month of the season, stole third
and scored on Gary Sheffield's fly ball to the track. One run, no
hits.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, it was more of the same. Devon White led off with
a double and was sacrificed to third on Adrian Beltre's bunt to the
right side. White scored on Paul LoDuca's flyout between center and
right field to give the Dodgers a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dreifort continued the most impressive stretch of his
career by pitching at least seven innings in his fifth consecutive
start. Dreifort allowed four hits, struck out six and walked two.
He's 4-1 with a 2.06 ERA in his last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he struck out four straight Mets. He finally bent
in the sixth inning when ex-teammate Roger Cedeno doubled to right
with one out and scored on pinch-hitter Matt Franco's two-out
double to right center as the Mets pulled within 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Dreifort got Ricky Henderson to line to shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek to end the inning before Mondesi gave Dreifort his
two-run cushion back.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who's still hearing boos every time he comes to the
plate, fouled a ball off his foot that sent him spilling onto the
batter's box dirt. A few gingerly taken steps, a little wincing and
Mondesi was back in the box against reliever Bobby Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi then pulled himself within three stolen bases and a home
run of the second 30-30 season of his career when he drove Taylor's
2-2 pitch down the left-field line for a homer and a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, who was shaky in the seventh, then saw the new tactic
of manager Davey Johnson, which is to push pitchers more than
they've been pushed all season. Instead of shaking hands after
seven innings, Dreifort pitched a perfect eighth before turning it
over to Jeff Shaw in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw recorded his 32nd save. Dreifort, who six weeks ago had a
hot ticket to the bullpen, has evened his record at 13-13 and
trails only Kevin Brown for the staff lead in wins (16).
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers, for one of the few times this season, did
exactly what they were supposed to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
