<HEADLINE>
NFL DECISION ON COWBOYS' LETT STILL ON HOLD 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The word from NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue in
July was that he would have a ruling on the punishment phase of
defensive tackle Leon Lett's indefinite substance-abuse suspension
before the NFL's regular-season opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That was contradicted yesterday by a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Leon Lett \Rdecision\S today. Probably next week,'' NFL
spokesman Greg Aiello said yesterday on behalf of Tagliabue, who
had an expansion committee meeting this week. ``The commissioner is
preoccupied with some other matters right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are preoccupied with the Washington Redskins. The
Cowboys now go into tomorrow's game not knowing when they will get
their former Pro Bowl defensive tackle back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones took the non-news in stride yesterday.
He said he respects Tagliabue's timetable, although nobody is sure
what that exactly is now.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Tagliabue missing his self-imposed target date,
Aiello said, ``This doesn't mean anything. We were pressed hard
\Rfor a decision\S, and the commissioner said at the time that he
hoped to have something by the first game. He changed his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiello intimated that this wasn't a big deal since there has
been nothing to indicate that Lett was going to be allowed back to
play in early-season games anyway.
</P>
<P>
   As customary, Jones watched practice yesterday, then issued a
brief statement that couldn't be interpreted as even mildly
combative by anyone in Tagliabue's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't gotten any word from the league about a change in
Leon Lett's status,'' Jones said. ``Again, I must respect the
league office and the commissioner's timetable.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly
Linebacker Quentin Coryatt still hadn't surfaced at Valley Ranch
when practice ended yesterday. For more than two weeks, he has been
away from the team, receiving treatment from a specialist in
Indianapolis for his chronic Achilles' tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Coryatt received a $1 million signing bonus in April and was
expected to be the Cowboys' starter at strongside linebacker. Owner
Jerry Jones and Coryatt talked by phone Wednesday. Jones said he is
eager to meet with him when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie wide receiver Wane McGarity has been named by coach Chan
Gailey to return punts against Washington. McGarity didn't return
punts at Texas and returned only five punts for a 4.8-yard average
in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Second-year wide receiver Jeff Ogden will be the Cowboys'
primary return man on kickoffs. Ogden returned three kickoffs last
season and one this preseason. He will be joined by McGarity.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
