<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-HOUSE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BUDGET CUTS, UMKC PONDERS RENOVATIONS TO CHANCELLOR'S
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the midst of a financial crunch that
requires cutting $2.8 million from the campus budget, University of
Missouri-Kansas City officials are proposing renovations to the
chancellor's residence that could cost more than $228,000.
</P>
<P>
   The house was occupied until 10 days ago by the former
chancellor, who resigned in January. The university has been paying
$3,750 a month to house the interim chancellor in an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   UMKC administrators said they thought this fall was a good time
to fix up the chancellor's house because it will be empty several
more months until a new chancellor is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   They say the house needs a better water-drainage system, a more
modern kitchen and bathrooms, and a remodeled first floor that's
more accessible to the public. UMKC officials also said a renovated
house could make the chancellor's job more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   So a committee of the governing University of Missouri Board of
Curators had planned to meet Friday in Columbia to discuss
renovation options. These range from minimal changes costing about
$228,000 to major changes totaling about $629,000.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday afternoon, the curators canceled the meeting,
saying they weren't ready to decide on renovations. The committee
said it would discuss the issue at a future meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Curator Paul Steele, from Chillicothe, is on the executive
committee that had planned to meet Friday. He said he did not feel
comfortable making a decision based on the information he had.
</P>
<P>
   Some UMKC chancellor's residence renovations have been paid for
with private donations before, but Steele said he had no indication
from UMKC officials that private donations would be used to pay for
these renovations. The curators recently approved a plan from
Manuel Pacheco, president of the four-campus University of Missouri
system, that called for major budget cuts on the campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Professors and a student leader at the campus said
administrators shouldn't consider major renovations after asking
academic departments together to cut about $1.2 million from their
budgets next year. UMKC has a total budget of about $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' medical school professor Wayne Simpson, a
member of the Faculty Senate, said of the proposed renovations.
``Other chancellors have lived in it. It can't be that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Hackmann, Student Government Association president, whistled
in amazement when she heard the university already has spent about
$26,000 to house the interim chancellor, and probably will spend
almost $15,000 more before a new chancellor arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackmann also questioned the need for such expensive renovations
to the university-owned chancellor's residence, which is in the
center of campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me that doesn't set a very good example,'' Hackmann said.
``If it is necessary (renovations)...to make it functional, OK. But
to make extravagant renovations in a time of budget cuts is
hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   The brick-and-stucco home, built in 1933, was donated to UMKC's
predecessor, the University of Kansas City, in 1958. UKC merged
into the University of Missouri system in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, no major repairs have been made to the house, which
is situated on an acre of lush, green lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The house has a major drainage problem, with water often
collecting in the basement, UMKC officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old, old house, and we have not put much money into
that house,'' said Barbara Smith, UMKC assistant vice chancellor
for communication. ``It is very difficult to move around in there.
And the toilets don't flush properly.''
</P>
<P>
   The house's first floor, where chancellors often have had
dinners or receptions for professors, students and community
members, is fairly cramped. The dining room only accommodates about
10 persons, and other rooms are small.
</P>
<P>
   The foyer is on a higher level than the other rooms on the first
floor, so the public floor of the house could not be reached by
someone in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by consultant SH Associates, fixing the
drainage problem would cost about $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Improving public accessibility for events on the first floor
would cost about $177,000. That would include lowering the foyer to
the level of the dining and living rooms, enlarging the foyer's
coat closet and adding a second toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Other more cosmetic changes to the house would cost more than
$100,000. They would include removing the first-floor carpet and
refinishing the hardwood floors underneath, and repainting and
remodeling the brown-and-yellow kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The house was occupied up to about two weeks ago by former
Chancellor Eleanor B. Schwartz, who resigned in January after seven
years as chancellor. The curators, who are appointed by the
governor, allowed her to continue living in the chancellor's
residence until Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Interim Chancellor Gordon Lamb, whose home is in Columbia, said
he wasn't aware of how much the university was spending for his
temporary housing.
</P>
<P>
   The university has paid about $26,000 since February to house
Lamb in a furnished apartment, university officials say. Lamb will
live there until the new chancellor comes to campus, which probably
will be after the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A chancellor search committee has narrowed the pool of
candidates for the top job to eight. By Friday, each member was to
have ranked those eight in order of preference and given their
rankings to the head of the search committee.
</P>
<P>
   The top six vote-getters will be brought to Kansas City for
interviews with the search committee. The committee will choose
three and forward their names to Pacheco.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellors are required to live in the chancellor's residence.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb and other UMKC officials said recruiting a top-quality new
chancellor would be easier if the school could offer a modern,
attractive residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you can recruit a chancellor to a house with
water in the basement?'' Lamb asked.
</P>
<P>
   But Simpson, who is on the chancellor search committee, said the
committee wasn't even aware that renovations to the chancellor's
residence were being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not even on the priority list'' of the committee, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
