<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' LUCK RUNS OUT AGAINST DODGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This was exactly the combination of events the New
York Mets had managed to avoid for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When the starting pitching was shaky for three-quarters of the
season, the bullpen was the stalwart. When, in recent weeks, the
bullpen has suffered, the starters have frequently been good enough
to keep the relievers in their seats. Rarely had the two gone wrong
simultaneously and neither was disastrous Friday night. But like an
exhausted sprinter trying to make a clean baton pass, both ends of
the Mets' relay team stumbled just enough to allow the Dodgers to
eke out a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Al Leiter allowed two runs on three hits in six innings,
not bad considering he had trouble getting ahead of most hitters
and struggled to throw a strike in the first inning. But by the
sixth inning, he had thrown 87 pitches trying to dig his way out of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And reliever Billy Taylor, who has pitched better recently
despite allowing 11 runs in the eight innings he had pitched
entering the game, gave up an insurance run during the one inning
he pitched, when he left a slider way up to Raul Mondesi, who
belted a home run into the left-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   With the powerful Mets' offense held to four runs and 12 hits in
the first two games of this series _ incredibly, they beat ace
Kevin Brown, but lost to mediocre Darren Dreifort _ the small slips
could not be made up.
</P>
<P>
   The lowly Dodgers have beaten the Mets in four of their six
meetings this season, but this loss was particularly painful for
the Mets, because Cincinnati beat Florida to close the gap in the
wild-card race to 2 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   If there has been a hallmark of Leiter's uneven season, it has
been his lack of control early in games. And although he rarely
gets shelled, he needs plenty of pitches to get out of trouble.
Friday night, he struggled immediately and walked the first batter
he faced, Eric Young, on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the Dodgers scored just one run off Orel
Hershiser _ a solo home run by Gary Sheffield. Friday night, they
were determined to take advantage of Leiter's shakiness to
manufacture more runs. Leiter threw two more balls to the next
hitter, Mark Grudzielanek, prompting a quick visit to the mound
from Mike Piazza. Grudzielanek grounded out on the next pitch, but
Young was running and made it to second.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter fell behind again to the next batter, Gary Sheffield,
going 3-1. Young ran on the next pitch _ just the second strike
Leiter had thrown _ and was safe at third. With the count full,
Sheffield hit a sacrifice fly to left field to give the Dodgers a
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter still struggled to get ahead in the count, but after the
run scored, he retired 10 of the the next 11 batters. To start the
fifth, Leiter got ahead of the leadoff hitter Devon White 1-2. But
White smacked the next pitch down the right-field line for a
double. Adrian Beltre sacrificed White to third and backup catcher
Paul LoDuca, batting eighth, hit a fly ball to shallow right
center. Roger Cedeno caught it, but his throw to the plate went
past Piazza and White scored the Dodgers' second run.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets' explosive offense, that would seem to have been
no problem, especially against Dreifort. He was just 12-13 with a
5.02 earned run average entering the game, but he was in the middle
of one of the best stretches of the season, having won three of his
last four starts. He had given up just five earned runs in 301/3
innings with 19 strikeouts and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   While Leiter was struggling, Dreifort continued his recent
efficiency. He retired all but two of the Mets he faced in the
first four innings, and he struck out the side in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had their best chance to score in the fifth when, with
one out, Cedeno singled under Young's glove at second base. When
Dreifort fell behind Rey Ordonez 2-0, the fleet Cedeno was off to
second. Ordonez walked and Leiter sacrificed them over. With
leadoff hitter Rickey Henderson, who was fourth in the National
League with a .444 on base average and sixth in batting (.331)
entering the game, up next, the Mets seemed poised to bail Leiter
out. But the count on Henderson went to 0-2 and when he tried to
check his swing, he was called out by home plate umpire Mark
Carlson.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Grudzielanek, whose brainlock error Thursday led to
Piazza's two-run home run, briefly opened the door for the Mets in
the sixth, when he overran Piazza's slow roller, then slipped on
the infield dirt, allowing Piazza to reach first with two out. But
Dreifort struck out Robin Ventura to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Mets scored in the seventh. With one out, Cedeno,
on an 0-2 count, drilled a double to right field. Ordonez grounded
out, but Cedeno went to third. Matt Franco, pinch hitting for
Leiter, hit a double to the gap between right and center that
scored Cedeno to make the score 2-1. But Henderson again failed to
drive a run in, lining out to Grudzielanek to end the inning.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
