<HEADER>
A8285 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SUSPECT-MONITOR-KAN &LR;      09-11 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSPECT-MONITOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EXPLANATION OFFERED ABOUT DEFENDANT WHO THWARTED MONITORING
SYSTEM  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA and MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Court and corrections officials Friday were
unable to explain how a defendant accused of strangling an elderly
Kansas City woman was on the streets for more than three weeks
after removing his electronic monitoring device.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Corrections knows that Michael L.
Farris removed his monitor Aug. 9, but did not say when it learned
he had done so. A request for an arrest warrant for Farris did not
reach a judge's desk until Sept. 7 _ four days after Sophia
Szymczak was found dead in her home in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the slaying, law enforcement officials could not or
would not say exactly when they were notified that Farris had
tampered with his monitor, or which authorities had received that
notification. Interviews with the prosecutor's office, state
corrections officials, and local probation and parole authorities
Friday indicated that the monitoring system worked as designed.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities, however, are not saying what was done in the 25
days between the removal of the monitor and Szymczak's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the killing, Farris was awaiting trial in the
burglary of Szymczak's home last year. He also was on probation in
Johnson County, Kan., after pleading guilty in a theft case.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Aug. 26, Johnson County officials knew Farris had
cut off his monitor, and moved for his arrest. The next day,
corrections officials in Jackson County prepared a report to notify
court officials in Kansas City, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Probation officials in Jackson County, Mo., who supervise
defendants on home detention awaiting trial, on Friday referred all
questions about Farris to Missouri Department of Corrections
spokesman Tim Kniest in Jefferson City. He said that the situation
was under review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're redoubling our efforts with Jackson County to develop
something to collapse notification time to the court,'' Kniest
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said he believed that
public attention to this case would lead to improvements in the way
courts are informed about a defendant's violation of pretrial
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem will rectify itself,'' he said. ``I
anticipate the courts will get (reports) in a more timely
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaird also said he and the presiding judge of the county's
criminal court division decided this week to limit use of home
detention to people charged with relatively minor offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said the Farris situation might have been avoided had the
Jackson County Jail annex opened earlier, as scheduled. Because the
jail was under pressure to keep its population down, Farris almost
certainly would have been released on bond had he been sent to the
jail to await trial, Beaird said. Home detention, he said, allowed
a greater degree of supervision at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Since the time Farris was placed on home detention, 176
additional beds have become available at the Jackson County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had happened now, it might have come out differently,''
Beaird said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Executive Katheryn Shields, who oversaw
construction of the annex, could not be reached for comment Friday.
She has said the delays were because of contractor problems.
</P>
<P>
   Farris now is charged with first-degree murder, and Beaird is
considering whether to seek the death penalty. Silencing a
potential witness is an aggravating factor that can elevate a
murder charge to a capital crime.
</P>
<P>
   County and state officials said Friday it was unusual for home
detainees to remove their monitors. Assistant Jackson County
Prosecutor David Fry said he could not recall another case in which
a defendant awaiting trial removed a monitor and committed another
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Home-detention devices are hard plastic rings that lock around a
person's ankle and communicate electronically with a monitoring
authority, over telephone lines. Officials at a remote center know
whether a defendant is home when he's supposed to be, but cannot
confirm his whereabouts when he is outside the range of the
transmitter. Every morning, the center sends a report to local law
enforcement officials on people in the program.
</P>
<P>
   If the device is tampered with, a signal alerts the monitoring
company and local authorities, according to a spokeswoman for B.I.
Inc., which manufactures the equipment in Boulder, Colo., and
tracks detainees from there.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was unaware of the Farris case.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Smith, unit supervisor for the pretrial release office of
the Missouri Board of Probation and Parole, said that if a monitor
is tampered with, his office is notified immediately. In those
cases, which Smith called unusual, a case supervisor is summoned to
investigate and the courts are notified.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that the design of the monitor and its locking device
made removal difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not something simply done,'' he said. ``It would take
some effort.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people on bond awaiting trial in Jackson County wear
the monitor in home detention, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Farris, who used the alias ``Sneakie Pete,'' has a history of
preying on elderly victims.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after being paroled for a 1976 burglary conviction,
Farris and five others invaded and robbed the home of a 61-year-old
man and his 51-year-old wife. The couple were bound with electrical
cord. After the others left, Farris stayed behind and attempted to
rape the woman.
</P>
<P>
   For that attack and a separate, similar incident, Farris was
found guilty of assault with intent to do great bodily harm with
malice, assault with intent to rape, two counts of first-degree
robbery and a crime against nature. The jury recommended a 440-year
sentence. The court imposed 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   But that and other Missouri verdicts were set aside after a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling that a Missouri law allowing women an
automatic exclusion from jury duty was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a new trial, Farris pleaded guilty in September 1979
to two counts of first-degree robbery. He was sentenced to
consecutive 25-year terms. The other charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, two years after Farris was paroled from prison,
he was charged with stealing $3,000 worth of jewelry from an
82-year-old Shawnee, Kan., woman while he was working for a moving
company.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months later, he allegedly burglarized Szymczak's
house.
</P>
<P>
   Farris is in custody now, and Beaird said he plans to seek a
murder indictment from a Jackson County grand jury. Beaird said he
would convene a committee of prosecutors to decide whether to seek
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird also said that he had met Wednesday with Jackson County
Circuit Judge John R. O'Malley, who presides over the criminal
docket. The two agreed that in the future the option of home
detention should be limited to cases involving bad checks,
forgeries, failure to make support payments and traffic offenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
