<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUND-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELISTED FIRM GETS TROUNCED BY INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Investors pounded Sound Source Interactive Inc.
shares Friday after the company was delisted from the Nasdaq
SmallCap Market and placed on Nasdaq's less-regulated Over The
Counter Bulletin Board.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which closed at 40.6 cents Thursday, fell to 25 cents
on the OTC Friday., a 38 percent drop. More than 22,000 shares
traded hands, a 23 percent increase over the average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Calabasas-based children's software company lost its listing
on the SmallCap Market Thursday, after market officials refused to
give the company more time to comply with listing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Bitetti, Sound Source chairman and chief executive
officer, said the company was delisted because its net tangible
assets fell below $2 million and its stock has traded under $1
since April.
</P>
<P>
   But Bitetti said the move to Nasdaq's less-regulated board would
not hurt Sound Source's long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view the OTC as a good place for us at this time,'' Bitetti
said. ``If and when we turn around the company, we will be able to
regain compliance with Nasdaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound Source, ranked among the six or seven largest educational
software publishers in the country, has struggled in recent years.
Bitetti said the company was especially hurt by dismal sales of
three ``Babe: Pig in the City'' titles last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired Los Angeles-based Wedbush Morgan Securities
earlier this year to find a buyer or strategic partner, but Wedbush
terminated the deal in late June. Just days later, Sound Source met
with Nasdaq officials to request a short-term exception to market
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Bitetti said he hopes a planned foray into the market for Sony
PlayStation games will help revive the company.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the Sound Source also needs a cash infusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the prospects are good,'' he said, ``but I really do
feel it's time to recapitalize the company.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
