<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAGLIABUE IN NO HURRY TO FREE LETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Waiting for Leon?
</P>
<P>
   (Insert mindless whistling here).
</P>
<P>
   (Jingle pocket change).
</P>
<P>
   (Hum a few bars of Barry Manilow favorite).
</P>
<P>
   Still waiting?
</P>
<P>
   To their growing chagrin, the Cowboys are maintaining a vigil,
too. Leon Lett, alas, isn't coming back tomorrow for the season
opener in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'll come back next week. Or next month. Or next time
there's a lunar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Lett: Lineman in Exile remains a continuing story. And NFL
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue can't seem to script the final chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Writer's block?
</P>
<P>
   No. It's more like the commish has other priorities. Like this
instant replay thing. And rearranging that always-pesky
Commissioner's Sock Drawer.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys and Owner Jones, no news yesterday was bad news.
According to the commish's office, Tagliabue had good intentions of
announcing the length of the Lett suspension, but he never got
around to it.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that's it. The dog ate his homework.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and the Cowboys, of course, would like to know exactly how
long their best defensive lineman is going to be out, so that they
can:
</P>
<P>
   1. Find a sober replacement.
</P>
<P>
   2. Order an extra Happy Meal for the team plane.
</P>
<P>
   3. Sell advertising on Leon's empty locker.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the owner is keeping his candid comments about the
situation to himself. Privately, his loafers are steaming. How's a
guy supposed to run a football team when he doesn't even know when
to expect his players?
</P>
<P>
   A good question. But let me suggest that Owner Jones should have
thought of that two Leon suspensions ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, two substance-abuse strikes and you're
probably out. But Jones chose not to ``correct'' the problem by
flushing Lett from the roster. Instead, he has continually welcomed
Leon back to the nurturing nest.
</P>
<P>
   Two scenarios, therefore, may be playing out themselves here.
First, there is the locally popular notion that Tagliabue harbors a
grudge against the maverick Jones and now relishes this opportunity
to make life miserable for him.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, it's both ragingly unprofessional and
thoroughly understandable. Commissioners are not hired to carry out
personal vendettas.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe this isn't personal. It's just an impersonal case of
Cowboys-needling. Tagliabue may not have it in for America's Team,
but he certainly doesn't owe it any favors.
</P>
<P>
   The union-negotiated rules regarding substance abuse allow the
commissioner to be as arbitrary and vague as he wants or needs to
be. Blame it on the system, not necessarily the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The other possible Lett scenario accuses the Tagliabue delay of
being both intentional and purposeful. The commissioner knows that
each week that passes without rendering a sentence for Lett is
another week of punishment for Leon. And that's the precise point.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jones still considers Lett a valued employee. He has made
no public moves, despite Lett's multiple suspensions, to discipline
him, trade him or release him. Granted, the players association
prevents Jones from imposing certain further sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   But the union doesn't say anything about continuing to employ
and pay him. A lesser Cowboy with a drug suspension, Clayton
Holmes, was quickly banished from the roster, you may recall. Yet
Jerry keeps the porch light on for Leon.
</P>
<P>
   In the second scenario, therefore, if Jones won't make it any
tougher on Lett, the commissioner will.
</P>
<P>
   These are theories, admittedly, not facts. But by the bright
light of an onrushing season opener, they have as much credence as
yesterday's he-didn't-get-around-to-it excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cowboys will miss Lett, provided that he is the
Leon Lett they know. The one that played last year was, at best,
inconsistent and, at times, invisible. The Cowboys dearly need
their front four to provide pressure, beginning tomorrow against
the Redskins' Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The starting defensive tackles in Washington are going to be
Chad Hennings and Alonzo Spellman. The backups hail from deep down
somebody else's depth chart and//or that overseas league,
Euro-Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   This could get worse before it gets better. Getting Leon Lett
back would probably help.
</P>
<P>
   But don't hold your breath. The commissioner will get around to
deciding that next week. Or next month. Or, well, whenever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
