<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTH-SCARES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BATTLE WITH MOSQUITOES AND PUBLIC PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CHANGES totals in 6th graf; DELETES 7th graf) (jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stephen Athineos, the manager of a bike messenger
service in Manhattan, is perfectly clear on two things. The first
is that the current threat of the St. Louis encephalitis outbreak
is a total fabrication of city officials. The second is that they
ought to be doing a much better job of containing it.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude underscores the fine line that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani must walk. Both the mayor and health officials are
challenged to appear extremely aggressive at controlling the
illness, which has claimed the lives of three people, while at the
same time quelling public hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   A day after helicopters clattered ominously above the city
spraying insecticide to kill the mosquitoes that spread the
disease, Giuliani held a press conference Friday in which he
convivially chided reporters for failing to protect their feet from
insects bites with socks. Vans with bull horns have crawled down
city streets bellowing public health warnings, but along those same
streets, city officials also set up command centers to provide
information to a nervous public with a decidedly folksier touch.
</P>
<P>
   And scores of city officials have also taken over phone banks to
take inquiries from nervous citizens, where the number of calls
since the outbreak emerged a week ago have far outnumbered the
amount ever received by the mayor's Office of Emergency Management
since its inception in 1996, sometimes clocking 800 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely difficult to strike the balance between
providing the public with all the information they need to know
while at the same time not creating undue concern or panic,'' said
Neal Cohen, commissioner of the city health department. He added
that for this reason, the encephalitis outbreak has been one of the
most difficult public health crises in his career.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a severe outbreak of E. coli, linked to a
county fair in upstate New York, has state health officials working
overtime to inform and assist a worried public. Officials believe
that heavy rain washed cow feces into an aquifer from a farm near
the fairgrounds in Washington County. From the aquifer, they
believe, it flowed into a well supplying the fair. As of Friday
evening, one child and one man had died, 611 people were suspected
of being infected, with 85 cases confirmed and 58 people
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials said they believed the outbreak of
primary infection had peaked last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem in the city is more complex, in part because of
the illness itself, which is extremely hard to diagnosis. Its
symptoms are very much like those of flu and a common form of
meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Further, it is not curable; only the symptoms can be treated.
While this is hardly a problem for mild cases, it raises the level
of fear about getting sick. Health officials say that babies and
the elderly are at greatest risk. And while the illness at first
seemed to be contained to Queens, there have now been reports of
possible cases across the city, lending the illness an appearance
of being out of control, even though the chance of contracting it
is slim. And while not a single child has died, parents do not seem
to be able to keep themselves from fretting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that it is a citywide issue that doesn't target one
community or one population makes it more frightening to the
public,'' Cohen said. ``A good part of what we are doing now is
assuring the public that the threat and risks are very minimal
given what we know about exposure.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And then there is the mayor himself, who seems to be struggling
at times to let the public know that everything is under control
with this major health scare while at the same time telling them
that the scare is perhaps not so big. At the news conference
Friday, he chided reporters for botching facts and inciting fear,
but at the same time pressed them to remind the people to douse
themselves with insect repellent, a point he underscored by giving
himself a little spray during his comments. He has insisted there
is no health threat connected to the city's spraying efforts, a
point many experts and the Environmental Protection Agency agree
with. But then Giuliani hinted that people might want to shut a
window or two.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some New Yorkers have turned their fears away from
mosquitoes and toward the chemicals being used to combat them.
``We're upset about the reality of the mosquito problem, but I
don't believe the chemical is totally harmless,'' said Eve Logan,
who lives on the Upper West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Kaplan, who lives in the Park Slope area of Brooklyn,
echoed the fear. ``I give my children only organic fruits and
vegetables and now they're spraying everywhere,'' said Ms. Kaplan,
who is seven months pregnant and has twin 2-year-olds. ``I don't
trust that they know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, like Athineos, who manages Mother's Messengers,
seem to see things both ways. ``The politicians have promoted
hysteria,'' he said. But he quickly added that the city should have
been more aggressive with its insecticide spraying up front.
``Basically if you have one case, you should spray the whole
city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
