<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      09-11 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS LOSE IN 12, BUT DAVEY SHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ By now, the Mariners are too far behind in the
American League wild card race for individual games to be pivotal.
Their 5-4 loss Friday night to the Baltimore Orioles, marred by
three unearned runs in the early innings and later failures by the
bullpen and offense, might have stung more if the M's were closer
than 9{ games behind the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting impression from the game, which ended when Mike
Bordick hit a solo homer off a high fastball from Robert Ramsay
with one out in the 12th inning, might be the performance of Tom
Davey. The rookie right-hander had his best performance as a
Mariner, working 22/3 scoreless innings in what he hopes is a
preview of his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can look at myself from a managerial standpoint, and you
don't know what you're going to get,'' said Davey, who was acquired
from Toronto in the David Segui trade on July 28. ``Is he going to
pitch well, or is he going to come in and walk guys and start
aiming the ball? I mean, you're going to have your days, but I've
had too many of those days this year where I've been bad,
especially since I've come over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Davey, who turns 26 today, entered the game with a 6.59
earned-run average in 10 games as a Mariner. He has not figured in
a decision, but he had been erratic, allowing 31 baserunners in
132/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, after Butch Henry and Jose Paniagua had allowed
the Orioles to tie the score, 4-4, on two singles in the eighth,
Baltimore threatened again with two on and one out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Davey came in, got Bordick to line out and allowed a single to
B.J. Surhoff on which Brian Hunter threw out Jerry Hairston at home
plate, ending the inning. The tie preserved, Davey worked 1-2-3
innings in the 10th and 11th. His most impressive at-bat came
against the dangerous Albert Belle, who struck out on fastballs
that ranged from 95 to 99 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Davey left the game with tightness in his right triceps. He
could have lasted longer, he said, had he not thrown so many
pitches before the game while perfecting a flaw in his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   When Davey is mechanically sound, his arm is raised near his
head by the time he lands on his left foot. Before Friday night,
though, his arm was dragging behind the rest of his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was landing on my front foot,'' he said, ``and my hand was
still behind my butt.''
</P>
<P>
   He corrected the problem Friday night, ``and instead of thinking
about 10 other things like I was before,'' Davey said, he
concentrated on making pitches. The result was probably his best
performance since he earned a save against the Mariners for the
Blue Jays on May 1, working 31/3 scoreless innings with no walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, I thought I showed everyone the pitcher they thought
they were getting from when I threw against them early in the
year,'' Davey said. ``For me, that's a confidence booster. If I
keep throwing the ball like that, I'll get more innings and be able
to help the team more.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Davey, starter Paul Abbott left early with a minor injury.
Abbott allowed three unearned runs over seven innings before
removing himself with a pulled groin. He said he expects to make
his next start.
</P>
<P>
   The first two runs came on a Belle double in the third that
followed a two-out error by shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who was
screened by baserunner Mike Figga and lost track of Surhoff's sharp
grounder. The Orioles' next run, in the fourth, was aided by an
error by second baseman David Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have played good defense all year, and we gave them three
runs there,'' said manager Lou Piniella. ``Those were the deciding
runs, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez tied the game with a two-run homer in the sixth, his
37th, and Edgar Martinez followed with his 23rd to put the M's in
front, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   But five Orioles relievers _ part of a bullpen that blew 20
saves in the first half _ limited Seattle to just two singles over
the final six innings. That allowed Baltimore to come back in the
eighth, when Cal Ripken drove in Surhoff with his fourth single of
the game. The hit came off Jose Paniagua, who was not charged with
a run but registered his American League-leading ninth blown save.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Right fielder Jay Buhner left the game in the seventh
inning with cramps in his left hamstring. Buhner did not consider
the setback serious. ... Reliever Mark Leiter, out for the season
with a torn rotator cuff, threw for five minutes before yesterday's
game. ``Originally they said November, but I threw today and it
went good,'' said the 37-year-old right-hander. ``If I can get
going by spring, that's more than I expected. It definitely could
happen.'' Whether a comeback happens with the Mariners is unclear,
since Leiter is a free agent this winter. ... Piniella may travel
to North Carolina Sunday for the funeral of Hall of Famer and
former New York Yankees teammate Catfish Hunter, who died Thursday
at age 53. ... With KIRO 710 AM covering the Seahawks/Lions game,
Sunday's Mariners game will be broadcast on KNWX 770 AM and 100.7
FM.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
