<SLUG> BC-BBA-GRIFFEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ME SERIOUSLY, JUNIOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ He has joked about it frequently, but in recent
days, Ken Griffey Jr. has become serious when discussing the
possibility of leaving the only team he has known.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Mariners' 5-4, 12-inning loss in Baltimore Friday
night, Griffey spoke forcefully about his future for the second
time this week. For those hoping he will play center field for the
Mariners after his contract runs out after next season, the message
was not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't think that I will leave, then they are sadly
mistaken,'' Griffey said, referring to Mariners management. ``I'm
not going to stay here and lose for the next eight years of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are trying to re-sign Griffey _ and shortstop Alex
Rodriguez _ and have made three contract offers to Griffey. But
since the club's sub-.500 finish last season, Griffey has insisted
that his decision to stay past this contract will be based on the
direction of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have they done to change my mind?'' Griffey asked. ``A
new ballpark is supposed to change my mind? They signed one player
out of spring training. What have they done since then?''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners maintained the same payroll from 1998 to '99, and
entered this season with four significant veterans set to become
free agents this winter. Pitcher Jamie Moyer agreed to a two-year,
$15 million extension in April, first baseman David Segui and
pitcher Jeff Fassero were traded and designated hitter Edgar
Martinez remains unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 23, the Texas Rangers have held a double-digit lead
on the Mariners in the American League West, and the M's seem
headed for their second consecutive third-place finish after
winning the division two of the previous three years.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners management has stressed that the move to Safeco Field
will allow the team to be competitive. Griffey said Mariners
players have higher standards, and expressed disappointment that
team president Chuck Armstrong and others have not stated loftier
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chuck (gives) his definition of a competitive team, or if
the organization gives one, then I might be able to give a
counter-proposal (to contract offers),'' Griffey said. ``But they
can't. Because we have two different opinions on competitiveness.
My opinion is I want to beat everybody. That's it. Their definition
is being competitive with Texas, Anaheim and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-uh. I want to beat the daylights out of everyone, and have
people afraid to come in and play the Seattle Mariners.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong would not comment Friday, other than to reiterate that
the club does not discuss contract negotiations and that it intends
to re-sign both marquee players.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who was presented with a reported seven-year, $135
million offer in July, has said numerous times that money is ``not
the issue.'' Yesterday, he defined just what the issue is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about respect,'' he said. ``I go out there every day,
(even) if I'm hurting. Everybody knows my knee's been messed up for
a month, two months, three months now. I go out there because
there's something I can do to help this ballclub, and I wouldn't go
out there if I felt like I couldn't contribute in any way, shape or
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have the respect of the guys in this locker room,
and the other locker rooms, about what I do out on the field. But I
don't have the respect of our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey referred to several incidents throughout his 11-year
Mariners career. He laughed when asked if players were consulted on
various aspects of Safeco Field, and he said the team should ask
players before using their likeness on giveaways sponsored by
companies those players may not endorse.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey also brought up travel-related issues _ ``Our travel
schedule costs us seven to 10 games a year,'' he said _ including
the club's infamous 1997 midseason trip to Zebulon, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who know me know that it's not, `Hey, I need this to
stay, I want this, I want that,' '' Griffey said. ``It's always,
`As a team, we'd like to have this, it's important that we get this
done.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak for the team. `I' and `me' don't really get along.
That's why it's so hard to answer when you (reporters) ask me
questions about me. I'm not real good about that. But what I am
really good about is telling people what's wrong, and what we need
to better our ballclub and organization.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also personal issues. This is the first extended
period that Griffey has been apart from his family during the
baseball season; 5-year-old son Trey has begun school at home in
Orlando, Fla. For Griffey to return to a team that plays so far
from his home, he will have to be convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Mariners) can make the decision real easy for me,'' he
said, ``or they can make it real tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0230EDT &QL; 
