<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT PASSES ANOTHER EXAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a curious thing. For the first 45 starts of
his career, everyone wanted to know what was wrong with Darren
Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, everyone is trying to figure out why everything is so
right with Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   Contemplation about moving him to the bullpen has been replaced
with talk of how dominant Dreifort can be. The latest example came
in Dreifort's latest masterpiece. He allowed four hits in eight
innings of a 3-1 win against the Mets to end the Dodgers' losing
streak at four games Friday night at Dodger Stadium. Raul Mondesi
added his 29th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's learning himself,'' Dodgers ace Kevin Brown said. ``He's
comfortable. It's him learning on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Dreifort was one more dismal start away from being
in the bullpen. Now he's 4-1 with a 2.06 ERA in his last five
starts and on the fast track to being one of the few nice surprises
in an atrocious season.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, Dreifort was 8-11 with an ERA near 6. Now,
he's 13-13 with a 4.84 ERA and trails only Brown for the club lead
in wins (16).
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew he was a great starting pitcher,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said with a wide grin. ``He shut down a good
hitting club. He never tried to really overthrow. He was completely
smooth the whole way.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this season, Dreifort would reach his pitch count by the
fifth inning. Against the Mets, he threw 100 pitches in eight
innings before giving way to Jeff Shaw, who notched his 32nd save.
</P>
<P>
   But it goes way beyond just the 70 strikes he threw and the
confidence on the mound. No longer does Dreifort throw every pitch
with maximum velocity.
</P>
<P>
   He's also regressed to his days of academia at Wichita State.
Dreifort has taken to studying hitters more and talking to other
pitchers and catchers during games he's not starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're sitting there for days and discussing things with the
other pitchers, and when someone gets a hit, everyone runs over to
the catcher to see what pitch was thrown,'' Dreifort said. ``The
first game of a series I might spend talking to the bullpen guys,
the way to pitch certain guys. Mike Maddux is a great guy for that.
He makes mental notes and writes things down, and he's easy to
approach and (bounce things) off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped a lot. Going into a game, it's going in and taking
an exam. If you prepare yourself, you're going to pass or you're
going to fail. You have to give yourself a chance to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hierarchy, as well as catcher Todd Hundley, also
said they've noticed Brown's impact on Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has a tendency to bear down with runners on base,
particularly when they're in scoring position. Dreifort has started
to do that and it showed in the seventh inning against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-teammate Roger Cedeno doubled to right with one out and
scored on pinch-hitter Matt Franco's two-out double to right-center
as the Mets pulled within 2-1. Dodgers second baseman Eric Young
tried to keep pinch-runner Shane Halter close to the bag, and
though Dreifort paid attention, his focus was instead on batter
Ricky Henderson, who lined out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn a lot just watching (Brown) pitch, just his
competitiveness,'' Dreifort said. ``He's a guy where you can just
watch him and sometimes he'll get himself into a jam, and all of a
sudden, one, two, three strikeouts, or a strikeout and a
double-play ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of like, you bear down for one out, but the other
thing is you're less concerned about the runner and you're less
concerned about everything but the batter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
