<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NEW-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEW COACHES, AMBITIONS ARE GRAND, EVEN IF TEAMS AREN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine head coaches are in new roles in the National Football
League this season and all are intent on infusing their franchises
with wisdom and style. In most of their situations, plenty of
infusing is required.
</P>
<P>
   The nine range in age from 41 (Andy Reid) to 59 (George
Seifert). Five are offensive-minded coaches _ Reid in Philadelphia,
Brian Billick in Baltimore, Chris Palmer in Cleveland, Mike Riley
in San Diego and Mike Holmgren in Seattle. Four are
defensive-minded _ Seifert in Carolina, Gunther Cunningham in
Kansas City, Ray Rhodes in Green Bay and Dick Jauron in Chicago.
Three are former pro head coaches _ Holmgren, Seifert and Rhodes.
Two have won Super Bowls as a head coach _ Holmgren and Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   And their initial seasons are expected to unfold this way:
</P>
<P>
   Good: Holmgren and Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: Billick and Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: Reid, Palmer, Riley, Seifert and Jauron.
</P>
<P>
   Jauron, for his part, said he is not concerned about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not particularly interested in what other people
think,'' he said, though the Bears trudged to 4-12 finishes in both
1997 and 1998. ``We're only interested in what we as a team think.
We'll see where their predictions are at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, some in this group will fly and others will fold.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren earns more ($4 million per year) than any coach and has
as much authority as any, including over personnel and contracts.
He has the autonomy in Seattle that he did not have in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a challenge to see how you can do it, from the ground
up, the way you want to do it,'' Holmgren said. ``It's new, but
it's something I'm excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Excitement has been rare in Seattle, where the Seahawks have not
had a winning season in nine years or a playoff berth in 11 years.
He has good players to work with.
</P>
<P>
   And the good players Holmgren left in Green Bay, Rhodes
inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes plans to turn loose quarterback Brett Favre. Holmgren
used to constrain Favre, but Rhodes' attitude is, let it fly and
take us to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   For Seifert, who won two Super Bowls as the head coach in San
Francisco, another Super Bowl seems far away. The Panthers were
4-12 last season, and they could be worse in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the unexpected in Cleveland, where Palmer helps an old
franchise start anew. The Browns are an expansion team dripping
with nostalgia, and with an assortment of players grabbed from
other team's rosters, from the draft and from free agency. It is a
mix that seems muddled now with a terrific fan base yearning for a
quick jell.
</P>
<P>
   Riley and San Diego fight a discouraging battle in the American
Football Conference West, where two-time defending Super Bowl
champion Denver reigns. Cunningham and Kansas City are also in that
division.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham worked for 30 years as a college and pro assistant
before gaining the Chiefs' head coaching job. His task is huge:
restoring luster and respect to the Chiefs after their ugly fall
last season, one in which they compiled a losing record (7-9) after
nine straight winning ones and in which they finished as the
league's most penalized team. Cunningham has the task of restoring
the fans' respect of a team that was boorish on the field a year
ago. Cunningham describes himself as ``blood and guts'' on the
sideline. Explosive. He wants his team to play in that manner.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, Reid said of his new job with the Eagles,
``I've never put myself in a bad situation.'' Many wonder.
Philadelphia looks porous.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens and their fans know that feeling. ``This is a city
starved for a winner,'' Billick said of Baltimore, where the Ravens
were 6-10 last season and had a four-game losing streak early and a
three-game losing streak late. ``I see a good core on defense and
an offense that just needs to be tweaked.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the new coaches, Billick said his players ``need to
change and find a new way of doing business.'' There are five areas
he plans to focus on: 1) Be well-prepared; 2) Provide attention to
detail; 3) Do not be prone to mental errors; 4) Exhibit passion for
the game, and 5) Do not allow big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to develop a team that is explosive,'' Billick said.
``We want an offense that doesn't put a good defense on a short
field. We will use a lot of multiple formations and groupings. We
can't line up and shove the ball; we're not that good. We will use
superior numbers and angles.''
</P>
<P>
   Be crafty. Create hope and keep it alive. Win. For most of these
new head coaches, that will happen only over the long haul. History
indicates that most will not earn the chance to finish what they
start.
</P>
<P>
   After all, that is how most of them got their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
