u s BC-FBN-TV-SANDOMIR-NYT &LR;      09-11 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SANDOMIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-ANNOUNCER BOOTH MIGHT EASE PRESSURE ON ESIASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cardinal rule of television production: three announcers in
the booth are definitely better than two if that is what you have
got, but two in the booth are far better if you have just shed one
of the previous three. Got it?
</P>
<P>
   At ABC's ``Monday Night Football,'' the departure of Dan
Dierdorf to CBS leaves Al Michaels and Boomer Esiason on their own
to boast about the benefits of being a pair. ``It's going to be
much easier,'' Esiason said.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels added: ``A benefit of three in the booth is you have a
lot of lively commentary if each analyst approaches the play from
different angles, but there can be redundancies. With a two-man
booth, we can allow the telecast to breathe. You don't have to keep
up a constant patter.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is entering its second season of ``Sunday Night Football''
with Mike Patrick, Paul Maguire and Joe Theismann. ``You do a
three-man booth when it works, and we found one that works even
though we backed into it last year to mirror ABC's three-man
booth,'' Jed Drake, a vice president at ESPN, said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a crucial season for Esiason, who was not experienced
enough to be the solo analyst last season. And his aggressive style
in dealing with Dierdorf led some viewers to think they disliked
each other. ``It was all in the ear of the beholder,'' Esiason
said. ``I was saddened. I never felt it.''
</P>
<P>
   With more time to talk, Esiason will be under pressure to
provide analysis on a par with that of Maguire, CBS' Phil Simms or
Fox's John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   The season marks ``Monday Night Football's'' return to a 9 p.m.
Eastern starting time _ to bring back West Coast viewers not home
for the early part of games that last season started at 8:20. ABC
will not bring back its inane pre-game show either, but halftime
with Chris Berman will emanate from New York's ESPN Zone
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first year since 1971 that Frank Gifford is not
with ``Monday Night Football.'' Esiason replaced him last season,
and Gifford's nominal role on the pre-game show was eliminated this
season. He was not offered a new role at ABC. ``He sounds fine,''
Michaels said, ``but he keeps his inner feelings to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   At CBS Sports, ``The NFL Today'' Sunday show underwent a radical
makeover, keeping the host, Jim Nantz, but bringing in the analysts
Randy Cross, Craig James and Jerry Glanville to replace Brent
Jones, George Seifert and Marcus Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three experienced analysts in the studio, which we
didn't have last year,'' said Sean McManus, who took responsibility
for the inexperience of last year's crew of analysts and made the
right choices to replace them.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports made no substantial changes, except to turn the cast
of the pre-game ``Fox NFL Sunday'' into animated Claymation
characters for promotional reasons. The program is also adding
forecasts from the Weather Channel to assure viewers that the Green
Bay tundra is frozen. If NFL games are not canceled or delayed
because of severe weather, it seems that gamblers will benefit most
from the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Cable's Fox Sports Net is launching ``NFL This Morning'' Sunday
at 11 a.m., Eastern with Chris Myers, Jackie Slater and Marv Levy,
which will lead into the noon ``Fox NFL Sunday.'' The show will
feature less mirth and more hard-core pigskin chatter than its
broadcast sibling.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of yet another NFL studio show again raises the
question: when is too much too much? Answer: never, at least to
those involved. ``On the day of the game, I don't think there is a
saturation point,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   But look out: the NFL has contemplated creating an All-NFL
Channel that will probably show used game uniforms being laundered
to fill time.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's ``Sunday NFL Countdown'' on Sunday stretched to two hours
last year and ``Monday Night Countdown'' bulks up to 120 minutes
Monday. Berman regrets that ESPN cannot start ``NFL PrimeTime'' _
its 45-minute lead-in to the Sunday night game _ at 7:15 p.m.
Eastern, rather than 7:30. He would also like the game to kick off
at 8:35, not 8:20. ``Forty-five minutes is hard,'' he said. ``As
fast as I talk, I have to talk faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The appetite for more and lengthier studio shows is largely a
result of the networks' eight-year, $18 billion NFL deals. Studio
shows are relatively inexpensive to produce and promote the games.
The league will receive $1.8 billion this season and each team will
receive $58.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN starts Sunday night when Pittsburgh plays in Cleveland,
with the expansion Browns resuming life after a three-year hiatus.
The NFL has missed the Cleveland market. In 1995, the Browns' final
year in Cleveland before Art Modell moved them to Baltimore, the
market's Sunday afternoon network rating averaged 16.9. In 1994,
the 21.3 Cleveland rating was tied with Dallas for the league's
best. By last season, the rating had tumbled to 8.6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more excited about this game than the two Super Bowls I
called,'' said Maguire, who grew up near Cleveland. ``Whether they
win or not is beside the point. They're back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
