<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-11 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EXTERMINATE THE REPLAY BUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a familiar phrase in pro football: rookie mistakes. And
when the National Football League season opens Sunday, mistakes are
sure to be made by its most controversial rookie: the new
television replay system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the system is going to do what it's designed to do,
change those game-breaking plays,'' Tony Dungy, the coach whose
Tampa Bay Buccaneers open at home against the Giants, was saying
the other day. ``But it's not going to be without a few bugs this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   What bugs?
</P>
<P>
   Dungy laughed and said: ``I just got a memo from the
commissioner's office. We weren't supposed to comment and be
critical, so I'm just going to leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL must exterminate those bugs.
</P>
<P>
   This new system has created an all-rookie team that should be
known as the Replay Bugs. Referees and replay-booth officials, no
matter how many years of experience they may have in other areas,
are still learning a new system just as a rookie quarterback must
learn an offensive system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the preseason would be a laboratory,'' said Jerry
Seeman, the NFL's senior director of officiating. ``Is the system
letter perfect? No way. But it's an insurance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's insurance against the catastrophic mistake that allows the
wrong team to win a game. As the Jets did last year, 32-31 over the
Seattle Seahawks, when Vinny Testaverde was awarded the winning
touchdown on a 5-yard quarterback sneak on fourth-and-goal with 27
seconds remaining. Replays clearly showed he had been stopped short
of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   That documented blunder, with a few others, prompted the NFL to
restore replay with a new system:
</P>
<P>
   In each game, a team is permitted a maximum of two challenges
that will initiate referee replay reviews. Each challenge requires
the use of a team timeout. If a challenge is upheld, the timeout
will be restored to the challenging team. No challenges will be
recognized from a team that has exhausted its timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   After the two-minute warning in each half and during overtime,
any review will be initiated by the replay official in the booth,
without limit and without a timeout's being charged.
</P>
<P>
   All replay reviews will be conducted by the referee on a
field-level monitor after consultation with other officials. A
decision will be reversed only when the referee sees ``indisputable
visual evidence'' that warrants the reversal. Each review will be a
maximum of 90 seconds, beginning when the referee puts on the
headset to the replay booth.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple enough, but bugs have surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 63 exhibition games, 14 of the 61 reviewed plays were
reversed _ 10 of the 47 challenges by coaches, 4 of the 14 reviews
from the replay-booth official.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had six errors,'' Seeman acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Seeman meant six plays that either were reversed incorrectly or
let stand incorrectly, but that's six bugs too many, even in
exhibition games. More than most teams, the Giants saw the bugs. In
Baltimore, running back LeShon Johnson was ruled to have fumbled
and the Ravens recovered. The video feed seen in the New York area
clearly showed Johnson down before the ball spurted loose.
</P>
<P>
   But the referee, Phil Luckett, was shown only the Baltimore
video feed that, to him, was not indisputable evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some exhibition games use only four cameras,'' Seeman said.
``All our network games will have a minimum of seven cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   That particular bug should not reappear, but others will. On a
Ravens pass, wide receiver Billy Davis was ruled to have caught the
ball out of bounds because his left foot came down on the chalked
sideline. When the Ravens challenged the call, Luckett reversed it
_ incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original call should have stood,'' Seeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jets, wide receiver Ike Hilliard of the Giants
fumbled out of bounds in front of the Jets' bench. Coach Bill
Parcells made his only preseason challenge, claiming that Jets
safety Chris Hayes had recovered the ball in bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Gerald Austin upheld Parcells' challenge _ incorrectly.
As Hayes recovered the fumble with one hand, his other hand was
discovered later to have been out of bounds. Austin did not notice
that.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jim Fassel, the Giants' coach, the downfield
official who made the original out-of-bounds call was never
consulted by Austin before the referee stuck his head inside the
video-replay flap on the field monitor _ a zebra suddenly turned
ostrich.
</P>
<P>
   To exterminate that bug, the NFL should have both the official
who made the challenged call and the referee peer at the replay on
the field monitor. Let the other official see it again.
</P>
<P>
   Other bugs will surely surface, but Parcells had a thought on
the new system that has created an upstairs booth with a replay
assistant, a video operator, a technician and a communicator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we don't hear the ballcarrier was down by contact,
the whistle blew,'' the Jets' coach said. ``That's what ruined this
thing the last time. Just let 'em play. In professional football,
the play kills itself. You see spearing, you call it, but you can
officiate the game without a quick whistle. That's the only thing
I'm hoping for because then the system loses credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   As it will if the Replay Bugs are not exterminated quickly,
beginning Sunday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-VIKINGS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-11 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSS PREPARING TO DANCE THROUGH THE SPECIAL ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Jets cornerback Aaron Glenn who got an
up-close-and-personal look at the next step in the evolution of a
superstar. Before Glenn's eyes, Randy Moss, the Minnesota Vikings
wide receiver, departed from his one-dimensional realm of being
only a deep threat.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation happened last season when the Jets played the
Vikings at Giants Stadium on Sept. 3. Moss was lined up on the far
right side of the field against man-to-man coverage by Glenn. Moss'
pattern was simple. He took a few quick steps forward, then sliced
inside, leaving Glenn in his wake. The play gained 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is one of the quickest cornerbacks in the National
Football League, but the move Moss made was done with such
aggression, skill, and grace. That kind of footwork usually takes
three or four years to develop. After one season in the league,
Moss has those dance steps down.
</P>
<P>
   A few plays later, Moss ran a 10-yard crossing pattern against
the cornerback Victor Green, smartly using a game official as a
shield. It was yet another veteran move.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot I have to learn,'' Moss said, ``and I'm
learning it pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he is. It's not that Moss never ran those kinds of patterns
as a rookie last season, because he did. He just did not do them as
well. He did not need to. His speed ruled. He had 69 catches for
1,313 yards and single-handedly changed the Vikings from a good
team into a great one that went 15-1 and failed to go to the Super
Bowl by a missed field goal. He so frightened the division rival
Green Bay that three of the Packers' first four picks in last
April's draft were defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings realized what they had and milked it as any good
team would. Why have him run a bunch of crossing patterns when he
can destroy a team's psyche with two deep touchdown catches?
</P>
<P>
   But even the most talented speedsters need to develop a total
game. And clearly that is what Moss has done. It is comparable to
when Michael Jordan developed an outside game to go along with his
inside skills.
</P>
<P>
   Moss spent much of the off season and training camp working on
his skills at running pass routes. In addition to going down field
like a gold-medal sprinter, he can now run a great post pattern, or
crossing route, or down and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy already had great moves last year but, yes, we're
emphasizing some of that more this season,'' said Vikings Coach
Denny Green. ``This season people will see that Randy is more than
just a deep threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The receiver's biggest challenge? ``I think staying healthy,''
Green said, ``because it's going to be real physical. Guys are
going to bang him and bump him more. He's going to have more people
coming after him because they know he can make a big play so he's
going to have to keep his mental edge.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, every time Moss makes a play, he can expect
tacklers to give him a brutal hit, or a shot to the ribs, a punch
or a twist of his ankle. It happened to Jerry Rice. It will happen
to Moss.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Vikings will be to find creative ways to
get Moss the ball. Moss is going to be the focus of every defensive
coordinator opposing the Vikings. One series, Moss might face a
double-team. The next series, he might draw single coverage from a
team's best defensive back. He could see triple coverage. He could
see Mel Blount coming out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Moss questioned whether his team had the same desire
it had last season. He expressed disappointment in the Vikings'
lackluster preseason and the poor play of the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of shocked me, to be honest with you, to see as far as
the veteran group of guys we got playing the offensive line,'' Moss
said last week. ``You know, they made some mistakes during the
preseason. And we all made mistakes. I made some during preseason.
You know, I think even Coach Green made some during the preseason.
So its just not the guys on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Moss is taking a leadership role in just his second
season, putting as much pressure on himself as others.
</P>
<P>
   It is always interesting to watch the NFL replenish itself. When
one superstar leaves or ages, another steps in his place. Rice has
only a short time left before he retires and goes into the Hall of
Fame. Here comes Moss, a more complete Moss, who has a chance to be
just as good.
</P>
<P>
   How close Moss gets to Rice's greatness is largely up to Moss.
It certainly does not hurt Moss that his repertory of moves has
expanded. And the Vikings' chances of getting a championship have
grown right along with him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
