<HEADER>
A8330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-BRONCOS-NYT &LR;      09-11 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS EARLY, BUT THE CHAMPS LOOK BEATABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two straight Super Bowl victories, trademark offense, glimmering
endorsements and a striking transformation from being that team in
the mountains with the funky orange jerseys to becoming the
football franchise by which all others are judged _ yes, everyone
in Denver agrees: Life with the Broncos is so royal, so regal.
</P>
<P>
   Fire up that Jacuzzi. Sip another glass of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Wait! The plug has been pulled. The bottle dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Star quarterback John Elway retires after January's Super Bowl.
Linebacker John Mobley drives his Jeep off the road and is slapped
with a charge of driving under the influence. Elway's successor,
Bubby Brister, is benched and walks out of camp. Brian Griese, who
has thrown all of three regular-season passes, is named the
starting quarterback. Bill Romanowski is accused of fraudulently
obtaining prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   All before the first regular-season snap against Miami Monday
night at home in Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   No Elway, plus controversies like these, further reduces the
chance that the Broncos will become the first team to win three
consecutive Super Bowls. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``People around here have had it pretty good, and there has been
little controversy here in the last couple of years,'' Broncos
Coach Mike Shanahan said. ``So, what's wrong with that now? It can
be good. I'm not trying to create it. But I embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take our quarterback position. I made my decision based on
minicamps, preseason games, practices and summer camp. Bubby is
better coming off the bench. Brian quickly came up. Now, I could
have done it the easy way. I could have let Bubby start, just play
the whole thing out, but that was not best for our football team.
Our players don't know the position like I do. As far as Bubby or
any of them, I'm not trying to be popular. I'm doing it for the
team. I told Bubby that if he could not accept it, if he couldn't
work with me, let me know so I could trade him. None of this
bothers me. What bothers me is not winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Every team in the National Football League is coming after the
Broncos now, full steam, especially the Jets from the American
Football Conference East Division and Jacksonville from the AFC
Central. National Football Conference powers on the Denver schedule
this season include Green Bay and Minnesota. It is open season on
the Broncos. Shanahan knows he and his team are the hunted.
</P>
<P>
   So, rather than quiver or shake, Shanahan shook up his team. The
initial results were promising. After a relatively listless
preseason, Denver's final preseason game was a 34-3 rout of San
Francisco in Griese's debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw guys finishing plays,'' the veteran Broncos end Alfred
Williams said of the game. ``I saw guys turning it on. That's what
we'll have to do to defy the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Ominous odds. Remaining energized and eager after consecutive
championships. Winning with a first-time starting quarterback who
is only 24. Replacing the leadership and playmaking of Elway.
Handling controversy. Meeting the league-wide, full-court press of
attention and competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not paying attention, rest assured that everyone
else is,'' Pat Bowlen, the Broncos' owner, said. ``When you're up,
you're not well liked. I know that because for the last 10 years, I
respected the 49ers and the Cowboys but I didn't like them much. We
lost our first three Super Bowls. They both won two straight.
That's where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Griese.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan liked him from the start. He drafted Griese from
Michigan in the third round of the 1998 draft. The trait he admires
most about Griese is his intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wunderlich test is given to players in the draft,''
Shanahan said. ``An average score is 15 to 20. A real smart
quarterback scores a 28. Brian scored a 39. He has picked up the
offense in total better than any quarterback I have been around.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shanahan has coached not only Elway, but also Joe Montana
and Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a coolness and calmness and great poise there,''
Shanahan said of Griese. ``At Michigan, he went undefeated his
senior season and won the national championship. Now, that wasn't a
great offensive team he played on; how many of those players are
star pro guys now? And given that he is the son of Bob Griese and
his dad is a Hall of Fame quarterback, you put a kid around a man
like that and it has to be an infectious environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Blah, blah, said Brister. He thought the starting job was his
because Shanahan anointed him as Elway's replacement soon after the
Super Bowl. And Brister believed the job was his to lose during the
regular season, not the preseason, although Brister led the Broncos
to just one touchdown on 18 offensive possessions in the preseason.
The number that mattered, Brister said, was that he was 4-0 as a
regular-season starter when Elway was injured.
</P>
<P>
   But Shanahan and Bowlen believed Brister was crumbling under the
pressure of replacing Elway. The grind, the baggage and the
responsibility seemed ``overwhelming, stifling and near
impossible'' for Brister, Bowlen said. ``If Brian had carried that
baggage for four months, I don't know if we would be talking about
him being the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Brister, initially emotional, said Shanahan had lied to him and
had made an unjust decision. Things have calmed, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine that there are guys on this team that I have
to win over and earn their respect because they wanted Bubby to be
the starter,'' Griese said. ``But I am more concerned about not
rushing things and being myself. I don't do a lot of talking.
People have compared my game to my father's, but I was 5 years old
when he retired. They say I play a lot like him, but it is not
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is getting this offense to score touchdowns; that's
how quarterbacks should be judged. I saw the relationship,
friendship, respect and trust that Mike and John had for each
other. That's the kind of trust that leads you to the Super Bowl. I
don't have to have the same kind of friendship. But I like being in
the game and knowing how my coach calls a game. I like to get into
his head and be able to anticipate what the next play call will be.
That's the kind of relationship that wins championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Williams said of Griese: ``He's so young. Miami is going
to bring the house against him. But I still see a party
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   A seasonlong party, Denver hopes, even with Romanowski's
situation hovering. Local and federal authorities are recommending
that he, his wife, Julie, and two others be charged for allegedly
using fraud to obtain prescriptions used for the drug Phentamine.
It is primarily used for severe cases of obesity but is also a
stimulant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing has no legs,'' Bowlen said. ``I'm in the
weight room with our players. We had 45 guys make 100 percent of
all off-season workouts and the rest made more than 80 percent. It
is a part of our program we emphasize. I'd have to be deaf and
blind to not know there was some serious drug abuse going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Broncos ``deaf and blind'' about a first-time starter at
quarterback possibly winning a Super Bowl? About the drug charge
and controversy eventually swallowing them? That they are on the
verge of possibly being embarrassed?
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan believes his offensive line is improved. That
sensational running back Terrell Davis can produce even more. The
defense added a star in Dale Carter from Kansas City, one of the
league's premier single-cover cornerbacks. Shanahan expects more
from his defense, especially until Griese finds his way. He said
this team is his deepest, even without Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prepare and get mentally connected or we are going
to get embarrassed,'' he said, his eyes full of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy? Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NATIONAL-3TAKES-N     09-11 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NATIONAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS, VIKINGS, 49ERS PICKS IN NFC 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: Teams are profiled in order of predicted finish
</P>
<P>
   NFC EAST
</P>
<P>
   1. Giants &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  Against Baltimore in the preseason, Michael Strahan
made crushing sacks of quarterback Tony Banks on back-to-back
plays. After one, he looked toward the Baltimore sideline and made
a face as if to say, ``No one can stop me.'' Like last season, when
Strahan recorded 15 sacks, the towering defensive end will be
unstoppable, as will linebacker Jessie Armstead. Despite questions
about when cornerback Jason Sehorn will return from his hamstring
injury, the Giants still have one of the top five defenses in the
league. That will be enough for them to win one of the weaker
divisions in football.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The offensive line will either be really good or
really bad. The only truly stable player is tackle Roman Oben, who
could have a Pro Bowl season. The rest is a toss-up. Who knows how
long center Brian Williams will hold up? And depth is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  Quarterback Kent Graham will have a big year and
Coach Jim Fassel, a smart coach, will finally unleash all of his
offensive plays because of his confidence in Graham. The receiving
group of Amani Toomer, Ike Hilliard and Joe Jurevicius is solid.
</P>
<P>
   2. DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 10-6, division champion
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  The old men are still hanging around. Quarterback
Troy Aikman, wide receiver Michael Irvin and running back Emmitt
Smith still have enough _ barely enough _ to win nine games. They
remain the center of the franchise. Larry Allen, the best offensive
lineman in football, will protect Aikman, and wide receiver Raghib
Ismail provides a legitimate deep threat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The Cowboys still can't stop the run. They gave up
101.2 yards a game on the ground last season, and this year
defensive lineman Leon Lett, a great run stopper, is out at least
four games because of a drug suspension.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The division race will come down to the Giants and
the Cowboys. The Cowboys will finish second because of their age.
Football is a young man's game and the Giants have more
20-something talents.
</P>
<P>
   3. ARIZONA
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 9-7, wild-card team
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  There may be no more exciting quarterback to watch
than Jake Plummer. Last season, he threw for 3,737 yards and 17
touchdowns, and his savvy and ability to escape drew comparisons to
Joe Montana. Plummer is the real deal. He doesn't have the strong
arm of Kent Graham, the veteran smarts of Troy Aikman, or the
supporting cast of Brett Favre, but he is the next star quarterback
in the NFL. Plummer alone gives the Cardinals a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  After the Cardinals went 9-7 and upset Dallas in
the first round of the playoffs last season, many in the league
thought Arizona was on its way to a great season this year. But
these are the Cardinals; they don't know how to handle prosperity.
This past off season they had a series of contract disputes, and
the team did little in free agency to upgrade itself. Arizona's
biggest problem is its own history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  Because of Plummer, Arizona is capable of winning
nine games. Because these are the Cardinals, they won't.
</P>
<P>
   4. WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  The Redskins have been in a desperate funk under
Coach Norv Turner, whose record in Washington is 32-47-1. Knowing
that the team's biggest weakness was at quarterback, the Redskins
traded with the Minnesota Vikings for Brad Johnson. In training
camp this year, Johnson has had some injuries, but when healthy he
has shown the kind of poise and accuracy he did with the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  There are potential problems everywhere. Defensive
linemen Dana Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson have been total busts.
There is little talent at running back. And so far Turner has not
shown that he is capable of being a top head coach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  Turner won a power struggle with the former general
manager, Charley Casserly, when the new owner, Daniel Snyder, sided
with the head coach. Now Turner has no one to blame but himself for
what is very likely to be an ordinary season.
</P>
<P>
   5. PHILADELPHIA
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 3-13
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  There is only one bright spot for what is certain
to be one of the worst franchises in sports in the next year, and
it is the rookie quarterback Donovan McNabb. In just a few
preseason games, McNabb has shown a flair and understanding of the
game that few rookies show immediately. He resembles Peyton Manning
in some ways, only he is more athletic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  No stars on defense. A terrible offensive line. No
wide receivers or a running game. Other than that, the Eagles are
fine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Eagles are going to win three games this year,
and the fans at Veterans Stadium, who have booed Santa Claus, will
have lots of fodder this season. The Eagles players are already
grumbling privately about whether the rookie coach, Andy Reid, has
the right stuff. This could be an ugly season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC East Player to Watch: Kent Graham, quarterback, Giants  &LR; 
There is no more motivated player in the NFL than Graham. He knows
the front office does not believe in him. He knows that many
members of the news media are waiting for him to fail. None of that
has distracted him.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has always been mentally tough, buoyed by his strong (and
private) religious beliefs and support from his family. After an
off season of intense preparation, which included showing up at
Giants Stadium before six in the morning to watch game film, Graham
is ready to have a big year. In fact, he could explode. His coach
supports him. His teammates do as well. And, for probably the first
time in his professional career, Graham has a complete offense
around him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NFC CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   1. MINNESOTA
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 15-1, division champion
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  In some ways what the Vikings did last season _
breaking every scoring record known to man _ has become a burden.
Everyone expects Minnesota to match that performance. That will
probably be impossible. Still, Coach Dennis Green, one of the
smartest in the business, is keeping expectations high, constantly
reminding the players that any letdown can lead to mediocrity. The
offense should also benefit from Green's becoming more involved in
the play-calling. The Vikings may have had a mediocre preseason
(2-2 record, outscored by 104-79), but with quarterback Randall
Cunningham, wide receivers Cris Carter and Randy Moss and running
back Robert Smith, they still have the best group of offensive
players in football.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  As the Jets showed against Minnesota in the final
preseason game, teams can still move the ball against the Vikings
in large chunks. But this team has few holes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Vikings are still the team to beat in the
division and a Super Bowl contender.
</P>
<P>
   2. GREEN BAY
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 11-5, wild-card team
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  Like Minnesota, the Packers possess a dazzling
offense, led by quarterback Brett Favre, who hasn't looked this
sharp in three or four years. General Manager Ron Wolf has done a
good job of keeping the team intact and even adding depth. His best
move was making sure wide receiver Antonio Freeman was locked up to
a long-term contract. Defensive end Vonnie Holiday is making the
Packers forget about Reggie White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The secondary is still vulnerable despite the
addition of several defensive backs via the draft. Safety LeRoy
Butler is in his 10th year and is a soft spot in coverage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Packers could easily make it to the Super Bowl
except for one problem: Green Bay still has no way of preventing
Moss from dominating.
</P>
<P>
   3. TAMPA BAY
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  The running game, led by Warrick Dunn and Mike
Alstott, remains one of the best. Last year, they combined to rush
for 1,872 yards and 10 touchdowns. Defensive end Warren Sapp vows
to take the Buccaneers to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  Two words: Trent Dilfer. He has supposedly
improved his game. He is supposedly more consistent. Blah, blah,
blah. Dilfer is Dilfer. As long as he is the quarterback, Tampa Bay
will most likely never be great.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Buccaneers, because of their defense and running
game, are a 10-victory team in a tough division. How far they go in
the playoffs depends on Dilfer. He has always been Tampa Bay's weak
link, a defensive coordinator's dream, and the only way the
Buccaneers will become a serious threat is if Dilfer sheds his
mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   4. DETROIT &QL; 
1998 Record: 5-11
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  No Scott Mitchell, for one. He was dumped into the
hands of Baltimore. The team still has good wide receivers in
Herman Moore and Johnnie Morton. Charlie Batch is a good young
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  Running back Barry Sanders will be watching
football games this season instead of playing for the Lions. The
team has no running game whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  Without Sanders, the Lions are a team likely to win
five games. Coach Bobby Ross had made them more competitive over
all, but the organization needs to take a hard look at how it came
to be that Sanders is no longer there. Losing him is one of the
biggest personnel blunders this decade.
</P>
<P>
   5. CHICAGO
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 4-12
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  A team with two consecutive seasons with four
victories has no strengths. Quarterback Cade McNown, Chicago's
first pick in the draft, has shown promise in training camp and
might start by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The Bears have a large gap in talent. Last season,
teams averaged 318 yards a game against them, and that might go up
this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Bears are again destined to finish as one of the
worst teams in the league. They are a long way from the days when
George Halas or Mike Ditka was running the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC Central Player to Watch: Brett Favre, quarterback, Packers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason the Packers feel they can get back to the
Super Bowl is because of their strong-armed quarterback. He showed
up to training camp at 214 pounds, some 20 less than his playing
weight in 1998. To Green Bay, that is a positive omen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in great shape,'' said the offensive coordinator, Sherman
Lewis. ``The last time he was in great shape like this was 1996,
the year we won the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Packers' Super Bowl victory, Favre admitted an
addiction to painkilling medication. He was also known as a serious
drinker. Since then, Favre has had no known further addiction
problems and stays away from alcohol. His conditioning and attitude
are the best they have been in years. For opponents, that is a
scary thought.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NFC WEST
</P>
<P>
   1. SAN FRANCISCO
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 12-4, wild-card team
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  A loaded offense. With Steve Young at quarterback
and Jerry Rice, Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes at wide receiver, the
49ers are formidable. Lawrence Phillips, if he stays out of
trouble, adds depth at running back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The first chunk of San Francisco's schedule is
interesting: the opener at Jacksonville, followed by games against
New Orleans, Arizona, Tennessee, St. Louis, Carolina and Minnesota.
If the 49ers aren't careful, they could end up winning only three
of those games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The 49ers can never sneak up on anyone. But everyone
expects Atlanta to win the division, and that will help the 49ers.
San Francisco still believes it is the class of the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   2. ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 14-2, division champion
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  Jamal Anderson is a smart, bruising back. He ran
the ball an NFL-record 410 times last year. He may have more
carries this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The key for Atlanta last year was that the
once-brittle quarterback, Chris Chandler, stayed healthy for most
of the season. The chances of his doing that in consecutive seasons
are slim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Falcons made a crucial mistake when they released
wide receiver Tony Martin (he is now in Miami). His replacement is
the former Giants wide receiver Chris Calloway _ a solid player but
excruciatingly slow. It can't be underestimated how much Martin's
speed _ and his 66 catches _ meant to the Atlanta offense. He
scared teams. Now, Anderson is sure to see more eight- and nine-man
fronts. The Falcons are still a team good for 11 or 12 victories.
</P>
<P>
   3. NEW ORLEANS
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  Ricky Williams put a scare into the organization
when he went down with an ankle injury in the preseason. Suddenly,
the idea of trading away the entire draft did not seem like such a
good idea. But Williams turned out to be fine and will start the
season opener against St. Louis. So far the trade was a good idea,
as Williams is a powerful runner who will keep the pressure off of
the Saints' weak passing game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The two Billy Joes, Tolliver and Hobert. Neither
can play a lick.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Saints are interesting to watch. If Williams is
good _ and so far he looks like a big-time player _ they could
sneak into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   4. ST. LOUIS
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 4-12
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  Trading for Marshall Faulk was a smart move that
will provide the Rams some much-needed offense. For the
Indianapolis Colts last year, Faulk had 1,319 yards rushing and 908
yards receiving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The Rams are still a terrible defensive team,
especially against the run.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  When quarterback Trent Green blew out his knee in the
final preseason game, any chance of the Rams' making the playoffs
disappeared. Teams will design their game plans to stop Faulk
because he is St. Louis' only true offensive threat.
</P>
<P>
   5. CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 4-12
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRENGTHS: &LR;  Tshimanga Biakabutuka is a solid runner. Fullback
William Floyd is a good blocker. Wide receiver Muhsin Muhammad
provides a deep threat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEAKNESSES: &LR;  The new coach, George Seifert, is putting in an
entirely new defensive system, and it will take time for the team
to adapt. Quarterback Steve Beuerlein is mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTLOOK: &LR;  The Panthers are years from having the talent to
compete seriously for the division title.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC WEST PLAYER TO WATCH: Jamal Anderson, running back,
Falcons &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the most talkative and friendly players in
professional football, and he is a leader on the Falcons. This is a
crucial season for Anderson. He is coming off a contract holdout
that sometimes got bitter and tested his relationship with Coach
Dan Reeves and his teammates. All are said to be fine with
Anderson, however.
</P>
<P>
   It will not take long to find out how true that is. Anderson
will be tested, mentally and physically, more than ever. Reeves
will surely call his number again and again, and Anderson will at
times feel like he is 70 years old.
</P>
<P>
   How well Anderson holds up is the key to Atlanta's season.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
