<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS CONTINUE THEIR MATURATION PROCESS FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On several levels, there are signs the 1999 National Football
League season will be the most pivotal one for the Giants franchise
since the team's 1990 Super Bowl season.
</P>
<P>
   If the team digresses from last year's 8-8 record, and
especially if the Giants have a disastrous season, there could be a
new head coach and a search for a new quarterback. In that case,
there would be a new offensive system, new assistant coaches, an
entirely new direction, and probably, plenty of soul-searching
about whether the Giants basic operating football philosophy needs
an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   It would mean the fourth coaching makeover in eight years, and
that's a lot of instability for a team wedded to constancy.
</P>
<P>
   But if this Giants season is a winning one, the picture changes
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It is a certainty that Coach Jim Fassel would get a contract
extension. A big part of the quarterback situation would have been
resolved. A belief in the Giants' methods of building a team
through the draft and a new, if limited, enthusiasm for free agency
would be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   The regime of General Manager Ernie Accorsi, which began a year
ago, would be off to a sterling start. With a contract extension,
Fassel would be chasing Bill Parcells and Allie Sherman, both of
whom were with the team eight years, for the longest Giants head
coaching term in the last 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot to rest on one season, a season which begins with a
difficult road game against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   If all this pressure is wearing on Fassel, he isn't showing it.
Always driven and meticulous to every detail, Fassel is nonetheless
visibly more relaxed this year than in the two previous seasons.
Friday, he said the stakes of this season as they relate to his own
status or personal gain have not crossed his mind for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about any of that,'' said Fassel, standing
outside the team's locker room. ``I've never worried about a job in
my life. If you're thinking about those things, you're not thinking
about the things that matter in your job, which is how you're going
to be judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big year, I know that. We have to win. But I don't
think anybody can put more pressure on me than me. I have more
confidence this team will perform at a higher level than any other
team I've had here.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi would not talk about the possibilities in a worst-case
scenario for his team, but he emphatically endorsed Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great degree of respect and affection for Jim
throughout the organization,'' Accorsi said. ``From ownership on
down, including me personally. It's a good working relationship
that we expect to be a long one.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel is confident the Giants are on the cusp of a breakthrough
season. Indeed, he might already have a contract extension, except
that Fassel told friends he was willing to gamble that his
negotiating leverage would be even better after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel believes the 1999 Giants have matured, with more veteran
players in key leadership roles like quarterback Kent Graham, who
is 30 years old, linebacker Jessie Armstead, who turns 29 next
month, and defensive end Michael Strahan, a 27-year-old beginning
his sixth season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, the Giants have been the youngest team
in the league. It was once a badge of honor. By last season, it was
more often the excuse for the team's stumbles and missteps. Fassel
and his players don't want to hear about their youth anymore. They
want to hear about how they are beginning to play as a seasoned
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year I was here, we were battling a lot of things -
a lack of confidence mostly,'' Fassel said. ``I didn't know how far
we were going, but we were building. The second year, I sensed we
might be misreading our growth and where we were, that we were too
overconfident. I tried to change that. It was tough to take, but we
got through it. This year, I see us understanding what it takes
mentally more than ever. And I think we acquired better players.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those players: Kerry Collins, an immensely talented backup
quarterback; tight end Pete Mitchell, a skilled pass catcher who
could be the team's leading receiver; center Brian Williams, the
emotional leader of the offensive line who is back after two years
sidelined with an eye injury; and the surprising rookie running
back Sean Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   The team's defense will again be a strength and should be good
enough to keep them in most games. Fassel has promised that the
offense would keep its daring and unpredictable preseason look. If
they pull the reins in as they have in other years, they could well
be doomed. National Football League defenses feast on the timid.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Giants contend there is a new attitude to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are fed up,'' Strahan said, describing his teammates.
``Last year, we had too many guys who were content. I want to win
now, I'm fed up with waiting, and I got plenty of guys with me.
</P>
<P>
   `` That's a bad mood to be in and that's nothing but good for
us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
