<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-11 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE IS SUCCESSFUL BEING LESS THAN PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde had gone through the batch of newspaper
clippings prepared each day for the Jets' front office. Now, he
looked at the cover sheet, which had a little saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some pursue happiness,'' the Jets quarterback read. ``Others
create it.''
</P>
<P>
   From the time almost 30 years ago when he tacked a poster of Joe
Namath onto his bedroom wall and imagined himself leading the Jets
to the Super Bowl, Testaverde has created his own happiness. And
now, in the funny way sports sometimes works, Testaverde has
created a spectacular situation by being less than perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped thinking about a perfect game last year,'' he said.
``I think about what Coach said. It's getting my job done. If
there's no play, you throw it away _ rather than taking a sack or
throwing an interception.''
</P>
<P>
   So he admits it is a more patient Testaverde, a Testaverde
content with doing less who leads the Jets Sunday against the
Patriots in the opener of a season many people believe will
continue until the end of January and the Super Bowl in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Testaverde has always been able to maintain
confidence in his own ability. In the uncertain world of
quarterbacks, it helps. Testaverde did it through the
interception-plagued years with Tampa Bay; he did it in Cleveland
when the fans wanted the prodigal son Bernie Kosar, and he did it
in Baltimore when, at the end, they demanded someone younger. That
confidence was not always rewarded in performance.
</P>
<P>
   In a pro career going back to 1987, Testaverde had never
finished a season among the top eight quarterbacks in any major
category _ touchdowns, fewest interceptions, yardage, completion
percentage. And not, certainly, in victories. As a starter, he had
a won-lost percentage of 36.7.
</P>
<P>
   So when Testaverde became a Jet last season, the wise, yet
cynical, Boomer Esiason _ another Long Islander who had been a
Jets' quarterback and can laugh about it _ telephoned him
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Boomer saying, `The Jets?''' Testaverde chuckled at
the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Boomer told me, `It's a double-edged sword. You win, it's
twice as good. You lose, it's twice as bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   What was it, then, when the Jets surged to 12-1 with Testaverde
starting? When he produced in the clutch: 10 touchdowns, no
interceptions, a completion percentage of 62.9 on third downs? When
Testaverde threw an astounding 29 touchdowns and a mere 7
interceptions and the Jets came within two or three dropped balls
of going to the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   It was ``the magical season,'' as Testaverde calls it.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers heaped respect on Testaverde, burnishing the
appealing hometown boy-makes-good story, and helped make the Jets'
offense one of the most dangerous in the NFL. And now the Jets are
American Conference East Division favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has come a long way. Through the bad years _
including six Tampa Bay seasons that never produced a record better
than 6-10 _ he remained the dogged competitor his father, Al
Testaverde, taught him to be. ``Vinny, if you're going to throw a
football, throw it as hard as you can,'' insisted Big Al, who died
last February. ``Whatever you do, don't do it half-speed. Learn as
much as you can about everything you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Testaverde might have learned losing, he never gave up.
And he always threw the ball hard. Sometimes too hard, too often.
</P>
<P>
   But last year something happened to the way Testaverde
approaches football, and that altered how he approaches life, he
says. He began to let the game come to him.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde was looking for work 14 months ago. He was a free
agent and the Jets were in need of a back-up to Glenn Foley.
Luckily for Testaverde, he had a history with some key Jets'
people-Bill Belichick, the defensive mastermind who, as head coach
in 1993, had brought Testaverde to Cleveland, and suffered the
wrath of the Dog Pounders by benching the beloved home-town boy
Kosar. And Scott Pioli, who had been Cleveland's personnel guru,
was now doing the same with the Jets. Both told Parcells about
Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   The new quarterbacks' coach, Dan Henning, also was in
Testaverde's corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got out of college,'' explained Henning, ``he went
with a team that was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioli, meanwhile, knew this telling statistic: In Testaverde's
career, he had been blessed with a 1,000-yard rusher in only one
season, the journeyman Reggie Cobb who did it at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   When he signed Testaverde in June 1998, Coach Bill Parcells knew
that the quarterback's career had been split in two. Since leaving
Tampa Bay in 1993, he had tossed 98 touchdowns to only 71
interceptions. He had gone to a Pro Bowl with Baltimore. Too many
people, however, remembered him for those horrid Tampa Bay
statistics: 77 touchdowns, 112 interceptions. Too few people knew
that in only one season of his 12-year pro career had Testaverde
been blessed with a 1,000-yard rusher, the journeyman Reggie Cobb
with Tampa Bay in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Vinny, `When you've been in trouble is when you started
to run with the ball and tried to make something happen,'''
Parcells said. ``I told him, `You don't worry about anything but
the passing game. We'll run the ball for you. We've got weapons for
you. Don't try to make things happen yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had an outstanding preseason, but Glenn Foley had an
equally strong showing and he started the year at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   It was a frustrating time for the Testaverdes. Once, Al
Testaverde, after watching his son take command of a practice,
looking more imposing at 6 feet 5 inches and 235 pounds than most
of his teammates, asked: ``Why don't they use my boy? Don't you
think he's better than Glenn?''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Parcells came to that conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But only after the coach had deprogrammed Testaverde of early
training that had encouraged him to take everything upon himself.
Testaverde recently reflected again on his changed approach to the
game. ``I think Bill's pretty accurate talking about what happened
when I got in trouble in the past. When I got out of the pocket
I've made bad mistakes on the run. If there's a wide receiver open,
get it to him. But if you have to scramble, throw it away.'' And
then Testaverde added, looking to his left, ``Don't throw it across
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   He realizes now that his progress as a pro quarterback was
delayed by his earlier successes: from a legendary high school
career, to Heisman Trophy winner at Miami, which led to his
selection as the overall No.1 draft pick with one of the sport's
worst franchises, Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for four coaches in six years with the Buccaneers,
Testaverde tried to do it all, whatever the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think early on, that's what my problem was,'' he said. ``I
thought I could throw on anybody. What's ingrained in me now is
there's nothing wrong with punting on fourth down. It's worse to
throw an interception on third down. If a play didn't work in past
years, I'd think, why didn't they run my play? When you start
thinking too many things, it clouds your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He rarely sounds bitter about the early years, but he does say,
with some pride, ``If I was that bad, would I have lasted that
long? Look who was quarterbacking before me at Tampa Bay: Doug
Williams, Steve Young, Steve DeBerg. All went elsewhere as backups,
and two of them led their teams to Super Bowls. I cannot allow
people to make me perform differently because of their
perceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   When he breaks the huddle Sunday, he said he will worry about no
one's responsibilities but his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to worry ... would the guard pick up the blitz? I don't
worry about it. That's not my job description. It's freed up a lot
of space in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has freed him of hometown doubts, but not of the burden
of hometown expectations. When asked how he would now respond to
Esiason's wry view of playing quarterback for the Jets, Testaverde
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right,'' he replied. ``It's twice as good. But I'm
going to say that with a lot of hesitation.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 0947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
