<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SEASON-ART-2TAKES     09-11 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEASON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENT APLENTY FOR MIGHT BE MASTERLY COACH'S LAST STAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The signs are everywhere, littered about like clues in a
mystery. In a league crammed with a half-dozen legitimate Super
Bowl contenders that could make this one of the most riveting
seasons in years, it is Jets Coach Bill Parcells _ his team and his
future _ at the center of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are this year's team of intrigue, mainly because of
their brilliant, intense and manipulative head coach. Parcells
appears to be preparing for one final, grand run at a National
Football League championship. After making several astute personnel
moves over the past few years _ the signing of running back Curtis
Martin, rejuvenating the careers of quarterback Vinny Testaverde
and linebacker Bryan Cox, and snagging the Pro Bowl safety Steve
Atwater from Denver _ Parcells has positioned the Jets at the brink
of something special.
</P>
<P>
   They will have serious competition. The Broncos are the two-time
defending champions and have the best running back in football in
Terrell Davis, Minnesota has a devastating offense led by wide
receiver Randy Moss, and Jacksonville could easily win at least 12
games. Yet it is the Jets who have the best of everything: balance
on offense, a solid defense and the best coaching staff in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and his team will have to deal with high expectations,
injuries to key players and edginess about the new instant-replay
system. But the Jets also face a unique set of problems. The team
is for sale and the head coach may be on his way out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells will not publicly discuss his future, but there are two
prominent signs that he could be making his last stand. First,
contrary to his strong public denials, Parcells is closely involved
with an undisclosed group to buy the Jets, according to a league
official. NFL rules prevent an owner from coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Parcells is working on another book, this one detailing
his experiences with the Jets. The last time Parcells wrote a
football book was in 1987, when he penned his autobiography the
same year he led the Giants to a victory in Super Bowl XXI. The
Jets hope that is an omen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, figuring out what Parcells will do is like trying to
decipher a Bill Belichick defense, which is almost impossible. So
there are as many opinions on Parcells' future as harsh words used
by Denver's Bubby Brister after learning he was being demoted as
the starting quarterback in favor of Brian Griese.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to guess, I would say this is his last year,'' said
John Madden, the Fox analyst, who knows Parcells well. ``He's a
great coach and he's done it all. He won when he was here with the
Giants. He won in New England. He has won back here with the Jets,
and he is probably thinking there is little else for him to do as a
coach. There were rumors before this season that this would be his
last one, and that was before the ownership situation. If that
situation is not right, then he will definitely be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who also played for Parcells in New England, said:
``Bill is so unpredictable, you never know what Bill is going to
do. Bill might coach for four more years, or Bill might stop
coaching at the end of this season. I don't even try to figure him
out. Sometimes it seems there is no rhyme to his reason. You're
asking me to get inside his mind. I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a handle on this season might be equally as difficult
because so many teams have a chance to be special.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When quarterback John Elway made his teary goodbye from the
Broncos this summer, no one had any idea what occur in his wake.
Because of Brister's poor performance in the preseason, the
uncertainty surrounding the second-year quarterback Griese, and the
burden of knowing that no team has won three consecutive Super
Bowls, the Broncos are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of teams peruse the league, see no clear favorite, glance
in the mirror and say: ``There is no reason we can't win this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, the Vikings are still angry at losing the
conference title game to Atlanta and vow a Super Bowl run, as do
the Falcons, led by running back Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jimmy Johnson thinks his Miami Dolphins, after adding the
controversial runner Cecil Collins (once accused of attacking a
female student while he was at Louisiana State) and wide receiver
Tony Martin (recently acquitted of Federal money-laundering
charges), have one of the most potent offenses in football. Johnson
is another coach who could retire after this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this team a lot,'' he said. ``Anyone who looks at us
and doesn't think we're capable of winning a lot of games is making
a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville added the best defensive back in the game, Carnell
Lake, to boost its defense, but it is the Jaguars' offense, sparked
by quarterback Mark Brunell, that makes them so formidable.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos still feel good about their team despite a
quarterback controversy and the possibility that linebacker Bill
Romanowski could face felony charges and NFL suspension. He has
been accused of illegally obtaining a prescription drug.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams could spring surprises. Green Bay quarterback Brett
Favre lost 20 pounds in the off season and the Packers added 200
pounds of intensity in Ray Rhodes, their new coach. The Giants may
have the best defense in the league, which should help their
chances of capturing the weak NFC East. In Buffalo, quarterback
Doug Flutie, the scrambling little man, has proven he can lead the
Bills to the post-season, a place where Peyton Manning, a
second-year player who is the next great quarterback, might land
his Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL hasn't seen a situation like this in quite some time: no
dominant team. No single group of superstars, which Dallas had in
the early 1990s. The door to a championship is wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree this is going to be an exciting season,'' Madden said.
``A lot of the division races might go down to the final week.
Right now it is really hard to pick one team and say, `That team is
the one.'''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be difficult to peg a favorite, it is not hard to
see which team has prepared hardest for this moment. Parcells has
built the Jets, player by player, to make a run now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be true, we may be ready now,'' Testaverde said.
``This could be a special year, but we have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Parcells was named coach of the Jets before the 1997
season, it did not take long for his strong will to infect a
demoralized franchise. Parcells brought in coaches and players who
would follow his orders without question. Many of them, like
Martin, were talented, expensive veterans, and it quickly became
apparent that Parcells was not building for the long term, but for
immediate success.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Parcells came within one half of reaching the Super
Bowl, but the Jets disintegrated against Denver late in the AFC
title game at Mile High Stadium. The way the Jets lost left
Parcells with a bitter feeling. He was not used to seeing a team of
his fall apart at such a critical time in a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells knew the Jets were where he wanted them and needed
only a few more pieces. He wisely decided to get a player from the
Denver team that beat him in Atwater, who played with the Broncos
for 10 years. Even at 32, Atwater is capable of changing a game
with a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets may have a young starting offensive line, but over all,
they are one of the smartest, most veteran teams in the league.
Coach Dennis Green's Vikings played the Jets in preseason, and he
walked away thinking they are the team to beat in the AFC and
perhaps the league. ``I think they're very good,'' Green said.
``They block well. They have a fine runner in Curtis Martin, Vinny
Testaverde plays smart, and then defensively they are very
scrappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Green can identify with Parcells' situation. Two years ago, the
Vikings were for sale, and Green coached through a turbulent and
uncertain year.
</P>
<P>
   When Green looks at Parcells, he is not so sure the Jets' coach
will retire. Parcells has lost weight, as Green did recently, and
to Green Parcells looks refreshed. Indeed, how Parcells feels at
the end of the season may be as big a factor in any retirement
decision as who buys the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is his last year or not because I think
he's really enjoying it,'' Green said. ``A lot will depend on the
sale of the team. I went through the same thing with the Vikings.
It can be stressful.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know something else?'' Green added. ``Look at him.
He's lost weight and looks great. He is obviously enjoying himself.
There are a lot of coaches who have come out of training camp
basically retired. They're tired and worn down. You can see it in
their eyes. That's not the case with Bill. He seems upbeat and
shows a lot of enthusiasm. Besides, I don't know if Bill knows what
he wants to do yet.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Parcells definitely wants is another Super Bowl ring.
This may be his best chance to get it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
