<SLUG> BC-U.S.-GLOBALPOWER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA TALKS AND (SOME) OTHERS LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ On the very day that the United States
helped bring one more Middle East peace agreement to fruition and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright witnessed its signing, a
crisis broke out at the other end of the world. Again, Washington
was called on to find a solution. But this time, in East Timor, the
United States found it not so easy to make the problem go way by
simply swaggering in at the opportune moment and brandishing its
influence.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast is stunning, if only because the world has long
thought of the Middle East, not some tiny corner of Indonesia, as
the toughest nut to crack among all the world's many intractable
disputes, and because the world has recently come to think of the
United States as the one power with enough influence to make just
about anybody sit up and listen _ the ``indispensable nation,'' in
one of Albright's favorite phrases.
</P>
<P>
   But just what does this singular U.S. power consist of, and how
and where can the United States use it? More important, are there
still moments, as with the Indonesians last week, when Americans
might be tempted to just throw up their hands and say it is beyond
their power to do anything?
</P>
<P>
   The question is hardly academic. Right now, Washington is trying
to help end a war in East Africa between Ethiopians and Eritreans.
In North Asia, it wants to stop the North Koreans from test firing
a ballistic missile, a threat that worries South Korea and Japan.
And in South Asia, the Clinton administration is unofficially
adjudicating the dispute in Kashmir between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The impulse for Americans to get involved in East Timor was
sudden and sharp, after murderous militias rampaged through the
Portuguese-speaking territory last week in an effort to overturn
the results of a referendum in which the population voted
overwhelmingly for independence. At least at first, Indonesia
flatly rejected U.N. efforts to send in a peacekeeping force,
leading U.S. officials to step in and try to persuade them to
either restore order quickly or let outsiders do so.
</P>
<P>
   In the initial moments of frustration with Indonesia, it might
have been tempting to think of the way American clout had just
played so important a role in the Middle East. But in fact, the
decision to get peace talks back on track with a revamped
land-for-security deal between the Palestinians and Israelis hardly
represented a precedent for success in Indonesia. Instead, it was
an unusually easy opportunity to make America seem irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   First, the immediate question to be mediated in the Middle East
wasn't really so tough. There was a quibble here over the release
of prisoners, a quibble there over the right to launch unilateral
actions. And a larger question underneath hinted at inevitable
American success. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had wanted as
little U.S. input as possible, preferring to bargain on his own
with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. But Arafat waited for the
comfort of a U.S. presence not just at the signing, but in the
deal-making itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the presence of Albright that gave the
Palestinian the confidence to sign up. For Arafat, this made
Washington a court of last appeal. Now, he can reason, if something
goes wrong with the implementation of the deal he can turn to the
Clinton administration for help.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of history has gone into that understanding _ nearly
three decades of a tenacious, expensive and often frustrating U.S.
commitment to help the Middle East find a lasting peace. The
question in other parts of the globe now is whether the United
States can similarly play the role of ``indispensable nation'' in
helping resolve situations like the one in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, Washington does seem to have a long history of
involvement, and hence considerable leverage, with Indonesia _
certainly a lot more than can be claimed by neighboring Australia,
one of Washington's staunchest and now most nervous allies.
Australia, whose northernmost port of Darwin is only about 400
miles from East Timor, clamored all week for U.S. help in calming
the violence and for U.S. logistical support in mounting a
peacekeeping mission to be sponsored by the United Nations. Very
quickly, senior U.S. military officers were in contact with Gen.
Wiranto, the head of the Indonesian army, telling him to curb the
militias or face consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But as Wiranto listened by telephone to Gen. Henry Shelton, the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the Indonesian knew he had a
very good hand to play as well. All of Washington's history of
backing the Indonesian military during the Cold War in fact brings
it little leverage these days; in recent years, almost all military
assistance has been cut by Congress because of the Indonesian
army's abuse of human rights. And as Wiranto listened, he knew
something even more important: that the United States is not about
to totally abandon Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous
nation and the master of sea lanes through which U.S. naval vessels
and oil carriers pass.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Indonesia is a strategically important country for the
United States in Asia, one that serves as a counterbalance to China
as well as Japan. (The Israelis have known something similar over
the years, of course, but their calculations have been different:
While no U.S. president could abandon Israel, the United States
also wasn't about to abandon its Arab allies who gave America
access to oil. Hence the pressure for all sides to seek peace.)
</P>
<P>
   Last week, before Clinton left Washington to attend the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum in New Zealand, where East
Timor's plight is sure to dominate the discussions, he suggested he
might push for the International Monetary Fund to curb economic
assistance to Indonesia. But on hearing this, Wiranto may well have
calculated that this was not a serious threat either. The end of
financial aid to Indonesia, where the economy is in perilous shape,
would produce the very troubles that the United States would like
to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States would hate to carry out that threat because
you would create chaos,'' said Walter Russell Mead, a senior fellow
at the Council on Foreign Relations, who is writing a book on the
history of American diplomacy. ``The last thing we want to be
forced to do is shoot the Indonesians in the head. To block all aid
would hurt United States interests as much as Indonesia's.''
</P>
<P>
   While Washington was displeased last week with the Indonesian
army's refusal to put out the fire in East Timor, the
administration also had reason to fear putting too much pressure on
the Indonesian military. With the decline of the major political
party, Golkar, and with democratic reforms in their infancy, the
United States still sees the army as the only national institution
capable of holding together an archipelago nation strewn across
thousands of miles.
</P>
<P>
   Mead also argues that Washington is hampered in the new crisis
by a lack of past identification with East Timor. In the Middle
East, for example, administration negotiators, who have been
dealing intensely with Arafat for nearly a decade, can tell him:
``Don't declare statehood, don't mess it up, you can't do that,''
Mead said. And then the administration can _ as Clinton did last
April _ promise to hold a summit meeting, always an attractive
offer for Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the lure of the United States as a broker is the
lure of the United States as a dispenser of economic assistance. In
the Middle East 20 years ago, Egyptian President Anwar Sadat did
not make peace with Israel primarily out of a desire for peace
itself, said Itamar Rabinovitch, a former Israeli ambassador to the
United States who has just written a history of Middle East
negotiations, ``Waging Peace'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux). ``He
wanted to disengage from the Soviet Union and have ties with the
United States,'' Rabinovitch said. Sadat's reward for settling with
Israel at Camp David consisted of huge infusions of annual aid to
Egypt in subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Rabinovitch argues, the priority today for Syrian
President Hafez Assad is not so much to make peace with Israel as
to make peace with Washington and then hopefully reap economic
assistance. Thus, Assad is insisting on an American broker as he
contemplates whether to get serious and start negotiations with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In Korea too, money plays a big role; it is why North Korea
accepts the United States as a mediator between it and the South.
In essence, Washington has been bribing crop-starved North Korea
with food aid to try to keep it from firing a missile. And for some
smaller countries, good behavior in American eyes can result in
largesse from the international financial institutions. With U.S.
involvement as mediator in the Ethiopian-Eritrean conflict, it is
almost certain that financial support would follow peace.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, then, it is the use of U.S. economic power as a club
or carrot that may prove the most promising way to persuade the
Indonesians to let the world help stem the violence in East Timor.
Indonesia is, after all, only now emerging from the economic crisis
that shook all of Asia just two years ago, and that brought about
the collapse of Indonesia's last government, under Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as though an industry of peace is our greatest export,''
said Mead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
