<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5397 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SLEEP-TIPS-TEXT-REVIE     09-11 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEP-TIPS-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW-TO-SLEEP BOOKS: TO READ, PERCHANCE TO DROOL ON YOUR PILLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sleep, while never exactly out of style, seems really in vogue
now. The Wall Street Journal this year proclaimed it ``the new
status symbol.'' Business superstars like Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com
and Marc Andreesen of Netscape _ in contrast with past
overachievers like Thomas Edison, who scoffed at sleep _ brag about
getting eight hours of luxuriant nod regularly, to the doubtless
envy of America's legions of sleep-deprived stiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing world has been busy sawing wood itself, producing
so many books on sleep and sleep disorders that the nation now has
a viable alternative to counting sheep. According to R.R. Bowker's
``Books in Print,'' scores of new titles on sleep have been churned
out annually in the late 1990s and there are now hundreds
available.
</P>
<P>
   Many are redundant, recommending familiar habits of healthful
living as keys to sound slumber. (Eat right, exercise, go easy on
the booze and caffeine, etc.) But even so, the books may not leave
your eyelids drooping _ for a close perusal yields passages that
surprise, startle, mystify or amuse. Here is a sampling.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 1: ``The Snoring Cure: Simple Steps to Getting a
Good Night's Sleep,'' by Dr. Laurence A. Smolley and Debra Fulghum
Bruce (W.W. Norton, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Through the years, bed partners have taken it upon
themselves to solve the snoring problem, using such obscure
remedies as stuffing a cloth in the snorer's mouth. Snorers have
claimed fractured ribs from getting hard pokes during the night by
a bed partner in an attempt to jolt the snorer and quiet the noise.
In an extreme case of listener annoyance, the gunslinger John
Wesley Hardin is remarked to have fatally shot a loud snorer in the
next room.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 2: ``The Sleep Rx: 75 Proven Ways to Get a Good
Night's Sleep,'' by Norman Ford (Reward Books, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Quote, on a stress-reduction method: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worry-Stopper No. 1: The Worry Tree
</P>
<P>
   Choose a tree in your yard or near your home that you see each
day as you come home from work. Designate it as your ``worry
tree.'' ... Leave all your worries on the tree as you enter your
home.
</P>
<P>
   If no tree is handy, visualize yourself pinning each of your
worries on a real or imagined clothes line. Or visualize yourself
burying each of your worries in a hole in the ground and covering
it with soil. Or ``see'' yourself placing all your worries in an
incinerator and burning them. Another variation is to place all
your worries in an imaginary garbage can. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 3: ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Getting a Good
Night's Sleep,'' by Dr. Martin Moore-Ede and Suzanne LeVert (Alpha
Books, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Revelatory opening line: Sleep: It's an activity we all try to
perform every day, just like eating or getting some exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 4: ``Don't Snore Anymore: Your Complete Guide to
a Quiet Night's Sleep,'' by Dr. Jeffrey N. Hausfeld (Three Rivers
Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Quote: An elderly couple made separate appointments to see me
and were placed in two adjacent examining rooms. When I first went
in to see the gentleman, his major complaint was a stuffy nose.
Upon examination, he had significant obstruction to his nasal
airflow, a very bulky uvula, enlarged tonsils and a short, heavy
neck. Suspecting that he might have a problem with snoring, I asked
him, ``How badly do you snore at night?'' His answer surprised me.
He said that he used to snore very loudly, but in recent years his
wife had not complained. It turned out that when I went to the
adjacent examining room to speak to his wife, she was there to
consult me about her progressive hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 5: ``The Promise of Sleep,'' by Dr. William C.
Dement and Christopher Vaughan (Delacorte, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Quote, on napping in the cockpit: Although pilot naps, intended
or otherwise, already occur on American flights ... it has proven
politically impossible to pass regulations allowing them; there is
still the unfortunate perception that permitting pilots to sleep in
the cockpit is dangerous _ even with a fully awake co-pilot _
despite studies that show planned napping to be safer than not
napping. This is one of the most preposterous and illogical policy
decisions of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 6: ``No More Sleepless Nights: A Proven Program
to Conquer Insomnia,'' by Peter Hauri, Ph.D., and Shirley Linde,
Ph.D. (Wiley, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Some patients get up in the middle of the night and eat,
without ever becoming fully conscious. In a behavioral state that
resembles sleepwalking, they may wander into the kitchen while
unconscious and eat. Sweets and pasta are usually preferred, but
some patients eat inappropriate foods such as raw, frozen or
spoiled food in odd mixtures of butter, fruit and leftovers
prepared in a blender. ...
</P>
<P>
   Patients with this disorder awaken in the morning with full
stomachs, skip breakfast, but still gain weight.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep Book No. 7: ``Desperately Seeking Snoozin': The Insomnia
Cure From Awake to Zzzz,'' by John Wiedman (Towering Pines Press,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   Quote, the author on his credentials: Let me introduce myself.
My name is John Wiedman. I am a mortgage broker with a degree in
finance from the University of Memphis. ... I do not have a Ph.D.
specializing in clinical psychology from some big name university.
I have not been in charge of a center for sleep disturbances for
the last 15 years. I am, however, a professional insomniac (or at
least I was until recently). ... I can help you rid yourself of
insomnia. And although I am not much of a writer, I will try to
present this information as effectively as possible. ...
</P>
<P>
   Tell your doctor you are going to read this book. If he is
skeptical about any of its contents, have him read the book. It is
not very long. I would appreciate it if you have him buy his own
copy. I need all the sales I can get.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
