</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Canals That Wouldn't Wash
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was a yearning for a deeper sense of history that
made city officials and developers in Scottsdale, Ariz., push so
hard for a grand redevelopment project called ``The Canals of
Scottsdale.'' They envisioned a sort of Venice of the desert, with
little barges to transport countless new tourists to shops and
restaurants along the banks.
</P>
<P>
   For precedent, Europhiles needed only look about 150 miles north
to Lake Havasu City, where the London Bridge was hauled, brick by
brick, and reconstructed in a fake English village 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But to just about everyone's surprise, the voters of Scottsdale
rose up on election day to soundly reject the canal project, 54
percent to 46 percent. It would have cost $653 million, including
$200 million in public funding, and would have wiped out about 40
small businesses and shops in the downtown area that sell Western
and Mexican-style wares.
</P>
<P>
   The voters' revolt seemed to catch the power elite of
Scottsdale, including the mayor, Sam Camapana, by surprise.
Backers, including a California developer, had spent $838,000 in
recent weeks in a campaign that featured glossy brochures and
expensively produced television commercials. The opponents, who
called themselves ``Save Old Scottsdale,'' raised about $12,000,
much of it collected in jars at local stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying, `Enough already,''' Lois Fitch, a retired
teacher, told the local newspaper, The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any paid volunteers,'' she said. ``We simply
had hard-core volunteers who said, `We're taking our city back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Revolution No. 9? Not So Fast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite warnings of a Y2K-style meltdown and prophecies about a
possible guest appearance by Satan, the date 9-9-99 _ the dreaded
nines _ came and went without any apocalyptic incidents.
</P>
<P>
   There were few reports of mayhem among an older generation of
computers that were expected to confuse the string of nines as a
cue to shut down. Those keeping an eye on the world's Year 2000
readiness saw the scarcity of glitches as a divine omen for Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Pessimistic astrologers looked at all those nines, turned them
on their head, and said they would be irresistibly alluring to the
devil. But if the stock market was any indication (the Dow rose 43
points that day), Lucifer didn't take the bait. On the contrary,
most people saw the nines not as jinxed sixes but as lucky sevens,
and lotteries across the country reported a run on the sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Although the West is largely ambivalent about the number, Asia
is far more passionate about its nines. The Japanese keep it out of
their hospitals _ the word nine is a homonym for the word pain _
while in China, it is the supreme number, a metaphor for the
emperor and a building block of traditional Chinese architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Adherents of Mary Katherine Kracht, a San Diego numerologist who
conducts seances on the World Wide Web, know that nine is the
finest of figures, a turning point and a prompt for new
opportunities. ``Anyone who sees sixes in nines is living in
fear,'' she said. ``Truth is, with nine you just can't go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREW JACOBS
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
