</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREW JACOBS
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Court Limits Use Of Force in Interrogations
</P>
<P>
   It was an issue that Israeli justices were loathe to touch. For
years, international human rights groups had condemned Israel for
allowing its security police to use physically coercive methods to
interrogate Palestinian detainees. But the Israeli government had
claimed it could not shackle its agents, not if their techniques
helped extract information to prevent terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After years of delay the Israeli Supreme Court unexpectedly
outlawed the use of forceful interrogation methods by the Shin Bet
security service, setting off a raging debate within Israel.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   Danforth to Examine Waco
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Attorney General Janet Reno named John
Danforth, a former Republican senator from Missouri, to lead an
independent reexamination of the FBI's tear-gas assault in 1993 on
the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas. Danforth was granted
full investigative and prosecutorial powers to charge federal
agents with crimes if he finds the law was broken. In part, the
choice reflected an effort by Reno to quiet her Republican critics
in Congress. But the outcry grew louder, with Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott telling reporters, ``I am beginning to think that
she should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Testifies Again
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was back before an independent counsel, giving
testimony under oath in the investigation of Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman. Lawyers said that the little-noticed inquiry into
accusations of influence peddling and campaign finance violations
by Ms. Herman appeared to be winding down. One of the president's
lawyers said Clinton was only a witness in the case, not a criminal
target.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN M. BRODER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Teachers End Strike
</P>
<P>
   It was back to school for teachers in Detroit after a strike
that lengthened summer vacation by more than a week for the city's
180,000 public school students and gave their parents child-care
headaches. The teachers voted to return to classrooms after their
union, the Detroit Federation of Teachers, reached a tentative
three-year contract agreement with the Detroit School Board that
gave them raises and promised smaller class sizes next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBYN MEREDITH
</P>
<P>
   Gore Unveils Health Plan
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore became the first of the current crop of
presidential contenders to lay out a detailed plan for health
policy. He promised to guarantee access to affordable health
insurance for all children by 2005, through a number of steps,
including expansion of the 1997 Children's Health Insurance
Program.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan was modest compared with President Clinton's
ill-fated 1993 proposal for universal coverage. Health policy
experts said the cost of Gore's plan would probably exceed $5
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   Gun Buyback Plan
</P>
<P>
   Opening a new round in the debate over gun control, President
Clinton announced a $15 million program to buy back and destroy as
many as 300,000 firearms, mostly in and around crime-ridden public
housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in November, the government will provide grants to
police departments of up to $500,000, and suggest that authorities
offer $50 for each working gun, either in cash, food, gift
certificates or tickets to sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   Let Us Spray
</P>
<P>
   To New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the answer to St. Louis
encephalitis, which by the weekend had killed three people in the
New York area, is clear: spray, spray and spray some more in all
five boroughs. ``The more dead mosquitoes, the better,'' he said.
But while the threat is real, some New Yorkers balked, with one
woman objecting to ``all those horrible chemicals in your child's
lungs.''
</P>
<P>
   And why did this nasty disease wander so far north? No one
knows.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Whitman Quits Senate Race
</P>
<P>
   Citing the overwhelming burden of running New Jersey and
campaigning for the U.S. Senate, Gov. Christie Whitman stunned her
Republican colleagues and Democratic foes by saying she no longer
planned to run for the seat being vacated by Frank Lautenberg, the
Democratic incumbent, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican leaders scrambled to find a backup who could
raise $12 million in one year.
</P>
<P>
   With Whitman out of the race, the two leading Democratic
candidates, former Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. chairman Jon Corzine and
former Gov. Jim Florio, who lost his office to Whitman in 1993, can
focus on beating each other.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PAUL ZIELBAUER
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin Shrugs Off Rumors
</P>
<P>
   So, Boris, what about those rumors you might be caught up in the
scandal involving money-laundering and the Swiss construction
company that got a big contract to fix up the Kremlin? Yeah,  &UR; that &LR; 
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The subject came up in a phone chat between President Bill
Clinton and President Boris Yeltsin the other day. Yeltsin stopped
short of replying, ``I am not a crook,'' in Russian, but blamed his
enemies for the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   Another Russian Campaign
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that the United States lost a war with Alabama and sued
for peace, only to see Alabama invade Mississippi, and you have a
rough idea of the Kremlin's latest military plight. The Russian air
force was hard at work bombing its own territory, the province-like
Republic of Dagestan, after Islamic radicals from neighboring
Chechnya marched in by the thousands, unmolested, with the aim of
taking it over.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens fought Russia's ragtag army to a standstill in 1996
and appeared to be holding their own this time. President Boris
Yeltsin, furious, ridiculed his ``careless'' generals on
television, and the military promised a swift campaign to oust the
rebels. But the Chechens promised to hit back.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL WINES
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
