<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-AMERICAN-3TAKES-N     09-11 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AMERICAN-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS, JAGUARS AND BRONCOS ARE AFC SELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: Teams are profiled in order of predicted finish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC EAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Miami
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (10-6), wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Recent Super Bowl teams have won with offense
highlighted. Miami will attempt to win a championship with defense
at the forefront. It has an oftentimes spectacular one that a year
ago helped the Dolphins allow the fewest points (265) in the NFL.
It starts directly over the ball where the Miami front is powerful,
flexible and deep. Tackles Tim Bowens and Daryl Gardener are
flanked by interchangeable ends in Jason Taylor, Lorenzo Bromell,
Kenny Mixon and Trace Armstrong. And then for added strength, Miami
signed free agent end Rich Owens from Washington. Zack Thomas leads
the linebackers and Terrell Buckley the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : The running game has been a sore spot for Miami in
recent seasons, but the Dolphins have retooled in alarming fashion.
Karim Abdul-Jabbar returns and so does John Avery and Stanley
Pritchett, but three draft picks at the position loom large: James
Johnson from Mississippi State, Rob Konrad from Syracuse and
talented but troubled Cecil Collins from McNeese State. The
receiving core needs a jolt and newly acquired Tony Martin can
provide it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : A team with a strong defense and Dan Marino at
quarterback always has a chance. Add an improved running game and
Martin and Miami will create a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   2. New England
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (9-7), wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : The quarterback (Drew Bledsoe), the cornerback (Ty
Law) and the receiver (Terry Glenn). Each is a Patriots staple.
Bledsoe is big (6-5, 233), strong and now in his seventh season is
experienced and ready to distinguish himself with a consistent
level of excellence. Law earned nine interceptions a year ago and
his first pro bowl berth. Glenn has been injured in each of his
first three seasons but when healthy provides Patriot thrills. With
him New England is 23-11; without him they are 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Without injured Robert Edwards, the Patriots start
over again at running back. No proven star, but rookie Kevin Faulk
from LSU is promising. Injuries crushed this team a year ago, with
16 starters missing 58 games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : Big play by Faulk and a healthy crew for the entire
seasons spells big success.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jets
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (12-4), divisional champion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths: &LR;  Everything with the Jets starts with the coach,
Bill Parcells, whose shadow looms large and whose coaching staff
excels. Parcells and his staff prepares his team with supreme
confidence and results. Vinny Testaverde at quarterback looks to
duplicate a rare pro bowl season and the weapons are there to
achieve it: Curtis Martin's daring running, Keyshawn Johnson's
flamboyant pass catching and a punishing defense led by linebacker
Bryan Cox. The special teams are always good.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  The offensive line is revamped and untested as a
group. How will it fare since last year's line played the entire
season in harmony?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : The Jets could easily move up if all falls into place
like last season, one full of close, harrowing victories. Seldom,
though, does a repeat like that happen.
</P>
<P>
   4. Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   1988 record (10-6) wild card team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : With quarterbacks Doug Flutie and Rob Johnson, the
Bills possess a 1-2 punch at the position that other teams envy.
Flutie features mobility, Johnson a strong arm and accurate deep
passing. Another duo at running back _ Antowain Smith and Thurman
Thomas _ makes the ground game viable. Eric Moulds at receiver is a
special player and the defense, once again, is anchored by
venerable 15-year pro Bruce Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  None of the Bills linebackers have been able to
reach the steady and big-play style of long departed Bryce Paup or
Cornelius Bennett. Buffalo finished 14th in pass defense a year ago
and needs improvement there. That is a big reason why it selected
Antoine Winfield from Ohio State and he is likely an immediate
starter in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook: &LR;  A tough, rugged, veteran-inspired team capable of
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   5. Indianapolis
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (3-13).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Peyton Manning's first pro season was a success if
his team's record was not. He threw for the most yards (3,739) ever
in a Colts season, beating Johnny Unitas. He threw touchdown passes
in 13 consecutive games. He played every down and started every
game and in his eyes and arm his teammates could see the future.
Marvin Harrison (59 catches, 7 touchdowns and a long score of 61
yards) was a favorite Manning target.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Defense. Teams scored 444 points on the Colts, 111
more than the next worse in the division (Buffalo with 333). In 11
leaguewide defensive categories, Indianapolis finished either next
to last or last.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : Defensive help arrives via free agency but not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC CENTRAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Jacksonville
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (11-5) Divisional champions
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : The Jaguars have been knocking at the Super Bowl
door for three seasons now. Their playoff losses in the last three
years have been dealt by New England, Denver and the Jets; after
those losses New England reached a Super Bowl, Denver won it and
the Jets reached the AFC championship game. Is it finally
Jacksonville's turn to topple the AFC full tilt? Everything appears
in place. Solid leadership in management and in Tom Coughlin, the
head coach. The complete package at quarterback in Mark Brunell. An
emerging running back in Fred Taylor. A star offensive tackle in
Tony Boselli. Great receivers, speedy linebackers, adept special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  A defensive star. No Jaguar on defense in past
years consistently dominated games. The addition of safety Carnell
Lake, in from Pittsburgh, and Dom Capers as the new defensive
coordinator figure to boost the defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : Sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   2. Baltimore
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (6-10).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Scott Mitchell, exiled in Detroit, gets a new
chance with the Ravens under new coach Brian Billick, the former
Minnesota Vikings offensive coordinator. Mitchell and Billick.
Their fortunes are intricately tied, thus, both need the other to
take the Ravens where they want to go. Billick has the right stuff
having tutored the Vikings offense to great heights. There are
other tools for Billick. Back Priest Holmes (1,008 rushing yards),
playmaking receiver and returner Jermaine Lewis (57.6 yards
averaged on his eight touchdowns scored), pro bowl tackle Jonathan
Ogden and a group of starting linebackers as good as any in
football.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Confidence, especially on offense. Baltimore
ranked 26th overall on offense, 20th rushing and 25th passing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : Can the Ravens earn early success and then build?
Yes, especially with three of their first five games against
divisional opponents and two of those at home.
</P>
<P>
   3. Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   1998 record 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : This has been an underachieving, nomadic team that
finally has a home in a new, downtown Nashville Stadium, a new name
(Titans) and new uniforms. This year will bring either success or
more riveting change to a team that yearns for consistency. Start
at quarterback. Steve McNair has shown what he can do with his
legs; now he needs to do more with his arm, especially deep
downfield. There is no problem at running back: Eddie George will
benefit from a two-back set that features former New Orleans Saint
Lorenzo Neal at fullback. The defense is young and improving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  The Titans need better field position, thus more
from their punt and kick return teams. Their 7.4 yard per punt
return ranked 26th. Their 20.5 kickoff return average ranked 24th.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : A new and permanent home should work wonders for a
team that has been full of talent but has lacked confidence and
cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (7-9)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths: &LR;  Resiliency, but is it waning? Pittsburgh's free
agents losses over the last few seasons could compile an all-pro
team but usually the Steelers rebound. Last year they did not,
toiling through their first losing season in Bill Cowher's seven
seasons as head coach. Jerome Bettis remains the key element of the
offense with his bruising, powerful runs Kordell Stewart at
quarterback has been both stellar and lousy. It is a big season for
Stewart, who hopes to be elevated by the addition of Kevin Gilbride
as offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Offensive production. In Pittsburgh's last five
games, the offense scored two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook: &LR;  Pittsburgh featured the best Red Zone defense in
football last season and looks for more, but the team's playoff
fortunes rely heavily on Stewart. Can he ``Slash'' once again?
</P>
<P>
   5. Cleveland
</P>
<P>
   First season of the new Browns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths: &LR;  Football returns to Cleveland beginning with a
Monday night game at home against Pittsburgh and after that, who
knows what is in store for an expansion team that has more history
than most NFL clubs. Certainly, the Browns should be fun to watch,
especially if the rookie quarterback Tim Couch, the team's first
pick in last year's draft, cracks the starting lineup. There are
other exciting players: rookie receiver Kevin Johnson and
cornerbacks Corey Fuller and Marquez Pope.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : New coach (Chris Palmer), new stadium, new
everything all trying to mesh over 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook: &LR;  Exciting, regardless of the record.
</P>
<P>
   6. Cincinnati
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (3-13)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : The Bengals are an enigma. A doleful enigma. They
have not flourished under Bruce Coslet, their head coach, and he is
the leading candidate among all NFL head coaches to be dismissed
first. Jeff Blake is the quarterback and he has been down, up and
then down again. Corey Dillon is a fluid running back fun to watch.
Few players on the defense have distinguished themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Horrible at finishing games and terrible at home _
the Bengals were 1-7 in home games a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : Cincinnati needs something good to happen starting
from kickoff in their first game at Indianapolis. Likely, it won't.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC WEST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Denver
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: (14-2) Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Mike Shanahan coaches his team with a heavy hand
and with a magnificent mind. Each player on the Denver roster is
hand-picked by Shanahan and he has assembled another talented group
minus one key player _ John Elway. Brian Griese in only his second
pro season will start at quarterback, replacing Elway and
supplanting Bubby Brister. Griese does not have to win games alone
with the magnificent back Terrell Davis, rock-solid tight end
Shannon Sharpe, receivers Ed McCaffrey and Rod Smith and a robust
offensive line providing plenty of help. The defense vastly
improved itself with the addition of one player, Dale Carter from
Kansas City, one of the league's best single cover cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  The leadership void left by Elway. Off-field
distractions, chief among them linebacker Bill Romanowski's
fraudelent drug prescription charges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook: &LR;  If the Broncos stay united, the divisional title and
the playoffs are easily theirs.
</P>
<P>
   2. Oakland
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (8-8)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Napolean Kauffman at running back. Tim Brown at
receiver. A spell-blinding cornerback duo in Eric Allen and Charles
Woodson. And a defense led by tackle Darrell Russell and defensive
coordinator Willie Shaw that could be the surprise of the 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  Rich Gannon at quarterback. A career backup who is
likeable, mobile, intelligent _ but he only takes you so far.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : The Raiders will begin a return toward the elite this
season under head coach Jon Gruden but too many holes remain to
talk Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   3. Seattle
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (8-8)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths: &LR;  A $32 million coach in Mike Holmgren, who runs the
Seahawks with full control. A still tenacious runner in Ricky
Watters and an exciting backup in Ahman Green. A terrific
cornerback in Shawn Springs. Non-stop linebacker Chad Brown and end
Michael Sinclair are primed for big seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Will Joey Galloway, a contract holdout, join the
fold?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : Seattle has long been a team full of ability that
spun its wheels but Holmgren is expected to change that. Old habits
often die slowly. Expect at least a year of transition.
</P>
<P>
   4. Kansas City
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (7-9)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Kansas City earned nine consecutive winning seasons
and then crashed last season. It was the league's most penalized
time and suffered a six-game losing streak. Gunther Cunningham,
formerly the Chiefs defensive coordinator, enters as head coach and
finds a wobbly quarterback (Elvis Grbac), a determined running back
(Kimble Anders), dashing receivers (Andre Rison and Derrick
Alexander), a smooth tight end (Tony Gonzalez) and a defense still
looking for linebacker Derrick Thomas to lead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses: &LR;  Kansas City needs a big year from Anders; Donnell
Bennett was last year's starting back and leading rusher with only
527 yards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook &LR; : The Chiefs are all shook up but how will it pan out?
Like Seattle, a year of transition is required.
</P>
<P>
   5. San Diego
</P>
<P>
   1998 record (5-11)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strengths &LR; : Mike Riley is the new coach and he inherits a team
that is 5-19 in its last 24 games, the worst record in the league
during that span, and a team that was reeling under the sour
influence of last year's top rookie pick at quarterback, Ryan Leaf.
Thank goodness for Jim Harbaugh. He enters as the starter, a
intuitive 13-year veteran who inspires and provides solid
quarterbacking. His job is to help re-invent an offense that has
scored one or no touchdowns in 28 of 32 games over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weaknesses &LR; : Preventing and producing turnovers; San Diego was
minus 24 in turnover differential, worse in the league.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Outlook: &LR;  Improved with Harbaugh, but still long days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC players and coaches to watch: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dom Capers and Kevin Gilbride &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Two guys that used to be head coaches (Capers in Carolina and
Gilbride in San Diego) now find themselves back doing what they
once did _ Capers as a defensive coordinator and Gilbride as an
offensive coordinator. Capers in Jacksonville, Gilbride in
Pittsburgh. Their goal is to have their sides of the ball excel,
win a Super Bowl and get back into the head coaching carousel.
Well, Capers has the inside track. He gains a defense in
Jacksonville full of speed and potential that has played
inconsistently and he is reunited with safety Carnell Lake. Watch
Capers devise aggressive, interesting schemes that help make
Jacksonville a Super Bowl favorite. Gilbride has the awesome task
of grooming and coaxing Kordell Stewart back into form. Stewart
last year slid into bad habits at quarterback and his play was
frightening. Since both are in the same division, the battle to
play ``Mr. Fixit'' between Capers and Gilbride will color not only
the division but the entire conference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tony Martin: Miami receiver &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OK, here was the deal for Tony Martin: face a few years in
prison for an association with a big-time drug dealer or continue
your NFL football career as a Miami Dolphin. Martin, a former
Atlanta Falcon, signed as a free agent in Miami, where his federal
trial was being held. Dan Marino testified on his behalf. Probably
everyone in the courtroom was a Marino and Dolphin fan. Martin won.
So do the Dolphins. This is one of the better route-runners in the
NFL _ watch the huge separation he gains on outs and on deep
routes. Marino has not had a receiver this good since the
Clayton/Duper days. Marino to Martin will be a fixture of the `99
season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brian Griese: Denver quarterback &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What will it take in Denver to fill the void at quarterback left
by the gorilla-like presence of John Elway? How about a second year
player who has thrown all of 3 NFL passes? Finally, the dust has
cleared _ and so have the tears and darts _ as Bubby Brister has
accepted his demotion as the starting quarterback and the
replacement for Elway. It is Griese now and forever, says Broncos
coach Mike Shanahan _ until Griese slips and then Brister gets the
call in the backup style that is his game. Griese is not your basic
second-year player. Wonderful genes, the son of a Hall of Fame
quarterback. Brilliant mind. A guy born to play quarterback. He
will play under intense glare for a team seeking a historical
three-peat. The odds are long against him, but his season will be
full of intrigue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
