<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GATES-SENIOR-PROFILE-     09-11 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-SENIOR-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDER BILL GATES TAKES ON THE ROLE OF PHILANTHROPIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When John D. Rockefeller turned his attention to
philanthropic causes earlier this century, he relied in many ways
on his son, John D. Rockefeller Jr., for help in deciding how to
disburse his colossal oil fortune. Both father and son famously
brooded, at times to the verge of mental exhaustion, over how hard
it was to give away money in an intelligent and useful fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a while before William H. Gates III, the 43-year-old
founder and chairman of Microsoft Corp. and now the wealthiest
person on the planet, asks his children for help with his
philanthropic endeavors. After all, Jennifer is only 3, and Rory
John is shy of 4 months. And since Gates remains at the helm of his
company, he is unable to concentrate full time on the task himself.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gates has looked in the other direction on the family
tree and given much of the responsibility to a genial, 6-foot-6
retired lawyer by the name of William H. Gates Jr. _ a man candid
enough to admit, if a touch sheepishly, that his techno-billionaire
son harbors ``a continuous frustration about the problems that
people like his father have with their computer,'' and droll enough
to enjoy the humor in going by the name Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a big kick out of that,'' the 73-year-old Gates said,
adding that it was especially true when he called people on the
phone. ``First, there's just a pause. They don't know what to say.
Or it's, `Are you kidding?' Or, `Come on, now, are you really?' And
to that I always say, `Sure, I am Bill Gates.'''
</P>
<P>
   As co-chairman of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, the
elder Gates sits atop a $17 billion organization, one that pledges
to make huge donations in the fields of education and global
health.
</P>
<P>
   The Gates philanthropic foundation recently became the largest
in the country, and with the David and Lucile Packard Foundation of
Los Altos, Calif., in the No. 2 position, it is a striking symbol
of the fast-growing role of high technology and West Coast money in
the world of American philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   With more donations expected, the Gates Foundation is virtually
certain soon to surpass the Wellcome Trust in Britain as the
largest philanthropic organization in the world.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The foundation remains highly unusual in having living
benefactors, and relatively young ones at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Fords, the Rockefellers, the Carnegies of the
foundation world, you can only go back into history to figure out
what their benefactors wanted,'' said Stacy Palmer, editor of The
Chronicle of Philanthropy, a newspaper covering nonprofit
organizations. ``The difference here is that you actually have
donors saying, `This is what I care about, this is the big
philanthropic bet I want to make.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, in an inversion of the usual roles, it is the father who
gets to help spend the son's money, soon to be a minimum of nearly
$1 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's broad priorities, as set by the Microsoft
chairman and his wife, include global health programs, especially
those focused on developing and distributing vaccines for malaria,
AIDS and other diseases; education, encompassing programs to
provide computers, Internet access and technical training for
libraries in lower-income areas across North America; and a variety
of community, educational and cultural programs here in the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But it is up to the elder Gates and the foundation's
co-chairwoman, Patty Stonesifer, a former Microsoft executive and
longtime friend of the younger Gates, to cull the possibilities and
come up with specific grant recommendations. (The elder Gates had
been in charge of the William H. Gates Foundation, which
concentrated on health issues and the Pacific Northwest, since
1994, while Ms. Stonesifer headed the Gates Learning Foundation,
created under a different name in 1997. Those two organizations
recently merged to become the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation.)
</P>
<P>
   The requests and recommendations pour in, including what the
elder Gates describes as an astounding number of letters from
people down on their luck and desperately seeking some cash; the
foundation, however, by its charter, cannot make donations to
private individuals.
</P>
<P>
   But even as there is a huge amount of speculation over the
impact of the Gates Foundation on the philanthropy world, the
organization is clearly making an effort not to rock the boat. The
senior Gates and Ms. Stonesifer, for instance, recently traveled to
New York City to meet with leaders of the 40 other top foundations
in the country to discuss ways to make their giving strategies
complementary. The meeting was arranged by Vartan Gregorian, the
president of Carnegie Corp. and a member of the Gates foundation
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a signal,'' Ms. Palmer said. ``They're saying
they're not trying to reinvent everything here and start from
scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If the two John D. Rockefellers found the task of philanthropy
daunting, especially as they labored over the details of building
brick-and-mortar institutions, like the University of Chicago,
which were created with Rockefeller money, the two Bill Gateses, at
least for now, seem less overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the younger Gates has said that while
philanthropy may one day become his obsession, he is simply more
immersed now in his young family and his company, which, among
other things, is embroiled in a huge antitrust battle with the U.S.
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   That means that, for now, he has left many of the details of his
philanthropy to his father and others.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, the grant-making process at the Gates
Foundation is simpler in one respect than that of the Rockefellers,
at least in the area of health, which the elder Gates has
concentrated on: The money has generally been donated to existing
groups or efforts, like the Malaria Vaccine Initiative and the
International AIDS Vaccine Initiative, rather than used to create
institutions. And both the elder Gates and Ms. Stonesifer say that
that is likely to remain the case for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, the man wading through all the possibilities for
gifts said he found that the daunting nature of the process was far
outweighed by the satisfaction of being able to do some good in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a pretty profound thing to have set out to be retired
and wind up close to preoccupied with the work of the foundation,''
Gates said in an interview the other day. ``But it's profoundly
satisfying. There is, of course, incredible joy in frequently being
able to say yes to something.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Philanthropy is not new to the elder Gates. A prominent Seattle
lawyer, he has long been involved in numerous charitable
activities, including the United Way _ ``and not just as chair of
the fund-raising drive,'' said James R. Ellis, a longtime friend
and partner in their law firm, Preston Gates &AMP; Ellis, which is one
of the city's largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can recall seeing Bill handing out United Way literature at
UW football games,'' Ellis said, referring to the University of
Washington, where Gates got both his bachelor's and law degrees.
``He is truly a hands-on guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates' philanthropic duties with the foundation, for which he
receives an annual salary of $90,000, grew out of a conversation a
few years ago with his son and daughter-in-law during a night out
at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For a time his duties with the foundation were largely conducted
from a basement office in the same unassuming home in Seattle's
Laurelhurst neighborhood in which he and his wife Mary raised their
son, who sometimes declined entreaties to come to the table for
family dinner by shouting from his room: ``I can't right now! I'm
thinking!''
</P>
<P>
   This is also the same son, still called Trey by the elder Gates,
who at the age of 12 simply announced that there was no logical
reason for him to carry out some of the household chores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an emotional reaction or resistance to the
imposition of somebody else's will,'' recalled the father, who can
afford to laugh about it now. ``With Trey, it was an intellectual
thing. It was, `I really don't need to clean up my room, Mother. I
do not need to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Gates, who was active in Seattle charities, died of cancer
five years ago, and Gates has since married Mimi Gardner Gates, who
is the director of the Seattle Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During the fateful night at the movies, Gates recalled, ``My son
was expressing a lot of frustration about his ability to deal
properly with requests for charitable gifts. He was concerned that
people were complaining that he didn't answer their letters, which
he didn't have time to do. And I just said, `Well, look, son, my
time isn't all that fully occupied. Why don't I help you with
that?' So that's how it all got started.''
</P>
<P>
   Over its first few years, and under the elder Gates' direction,
the foundation has given gifts that include $100 million to reduce
delays in the delivery of new vaccines to children around the
world; $50 million to the Maternal Mortality Reduction program at
Columbia University; $50 million for research on the malaria
vaccine, and $25 million to the AIDS vaccine initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The learning foundation has given about $200 million to the
library project, which has so far installed computers and Internet
connections in 1,745 libraries in 32 states, with a five-year goal
of reaching 10,000 libraries in the United States and 3,000 in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But as significant as these gifts are, they may well pale in
comparison to coming grants, because under federal regulations, the
foundation will have to give away roughly 5 percent of its assets a
year _ close to $1 billion with the current endowment, and more as
the assets grow.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, who for years have faulted the younger Gates for not
giving away more of his holdings, have suggested that his
philanthropic contributions do not stem from purely altruistic
motives: The huge gifts come at a time when both he and his company
are trying to bolster a public image damaged by the antitrust
fight, and the library-wiring objectives of the learning foundation
are hardly incompatible with the goals of his software company.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a huge amount of new money coming into the
philanthropic pipeline, and many of those in the health field say
that Gates' willingness to spend on vaccines could help bring about
major medical breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Gates understands that vaccines are like investing in
software,'' said Dr. Seth Berkley, president of the International
Aids Vaccine Initiative in New York City. ``You spend a fortune
getting it together, getting it right. Once you've got the
technology, and you know it works, then you can produce it cheaply
and use it globally.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Gates has made much the same point, and also said
that vaccines should be such a high priority because they carry
with them the promise of staving off tens of billions of dollars in
health-care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Berkley said of the Microsoft chairman, ``It's clear he's
delegated a lot of authority to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   And the responsibility is obviously a deeply serious one for the
elder Gates, who will soon be off on a trip to Nepal, Bangladesh
and Indonesia to study health programs.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While the elder Gates does not seem consumed with the mental
anguish that periodically visited the Rockefellers, he has
concluded that the problems the foundation hopes to alleviate are
immensely complicated, and not solvable only with money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The health problems of the underdeveloped world are
horrendous,'' he said, ``and there isn't enough money being devoted
to it to raise the slightest possibility of seriously affecting it
except over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the world is more humane than that sounds, because, in
fact, it's not exactly clear, if you had 10 times as much money,
what you would do with it,'' Gates said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Because there are environmental conditions that have to come
along, infrastructure, public attitude, political problems _ all of
those things have to play a role.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gates meets and exchanges e-mail frequently with his son
and daughter-in-law about foundation matters, he said he tried to
bother his son as little as possible when he had computer problems,
even with Microsoft programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the language of some of those messages that come
up,'' he said, shaking his head with a laugh. ``It just absolutely
drives me crazy. They are flat-out incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have an internal ambiguity about talking to my son,'' he
continued. ``In part I'm so angry at something that's happened that
I want to tell him about it. And in part I know he feels bad about
all that stuff, and I sort of hesitate to lay another problem on
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
