<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-CAPITAL-ART-6     09-11 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-CAPITAL-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA , AT DAWN OF A DEMOCRACY , FINDS MAKING LAWS IS NO PICNIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ His cell phone had been ringing with
increasingly urgent calls from his constituents: The quelea birds
were here! Locusts were coming!
</P>
<P>
   So quelea birds and locusts were the order of the day for
Suleiman Isyaku, one of the 360 members of Nigeria's brand new
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast in the cafeteria of the still-unfinished National
Assembly building, Isyaku, 35, explained the motion he would
present later in the day. The legislation _ a big step in his new
career as a lawmaker, a small one in his country's path toward
democracy _ would urge the minister of agriculture to ``take
immediate action with a view to combat'' quelea birds and locusts.
</P>
<P>
   The pesky migratory birds had been spotted in Isyaku's home
region, feasting on the millet, sorghum and other crops grown in
the Sahel area of northeast Nigeria. If that were not enough,
history showed that locusts would follow.
</P>
<P>
   A motion has no power of enforcement. But should the agriculture
minister not respond immediately, Isyaku said, he would attack him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say, `People are suffering because of him. He's inhuman,'
'' Isyaku said. ``I'll go on radio, on TV, in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Abuja is like that these days. Once the dormant capital of a
nation ruled by decrees quietly issued and then rigidly enforced by
Nigeria's military rulers, Abuja is abuzz with the noisy workings
of representative government.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation, has ended nearly 16
years of military rule, and its politicians have plunged into the
new system with typical Nigerian spirit: headlong, combatively and
with a reserve of jaw-dropping surprises.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Toronto has suddenly become the most famous foreign
city in Nigeria, after Ibrahim Salisu Buhari, who was the house
speaker and No. 4 in the government, said he was a graduate of the
University of Toronto. Also, he said, he was 36 years old, well
above the minimum age of 30 to be a House representative. Untrue
said a magazine called The News, in a story titled ``The Face of a
Liar.''
</P>
<P>
   After vehement denials, the 29-year-old, non-college-educated
speaker was forced to resign. Critics of the new lawmakers began
attacking them as ``Toronto'' politicians. As the Canadian city
became a code word for fraud, the politicians defended themselves
by saying that they were not, in fact, Toronto men.
</P>
<P>
   (The Senate president is also facing accusations in the media of
having lied about his age and academic credentials. But so far no
one appears to have produced irrefutable evidence to turn the No. 3
in the government into a Toronto politician.)
</P>
<P>
   In the face of these setbacks _ and others that followed _ new
lawmakers argued that they were all learning about democracy and
how to build it in a highly diverse country of 110 million people,
many of them with memories of nothing but military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Laoshe, a representative from Lagos, and other lawmakers
pointed out that since the military handed over power to a civilian
government, the executive branch was headed by President Olusegun
Obasanjo, a military ruler in the late 1970s, and other
recognizable faces. The ministries, too, were led by men known to
most Nigerians from the years of army dominance.
</P>
<P>
   And so the creation of the Senate and the House of
Representatives, they argued, were the areas where real progress
toward democratization had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole generation of Nigerians who don't know
anything about democracy,'' said Laoshe
</P>
<P>
   ``But democracy is this house,'' he said, referring to the
National Assembly building.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consider the quelea birds and locusts. Under previous military
regimes, farmers in northern Nigeria had been reduced to pleading
with military administrators for planes to spray pesticides. Given
the corruption and general lack of accountability, though, farmers
were never sure what the planes were releasing.
</P>
<P>
   One time, a plane _ carrying kerosene, it was later learned _
blew up in the sky. Another time, a plane was spraying water.
``Look at this madness,'' Isyaku said, recounting the farmers'
reaction. ``Spraying all day. Disturbing our families. And the
birds are not dying. So they attacked the pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   The farmers resorted to what Isyaku described as primitive
methods of repelling the tiny red-billed quelea birds, which
typically migrate in groups of hundreds of thousands, darken the
sky as they slowly circle above a field and then suddenly swoop
down to eat. The farmers shoot rifle rounds in the air. ``Or you
take the whole of your family,'' Isyaku added, ``and you scare them
away by shouting.''
</P>
<P>
   A real estate developer until recently, Isyaku said he was asked
by his village elders to run for the House seat, but not because he
had done remarkable things for his community. ``Honestly, there is
no big thing I did for them,'' he said. ``The only thing is maybe I
am a good boy, someone who doesn't smoke and drink, who respects
his elders.''
</P>
<P>
   His two brothers _ one also a developer, another one a
businessman involved in refined oil _ bankrolled his campaign to an
easy victory. The job was not what he had expected, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be easy work,'' Isyaku said of his
legislative duties, considered part-time in the Nigerian
Constitution. ``Come in the morning, one or two debates, then do
something else in the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were endless committee meetings in the afternoons, so
many documents to read in the evenings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to his government-supplied house, in the
Levittown-like government-designated neighborhood where most
legislators live in two-story duplexes, Isyaku pointed to the
balcony that he was planning to turn into a study for all the
unexpected work. ``It's like being a student again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers were installing tiles inside his three-bedroom house,
which like many of the legislators' houses was still undergoing
renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The houses, and especially the seemingly harmless issue of
furniture, have become sore spots for the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing military government had budgeted about $120,000 in
furniture for each representative. The members, arguing that the
figure was too high and that the furniture contractors were cronies
of the military, asked that it be reduced to $25,000 _ but that
they be given the money and allowed to buy their own furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The executive branch agreed, furniture makers swarmed into
Abuja, and the lawmakers suffered their biggest public relations
black eye to date.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the legislators would buy shoddy furniture and
pocket the difference. The lawmakers said they were saving
Nigerians money.
</P>
<P>
   ``That showed they are not fighting for change,'' said Adams
Oshiomhole, president of the Nigeria Labor Congress, the country's
biggest union umbrella group. ``They want the corrupt practices to
continue, but they want to be the beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Oshiomhole said that in the spirit of transparency, they should
have advertised for new bids in newspapers and not used the
military regime's budget as a yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   The union organized a huge rally here. Protesters shouted
``Thief!'' to lawmakers entering the National Assembly. They said
it was unseemly to hand out $25,000 for furniture in a country
where the lowest paid public workers were demanding a wage increase
_ to $35 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like all of them have a common interest, which is what
they can get for themselves,'' said Bashir Shehu, 32, who was
visiting the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Another visitor, Musa Abubakar, 57, was more generous. ``We have
to give them time,'' he said. ``Three months is not enough to judge
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular day, the National Assembly's two photocopiers
malfunctioned and delayed the start of the session by two hours.
The first motion, on flood disaster, sailed through the House.
</P>
<P>
   But time was running out to consider Isyaku's motion on quelea
birds and locusts. Besides, some members wanted to be heard on
another matter _ the poor state of their housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my tableware is now wet,'' said one representative whose
house had a leaking roof.
</P>
<P>
   Isyaku's motion would have to wait a day.
</P>
<P>
   After a recess was called, as he waited for an elevator, Isyaku
ran into Anthony Aziegbemi, one of 18 members who was co-sponsoring
his motion on quelea birds and locusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honorable, you were not able to present your motion on quelea
birds,'' said Aziegbemi, who is from the rain forest region and had
never seen a quelea bird.
</P>
<P>
   As the elevator door opened, Aziegbemi turned to Isyaku, two
politicians from two completely different corners of the country,
partners perhaps in the new Nigeria. The co-sponsor had a question:
</P>
<P>
   ``What are quelea birds anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
