<HEADER>
A8391 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-WILDERNESS-REVIEW-ART     09-11 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDERNESS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR EDEN: THE DEFINITION OF WILDERNESS IS INCREASINGLY
ELUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From the sandpiper-congested shores of the Copper
River Delta in Alaska to the hardwood forests of New England,
volunteers have been out with maps and magnifying glasses this
summer, trying to find scraps of the American Eden.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 4 percent, or 103 million acres, of the nation is
designated as protected wilderness. And this month, the 35th
anniversary of the law that allowed Congress to set aside public
land as forever wild, supporters of more wilderness say at least
another 100 million acres could be added to the system.
</P>
<P>
   But at century's end, the definition of what qualifies as true
wilderness in a country of 260 million people has never been more
elusive. And the purpose of setting aside land in its native state
has never been more contentious. American wilderness has long been
held up as a high esthetic, something that has a right to exist for
its own sake, even if nobody ever visits it. But increasingly,
there is a clamoring for open land as a playground for thrill
seekers propelled by ever-more-sophisticated toys.
</P>
<P>
   By law, wilderness is defined as ``an area where the earth and
its community life are untrammeled by man, where man himself is a
visitor who does not remain.'' The intent of the 1964 Wilderness
Act was to rope off a few areas from ``expanding settlement and
growing mechanization.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the biggest wilderness fight in the country is
centered in the slickrock canyons, leathered mesas and expanse of
rust-colored emptiness in central and southern Utah. It is a place
where a shout is never returned, even by echo, on most days. But it
is also part of what was perhaps the most densely populated area in
the America West _ the Anasazi Indian country of 1,000 years ago,
when perhaps as many 250,000 people lived in the broad area known
as the Colorado Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   The Anasazi, who sealed up their cliff homes and fled for
reasons that remain unclear, left behind thousands of petroglyphs
and pictographs _ the rock art of the Southwest. Wilderness
advocates say the area has returned to a sufficiently wild state,
and thus qualifies for protected status because it now meets the
standard of the law that protects land where ``the imprint of man's
work is substantially unnoticeable.''
</P>
<P>
   That standard has prompted opponents of protecting wilderness to
rush to scar land so that it will not fit the definition.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, people have been racing through the red rock country in
off-road vehicles, trying to imprint the ground with visible
tracks, which are then photographed and brought to Congressional
hearings. In Alaska, a rush is on by timber interests to build a
primitive road through the biggest wetland in North America _ the
Copper River Delta _ in part so it can then be considered
ineligible for future wilderness protection.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists have been just as busy, mapping and
photographing areas the size of tiny Eastern states that the
government has overlooked when it seeks out raw nature. In Utah,
they say they have found 8.8 million acres that could qualify as
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in this debate is the concept that wilderness and
humans should have nothing to do with each other _ that people have
no place in wild country, except as occasional visitors. Some
conservationists now say it may be time to allow a greater human
presence in the wild, which could actually open up more land for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   This idea of letting people have extended stays or even live in
the wilderness will soon be tested in Death Valley National Park,
where a deal is close to approval that would allow the 300-member
Timbisha Shoshone tribe to resume what are classified as
traditional activities over 300,000 acres of wild land. The tribe
has lived in the desert for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, which must be approved by Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt, the Indians would be allowed some hunting,
gathering and cultural activities _ but only the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some inherent conflicts,'' said William Meadows,
president of the Wilderness Society, which supports the tribe's
efforts. ``But we have to be careful not to read more into what
qualifies as traditional use of the land. I don't think using off
road vehicles to hunt would be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wilderness Act was created before Jet Skis, paragliding,
helicopter skiing and other outdoor thrill sports became so
popular. The law generally prohibits temporary roads or any motor
vehicle use. There are exceptions _ an airstrip in the Frank Church
River of No Return Wilderness in Idaho and roads to old mining
claims in Colorado among them.
</P>
<P>
   But the participants of the new outdoor sports are knocking on
the door of wilderness, asking to be let in. Aldo Leopold, the most
influential early proponent of wilderness, traversed the Gila
National Forest in New Mexico on horseback. In is unlikely he
envisioned a day when people would want to glide over the same area
with nylon wings.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, like Washington's Sawtooth Range in the North
Cascades, the divisions are jarring. A sign on weather-bent trees
delineates wild land from the non-wild. On one side, the serrated
sound of all-terrain vehicles rises up to what is supposed to be an
area untrammeled by man.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when the latest numbers from the Dow Jones industrial
average are flashed into once-private corners, wilderness is
trumpeted as the last hideout from the storm of modern times. Huck
Finn, Walt Whitman and Crazy Horse were evoked when the act was
signed in 1964; wilderness was said to simply be part of the
American DNA.
</P>
<P>
   And later, writer Wallace Stegner memorably labeled wilderness
``the geography of hope'' and argued that it should never have to
prove its utility to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply need that wild country available to us,'' Stegner
wrote, ``even if we never do more than drive to its edge and look
in.'' The question now is whether the road to the edge belongs in
the American idea of wilderness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
