<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Sept. 12, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, Indonesia) _ Guarded by a tight cordon of
security, the streets of East Timor's capital shattered and still
smoking around him, the chief of Indonesia's armed forces, Gen.
Wiranto, conceded Saturday that he had lost control of elements of
his military. And although Wiranto said he was becoming more open
to help from foreign troops, he added that the time was still not
right. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JIANG (Auckland, New Zealand) _ President Clinton and
China's leader, Jiang Zemin, declared an end Saturday to months of
frozen relations following the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, and ordered their trade ministers to meet on Sunday in
hopes of closing a broad deal that would get China into the World
Trade Organization this year. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-CAPITAL (Abuka, Nigeria) _ Once a dormant capital of a
nation ruled by decrees meted out quietly by Nigeria's military
rulers, Abuja is today abuzz with the noisy workings of
representative government. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and a map.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Berlin) _ Marking a clear break with the
caution of German foreign policy since World War II, Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder has laid out a new vision of his country's
international role, describing Germany as ``a great power in
Europe'' that will not hesitate to pursue its national interests.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LAUNDER (Moscow) _ Irritated by allegations of money
laundering, some of Russia's leading businessmen insist that the
West has overlooked a simpler explanation for the billions of
dollars that have flowed through several suspicious accounts at the
Bank of New York: the old game of dodging Russian tariffs and
taxes. By Celestine Bohlen and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KGB-KENNEDY (Washington) _ The KGB fabricated evidence linking
the CIA to the assassination of President John F. Kennedy and
passed the material to unwitting conspiracy theorists in the United
States, according to a new book based on KGB files brought to the
West by a former Soviet officer. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CULT (Tokyo) _ Underscoring the immense fear that the Aum
Shinrikyo religious sect invokes in Japan, a growing number of
cities are using public money to drive its followers out of town,
often buying property owned by the doomsday cult. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-HOLOCAUST (Paris) _ Two members of a commission set up by
the French government in 1997 to establish the facts about the
looting of property from Jews in France during World War II come to
Washington this week to tell American officials that France will
not flinch from a full and final accounting for its actions. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Mendoza, Argentina) _ Domingo Cavallo, the
former economy minister credited with whipping Argentina's
hyperinflation in the early 1990s, will almost certainly run a
distant third in the presidential election next month. But he will
probably have long enough coattails to elect a substantial
congressional delegation for his small conservative party, and
there is an outside chance he could throw the election into a
second round, which could give him decisive bargaining power over
future economic policy. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and a map.
</P>
