<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SUV-PROBLEM-2TAKES-LA     09-11 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-PROBLEM-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE CARNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 
PARKING LOTS NOT DESIGNED FOR SUVs' SIZE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Sport-utility vehicles -- those rolling behemoths
with armored bumpers and beefy tires -- are built to conquer
wide-open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, all they conquer are parking spaces -- many
too small to fit SUVs and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   When Andee Pariser wedged her 78-inch-wide Ford Expedition into
a compact space only 96 inches wide, she knew it would be a
nightmare for drivers squeezing in on either side and trying to
open their doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if somebody keys me sometime, because
I do get pretty close,'' said the 38-year-old, trying to wriggle
into her SUV, jammed up against a small car. ``Nowadays you really
should make larger spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally. parking experts are starting to listen.
</P>
<P>
   As sales of SUVs and pickups continue to outpace cars,
parking-lot designers, city planners and even parking enforcement
bureaus are scrambling to deal with difficulties posed by these
oversized vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Burbank city planners ordered two developers to
reduce the number of compact spaces in their projects to fit an
expected crush of SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   International Parking Design Inc. has begun advising its clients
to allot 10 percent fewer compact spaces than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto police have begun ticketing SUVs that overrun compact
spots, while Los Angeles's parking bureau is considering whether to
change its rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems will only get worse as Americans continue
buying big.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want the capability of off-road, whether or not they
just go to the supermarket,'' said Michael Pak, a research analyst
who studies the auto industry for the New York brokerage firm ING
Barings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the empowerment notion. But common sense dictates it
would be hard to find parking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, three of the five top-selling vehicles in the country
were full-size pickup trucks -- the Ford F-series, Chevrolet C/K
and Dodge Ram. The Ford Explorer SUV ranked third, and the only
passenger car was the fourth-place Toyota Camry. The combined
number of Camrys and Honda Accords -- the most popular passenger
cars -- still didn't equal the number of Ford pickups sold last
year, 830,000 to 836,000. And for 2000, Ford is coming out with its
Excursion SUV -- a massive 80 inches wide and 226.7 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Los Angeles still allows up to 40 percent compact spaces for
all parking lots and garages with 10 or more slots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty percent is very high,'' said Los Angeles city planner
Reuben Arceo. The limit was 15 percent in other cities he's worked,
such as Montebello and La Habra.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles requires that parking spaces be 108 inches wide and
240 inches long, while compact spaces can be 96 by 180 inches, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people don't abide by the compact stall rules, that's
when you have problems,'' Arceo said. ``The complaints are rising
-- from slamming or jamming doors, an inability to get out, and
large vehicles parking in these areas that are supposed to be for
smaller vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Compact spaces started appearing in parking lots after the gas
crises of the the 1970s, when motorists began buying compact and
subcompact cars. But now the economy is booming, gas prices are at
an all-time low when adjusted for inflation, and drivers no longer
want to fold themselves into Matchbox cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proliferation of large vehicles has been coming over the
last few years. There are far fewer compacts to full-size than
there used to be,'' said Greg Parker, senior project manager at
International Parking Design, the 30-year-old consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUES ON SECOND TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen grown men come close to begging,'' he said.
``Parking is such a critical issue to merchants. The City Council
is usually sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many cities, in order to avoid those problems, avoid compact
parking altogether. But some don't. They're trying to be
business-friendly,'' Arceo said.
</P>
<P>
   Pariser said she tries not to use compact spaces, but does
sometimes so she won't have to haul her two small children across a
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally try to be cognizant of other people, because I know
my car is large,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lieberman parked his Explorer beside another SUV, both in
compact spaces. The 60-year-old said he thinks compact car drivers
should park only in compact spaces, leaving regular-sized spaces
for SUVs and larger vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to squeeze in and worry about hitting somebody else's
car. I'd actually search for regular space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Linda Kenworthy said her Chevrolet Camaro is even too large
for some compact spaces she's seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have larger vehicles, we should have larger spaces,''
she said. ``It's ridiculous. I think the subcompact days are
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbank is reacting to the end of that era. Noting the
proliferation of SUVs, pickups, minivans and other large vehicles,
the Planning Board there asked two developers to cut back on their
compact spaces in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't work that well anymore. There's more and more
behemoths on the road and less and less small economy cars,'' said
Greg Jackson, Planning Board vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   One of the projects, a 16-screen AMC movie theater downtown,
lost all but 12 compact spaces out of the 1,200 total parking
spaces planned, said Fred Bruning, president of Center Oak
Properties of Torrance, the theater developer. His company erased
49 compact spaces, but the project will still have a surplus of
parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, customers will reward that by buying a lot of
tickets and a lot of popcorn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruning, who himself drives a Jeep Cherokee, added, ``People
will tend to abuse the compact-car only policy. You can go into any
lot anywhere in any town and find that SUV parked in two compact
spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens in Palo Alto, the SUV might have a ticket on its
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, police there began enforcing a new ordinance against
big cars, trucks and other vehicles parking in compact spaces.
Anything more than 72 inches wide or 180 inches long has to circle
the lot again, or the driver risks a $30 citation.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto police agent Jim Coffman said that, when someone has
parked too close to his driver's-side door, to get in ``I've had to
climb over the center console of the police car. That's not a
pretty sight.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Los Angeles, Arnold Schwarzenegger could cram his Hummer
(a whopping 86.5 inches wide) into a compact space and never get
into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City Council has yet to address anything about this
issue,'' said Rudy Carrasco, parking enforcement manager with the
city's Department of Transportation. ``We don't have anything like
that on the books in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the example of Palo Alto, Carrasco said L.A.'s
Office of Parking Management is looking at the problem, but so far
``we are not pursuing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's slow progress is not unusual, though, as parking
strategies nationwide still lag far behind what is actually rolling
into the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, with International Parking Design, said he believes that
in coming years vehicle sizes will start to settle in some middle
range -- between the Miatas and the Expeditions of the world. And
his firm is working on designs for a universal parking space that
will fit them all.
</P>
<P>
   The Burbank Planning Department is also crunching the problem,
and the Planning Board and City Council expect to vote on a
one-size-fits-all space in November and December, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But what will fill those universal spaces remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the economy, gas prices, environmental rules and
consumers' whims will ultimately decide what vehicles become
popular in the future -- and just how big their parking spaces will
have to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complexity of parking -- it's a very critical issue,'' he
said. ``It is very important, and it's much more involved than
anybody realizes.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
