<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8404 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-RDP-480(2TAKES)     09-11 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-RDP-480(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKARTA CONCEDES A LOSS OF CONTROL IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ Guarded by a tight cordon of security, the
streets of East Timor's capital shattered and still smoking around
him, the chief of Indonesia's armed forces, Gen. Wiranto, conceded
Saturday that he had lost control of elements of his military.
</P>
<P>
   On a tense and eerie visit with a high-level U.N. delegation to
this small seaside town, Wiranto said he was becoming more open to
help from foreign troops but added that the time was still not
right for their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was still struggling to persuade his men on the
ground to crack down on East Timorese militias, to which he said
they felt an emotional allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not reject the offer of an accelerated deployment of an
international peacekeeping force at all,'' he said. ``The offer of
an international peacekeeping force must be considered as an option
by the Indonesian government.''
</P>
<P>
   Making his statement a second time, he changed his reference
from ``peacekeeping force,'' to ``security cooperation,'' prompting
a U.N. official to describe his words as ``Delphic.''
</P>
<P>
   International pressure for foreign peacekeepers to deploy in
East Timor has mounted in recent days as militias aligned with
Wiranto's forces ransacked the island territory, terrorizing and
killing hundreds of inhabitants and driving tens of thousands from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton suspended arms sales to Indonesia, and in
remarks on Air Force One en route to New Zealand for an Asian
economic summit said it was clear that the Indonesian military was
aiding and abetting the violence.
</P>
<P>
   In New Zealand, the president was asked about a timetable for
Indonesian agreement to deployment of an international peacekeeping
force, and replied: ``Well, I think you'll see a development here
in the next couple of days. I think something will happen. I'd be
surprised if it doesn't. We're working, not just the U.S., people
all over the world are working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials traveling here with the five-member delegation from
the U.N. Security Council said it was not yet clear what effect
Wiranto's statement might have on East Timor. Its inhabitants voted
on Aug. 30 for independence from Indonesia, which invaded and
annexed the territory after Portugal abandoned its colony in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   As the Timor Sea sparkled in the sunlight, Dili was silent and
nearly deserted Saturday. Large groups of refugees sat at the
roadsides, surrounded by piles of belongings and staring dully at
the passing convoy of dignitaries. Behind them, shattered
buildings, looted and roofless, still smoldered.
</P>
<P>
   But with hundreds of armed soldiers lining the delegation's
route, Dili was calm for the first time since the vote. ``A
Potemkin operation,'' said Sir Jeremy Greenstock, the British
representative at the United Nations. ``But they can't cover up
what happened in Dili. The place has been trashed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The message this scene sent may not have been the one intended
by the Indonesian authorities. ``It illustrates that you can never
know whether these people are going to switch it on or switch it
off,'' Greenstock said, referring to the violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the U.N. compound, with its 1,000 refugees and its
exhausted staff, was reported to be a place of terror, with militia
gunshots, looting and threats unrestrained _ and even aided _ by
uniformed soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it appeared to be one of the most secure places on
earth, ringed by ranks of alert, all-business soldiers with
automatic rifles at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first day we can see the sky _ yesterday, it was
dark with smoke,'' said Nick Birnback, one of 80 U.N. workers who
insisted on remaining here to protect the refugees when the bulk of
the staff was forced to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, there was not a gunshot to be heard in this largely
abandoned town, which one diplomat compared to Phnom Penh in
Cambodia after it was emptied of its residents by the Khmer Rouge
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few thin columns of gray smoke rose into the blue sky
from burning buildings here.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the efforts made to sanitize the city and despite
the blithe and smiling officers who escorted the delegation,
Wiranto voiced something approaching angst.
</P>
<P>
   His orders to halt the violence and restore calm had not yet
been obeyed, he implied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be something which has caused there to be such big
problems,'' he said, ``whether it was caused by a technical or
psychological problem, or perhaps by a false procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have checked in the field, and I concluded that the main
problem is a psychological constraint among our personnel on the
ground _ those who have been living with the East Timorese for so
long,'' he said. ``For more than 20 years, our personnel have been
working hand in hand with the people to develop East Timor. I can
understand that it is very hard for them to shoot their own people,
who have been regarded as their brothers, and who are not really
criminals. And they defend their basic principles emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would take time and delicacy to pull his soldiers
into line, and he asked the outside world for understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his statement about peacekeeping forces reflected a
change in his policy, Wiranto said, ``Yes, yes. It's very
complicated, not only in the region. It's an international problem,
and other countries have their opinions on East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all members of the delegation accepted Wiranto's
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason to think that they are having major
difficulties controlling the situation,'' said an official
traveling with the delegation, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``Look at today and look at election day when everything was
brought under control with the snap of a finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a coordinated and planned campaign _ evacuating
towns, assassinating moderate leaders, moving huge numbers of
people into forced exile _ that it could only have come from the
top,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since invading East Timor in 1975, the Indonesian military has
waged an unending war against separatist guerrillas and forged
close links with those East Timorese who want to remain part of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a remote and small province of Indonesia with
just 800,000 inhabitants, East Timor holds a crucial place in the
history and ethos of the country's military. This territory is
where most senior officers have earned their stripes, where many
have put down roots and grown wealthy, and where thousands of their
comrades have died.
</P>
<P>
   The military, which has played a key role in Indonesia since
this country _ the world's fourth largest _ won independence from
the Dutch in 1945, also apparently fears that losing East Timor
could lead to the loss of other rebellious and remote regions.
</P>
<P>
   When President B.J. Habibie declared in January that East Timor
could go free if it rejected his offer of an autonomous status
within Indonesia, the military responded by recruiting and arming
irregular militias in a clear attempt to undercut the referendum on
independence.
</P>
<P>
   That policy, which Wiranto may have fostered or tolerated at the
wishes of officers dedicated to maintaining their hold on East
Timor, appears in recent weeks to have slipped beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   Alphons Hamer, a Dutch representative to the United Nations and
a member of the delegation here, said Habibie told the envoys when
they were in Jakarta that a principal reason for resisting
peacekeeping forces was the damage their introduction would do to
the reputation of the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a military man, it must be worrying, to say the least, to
see your orders not going down and information not reaching up,''
Hamer said.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after the military reacted to the international outcry
by declaring martial law in East Timor, Wiranto's newly appointed
commander here, Maj. Gen. Kiki Shahnakri, indicated Saturday that
progress in restoring control was slow.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the introduction of five battalions of fresh troops,
he said, just 27 weapons had been confiscated from the militias
that have taken over much of the province.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing in the military headquarters _ one of the few
substantial buildings in Dili not to have been vandalized _
Greenstock pressed Kiki forcefully to protect the U.N. headquarters
here.
</P>
<P>
   If not, he said, using the initials for the Indonesian military,
``you must realize that TNI will have to carry the responsibility
for that failure,'' adding, ``The Security Council mission is
therefore asking you, commander, to make absolutely sure that
security for Unamet is comprehensive and continuous.'' Unamet is
the acronym for the U.N. mission here.
</P>
<P>
   The general replied, ``I fully realize what you are saying, and
I am willing to do all I can to secure Unamet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
