<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-EXP-TIMES-EXPRESSBUDG     09-11 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-TIMES-EXPRESS </SLUG>
 BUDGET-NYT  
(jt)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the top Times Express stories planned for Sunday, Sept.
12. The N.Y. Times News Service night supervisor is Ned Kilkelly;
phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-TIMOR-RDP (Dili, Indonesia) _ Guarded by a tight cordon of
security, the streets of East Timor's capital shattered and still
smoking around him, the chief of Indonesia's armed forces, Gen.
Wiranto, conceded Saturday that he had lost control of elements of
his military. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-CLINTON-JIANG (Auckland, New Zealand) _ President Clinton
and China's leader, Jiang Zemin, declared an end Saturday to months
of frozen relations following the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, and ordered their trade ministers to meet on Sunday in
hopes of closing a broad deal that would get China into the World
Trade Organization this year. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-NIGERIA-CAPITAL (Abuka, Nigeria) _ Once a dormant capital of
a nation ruled by decrees meted out quietly by Nigeria's military
rulers, Abuja is today abuzz with the noisy workings of
representative government. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-GERMANY-POLITICS (Berlin) _ Marking a clear break with the
caution of German foreign policy since World War II, Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder has laid out a new vision of his country's
international role, describing Germany as ``a great power in
Europe'' that will not hesitate to pursue its national interests.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-RUSSIA-LAUNDER (Moscow) _ Irritated by allegations of money
laundering, some of Russia's leading businessmen insist that the
West has overlooked a simpler explanation for the billions of
dollars that have flowed through several suspicious accounts at the
Bank of New York: the old game of dodging Russian tariffs and
taxes. By Celestine Bohlen and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-KGB-KENNEDY (Washington) _ The KGB fabricated evidence
linking the CIA to the assassination of President John F. Kennedy
and passed the material to unwitting conspiracy theorists in the
United States, according to a new book based on KGB files brought
to the West by a former Soviet officer. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-JAPAN-CULT (Tokyo) _ Underscoring the immense fear that the
Aum Shinrikyo religious sect invokes in Japan, a growing number of
cities are using public money to drive its followers out of town,
often buying property owned by the doomsday cult. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-FRANCE-HOLOCAUST (Paris) _ Two members of a commission set
up by the French government in 1997 to establish the facts about
the looting of property from Jews in France during World War II
come to Washington this week to tell American officials that France
will not flinch from a full and final accounting for its actions.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Mendoza, Argentina) _ Domingo Cavallo,
the former economy minister credited with whipping Argentina's
hyperinflation in the early 1990s, will almost certainly run a
distant third in the presidential election next month. But he will
probably have long enough coattails to elect a substantial
congressional delegation for his small conservative party, and
there is an outside chance he could throw the election into a
second round, which could give him decisive bargaining power over
future economic policy. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-FORD-POLLUTION-FIGHT (Detroit) _ Mark Pickrell used to be a
lawyer for Big Tobacco. Now he's representing a one-man Internet
site against Ford, and contends that the auto industry's handling
of sport utility vehicles' air pollution and poor fuel economy is
just like the tobacco industry's handling of smoking issues. Ralph
Nader agrees, and has coincidentally asked the Justice Department
to reopen an antitrust investigation from the 1960s into whether
Detroit colludes not to put advanced pollution-control equipment on
automobiles. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-CONGRESS-2000 (Washington) _ The battle for control of
Congress in 2000 has set off a furious tug-of-war among House and
Senate leaders within both parties who are competing to recruit the
best candidates with hard-sell appeals and enticements like choice
committee assignments and fund-raising help. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-CHEMICAL-ACCIDENTS (Washington) _ Environmental advocates
have published on the Internet new information about the risks of
chemical accidents, outflanking an attempt by industry groups and
security agencies to suppress the information on the grounds that
the details could help terrorist groups. By Carl Hulse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
