<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TWENTYFOUR-SEVEN-REVI     09-11 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWENTYFOUR-SEVEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
24/7: REDEFINING A LIFE OF NONSTOP POSSIBILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks like a top-heavy fraction whose value is a bit larger
than Pi. But to trend watchers, the expression ``24/7'' has worked
its way into the language as an abbreviation for a clock-defying
world where financial markets run continually and news channels
promise never-ending headlines (along with weather and traffic
reports).
</P>
<P>
   Log on to Slate, Microsoft's online magazine, and you'll find a
section called ``24/seven'' that contains columns and e-mails to
the editor. Redbook magazine had ``24/7'' for quick recipes and
life-style tips. United Airlines has used it in an advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out how 24/7 became popular, though, is almost a 24/7
proposition in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how it got into the vernacular,'' said Kurt
Jenkins, a graphic designer who uses the Web address www.24-7.com.
``It's a younger people's saying.'' (This from someone who is all
of 29.)
</P>
<P>
   Chris Wilson, the entrepreneur who owns Jenkins' address and
about 200 others containing alphanumeric variations on 24-7, agreed
that it probably originated with people under 30. ``It began as a
kind of a Generation X term to describe the Internet,'' he said.
``We figured that a lot of older people had tried to capture this
catch phrase with symbols and logos, but they missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world where speed counts, syllables are precious. ``It's
just too long to say `24 hours, 7 days a week,' so it was
abbreviated,'' said Andrew Nelson of Britannica.com, the online arm
of the venerable Encyclopaedia Britannica. ``In the Web world, 24/7
is the shorthand for saying `We're live all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Is it written 24/7 (with the numbers separated by a slash)? Or
simply the consecutive digits 2, 4 and 7? `` 24/7 is the way it
should be written,'' Wilson said, ``but on the Internet the only
punctuation is a dash. I think a lot of people rushed to capture it
and they missed the boat.'' The dash is crucial, he said. ``You
look at 247 and think, `What's that?'' A 7-Eleven doesn't say
`711.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dictionaries have yet to take note of 24/7. Not even Microsoft's
new Encarta, which has entries for ``twenty questions'' and
``twenty-twenty,'' defines it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the monumental Random House Historical Dictionary
of American Slang; its third volume, covering entries from P to Z,
has yet to be completed. The project editor, Jesse Sheidlower, said
recently that he had not reached the T's, but 24/7 was certain to
be included. ``The definition will probably be something very
simple like `constantly,''' he said. ``It doesn't mean 24 hours a
day, seven days a week. It refers to things that can't literally be
24 hours a day, seven days a week. We have an example like running
the vacuum cleaner 24/7 for two days in a row.'' Not possible, he
said. ``If you had an example like `He was happy 24/7' or `He was
stoned 24/7,' you'll never know if that's absolutely literal. It
probably means `most of the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not to terrified executives who dread having to deal with
round-the-clock customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Shannon, a co-founder and chief creative officer of
agency.com, a New York Internet advertising agency, remembers a
strategy session with one high-powered client a couple of years
ago. ``I was talking about the nature of the Internet and how it's
this two-way thing, not just putting messages out but getting
messages back,'' he said. ``She went, `Oh, my God.' She said, `This
Internet thing, it's like a 24/7 focus group.'''
</P>
<P>
   The sociologist Stephen Bertman maintains that the ``social
speedometer'' has continued to climb in the 1990s. ``We are now
nearing a velocity called `warp speed,''' he wrote in
``Hyperculture: The Human Cost of Speed'' (Praeger, 1998). ``It is
one that can, if we are not wise enough or strong enough, warp the
fundamental nature of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, 24/7 is defined as when people are sitting at a
computer,'' Shannon said. ``But the Palm VII and interactive
television are coming. Right now the Internet is a place you log on
to. It's going to become like a dial tone, all pervasive. That will
be real 24/7.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0102 </DOCNO>
