<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHERE ARE THE AGASSI AND SAMPRAS HEIRS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I have to admit that I have not spent much time
worrying where the next great American tennis player is coming
from, or if he is going to come at all before Y3K. Maybe this will
become a priority concern when Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi are
finished carrying the men's game around on their backs like a sack
of potatoes, but, definitely, no sooner than that.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there is no American male heir apparent to Sampras
and Agassi frequently comes up in conversations, especially at this
U.S. Open, which lost Sampras to a back injury. Lo and behold, it
managed to survive that potential calamity all the way to
Saturday's semifinals. If you are of the mind that we need our guys
to authenticate our tournament, then give a bare-chested salute to
Agassi and a shake of the fist to Todd Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Both Americans are 29, which is practically prehistoric in a
sport where the ball has more fuzz than many of the unlined faces
you can stroll past any day in the locker room. Yet here was
Martin, who moves stiffly around the court as if his limbs are
fastened to his body by nuts and screws, first on in the Ashe
Stadium Saturday against France's unseeded veteran, Cedric Pioline.
And then came Agassi, playing more tenaciously than he ever has for
much of this summer, against the talented but unpredictable
Russian, Yevgeny Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
   With all the talk about the sorry shape of men's tennis and the
shaky state of the sport in this country overall, we boosters may
console ourselves with the conclusion that whatever the problem may
be, it's not the Americans. On both sides of the draw, men and
women, we have been holding up our end, and then some. Counting the
sensational Williams sisters and Lindsay Davenport, five of the
eight Open semifinalists were homegrown. And of the first six Grand
Slam singles titles already won this year, half have been claimed
by Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   I know many of my fellow baby boomers are too busy fondling
their five irons and the tennis ratings don't reflect this, but we
are a long way from the days of Ivan Lendl versus Miloslav Mecir.
This is a time that tennis people, who have the annoying habit of
lamenting lost days while hoping for better ones ahead, will fondly
recall.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, 28, has been the decade's dominant men's player.
Agassi, alternately brilliant and invisible, has managed to win all
four slam events in his career, one of the most diverse
achievements in a single sport. Until this past year, Michael Chang
was a top-five fixture. Jim Courier had a nice run, especially in
Paris, early in the early 1990s. Martin, back from an assortment of
injuries to claim the No. 7 seed at the Open, has been a solid if
unspectacular pro right on through.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, with the exception of a Stefan Edberg
here, a Boris Becker there, that world out there has been serving
up a diet of hardcourt fakers and hangdog chokers. Marcelo Rios?
Give me a break.
</P>
<P>
   Next great American? If a dry spell is inevitable _ and I say if
because no one can say when another Agassi will announce himself _
then give our tennis academies a chance, and some needed and
deserved time. Let the Germans and the Swedes, the Czechs and the
French churn out a few colorful champions until we can replenish
the well. Sampras will recover to renew his bid to bypass Roy
Emerson, and Agassi will continue to mine his magnificent tennis
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say at this stage of my life I'm appreciating the
opportunities I have in my career more than ever,'' he said. ``The
motivation really seems to come rather easily now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the decade's noblest names have been stepping aside at
an alarming rate, it is hard to believe Agassi is pushing 30, the
great adult hope with Sampras not around. The one-time teen idol
and shaggy dog is as passe to the kids as a Beanie Baby, but I
recall being at Stratton Mountain, Vt., when Agassi first showed
himself 13 years ago, with his blond punk hairdo with the garish
black highlights. Early in a match against this strange-looking
kid, John McEnroe hit a short approach shot and Agassi nearly
beheaded him with a vicious forehand pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who the hell is this?'' McEnroe said, looking up to his good
friends in the press section behind the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career, Agassi admittedly has allowed his career
to be defined by a lousy work ethic, which has also enabled him to
reinvent himself at an age when Borg, McEnroe, Wilander and Becker
were, for various reasons, finished as Grand Slam forces. Rare has
been the tennis player who has made himself better at Agassi's
advanced age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it depends on the individual why an athlete breaks
down,'' Agassi said. ``My game never left me. I fell in the
rankings because I wasn't in shape. But I think athletes playing
great sports into their mid-30s has been proven by a number of
people, not just in tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, 30-plus tennis champions have been the rarest of
exceptions recently. Trust me. We won't need Agassi and Sampras to
hang on until 3000. Just a few more. The next great Americans were
out there Saturday, watching Agassi and Martin, the way they
watched the Williamses and Lindsay Davenport, too. Baby boomers are
aging, and interest in tennis here is waning. As long as we have
champions, it isn't dying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
