</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JIANG-905(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JIANG HEAL RIFT AND SET NEW TRADE COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ President Clinton and China's leader,
Jiang Zemin, declared an end Saturday to months of frozen relations
following the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, and ordered their trade ministers to meet on Sunday in
hopes of closing a broad deal that would get China into the World
Trade Organization this year.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. and Chinese officials emerged from the hourlong
meeting, on the fringes of the annual Asian economic summit
conference, brimming with confident assessments of the encounter.
It was the first between the two leaders in over a year.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials appeared particularly pleased that Clinton had
been openly critical of President Lee Teng Hui of Taiwan for his
statements over the summer that described the island as a separate
state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, according to his national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, told Jiang that Lee ``had made things more difficult for
both China and the United States'' with his comments, which
appeared to inch Taiwan toward independence. But Berger said that
Clinton repeated a warning that if China resorted to military force
against Taiwan ``there would be grave consequences in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the meeting was consumed with discussion of the final
deal to usher China into the World Trade Organization, which would
give the Chinese prestige and protection from economic sanctions
and trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton walked away from a deal in April, during a visit to
Washington by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China, but soon came to
regret the decision.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications, any final deal negotiated in coming days or
weeks is likely to closely resemble the offers to open markets that
Clinton judged insufficient five months ago. The soured political
atmosphere between the two countries appears to have affected the
White House assessment of what constitutes a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   After the accidental embassy bombing, which killed three
Chinese, and charges of nuclear spying by the Chinese in U.S.
weapons laboratories, Clinton's aides apparently view the trade
accord as the one concrete step they can take to begin to repair
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now is how quickly a deal can be struck. The U.S.
trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky, is expected to open
talks on Sunday with her Chinese counterpart on the three big
remaining differences: automobiles, textiles and the rules that
prevent Chinese industry from ``dumping'' products in the United
States at below-market prices.
</P>
<P>
   One U.S. official said that ``with the dose of political will,
this is stuff that can be worked out in two days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's national economic adviser, Gene Sperling,
cautioned against expecting an agreement while the two leaders are
in New Zealand for the summit meeting and simultaneous state
visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there's enough issues that are on the table that
I would not have significant expectations over the next several
days,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   China's spokesman, Zhu Bangzao, also declined to estimate how
long the negotiations might take.
</P>
<P>
   ``China will never accept terms that exceed the economic
capacity of the country,'' he said, referring to the fear in China
that opening markets at a time of severe economic downturn would
worsen unemployment and deflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the United States is flexible, I don't think the
accession will be that difficult,'' he said, using the term for the
process of joining the trade organization. ``But if the U.S.
persists in its high demands, that will be difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States the advantage of an agreement is
straightforward: All of the concessions and reductions of trade
barriers come from the Chinese, with none from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For China, membership is a mixed bag. While it must agree to
open its highly protected markets to foreign competition, as a
member of the trade group it would gain protection against
unilateral sanctions by all of its trading partners. Disputes would
go to the World Trade Organization's court, and China would be able
to challenge efforts by the United States and others to restrict
imports of its goods.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the deal will most likely prove politically difficult
in both countries. At a time of growing economic troubles in China,
Jiang risks accusations that he is allowing the world's most
powerful economy too much access to China's markets. The complaints
have been particularly strong in the telecommunications industry
because the deal proposed in April would allow foreign companies to
own a majority share of Chinese cellular telephone concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton must worry about a possible revolt in his own party, one
that would particularly hurt Vice President Al Gore's candidacy for
next year's presidential race. Labor unions have already protested
White House trade policy and some have withheld endorsements of
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the United States' biggest unions say they will actively
oppose any trade deal with China. They are particularly incensed
about China's insistence that the United States agree to curb its
powers to act unilaterally in dumping cases. China is already at
the center of several dumping charges.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Jiang went into detail about these problems
at the session on Saturday, according to officials who were
present. They will leave the hard slogging to the trade
negotiators.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders would step in only to resolve serious logjams,''
said one Clinton aide.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang seemed particularly eager to score points on Saturday at
Taiwan's expense, telling Clinton, according to Berger, that the
question of the island's status was ``the most important'' of the
questions Clinton raised on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At a photo session as the two leaders were sitting down, Jiang
said in response to a reporter's question, ``If there were to be
any foreign intervention, or if there were to be Taiwan
independence, then we would not undertake to renounce the use of
force.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that U.S. policy toward Taiwan had not changed.
He was apparently seeking to defuse Chinese suspicions that the
United States was behind Lee's statements that talks between Taiwan
and the mainland constituted ``state-to-state relations.'' The
United States has recognized only one China since President Nixon's
opening to Beijing a quarter of a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We favor one China,'' Clinton said in the presence of
reporters, eager to show he was not diverging from the policy of
Democrats and Republicans before him. ``We favor a peaceful
approach to working out our differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang urged Clinton to stop arms sales to Taiwan, particularly
recent sales intended to counter growing missile threats to the
country. Clinton declined, citing the requirements of the Taiwan
Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton briefly raised human-rights concerns, and Jiang
responded by describing the recent crackdown on Falun Gong, a
religious group that has attracted a huge following and that staged
a silent demonstration outside the Chinese leaders' compound in
Beijing in April.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang called Falun Gong ``a cult,'' and gave Clinton some books
about it. Presumably they were officially sanctioned volumes that
disparaged a group that the apparently rattled Chinese government
banned in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
