A8442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-11 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO LUCK INVOLVED HERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One believes in luck, the other does not. But neither
Martina Hingis nor Serena Williams believes in sitting around and
waiting for the propitious moment to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis and Williams would meet Saturday afternoon for the
women's championship at the U.S. Open, in which the women _ with
their long points, strong personalities, skill and steel flashes of
glamour; yes, even the bickering and the infighting _ have been far
more captivating than the men.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis has tried to keep girls in their early teens from the
hurly-burly of the circuit, the so-called Capriati Rule. But at
this Open, three of the four semifinalists were still under 20, and
all four are making women in their late 20s almost outmoded.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists do disagree on the subject of luck. Serena
Williams does not want to dwell on it, while Martina Hingis courts
its will-of-the-wisp existence.
</P>
<P>
   The Czechoslovakian-born Hingis and the American Williams are
surely too young to be versed in the collective wisdom of the late
Charles Dillon Stengel, who once simultaneously taught philosophy
and managed the New York Mets just across the boardwalk at Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make your own luck,'' Stengel preached.
</P>
<P>
   And Branch Rickey, builder of baseball clubs, was known to say,
``Luck is the residue of design.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, known in her family as the combative one,
believes nobody gave her anything, en route to her first Grand Slam
final.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis works no less hard than Serena, or Lindsay Davenport or
Venus Williams, for that matter. But Hingis reserves the right to
receive that inexplicable ray of light that lands on the impartial
but human mind of a line judge or the fickle frame of a racquet.
</P>
<P>
   One case in point was the first semifinal Friday in which Serena
Williams, approaching 18, outlasted Davenport, all of 23. As Serena
broke Davenport in the seventh game of the third set, one clunker
of a return somehow wobbled over the net to produce a vital point.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 17 years, I say I deserve a break once in a while,
too,'' Serena said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was asked how much luck is involved in surviving the
demolition derby of two weeks in Flushing Meadows, which lost both
Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter to injuries. ``I had a pretty lucky
shot today with that one return,'' Serena Williams said. ``I don't
much believe in luck. I think it's skill. You go out there and you
fight and you work. You don't work hard to have luck; you work hard
to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I'm not lucky,'' Williams added. ``I have to go
sweat in the sun every day when I could be at the pool with some
lemonade. That's not luck; that's work. I'm sure Pat, when he won
his Slams, Pete, I'm sure they were doing a little sweating, too.
It wasn't necessarily luck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second semifinal, Venus Williams, who reached 19 in June,
was outlasted by Hingis, who turns 19 on Sept. 30. One key play,
while Venus was trying to hang on with thigh cramps, was a lunging
backhand stab by Hingis that produced an eerie guided missile that
somehow landed in the deepest left corner on the next to last point
of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Venus was asked the same question about luck (by the same
Nigerian journalist, Jacob Akindele). It should be noted that Venus
and Serena could not possibly have compared notes, but were
separately reflecting the bootstrap self-reliance preached by their
dedicated parents, Richard and Oracene Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if it all came down to luck, I would lay in bed every
morning,'' Venus said. ``I wouldn't get up and start practicing. It
wasn't luck that Martina won the match. Everyone has the right to
believe in what they want. I don't believe in luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that comes, comes for a reason,'' Venus added.
``The reason is hard work or something else. I don't believe things
just happen because the wind blows and luck just lands on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Williamses, Hingis has been prepared by her mother
and coach, Melanie Molitor, to seize the main chance. She tried to
work Williams all over the court Friday, remembering how Venus had
once cramped in a long match in Australia (which Venus won). At the
same time, Hingis was taking long breathers between points. Hingis'
lungs somehow outlasted Venus' thigh muscles, and then Hingis
profited from a foot-fault call on Venus and her own fantastic
lunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Hingis said. ``I was so lucky. I put my
hand there; the racquet just went in.''
</P>
<P>
   And did Hingis believe in the luck of mis-hits, let cords, bad
calls?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think luck is always on the side of the better player at the
moment,'' she said, noting that Venus had been lucky at the net
earlier. ``I think at certain stages, you're just the lucky one if
you want it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Having survived the gentler of the Williamses, Hingis knew she
had a tough final with a Williams coming along Saturday afternoon _
``another one,'' Hingis said, with a chuckle. She would not turn
down one lucky break. In fact, Hingis almost seems to think she
deserves it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-LAUNDER-1200(T     09-11 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-LAUNDER-1200(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS SAY BANK SCHEME MAY NOT BE WHAT IT SEEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN and MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Irritated by allegations of money laundering, some of
Russia's leading businessmen insist that the West has overlooked a
simpler explanation for the billions of dollars that have flowed
through several suspicious accounts at the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that some Russian money stashed abroad may
have been gained from organized crime or other criminal activity,
they suggest that many of the thousands of transactions now under
investigation can be attributed to Russian importers engaged in old
games of dodging Russian tariffs and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The businessmen agree that laws may have been broken but insist
that they were Russian, not foreign, laws. A government was
cheated, they say, but it was the discredited Russian
administration, not the U.S. government or the International
Monetary Fund. And yes, funds were used in dubious ways to buy
goods, but they were furniture, food and electronics for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that these businessmen have their own
motives in touting this explanation. They want to remove the taint
of money laundering and organized crime that has cast a cloud over
all Russian companies, legitimate and corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the context of Russia's chaotic economy and
get-rich-quick approach to capitalism, their explanations appear
largely plausible, if incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in interviews with foreign and Russian reporters,
businessmen described schemes that break or bend Russian law but
are nonetheless common in an economy in which many have learned to
cheat the government. Whenever possible, these businessmen say,
profits are kept or taken abroad, and companies like Benex _ which
is thought to have moved billions of dollars through the Bank of
New York _ are essential to that process.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is saying Benex was not partly criminal,'' said Yuliya
Latynina, a respected financial journalist who wrote several
articles on the subject last week. ``But it was a service that
anyone could use, Russian companies or just ordinary people. It was
very, very important for the importers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to one leading businessman, who says he has looked
into the practice, the scheme, in its simplest form, works like
this:
</P>
<P>
   A Russian importer buys water at $3 a bottle from a foreign
supplier. But to avoid a heavy tariff, he draws up an official
contract setting the price at $1. The remaining $2 a bottle is paid
under the table using fictitious shell companies and foreign
accounts like Benex, which carry out wire transfers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Schemes to transfer undeclared profits and payments out of
Russia have been an open secret since the country plunged headfirst
into free-market capitalism in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   They were developed by importers who first fed Russia's pent-up
appetite for Western consumer goods and quickly set about finding
ways to duck rigid customs duties. These duties are not only high
but unpredictable, changing profit levels with one stroke of a
bureaucrat's pen.
</P>
<P>
   Such schemes to shift or keep capital abroad may also have been
used, even set up, by organized crime groups, many of which are
linked with Russian importers. In the early 1990s, in the absence
of any civil court and credible banks, such importers were
extremely vulnerable to racketeers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the businessmen say, only the FBI and the people
behind the Benex scheme can make an accurate accounting of where
money came from and where it went, and they are not talking.
Russians concede, however, that the amount of money passing through
the mysterious accounts is huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awful lot of people in this town are afraid of this
story,'' one leading Russian banker said.
</P>
<P>
   One Russian businessman, who said he had looked into the
allegations, said a total of $6.3 billion had passed through the
mysterious accounts maintained by Benex and similarly murky
organizations, like Lowland and Becs, over the last four years. The
newspaper Kommersant, citing its own sources, estimated the sums
passing through these firms at $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the United States have stated that $4.2 billion to
$10 billion passed through Benex accounts over an 18-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Since imports ran at $60 billion last year, and are estimated at
up to $50 billion this year, the sums are credible, some analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Benex clearly has other uses.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's major banks, eager to dodge creditors after the August
1998 financial crash, may have used clearinghouse accounts like
Benex to take money out of Russia, the analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had experienced people who targeted this niche,'' the
banker said, so that after August 1998, they were the only ones
with a reputation to pick up where the pseudo-bankrupt banks left
off.
</P>
<P>
   Others used Benex to get money into Russia. One foreign
businessman in Moscow, who said he had contacted a service
recommended by a business associate, said his company had
transferred $70,000 through Benex from the United States. He said
he had used the service when his own accounts in a Moscow bank were
frozen during the financial crisis and he desperately needed
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a money launderer, but I used the
service because it was recommended to me as trustworthy,'' he said.
``They only charged a 1.8 percent commission, compared with the 3
percent I had been paying at my bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Other banks, scouring their accounts, also turned up odd
payments made through Benex. An official at Menatep, a major bank
that has frequently been mentioned in connection with the Bank of
New York scandal, said that an internal audit showed that $12
million had been paid through Benex, used exclusively to buy
apartments in Moscow. Given the size of Menatep's banking business,
the amount was relatively small, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Benex accounts may also have been used by Russians looking
for a safe haven for their money and an alternative to a banking
system that has all but collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by Canadian and Russian economic
institutes, capital flight from Russia totaled about $130 billion
from 1992 to 1998. It continues at a rate of up to $2 billion a
month, according to economists here.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the capital flight, the study concluded, was
legal. Demand for services enabling the flight was large, and the
access to them, while a tightly held secret, was relatively easy
for those with the right contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian businessmen have an almost pathological desire to keep
their money abroad because they feel uneasy about keeping it
here,'' said Alexander Lebedev, the chairman of the National
Reserve Bank and a leader in the Our Home Is Russia party of Viktor
S. Chernomyrdin, a former prime minister and the chairman of the
vast Gazprom concern. ``Criminal money is not the lion's share.
Most of the money leaving the country is legal, but for a lot of
businesses, it is not easy to find a way to do it, so they are
eager to find someone who can offer them a service.''
</P>
<P>
   Several businessmen, fearing that the practices of importers and
other businesses will tarnish everyone, have criticized the
government for failing to conduct a vigorous and public
investigation of the root causes of the Bank of New York scandal.
``The Russian government has to understand that this mess has to be
cleaned up,'' Lebedev said. ``But if the scandal succeeds in
pushing money out of foreign banks, back to Russia, then it will be
a good thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But some importers say that unless Russia's tax and customs laws
are overhauled, they and their competitors could not survive
without the kind of services that Benex and other brokers offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I obeyed the law I would pay $110,000 for a shipment of
goods instead of $70,000,'' said one thriving importer who
explained a tax-dodging scheme similar to the one ascribed to
Benex. ``There is no way I could do business. I would be undercut
by all my competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Another importer, an appliance wholesaler, said the scheme was
carried out with a network of dummy companies, banks and the
connivance of corrupt government officials.
</P>
<P>
   This importer faced customs duties and value added taxes
totaling 60 percent of the value of the goods he bought. So instead
of paying for the goods with an aboveboard contract, he turned to a
broker who specialized in under-the-table money transfers.
</P>
<P>
   The broker works regularly with two or three Russian banks,
which the importer said set up dummy companies whose sole function
is to transfer money abroad. The dummy companies transfer money to
accounts like Benex or directly to the supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the dummy companies have a life span of three months,
declaring bankruptcy just when they are required by Russian law to
declare their earnings. No sooner does one company die than another
is born _ sometimes registered in the name of people who have lost
their passports, or alcoholics who have sold their passports for a
drink, the wholesaler said. The final touch is added by the
collusion of government bureaucrats, the importer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have bureaucrats who dreamed up laws that are all but
impossible to adhere to, and then you have bureaucrats who are
supposed to implement the laws,'' he said. ``The latter helps
people find a way around the laws, in collusion with the former.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
