<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN &LR;      09-11 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GAYS IN SPORTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dave Kopay, the former running back known as Psych
for his violent intensity, was choking on tears. ``I know this
isn't politically correct,'' he said, ``but I wish I had outed
Jerry Smith. He might be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years ago, Kopay became the first athlete in a major
American team sport to acknowledge publicly that he was gay. Smith,
his Washington Redskins' teammate and close friend, never
acknowledged his homosexuality outside of gay bars. Kopay thinks
that the only way to have broken the cycle of shame, alcohol, drugs
and anonymous sex that led to Smith's death in 1986 of AIDS would
have been to force him to address his life by disrupting it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the team, according to Kopay, including Coach Vince
Lombardi, knew of Smith's homosexuality and ignored it because of
his contribution; the wide receiver scored 60 touchdowns over 13
years. And as long as Kopay was willing to block on the pass rush,
he, too, was protected from locker-room gay bashers.
</P>
<P>
   Open and emotional, Kopay offered extraordinary testimony in a
historical evening last Thursday, as four athletes moved an
audience at the Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln Center to laughter
and tears in a discussion called ``Breaking the Silence: Gays and
Lesbians in Professional Sports.'' Diana Nyad, broadcaster and
long-distance swimming legend, described an attempted rape, when
she was 14, by her coach. Mariah Burton Nelson, pro basketball
player and author, imagined a revolution beginning with even
straight men shouting, ``I am a lesbian.'' And Billy Bean, no
longer the closeted smoothie of a thousand booster breakfasts,
appeared in his first public forum to share the torch that Kopay
has carried alone.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two months, Bean, a former backup outfielder for
three major-league teams, has stepped out onto larger and riskier
platforms discussing a nine-year pro baseball career burdened by
his fear of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like never having paid your taxes,'' he once said,
``and you go through life waiting for the IRS to catch up to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean's process of coming out began last June, after a college
teammate was killed in a car crash. Bean missed the funeral because
none of their mutual friends had his telephone number. He had
distanced himself from them rather than lying about his life or
risking rejection by telling the truth. That led the Miami Beach
restaurant owner to a revealing conversation with a local reporter,
then calls to the old baseball buddies he had avoided, and last
week to an extensive interview in The New York Times. The response
has been overwhelmingly positive and supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday night, at a forum sponsored by The Times and
moderated by this columnist, Bean spoke haltingly at first, his
voice cracking, about the death in 1995 of his first longterm
partner, hours before a baseball game. Heartbroken, with no one to
share his grief, he played the game. It was the beginning of
choosing a personal life over baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Kopay, 57, just back from a gay cruise to the Greek islands,
speaks openly about his sex life, which he says included other
National Football League players, about checking out male bodies at
sports events, and about the NFL's failure to take a principled
stand against Reggie White, the now-retired star who ``spouts
hate'' in his diatribes against women and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Almost prim in comparison, Bean, 35, finds it difficult to use
the word ``lover,'' claims to have never known or heard of another
gay major-leaguer, and seems grateful that most current players
asked had no problem with him in the locker room, although
executives admitted they would not bring up a gay player from the
minors unless he was enormously gifted.
</P>
<P>
   Were the differences related to the length of time they have
been out, to their age or their sports? Football is ``homo-erotic
although not necessarily homosexual,'' said Kopay breezily, while
Bean still thinks baseball is ``sacred.'' Both men miss the game,
and would return in a coaching or executive capacity ``in a
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesbians in sports, agree Nelson and Nyad, have had far more
support from teammates than have gay men, but face more nuanced
problems which include traditional sexism. Nelson, whose books
include ``The Stronger Women Get the More Men Love Football'' and
the forthcoming ``The Unburdened Heart,'' thinks many of the
problems begin when owners and agents put pressure on female pros
to be more feminine, code for heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Nyad, now a National Public Radio and Fox Television Sports
commentator escaped some of the pressure from owners as a star in
an individual sport. But not as a television personality. At the
American Broadcasting Company, she said, she was told not to bring
her partner to company social events and to make sure her
lesbianism stayed in the closet where it couldn't scare the Nielsen
families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
