<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CHEMICAL-ACCIDENTS-62     09-11 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEMICAL-ACCIDENTS-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP PUTS DISASTER DATA ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.C., Fla., Va.)  (lb) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Environmental advocates have published on the
Internet new information about the risks of chemical accidents,
outflanking a new law that suppresses this kind of information on
the ground that the details could help terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The published information includes state-by-state summaries of
``worst-case scenarios'' presented by thousands of companies in the
United States to the Environmental Protection Agency, part of an
effort to help government agencies and people who live near
factories prepare for toxic catastrophes like explosions at
chemical plants.
</P>
<P>
   The following are among the potential disasters that the
hypothetical summaries describe:
</P>
<P>
   _ A 90-ton rail car of chlorine at a chemical plant in Muscle
Shoals, Ala., ruptures and sends a toxic cloud 14 miles.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Wilmington, N.C., the consequences of a major accident at a
sulfur products company are felt 25 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 1-ton container of chlorine leaks at a water plant in
Bradenton, Fla., sending fumes into a nearby neighborhood and state
park.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency's original intention was to
put the entire document online for the public to browse. But
Congress and President Clinton, presented with warnings by security
specialists that electronic dissemination of the information could
provide terrorists with a road map to sensitive domestic targets,
suspended release of the information last month for one year.
</P>
<P>
   But a right-to-know group has published state-by-state executive
summaries of the accident scenarios on its Web site, saying it
wanted to give the public some sense of the risks posed by the
sites as well as the information that the government chose not to
disclose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the futility of trying to restrict public
information,'' said Rick Blum, a spokesman for OMB Watch, one of
the public interest groups that run the Internet site at
http://www.rtk.net.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this information age,'' Blum said, ``information is going
to be used. It will be copied and it will be redistributed. You
can't put the genie back in the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   The summaries of the risk-management plans are not heavily
detailed and do not include estimates of how many people live
within reach of a plant-accident site _ a number that critics said
could be used by terrorists to rank targets by potential
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   But the roughly 14,000 summaries do include brief descriptions
of the consequences of major events at sites _ usually described as
highly unlikely _ as well as more likely but less severe accident
scenarios, some based on actual past events.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of releasing the information say the compilation of
the summaries, which were not suppressed under the new law, could
show the public that the information was kept off the Internet more
to avoid embarrassing chemical companies than to impede terrorists.
They say that hundreds of accidents occur at plants each year,
although the FBI has acknowledged only a single thwarted act of
sabotage, against a chemical plant in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The summaries can be obtained from the EPA but are not as easily
accessible as the group has made them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping this information out of a national database has never
been a serious barrier to terrorists,'' said Paul Orum, the
Washington coordinator of the Working Group on Community
Right-to-Know. ``To actually combat terrorists, companies need to
improve site security, harden facilities, add fail-safe equipment
and, most fundamentally, reduce the hazard they knowingly bring to
a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Security officials who backed restricting the information said
that publishing it would turn the government into a clearinghouse
for information that could threaten national security.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Burnham, chief of the bureau's domestic-terrorism
section, told Congress in May that ``the FBI has consistently
maintained that the potential release of this worst-case-scenario
data in an uncontrolled manner would provide targeting tools and
new ideas for criminals and terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, in a bipartisan action, agreed to suspend release of
the information, and some expressed outrage that the EPA intended
to make the data easily accessible under the Clean Air Act
amendments of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., who heads the Commerce Committee,
said in July that Congress ``never imagined'' that the information
collected from chemical companies under that law would become ``a
worldwide electronic database, easily searchable from Boston to
Baghdad, from Los Angeles to Libya.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case-scenario information is exempt from the Freedom
of Information Act for one year to allow the administration to
devise a system for releasing the information while assessing ``the
increased risk of terrorist and other criminal activity''
associated with posting the information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides involved in drafting the legislation said
they were not overly alarmed by the availability of the summary
information on the Internet, noting that it was not as detailed as
the complete worst-case-scenario report.
</P>
<P>
   The text is often dense when describing the worst possible
disaster at a plant, and it emphasizes the precautions that sites
take in handling hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a worst-case scenario in which acetylene, ammonia
and three other toxic substances are released at a chemicals plant
in Gainesville, Fla., officials at the plant, Archimica Inc.,
emphasize in their summary that their ``prevention program ensures
that our facility is operated under safe conditions and that any
risk of a release is minimized.'' The plant does acknowledge three
incidents in the last five years in which chemicals were released,
with off-site consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental advocacy groups hope to win more complete
disclosure in the future, noting that publication of annual
toxic-release audits by the EPA has led many companies to reduce
their emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to help anyone create a problem,'' said Blum.
``It is going to help communities make themselves safer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
