<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AFTER-MAS-CANOSA-ART-     09-11 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFTER-MAS-CANOSA-ART-1000(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CUBAN-AMERICANS, THREE FOLLOW FOOTSTEPS BUT NONE WALKS ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (Eds: Story was slugged AFTER-CANOSA on the budget.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The crisis of June 29 cried out for a strong leader in
Miami's Cuban exile community.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard had stopped six Cubans aboard a small boat
within sight of land north of Miami Beach. When the Cubans refused
to turn back, the Coast Guard blasted the boat with a water cannon
and squirted the Cubans with pepper spray. All of it was caught by
the television news helicopters that hovered overhead. The six men
were detained, and some or all faced possible repatriation.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-American leaders, in Miami and in Washington, faxed their
statements of outrage to news organizations and set to work,
through the proper channels, to demand apologies from federal
authorities and to try to free the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   While they seized the moment to send news releases and e-mails,
Ramon Saul Sanchez seized a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, leader of the Movimiento Democracia, one of many Miami
groups working for a free Cuba, walked into traffic on the
MacArthur Causeway and sat down. It was the start of a sit-in
involving hundreds of people that stopped traffic on the Miami
Beach causeway and, Sanchez said, forced federal officials to free
the men.
</P>
<P>
   It was not remarkable, experts on Miami's exile community said,
that a relatively unknown person like Sanchez would offer to lead.
What is remarkable is that, almost two years after the death of the
undisputed head of the Cuban exiles, Jorge Mas Canosa, a void in
leadership remains.
</P>
<P>
   Mas, as head of the powerful Cuban-American National Foundation
from 1981 until his death from lung cancer in 1997, would have been
the voice of outrage in such a crisis, and his outrage would have
registered in the Oval Office. Instead of staging a sit-in,
according to people who knew him, he would have called the
president, and gotten through.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cuban-American sections of Miami, which is almost
everywhere in this city, people say there will never be another
Mas. That is, in part, because of the power and strong personality
of Mas, whose organization, with 50,000 members and 120 well-off,
well-connected directors and trustees, gave him a solid platform.
</P>
<P>
   And, some experts said, it is also because Miami's exile
community is much more diverse, swelling with people who were born
after Fidel Castro's revolution, and much harder to bring under one
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   He is especially missed among the Cuban-Americans who built
lives in Miami with Mas always in their peripheral vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the exile community has been able to fill that
void,'' said Dario Moreno, a professor of political science at
Florida International University and an expert on the exile
community.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious successor, Mas' American-born son, Jorge Mas
Santos, is seen by many as too young, at 36, and he has the
all-but-impossible job of living up to his father's legacy as
foundation chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is not to walk in my father's footsteps, but to extend
those footsteps,'' said Mas, who has found that operating the
family's huge communications company Mastec _ with $1 billion in
revenues in 1998 and about 10,000 employees _ is easier than
replacing his father in the minds and hearts of many exiles.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While he has been warmly received here by crowds of exiles who
chant ``adelante'' _ Spanish for forward _ many will wait and see
if this Mas can hold their loyalty and protect their interests as
his father did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake to place all hopes on a single person,'' said
Jose J. Basulto, a pilot and president of Brothers to the Rescue,
Cuban-American pilots who search the Florida Straits for rafters.
``After Mas Canosa's death, we have become extremely vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Basulto, along with Mas and Sanchez, is often mentioned when
Cuban-Americans talk about new leaders in Miami. But in Little
Havana, at the takeout windows where people stop for tiny cups of
strong, sweet Cuban coffee, there is no replacing the elder Mas.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Rey, 62, of southwest Miami, pondered the question of a
successor as he watched friends click dominoes across a table.
``Nobody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the community will accept someone who just says,
`Cuba si, Castro no,''' said Rafael Penalver, a Cuban-American
lawyer and president of the San Carlos Institute, a Cuban heritage
center in Key West. Castro is still the hot-button issue, Penalver
said, but he must share space on the agenda with Social Security,
affirmative action and other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The dream of a free and democratic Cuba is worn smooth around
the edges from use. For most of the past two decades, the man
holding the symbolic sword to Castro's head had been Jorge Mas
Canosa.
</P>
<P>
   He monopolized U.S. policy on Cuba by winning legislation like
the Cuban Democracy Act of 1992, which tightened the longstanding
embargo on the island, and warred on The Miami Herald because he
disagreed with its editorial stance.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Moreno and other experts on the community have argued that the
real leaders among Cuban-Americans, many of whom have never lived
in a free Cuba and come without the hatred of Castro, are elected
officials. They include Miami-Dade County's mayor, Alex Penelas,
and three Cuban-American members of Congress: Ileana Ros-Lehtinen
and Lincoln Diaz-Balart, Republicans from South Florida, and Robert
Menendez, a Democrat from New Jersey. And they, unlike Mas, are the
ones to whom more moderate Cuban-Americans will look for leadership
beyond the question of a free Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But they are hampered by their offices in time of crisis, as on
June 29. Penelas, political experts say, could not put his
responsibility for law and order aside and take part in civil
disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed, many exiles say, is a combination of a political
heavyweight and a trusted grass-roots leader, unencumbered by
office, selfish to one cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean there aren't prominent contenders _ there
are three,'' Moreno said, naming Jorge Mas Santos; Sanchez, an
office manager whose grass-roots organization operates from a code
of nonviolence; and Basulto, the respected 59-year-old pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they have all the elements needed to assume
leadership, but not as individuals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Jorge Mas Santos, his son, has inherited the organization and
the money, but has yet to prove himself as a popular leader,''
Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, he said, ``has the charisma, that touch of pueblo.
Movimiento Democracia has a great deal of popular support because
of their policy of nonviolent protest. But Sanchez doesn't have the
coffers or the extensive organizational capacity of the foundation,
nor the fund-raising muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   Basulto ``has put his life on the line in the anti-Castro
movement,'' Moreno said. ``There's nothing Cubans like better than
political martyrs for causes.'' But while Basulto has romance on
his side, he lacks financial and political clout.
</P>
<P>
   That aura of romance may be the greatest gap in the resume of
the younger Mas, who was born in this country. But, he responds,
``I was born as a Cuban exile.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, only the young Mas swings the big hammer that
money and influence have forged. In the Miami headquarters of
Mastec, he pauses beside a portrait of his father. The resemblance
is striking.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, he is afforded the respect of a visiting head
of state of a government in exile. At the recent presidential
inauguration in Panama, Mas and the foundation were given a section
of honor, right beside the Cuban one.
</P>
<P>
   His father, he said, taught him how to use that power. As
Sanchez sat on the hot asphalt in June, Mas Santos was on the phone
with the State Department. The next morning, when the six men
walked free from a federal detention center, he was at their side.
The foundation's influence, as much or more than any sit-in, had
won their freedom, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is exploring how it can help restore democracy in
post-Castro Cuba. Meanwhile, he continues his father's hard stance
on the U.S. embargo and fights any warming of relations with
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always told me, `Your time will come,''' Mas said.
</P>
<P>
   Miles away, in a small office hung with pictures of Gandhi and
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., Sanchez fights communism on a
shoestring budget. In this city where bombs are still regarded by
some as legitimate weapons against communism, he prefers hunger
strikes and symbolic gestures.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was inconceivable that you would have to struggle
for something so dignifying as freedom with something so
destructive as war,'' said Sanchez, whose organization has no
membership roster and supports itself with donations of $1 or $5 a
person.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Sanchez supported more extreme actions, and in 1982 he was
subpoenaed to appear before a federal grand jury in New York.
Prosecutors believed that Sanchez was a member of Omega 7, the
violent anti-Castro group that had claimed responsibility for
bombings in Miami and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, while denying he was a member of Omega 7, refused to
answer questions. He was convicted of contempt of court, and served
four years in prison. There, he saw brutality and ``made the
decision that when I stepped out of prison, I would begin working
in nonviolent ways,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has planned and led several nonviolent
demonstrations. He planned the blocking of the Lincoln Tunnel in
1995 _ ``Clinton was sending rafters back to Cuba,'' he explained _
and various sit-ins.
</P>
<P>
   He has been rammed by a Cuban gunboat, during a freedom flotilla
that encroached on Cuban waters in 1995, and had his boats
confiscated by U.S. officials who were afraid he would touch off a
war.
</P>
<P>
   Basulto still dreams the dream of many in his generation. In it,
the people rise up and restore democracy to Cuba. For now, his
planes search the Florida Straits, dropping food and water to
rafters. He is not looking for power, he said: ``The power we are
looking for is that in each person in Cuba,'' for the people of
Cuba to make their own change.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
