<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-ART-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE CANDIDATE TAKES LONG VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENDOZA, Argentina _ The campaign stop had much potential for
pizazz: the inauguration of a glassy shopping mall complete with
brass band, fashion show and mountains of caviar and champagne. But
as Domingo Cavallo climbed to the stage, his smile was a tad too
broad, his wave a tad too perky and long.
</P>
<P>
   If economics is the dismal science, then Cavallo, the former
economy minister credited with whipping Argentina's hyperinflation
in the early 1990s, is the dismal third-party candidate in the
presidential election next month.
</P>
<P>
   Between shaking hands and lecturing reporters on the benefits of
deregulation and tax cuts, the double-chinned and balding candidate
toured a stereo store and posed for photographers with headphones
on his head. It was an obvious appeal for the youth vote, but the
prop made him look neither hip nor presidential, an impression
reinforced when he ambled over to a fire-red Corvette and other
model cars on display for more shots.
</P>
<P>
   With neither money for television commercials nor a party
machine to get out the vote, Cavallo will almost certainly run a
distant third on Oct. 24 behind the Buenos Aires governor, Eduardo
Duhalde, of the ruling Justicialist Party, and the Buenos Aires
mayor, Fernando de la Rua, of the opposition Alianza coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But Cavallo will probably have long enough coattails to elect a
substantial congressional delegation for his small conservative
party, Action for the Republic. There is an outside chance he could
throw the election into a second round, and that might give him
decisive bargaining power over future economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo scores a bit below 10 percent in the presidential
preference polls, but most analysts see that as an achievement
given the dismal failures of past third-party campaigns in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else his long shot at the presidency achieves, Cavallo
is breaking the mold of populist Argentine politicians like Juan
and Eva Peron and the last two presidents, Raul Alfonsin and Carlos
Saul Menem. Cavallo says that any reasonable showing will create
space for a new kind of politics in Argentina and make him an even
more credible candidate in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two traditional parties are personality, sentimental
parties,'' Cavallo, who is 53, said in an interview. ``Argentines
traditionally have looked for the most sensitive and most
affectionate candidate, not for the best to govern. But every day
the people are thinking more carefully about their vote and my
candidacy is reinforcing that process.''
</P>
<P>
   In a race in which the two leading candidates offer a lot of
vague promises, Cavallo issues detailed position papers on
restructuring pensions and health insurance and decentralizing
control over the nation's education system. Though his true love is
talking economics, he appears to be most effective when he
discusses the darker side of Argentine society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organized crime is powerful in Argentina,'' Cavallo said on a
local television talk show. ``It has infiltrated the courts, all
levels in government, in the police and in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that a three-year string of suicides of people
suspected of being either witnesses to or actors in a variety of
scandals involving the Menem administration was more than a
coincidence. And he even lent credence to charges by Zulema Menem,
the former first lady, that the helicopter crash in which her son
Carlos Menem Jr. was killed four years ago was murder, not an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   But Cavallo's powerful indictment on the talk show got watered
down by repeated returns to his pet subject: the ins and outs of
monetary and fiscal policy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At one point, Cavallo drove the chatty television interviewer to
exasperation by refusing to let him take a break for an
advertisement before he completed a professorial critique of
International Monetary Fund policies.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, Cavallo's speeches are little lectures on ways to
bring down interest rates, increase productivity and strengthen
investor confidence. His idea of a snappy sound bite is a 10-minute
theory on how to reduce production costs to generate employment.
His campaign pamphlets are full of graphs, numbers and academic
jargon explaining the ``supply-side shock'' that he proposes to
lift Argentina out of its deep recession.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign slogan is characteristically uncatchy: ``Cavallo
has a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fullness of his oratory, and the sparsity of his
campaign resources, Cavallo is receiving significant news-media
attention, in large part because he is widely recognized as the
most important Cabinet member of the early years of Menem's two
five-year terms as president.
</P>
<P>
   As Menem's first foreign minister, Cavallo restored diplomatic
ties with Britain for the first time since the 1982 Falkland war.
Then, as economy minister, he engineered the so-called
convertibility plan, which pegged the value of the peso to the
dollar _ a policy that made him a hero on Wall Street and the most
acclaimed economist in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to resign in 1996, though, after making a speech
before the Congress describing an expanding web of organized crime
with links to the highest levels of the Argentine government.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Argentines, Cavallo is like a doctor,'' said Joaquin
Morales Sola, a columnist for the newspaper La Nacion. ``You don't
have to like him, but you go to him for a cure when you are sick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
