<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-HOLOCAUST-NYT &LR;      09-11 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURVIVOR HELPS TRACK FRENCH DEBT OF WARTIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Adolphe Steg, a veteran of the World War II Resistance
who later became a famous surgeon, has treated presidents and
received high French civilian honors. But that, he says, is not who
he really is deep down inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am also the little boy in the stetl that I left at the age
of 7, studying the Talmud and rolling my peyes with my fingers,
before all that turned into a nightmare,'' he said in his
fourth-floor apartment, on the Quai d'Orsay down the Seine from the
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish village where he was born 74 years ago, Nizhny
Verecky, now Ukrainian territory, did not survive the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Steg, his parents, and his two sisters, living in France when
deportations began under the German occupation, did survive, in the
wiggle room between the collaborationist Vichy regime's willing
persecution of French Jews and the compassion of ordinary French
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Steg and a French historian, Claire Andrieu, will try this
week to explain, to American officials who are eager to see all of
Europe try to make up for what it let the Nazis do half a century
ago, that France will not flinch from a full and final accounting
for its actions.
</P>
<P>
   Steg is the deputy chairman and Mrs. Andrieu is a member of a
blue-ribbon panel set up by the French government in 1997 to
establish the facts about the looting of bank accounts, insurance
policies, art works and other property from Jews in France during
the war.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, whose chairman is Jean Matteoli, a decorated
Resistance leader, plans to publish findings this year and make
recommendations on restoring what still remains in the wrong hands
to the rightful owners or their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The two will appear before the House Banking and Financial
Services Committee in Washington on Tuesday, and will meet two days
later in New York with the city comptroller, Alan Hevesi.
</P>
<P>
   While organizations representing Holocaust survivors have
pressed Swiss banks for over $2 billion in compensation for
Switzerland's wartime handling of gold that the Nazis seized from
Jews, Jewish groups in France have been less vocal, preferring to
put their trust in the integrity of the Matteoli Commission rather
than use moral suasion on French financial and insurance
institutions to make them contribute to international funds for the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Steg would not say exactly how much money belonging to Jews he
and his colleagues had found moldering in French bank vaults,
safety deposit boxes and insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have an approximate sum at the end of the year, but that
doesn't mean that this will be the totality of what is owed to
survivors,'' he said. ``There's a moral debt as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin announced last year that a fund
would be created with assets for which no surviving claimants could
be found, leaving the commission to decide what to do with the
money. ``The banks have agreed to make a significant
contribution,'' Steg said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel had found, he said, that at least 75 percent of all
property seized from Jews in France during the war had been
returned after the Liberation. But it also found the equivalent of
nearly $1.6 million, seized from the 75,721 Jews whom French
authorities sent to Auschwitz from camps in the German-occupied
zone between 1941 and 1944, still in a state bank, the Caisse des
depots et consignations. Only 2,564 of the deported Jews survived
to return.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Steg's father, Martin, who had come to France
from Czechoslovakia in the 1930s but was sent to Auschwitz in 1942.
He came back to France at war's end and later went to live in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty sturdy,'' said Steg, who was with his mother and
his two sisters in Paris on July 15, 1942, when a friend tipped him
off that the police were planning a mass arrest of Jews the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, wearing the star, and 16 years old, and what
could I do?'' he said. ``I went to the concierge of our building,
and the concierge hid us in a vacant apartment. You see, right
there, there's the mixture, which was typical of the whole period,
of cruel efficiency on the part of the Vichy police on the one
hand, and an immense effort of solidarity by the people on the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Good luck followed him and a sister as far as Lyons, where the
French police arrested them for trying to escape into the
unoccupied zone by using false identity papers. They were freed by
a French court three months later, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later sent to a French shelter for deported German Jews by a
group called Christian Friendships, he became its deputy director,
he said, because he was the only one of the refugees who could
speak French without an accent. That led him to the Resistance, and
activities for which he was later arrested and tortured by the
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   But that, he says, waving away requests for details, is another
story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
