<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FOLK-SCHOOL12-COX     09-11 1772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLK-SCHOOL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uplifting all kinds of folk
 &HT;    By Candice Dyer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASSTOWN, N.C. _ Cooking classes at the John C. Campbell Folk
School in the early part of the century relied as much on a globe
as on pots and pans. The Yankee teacher, wanting to give her
mountain students a glimpse of the world beyond the peaks of
southern Appalachia, pointed to far-flung continents to show the
origins of herbs and seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folk school was started by outsiders as a way to civilize
mountain people,'' says Jan Davidson, the school's executive
director. ``Today, mountain people run the school to civilize
outsiders from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The John C. Campbell Folk School began in 1925 in Brasstown as a
mission project to educate and assimilate poverty-stricken
highlanders. It now teaches native arts and crafts to a variety of
students _ some professional artists, others yuppie outsiders and
nostalgic retirees intent on beating back urban malaise with a
lathe or a needle. Ironically, today's folk school students
desperately want to flee the city for the backwoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an insurance claims adjuster, so I come here for my
soul,'' says Lynne Lockie of Hixson, Tenn., as she contentedly
weaves an egg basket.
</P>
<P>
   One of the quaintest-sounding, and most popular, programs is
blacksmithing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best blacksmiths in the country teaching here and
taking classes,'' says Tim Ryan, the resident gardener, nature
studies teacher and board member of the school. He has taken so
many blacksmithing classes at Campbell that he recently started
teaching it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some who take it are artists,'' Ryan says, ``some are
re-enactors or people who work in living-history museums, but most
of them get into it for the same reason I did: nostalgia for a
simpler time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Dolson, a swimming instructor who lives in Helen, Ga., said
she signed up for blacksmithing because her grandfather made a
living by bending hot metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to connect somehow with my grandfather,'' she says.
``I found out you get hot, filthy and sweaty, and you make a lot of
noise. And you have the best time of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   In her class, she made a hook, a garden hanger, a letter opener
and something she euphemistically calls an ``abstract conversation
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   The leafy campus feels like a homespun bohemia, on the Left Bank
of the Hiawassee River instead of the Seine. The farmhouse
dormitories have no telephones. Students learn at their own pace in
small classes with no grades or certification. After a few days of
eating communal meals to mandolin music and savoring the life of a
cracker-barrel dilettante, at least 60 percent of the students sign
up for repeat visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is creative, productive leisure of a high order that
draws on the whole person: senses, intellect and spirit,'' Davidson
says.
</P>
<P>
   So how did anthropological first aid for farmers evolve into
therapy for the computer-addled mainstream?
</P>
<P>
   To Davidson, the folk school's student-becomes-teacher dialectic
interlaces as logically as any pattern on a loom, and his personal
history forms many of the threads. He grew up in nearby Murphy, and
his family was among the residents who, in an enthusiastic
proclamation, offered ``land, labor and folks'' to the idealistic
New Englanders scouting southern Appalachia for a school site.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Campbell and his wife, Olive Dame Campbell, had studied
the area around the turn of the century when it was viewed as a
barbaric ``mission field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The founders had a sincere desire to educate a region that was
believed to have no culture of its own,'' says Ryan. ``But after
they visited people here, it became obvious to them that mountain
people, while living in the simplest of homes, had handmade quilts,
baskets and clothes that were exquisitely crafted. These people led
simple lives and poor lives, but not crude lives. In fact, because
they were so uncorrupted by industrial civilization, they were the
great preservers of a very rich culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Campbells decided that the Danish folk school system, based
on noncompetitive ``learning by doing'' and plenty of interaction _
so different from the traditional rote memorization model _ could
educate mountain residents without condescending to them. Campbell
died before his plans were realized, but his widow and her friend
Marguerite Butler established the school with the motto ``I Sing
Behind the Plow,'' the title of a Danish poem.
</P>
<P>
   The original curriculum focused on farming techniques and food
preparation. With a dairy, cannery and credit union, the school
quickly became the center of the community, and the teachers used
their agrarian resources for lessons in science, geography and
history whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did was bring the world to Brasstown,'' says Clay
Logan, a folk school board member whose first job was milking cows
at the dairy. ``They introduced us to all kinds of knowledge we
wouldn't have had otherwise. And we taught them things, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson explains, ``The teachers used genealogy to teach
history, and Olive Campbell would point to the stars and tell the
farmers about Greek, Roman and Norse mythology behind the
constellations. Then the farmers would tell her about planting by
the signs.''
</P>
<P>
   The school began to incorporate the arts into its curriculum
after Olive Campbell noticed some men whittling on a ``loafers'
bench'' at a general store. Irritated by what she deemed idleness,
she instructed them to carve figurines and sell them through the
school to add to their families' incomes. (Regional artisans still
sell their carved wooden figures at the school's store.) Soon, the
school was known as much for its crafts, music and folk dancing as
for its farming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny that her New England work ethic took a dim view of
that act of mountain meditation, which is the very thing that draws
people today,'' Davidson says.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls visiting the school as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking that the pottery and Danish folk dancing
were a lot more fun and creative than (my school),'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In such an atmosphere, Davidson soon had an epiphany about
heritage that sums up the spirit of the folk school today. After
listening to his grandmother sing a ballad about the hanging of
``Charlie McGraw,'' Davidson, then in junior high school, looked up
the lyrics in a folklore book. He discovered that the song
originally told the story of Charles Guiteau, who assassinated
President James Garfield in 1881. Davidson visualized his
grandmother's forebears warbling ``Guiteau'' into ``McGraw,'' a
Scots-Irish name they more easily recognized, and he suddenly felt
the sweep of history. The past can be progressive, he decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time I realized there was something special
here,'' recalls Davidson, now 51 and wearing a mountaineer's beard.
``The way the ballad evolved was a revelation to me that there are
two main qualities of folklore. One is that it's very old. The
other is that it can be changed and adapted.''
</P>
<P>
   The folk school demonstrated its ability to change after World
War II, when the economy shifted away from agriculture. By 1970,
the school had closed its cannery, dairy and farm programs to focus
on arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then what was kindly known as the `homesteading' or `back to
the land' phase of the folk school began,'' gardener Ryan says.
``The folk school was kind of a hippie place, the way so many
things were back then, and it was a time of struggle because some
of the local Baptists didn't approve of what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Davidson, a musician and college student, took
classes and played in concerts at the folk school. From the
bandstand one Saturday night, he spotted a weaving student named
Nanette, and they soon were married under the school's pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, like many sons and daughters of the region, loved the
family farm but itched to leave it for the globe used in those
early cooking classes. After earning a master's degree in English
with a minor in folklore from the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill, he studied literature at the University of Edinburgh
in Scotland, and later earned a Ph.D. in folklore, history and
museum studies from Boston University. ``I spent the first 18 years
of my life trying to get out of Cherokee County, and the next 18
trying to get back,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He became director of the folk school six years ago, when it was
getting about 2,500 students a year and faced a financial crisis.
It usually closed during the winter, and employees occasionally
worked without being paid.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the school bursts at its hand-stitched seams with 4,000
students taking 700 classes 49 weeks a year. The campus has just
added a historical museum, and a sprawling farmhouse-style building
is under construction. The new building will hold a kitchen area
with open-hearth stoves and studios for dance, fiber arts and
music. And employees now get pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were shaky for the school when he took over, and now
it's solvent, almost completely self-supporting and growing,'' Ryan
says.
</P>
<P>
   The growth is usually attributed to Davidson's homeboy
understanding of the region and the force of his charisma. A
musician and amiable wit, he spins yarns and strolls the campus
playing songs on his groundhog-skin banjo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely necessary to have roots here to preserve an
institution like this one,'' says board member Logan. ``You can't
keep alive that special feeling if you don't have it deep down in
your soul. You have to know how hard the times were here. You have
to have lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ballad of ``Charlie McGraw,'' with its lesson of adapting
the old, continues to affect Davidson. At the moment the school
lacks a plow to sing behind, as its motto calls for, but he is
reinstating a gardening curriculum and cooking program. Students
once again can learn how to rotate crops and bake bread over an
open hearth. They also can study aromatherapy and Thai curries.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people confuse what we do with history, but change is
at the crux of folklore,'' declares David Brose, the school's
official archivist. ``Folklore is a living, breathing, undulating
thing that enables us to draw from the past and move into the
future. We really love what happened in the last century, but we
also love what will happen in the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The John C. Campbell Folk School can be reached at (800)
365-5724 or online at www.folkschool.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
