<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8471 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-INCINERATE12-COX     09-11 2070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCINERATE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some fear restart of La. waste incinerator
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMELIA, La. _ Gardeners tend to savor a good rain, but Nguyen
Bui used to worry when clouds gathered. Raindrops seemed to carry
the noxious chemicals spewed by the Marine Shale Processors
incinerator a couple of miles away, and his lush garden would
suffer. His flowers, which he gave weekly to the Catholic church
across the street, would wilt or die.
</P>
<P>
   Bui, 94, said he suffered as well when the incinerator was
burning waste. He'd get headaches and feel dizzy or listless, he
said. So would some of his neighbors, who, like him, came to
America as Vietnam War refugees; Amelia, population 2,700, is
almost half Vietnamese, the largest percentage of any town in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, they coughed and wheezed as thick, black smoke
belched from the incinerator's stack. When the putrid smell of
burning plastic got too intense, they closed their windows, turned
off their air conditioners and avoided driving past the plant on
old U.S. 90.
</P>
<P>
   Three miles west in Morgan City, five children contracted a rare
and fatal form of brain cancer in one year, 1987. Neuroblastoma has
been linked to exposure to toxins, but studies did not link the
Morgan City cluster directly to emissions from Marine Shale. But
the families feel certain the incinerator poisoned their babies.
Lawsuits are pending.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, federal and state agencies won a protracted court
battle and shut down Marine Shale for violating hundreds of
hazardous waste rules. Marine Shale agreed to pay more than $10
million in penalties. Bui's garden began to flourish, and he
stopped worrying about his grandchildren, who attended the
elementary school a mile from the plant. Six residents who fought
Marine Shale for almost a decade received cash rewards from the
Environmental Protection Agency for their vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for some residents of Amelia, the unthinkable happened. In
February of this year, with the EPA's blessing, the Louisiana
Department of Environmental Quality gave the incinerator a permit
to reopen. The facility, renamed GTX but still about 48 percent
owned by Marine Shale, will be able to handle 400,000 tons of waste
a year, making it the largest hazardous waste incinerator in the
world. At full capacity, it could burn more than half the nation's
hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
   While some residents are not opposed to the plant, and many more
welcome the large number of jobs it would bring, opponents have
gone to state court to fight the permit, claiming that the LDEQ
violated its own rules when it gave the incinerator permission to
reopen. A decision is expected this month.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 Vietnamese families didn't wait for the ruling. Upon
hearing the incinerator might reopen, they simply left town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't trust the government when they say it's safe,''
said the Rev. Francis Bui (no relation to Nguyen Bui), the parish
priest for Vietnamese Catholics in the area. The Rev. Bui, 40, a
small, soft-spoken man who escaped Vietnam in 1979 in a rickety
boat, notes the irony that these families came here under the
protection of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they reopen, they will indirectly destroy the Vietnamese
community here,'' the Rev. Bui said. ``More families will leave.
Why does it have to be so close to a residential place? We are
human beings, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A `white knight'?
</P>
<P>
   The incinerator's new majority owner, Kevin Moody, did not
return phone calls, but he was quoted last year in the Baton Rouge
Advocate as saying he wants GTX to be the ``white knight'' that
cleans up the 350,000 tons of hazardous waste left when Marine
Shale closed. In a consent decree reached with the EPA to settle
its lawsuit, Marine Shale and GTX agreed to clean up the waste
within several years _ if they could upgrade and reopen.
</P>
<P>
   GTX General Manager Tom Fancett said the company is spending $60
million to upgrade the site and turn it into a first-class,
clean-burning facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plant will be safe,'' he said during a tour. ``A truck
driving down the highway will have more emissions than this
facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, including several city and parish governments, say
the permit was granted for political reasons. Moody and Marine
Shale owner Jack Kent have strong ties to Gov. Mike Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's brother, Pres, was on the St. Mary's Parish Police Jury
_ which functions like a county commission _ when Marine Shale was
given approval to open in 1984. Foster's son, Murphy, was Marine
Shale's attorney during the years of battling the EPA and the LDEQ
in court. Kent spent hundreds of thousands of dollars in negative
ads against former Gov. Buddy Roemer, who made cleaning up the
environment a priority. Those ads helped Foster defeat Roemer in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The incinerator is in Foster's home parish. Foster pushed so
hard to have the road that runs through the parish upgraded to
interstate quality that his transportation director resigned last
fall in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has close ties to the Moody family as well. The
Moodys have a large string of businesses that include oil, gas,
fast food chains, newspapers and the Evangeline Downs racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's connections to Moody and Kent have nothing to do with
his outspoken support for the incinerator, the governor said
through his spokesman, Terry Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   ``His connections (to the owners) are legitimate points for
discussion, but the governor has said all along to the LDEQ that if
there is a scientific reason not to grant a permit, then don't do
it,'' Ryder said. ``Otherwise, proceed as you would with any other
application. There is no question that the way Jack Kent operated
initially pushed the envelope, but the agencies have made their
point. There is a lot of investment down there and a lot of people
who depend on that plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent would not be interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Owner beat bribery charges
</P>
<P>
   When Marine Shale was granted a permit in 1984, Kent claimed it
was a recycler, not an incinerator. He had a patent to create a
supposedly harmless aggregate out of hazardous waste by burning it
and then ``vitrifying'' it.
</P>
<P>
   Vitrification cooks the burned waste, a gravelly substance, at
such high temperatures that the resulting material is a shiny,
black, glasslike substance that locks in dangerous metals. Since
the aggregate is nonhazardous, Kent said, it could be sold and used
as road fill. Kent said vitrification would revolutionize the waste
disposal industry. His is still the only commercial incinerator in
the country to have used vitrification, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
   But when residents began to complain about noxious odors,
sickness and black smoke billowing from the incinerator's stack,
the LDEQ and EPA took a closer look. Regulators called Marine
Shale's recycling status a ``sham'' cooked up to avoid the costly
and complicated restrictions on incinerators. After taking Marine
Shale to court to force it to conduct environmental tests, the LDEQ
found that air, water, soil and fish in the area were contaminated
with high levels of toxins. Waste was lying underwater in the Bayou
Boeuf, a busy waterway abutting one side of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   When the EPA tested the black aggregate, it found that it could
leach out dangerous lead if heated to certain temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Kent had a lot riding on Marine Shale _ it was listed as one of
Inc. Magazine's fastest-growing companies two years in a row _ and
he fought every attempt the agencies made to regulate the facility.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Kent was indicted along with two others for trying to
give a federal judge a $2 million bribe for favorable rulings in
the EPA lawsuit. Kent was acquitted, but his alleged
co-conspirators were convicted. Later, another judge said Kent had
a ``virtual contempt for the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 consent decree settling EPA's lawsuit against Marine
Shale bars Kent from having a majority stake in the company and
from participating in the day-to-day operations of the facility. It
even says he can't have an office ``inside the fence'' of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   One building has been left outside the fence. Fancett said he
didn't know if Kent would have an office there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lives in Wyoming and he has millions of dollars,'' Fancett
said. ``Why would he want to be here?''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs welcome in community
</P>
<P>
   Not all residents are against the incinerator. Fancett says the
opponents are a ``small, vocal minority.'' He says GTX did a survey
that shows 70 percent of nearby residents are in favor of GTX.
</P>
<P>
   When GTX held a job fair, people lined up for two days to apply
for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Russo, principal of nearby J.S. Aucoin Elementary School,
says she is ``comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've invested millions and they seem to have done their
homework,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fancett said people have nothing to worry about. About $10
million will be spent on state-of-the-art air filtration alone. The
main building will be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Temblet, the LDEQ chief under Roemer, said he has looked
into the new facility and thinks it is the same basic technology as
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may operate it a little cleaner and let's hope they do,''
said Temblet, now a professor of environmental studies at Louisiana
State University. ``The question is, why would Louisiana want such
a thing? We have private incinerators at the individual plants.
There's not enough demand for an incinerator here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there are 25 hazardous waste incinerators, three of
which aren't operating, according to the EPA. That number is down
from several years ago because there has been a reduction in
hazardous waste in the United States, said EPA spokesman Dave Bary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has driven the demand for capacity down,'' Bary said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Temblet said, Louisiana is already by far the worst
polluter in the nation, per capita. Becoming the nation's hazardous
waste epicenter won't help the state's dismal environmental
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   State waived buffer requirement
</P>
<P>
   The appeal filed by the incinerator's opponents centers on flaws
in the permit process. The LDEQ's own rules require a hazardous
waste facility to have a 200-foot ``buffer zone'' surrounding it,
in case of accidents. But the GTX/Marine Shale facility looms over
Bayou Boeuf, which is used by thousands of commercial and
recreational fishing boats as well as industrial boats.
</P>
<P>
   The LDEQ said in its brief to the state court that the safety
measures inherent in the design of the facility eliminate the need
for the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, meanwhile, point out that an EPA risk assessment of
the facility projected an elevated risk of cancers associated with
airborne vinyl chloride escaping from the plant. The LDEQ countered
that the EPA, while noting this risk, did not recommend denying a
permit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this question remains: Why is the EPA allowing the state
to permit a site it spent several years and millions of dollars
shutting down?
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say it's because the EPA would have had to force
Marine Shale to clean up the waste at the site if it hadn't agreed
to the consent decree. That would have meant more costly court
battles.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA counters that it has no authority over granting permits
in states where the local environmental agency _ in this case the
LDEQ _ has been given permitting power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their job and their call,'' said Ruben Casso, an engineer
with the EPA's hazardous waste permitting branch.
</P>
<P>
   A `genius' feels frustrated
</P>
<P>
   Many residents feel, quite simply, invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Vietnamese community remained silent during the
battle against Marine Shale _ many can't speak English _ they are
beginning to raise their voices. They are a party to the permit
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Wilma Subra, who owns a chemistry lab and an environmental
consulting firm in nearby New Iberia, has been working against the
incinerator from the beginning. She won a MacArthur Foundation
``genius grant'' in June, in part for her contribution to shutting
down Marine Shale. She grew up in Morgan City and still has family
there. She spent hundreds of hours this summer poring over
government documents and poking holes in the LDEQ's permitting
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so frustrating,'' she said. ``But somebody has to work
for the citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
