<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-INDUCEMENTS12-COX     09-11 1909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-INDUCEMENTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta bid team wooed Olympic voters' children, too
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Raj Ruhee of Mauritius arrived in Atlanta to
enroll at Georgia Tech for the 1990 fall term, he settled into
convenient digs at City View Apartments. The first five months'
rent already was paid. His apartment was filled with furniture
leased from Aaron Rents.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangements, including Ruhee's admission to Tech, were
handled by the Atlanta Olympic bid team.
</P>
<P>
   Why would they care about the higher education of a young man
from an island republic in the Indian Ocean? Because his father,
Ram Ruhee, was one of 86 International Olympic Committee members
who were voting whether to award the 1996 Centennial Summer Games
to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Newly released documents that detail the city's bid efforts show
that perks were not limited to IOC voters but were extended to
their offspring.
</P>
<P>
   The documents do not suggest that Atlanta bidders went to the
extremes of their counterparts in Salt Lake City, whose excesses in
winning the 2002 Winter Games led to the ouster of 10 IOC members.
But they do illustrate a pattern of favors for IOC families that
the Salt Lake team may have adopted and taken to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   As for Raj Ruhee, records show that he was presented a list of
expenses accumulated by the Atlanta group, but nothing in the three
dozen boxes made available to The Atlanta Journal-Constitution says
whether he paid reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the bid group's efforts, the young man stayed one
semester, dropped out and returned to Mauritius. The vote on Sept.
18 that won the Games for Atlanta was by secret ballot, so it is
not known if Ram Ruhee returned the favor by siding with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing the hearts and votes of IOC members by lavishing
benefits and attention on their children appeared to be at the core
of Atlanta's strategy. It included college assistance, job
opportunities and first-class airplane trips to the city _ with
side excursions to New York City and Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Although Atlanta Organizing Committee heads Billy Payne and
Andrew Young stated in a report to Congress on June 1 that they
only accommodated ``minor children'' traveling with their IOC
parent, records indicate they often invited the adult children to
join their parents in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   They also encouraged the children to make their own
all-expenses-paid visits to the city and other locales. IOC rules
allowed one trip for two people to a candidate city. Documents
indicate that the Atlanta committee violated that rule dozens of
times. Many IOC members made several visits, often bringing spouses
and children along. The first-class tickets cost as much as $7,000
apiece. The report to Congress omitted entirely some celebratory
visits made by many IOC members immediately following Atlanta's
victory in Tokyo. Payne and Young said in the report that the
additional visits were ``appropriate.'' In fact, they urged IOC
members to visit more than once, even though it was against the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Pirjo Haggman of Finland visited with her husband and two young
children in November 1989. Payne fired off a letter telling her how
much the AOC enjoyed their presence and said he looked forward to
the family's return ``in the not too distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne wrote that he would be ``delighted to make all your
arrangements including a visit to Disney World as a guest of one of
the members of the organizing committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Haggman was forced to resign from the IOC as a result of the
Salt Lake bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Because of discrepancies found by congressional investigators in
the original report and documents found in boxes of materials on
the Atlanta bid, the AOC's lawyers, led by former U.S. Attorney
General Griffin Bell, are rewriting the account.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern to investigators are correspondence and
memoranda detailing offers of college assistance to the relatives
of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals to Atlanta, Salt Lake
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships formed the core of Salt Lake City's strategy to
secure votes in its scandal-ridden campaign. While the Atlanta bid
team may have used its influence with local universities to bypass
standard admission procedures, the Salt Lake team actually wrote
the checks.
</P>
<P>
   IOC member Lamine Keita of Mali appealed to both U.S. candidate
cities to educate his youngsters. He approached Young, the Atlanta
bid chairman, in 1990 about scholarship opportunities at
Atlanta-area universities for his daughter, who was just finishing
her secondary education. Young's aide, Elizabeth Clement, wrote in
a July 1990 memo that she suggested Spelman College and that
another bid team member, Linda Stephenson, suggested Agnes Scott
and Oglethorpe. ``Linda will make some calls to get this ball
rolling,'' Clement wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The documents reviewed by this newspaper did not show whether
Keita's daughter attended college in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Keita sought help from Young to get his son,
Moriba, into Howard University in Washington, D.C. Young again
asked Clement to follow up. She reported in a March 1993 memo that
Howard officials told her Moriba would not qualify for a
scholarship until he had permanent resident status.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Keita turned to Salt Lake City, then in the midst of
its bid. There he found a money tree. Before Moriba graduated from
Howard, Salt Lake City bidders had spent close to $100,000 on his
tuition and other benefits. But Keita paid a price for the benefits
_ he was expelled from the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The documents don't paint a complete picture. While many offers
of help were found, the trail goes cold when trying to determine
whether the students were admitted to colleges and who paid the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Other documents confirm that bid team member Bobby Rearden told
Pal Schmitt of Hungary, a member of the IOC evaluation team that
ranked the 1996 candidate cities before the final vote in Tokyo,
that he could obtain a tennis scholarship for his daughter at the
University of Georgia. A memo from Rearden said, ``He clearly wants
his daughter to come to the U.S. to college. ... I told him we had
a scholarship for her at the University of Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Rearden invited Petra Schmitt to travel to Atlanta. ``The
purpose of the visit would be to look at schools to see if she
likes them,'' Rearden wrote in his memo. ``(Schmitt) said it would
be great if Petra is in school in Georgia and Atlanta gets the
Games because I could visit her often.''
</P>
<P>
   Petra instead enrolled at the University of Southern California
in 1992 and was a two-time All-America player on the tennis team.
</P>
<P>
   While documents verify that the IOC members were not shy in
asking for special treatment, they also show that the Atlanta bid
team proffered countless unsolicited favors, not all of which were
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   When the late Mohammed Benjelloun of Morocco visited with his
wife and son in June 1990, the family took a side trip to New York
and stayed two nights in a $469-a-night suite booked by the AOC at
the Marriott Marquis on Times Square. A memo from one bid team
member fretted, ``He wants to pay for it. We will offer again.''
</P>
<P>
   `Good wrestling opportunity'
</P>
<P>
   Payne and his aides were avid researchers, compiling profiles of
the members and developing individual strategies to woo each one.
If their information-gathering found a college-age teen-ager or
job-seeking relative, they were quick to play the benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Rearden wrote in a memo to Payne in July 1990 that he recently
had dined with Germany's Walther Troger and noted the IOC member
was inclined to vote for Melbourne, a rival candidate city. But
there was still hope. During the dinner, Troger mentioned he had a
daughter who was getting a divorce in California ``and might like a
teaching job in the Atlanta area.''
</P>
<P>
   After Troger's daughter apparently was offered Atlanta's
assistance, which was turned down, Payne wrote a letter two weeks
later that practically insisted the bid team be allowed to help
find her a job. ``I know your daughter is reluctant for any help
with universities in our area, but I hope you will emphasize to her
that what we want to do is invite her to visit us and see some of
the institutions and get information for her as she deems
appropriate,'' he wrote. ``We certainly do not want to interfere
with the process, but we would like to help if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Often Payne was successful. At his behest, George Gillett Jr.,
chairman of Vail Associates, apparently offered Russian IOC member
Vitaly Smirnov's son a job at a Colorado ski resort in 1990. Payne
wrote a note of thanks to Gillett, saying, ``As you probably know,
Mr. Smirnov came to us and wanted us to find an opportunity for his
son where we would work him tirelessly, teach him English and most
importantly, give him some parental care and guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   The records do not indicate if young Smirnov took the job and
who paid his salary.
</P>
<P>
   Bid team member Horace Sibley, a King &AMP; Spalding attorney,
played host to the son and daughter-in-law of IOC member Flor
Isava-Fonseca of Venezuela. He took them to the Doral Open, a men's
golf tournament in Miami, and apparently arranged a job interview
in Atlanta. In a follow-up letter to Isava-Fonseca in March 1990,
Sibley wrote, ``I hope Fernando had a good visit. I also hope that
his business interview proved successful. ... After Fernando left I
personally spoke with the president of one of the banks. I believe
something can be worked out to Fernando's advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Wallwork, son of IOC member Paul Wallwork from Western
Samoa, was a budding wrestler. Payne offered to find him training
in the United States. In a letter written in June 1990, he said,
``We look forward to receiving specific information on Jerry, as I
am certain we can come up with a good wrestling opportunity here in
the states.''
</P>
<P>
   After a visit to Atlanta in 1989, Wallwork, his wife and
daughter took a trip to Disney World on the AOC's tab. They stayed
in the luxurious Grand Cypress Hotel. Total airfare for the three
was $19,828. Other IOC members and their families, including Phil
Coles from Australia and Anton Geesink from the Netherlands, also
took the Disney trip.
</P>
<P>
   The bidders did not forget about their friends after Atlanta won
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   They flew the son of the now-expelled David Sibandze from
Swaziland to Atlanta for a weeklong stay at the Marriott Marquis.
The airfare and hotel alone cost the bid team $5,100. They gave
Musa Sibandze tickets to the Atlanta Symphony and picked up his
bill at an exercise studio.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar Chowdhry, president of the international boxing
federation, who wielded considerable influence with IOC members,
sought and received assistance in getting his two daughters into
Georgia Tech. Then he asked bid team member Charlie Battle to help
a federation official get his son into the university.
</P>
<P>
   Battle made some phone calls and arranged interviews ``with the
appropriate people at Tech,'' he wrote to Payne in a January 1991
memo. The student started taking Tech's ``English as a Second
Language'' classes and then began regular courses that spring,
living in the dorm building next to the Chowdhry girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech has been completely accommodating,'' Battle wrote, adding
that the federation official ``truly believes we performed a
miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
