<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL RELENTS, LETTING ARAB LIVE FOR NOW IN JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On a visit to East Jerusalem in July, Interior
Minister Natan Sharansky announced that he wanted to end an Israeli
policy that in recent years has stripped some Palestinians of their
right to live in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to change this policy and to stop canceling
the residence of inhabitants of East Jerusalem,'' Sharansky said.
``We cannot talk about a united Jerusalem without proper treatment
of the residents of East Jerusalem. We need to do everything to
insure that residents of the east receive equal treatment to those
of the west.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics had long condemned the practice of stripping
Palestinians of their East Jerusalem residency as a means of
curbing the growth of the Arab population in this bitterly
contested city.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Ministry figures show that nearly 5,400 Palestinians
have lost their East Jerusalem residency in this way since Israel
captured the area in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. About half lost it
during the three-year term of the rightist government of Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who was defeated in national elections
in May.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after Sharansky spoke, a test case landed in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   Following standard procedure, his ministry had sent an eviction
letter to another Palestinian, this time a member of a prominent
Jerusalem family that has lived in the city for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Musa Budeiri, 53, a political science professor who has
British citizenship and travels regularly abroad, was served notice
that his residence had expired and that he was henceforth a
tourist, required to leave Israel within 30 days. His British
residence permit, obtained after he married a British woman, was
cited as the reason for this move.
</P>
<P>
   Under ministry regulations, East Jerusalem residence expires if
someone has ``moved the center of his life'' outside the city for
more than seven years, received a permanent residence permit in
another country or become a foreign citizen. Those expelled are
apparently free to go to the West Bank or Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Budeiri stayed home beyond the Aug. 22 eviction deadline, vowing
to fight the order. His predicament drew public protests from
academic colleagues in Israel and abroad and was widely reported in
the press, becoming a high profile test of Sharansky's statement of
intent.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky, a former human rights campaigner in the Soviet Union,
came under criticism for violating Budeiri's right to live in his
native city.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has for years sought to maintain a large Jewish majority
in Jerusalem, primarily through restrictions on Arab housing
construction. But while Jews make up two-thirds of the city's
population of 633,000, a recent Israeli study has found that
because of population shifts and a higher Arab birthrate,
Jerusalem's Arab population is increasing at three times the rate
of the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry has routinely maintained that in revoking
residence permits it is simply applying the law to the Arabs of
East Jerusalem, which was annexed to Israel in 1980 and whose
inhabitants have been granted the status of permanent residents,
not Israeli citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Many Palestinians in search of housing have moved to West Bank
suburbs of East Jerusalem outside the Israeli-drawn city limits and
lost their residence rights, including Israeli health insurance and
social security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Budeiri, who is the founding director of the Israeli studies
program at Al Quds University here, said that the policy belied
Israel's claims that Jerusalem was a united city.
</P>
<P>
   ``If unifying the city means that its 200,000 Arabs can have
their residence revoked at any time,'' he said, ``what do you
unify? The stone?''
</P>
<P>
   Last week brought the first sign of a change. After extensive
consultations, Sharansky suspended the revocation of Budeiri's
residency. However, the Interior Ministry also notified Budeiri's
lawyer that while his client retained his residency, there had been
legal grounds to revoke it, and that the case would be reviewed in
six years.
</P>
<P>
   Budeiri had won a battle, but not the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
