<HEADER>
A8481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-GUNSHOW-NYT &LR;      09-11 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GUNSHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES COUNTY SEEKS DISTANCE FROM GUN SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a significant setback for the nation's largest
gun show, Los Angeles County has adopted a law banning the sale of
weapons or ammunition on its property.
</P>
<P>
   The law, approved by the county's Board of Supervisors on
Tuesday, threatens to undermine the core business of the Great
Western gun show, held four times a year on the county fairgrounds
in Pomona, Calif., about 60 miles east of Los Angeles. The event
draws as many as 2,000 exhibitors and 35,000 enthusiasts and brings
the county an estimated $600,000 a year, the largest share of the
rent it earns at the fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is, the county should not be profiting from the
gun business,'' said Zev Yaroslavsky, the county supervisor who
sponsored the motion. ``We shouldn't be leasing or renting our
property for the sale of guns or ammunition of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure also bans discussions about firearms sales on county
property, which would effectively limit the gun show to a display
of weapons and their prices.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the event's promoter, Great Western Shows, has
vowed to file a lawsuit, as early as Monday, that accuses the
county of breaching its contract and impinging on constitutionally
protected political and commercial speech. Great Western Shows said
it would also seek a restraining order to block the county from
enforcing the law.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the county officials who supported the law
jumped on a bandwagon that would have little practical effect on
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County is among several municipalities in the United
States that have filed lawsuits against gun manufacturers, and it
has banned the sale of inexpensive handguns in its jurisdiction
(the county governs areas that are not covered by incorporated
cities). A state ban on cheap handguns was signed into law late
last month by Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The county law was enacted in the same week that mayors and
police chiefs from around the country went to the White House and
Congress to highlight what they feel is the need for more gun
control laws, including closing loopholes in the regulation of gun
shows. The shows are increasingly seen as places where guns are too
easily obtained, often for illegal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other states and the federal government, California
has fairly strict regulations covering transactions at gun shows.
All sales must be conducted through a licensed firearms dealer, and
buyers must pass a background check and wait 10 days before
receiving their weapons. But recent events made officials wonder if
the show was simply too large to be policed effectively.
</P>
<P>
   State-banned assault rifles owned by two men killed in a
shootout with police after a bank robbery in North Hollywood two
years ago were traced by the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms to the gun show in Pomona. Last May at the show,
undercover agents from the California attorney general's office
were able to buy two assault weapons and five converter kits used
to make them fully automatic, without being subjected to a
background check or the waiting period. In another sting, federal
agents last month arrested a man they met at the gun show who sold
them 10 machine guns and a Browning automatic rifle. Yaroslavsky
said hate literature and Nazi memorabilia have been obtained at the
show by members of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   The law takes effect in one month, which would bar transactions
at the next scheduled show, in late October.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the event, Chad Seger, said the ban on sales
would hurt the gun show tremendously, because dealers come from as
far as Europe and Australia and do not have stores in the area
where they could conduct sales when the show is over. He said only
10 percent of the booths at the show deal in modern firearms, and
that 30 percent to 40 percent of them deal in antiques and
collectibles. The remainder are taken up by a variety of businesses
hoping to appeal to firearms enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   The firearms that are the primary focus of the show ``are ones
nobody in their right mind would use to commit a crime,'' Seger
said. Further, Seger said, the gun show has long been a forum for
political speech and historical discussions that are protected
under the First Amendment; by eliminating gun sales, which draw
most people to the event, the county is undermining that exchange,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seger said there were only five or six other sites in Southern
California big enough to handle the show, and those were all booked
a year in advance. Great Western has been at Pomona for 22 years,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Volokh, a law professor at UCLA who specializes in free
speech issues and the regulation of firearms, said the county has a
right to control commercial enterprise on its property, even if the
items for sale are legal. And he said the fair could continue to be
a forum for free speech even if gun sales were banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claim is not laughable, but I think it is a very weak
claim,'' Volokh said. ``Surely they lose some part of their
audience, but the audience is turning out for a nonspeech activity
that is itself not protected by the First Amendment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
