<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston had its wettest day in 15 months on Friday when 4.71
inches of rain fell, but high pressure sprawled along the Atlantic
Seaboard will produce very dry conditions from New England to
Georgia Sunday. Sunshine will be abundant in the Northeast and also
the Southeast, though streamers of high clouds will move eastward
from the Ohio Valley into the Middle Atlantic states. After a cool
start, temperatures should rise to slightly above seasonal levels
across most of the East.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore winds will strengthen along the Georgia and Florida
coasts, encouraging rip tides and rough surf. Thunderstorms will be
scattered over central and southern Florida Sunday afternoon.
Meanwhile, Hurricane Floyd will move north of Puerto Rico into a
region less favorable for strengthening as three new tropical
disturbances farther east in the Atlantic strengthen.
</P>
<P>
   A surge of warm, humid air from the southern Plains will
instigate a cluster of showers and thunderstorms from Oklahoma into
Missouri. Farther north, more showers and storms will develop in
the western Great Lakes as warmer air returns. Low pressure near
Duluth, Minn., will bring a cool, soaking rain to northern
Minnesota. Meanwhile, thundershowers will attend the cold front in
the middle Mississippi and Missouri Valleys and in north Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Except for residual thunderstorms in New Mexico and southern
Colorado, the West will become brighter with abundant sunshine.
Offshore winds will bring hot air to the north Pacific Coast with
record heat possible west of the Cascades in Oregon. Low clouds
will linger from San Francisco to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Coastal Chill
</P>
<P>
   Clouds help control summer temperatures. During the past few
months, this has been true in the Southwest. July brought frequent
rain clouds to the deserts resulting in a very cool month for Las
Vegas as the mercury failed to reach 100 degrees on more than half
the days. Even along the southern California coast, ocean clouds
have persisted long into the summer days producing the coolest
summer in 66 years at San Diego. From June through the August, the
temperature averaged 3.7 degrees below normal. A cooler than usual
sea surface has undoubtedly contributed to California's coastal
chill as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
