<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SAYS JAKARTA IS EASING OPPOSITION TO PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-RDP) 
(js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Saturday that
Indonesia seems to be softening its position daily on the
deployment of international peacekeeping troops in East Timor and
that he hopes to get an official go-ahead from President B.J.
Habibie on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seem to be indications that there may be a shift in the
Indonesian position,'' Annan said as he arrived for the first open
Security Council debate on East Timor, at which perhaps more than
two dozen nations are expected to speak over a period of two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be talking to President Habibie tomorrow morning,'' he
added, ``and I hope I will be able to hear from him directly what
the position is.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Indonesia may be considering allowing a
previously planned peacekeeping operation to be deployed in the
territory ahead of schedule, which would amount to a face-saving
compromise under which Indonesia could avoid appearing to have
caved in to international demands for an immediate intervention
force.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement signed by Indonesia, Portugal and the United
Nations on May 5, a peacekeeping force was to have been permitted
to enter East Timor after the Indonesian Parliament had ratified
the results of the territory's vote for independence later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers would then be responsible for law and order as
political power is transferred to the East Timorese and elections
would be held in the new nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday Wiranto was saying in three months time,'' Annan
said. ``Today he seems to have softened the position, indicating
that they may allow the peacekeepers to go in earlier. I hope the
decision will be taken soon, not later.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's unusual open session of the Security Council was
demanded by Portugal, the former colonial overlord of the
territory, which had spent the week pressing furiously for a public
debate. All council sessions on the issue last week were held
behind closed doors, as all member nations balked at forcing a
violation of the agreement with Indonesia by deploying troops
without Jakarta's consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go straight to the point,'' said Antonio Monteiro,
Portugal's delegate to the United Nations, said in his speech
Saturday. ``Portugal has repeatedly requested this meeting of the
Security Council to confront the council with its responsibilities
in managing the appalling crisis in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rape of East Timor has taken place before our eyes,'' he
said. ``The United Nations cannot, must not, afford once again to
intervene in a conflict only to stand by while the process then
loses its course.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the council before his speech, Monteiro told
reporters that the shift in Indonesia's position on troops was
``exactly what we want.'' Portugal, which decided to abandon East
Timor in 1974, has worked for nearly a quarter of a century to
dislodge Indonesia, which seized the territory by force in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. representative here, told
reporters outside the council chamber before his speech, ``It was
important that the world community have this discussion today, but
the obligation to fix this problem remains squarely with the people
who caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Council session was the first part of a two-day
meeting that will culminate on Monday with a report from a
five-member Security Council team that spent most of last week in
Indonesia, capped by a visit Saturday to East Timor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAK     09-11 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEWHERE, A PLACE FOR FORBES, MAYBE 
VENTURA CAN'T MAKE PEROT SAY `UNCLE' 
WHEN $5 MILLION DOESN'T ADD UP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Ky., Mass., Minn., N.J., Texas)  (rk) 
 By   B.DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As chairman of the National Republican Senatorial Committee,
Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky is responsible for rounding up
enough money and strong candidates to guarantee that his party
retains control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   So when Gov. Christie Whitman pulled out of the New Jersey
Senate race on Tuesday, saying that on second thought she would
rather run New Jersey than run for Congress, McConnell expressed
``big disappointment'' and lamented that her exit ``makes it less
likely we'll win the Senate seat in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he began to ponder the matter of a replacement candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't Steve Forbes go for it?'' he asked when some
Republican strategists and members of his senatorial committee
gathered a couple of nights later at a Washington steak house for a
brainstorming session.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a worthy idea and was kicked around a good bit, one
participant recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is a candidate for the Republican presidential
nomination, of course. But the focus of the dinner conversation was
on the fact that he hails from New Jersey and, should he run for
the Senate, would start off with good name recognition, an
experienced campaign organization, lots of popular ideas about tax
reform and pockets every bit as deep as those of the wealthiest of
the Democratic Senate hopefuls, Jon S. Corzine, a former Wall
Street tycoon estimated to be worth $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what of Forbes' hopes for the White House?
</P>
<P>
   Not going to happen, the dinner group concluded without serious
dissent or discussion, not with him still struggling to reach
double digits in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   No formal decision was made on broaching the idea of a Senate
race with Forbes. But by noon the next day word of the session had
reached the Forbes camp.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it, his people said. Not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   But wait.
</P>
<P>
   By suppertime that day, word of the session and the ``Forbes
solution'' had trickled all the way down to Texas and the
presidential campaign camp of Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Really great idea, said some of the governor's people _ few of
them seriously concerned about Forbes' ability to snatch the
party's nomination from Bush but all worried about his ability to
use a caustic, multimillion-dollar ad campaign to cripple the
governor for the fall race. One of them, a top strategist, floated
a sweetener.
</P>
<P>
   Should Forbes jump out of the presidential contest and into the
New Jersey contest, he mused, Bush, for openers, very well might be
willing to campaign for him and maybe even hold a few rallies.
Perhaps even more enticing, the Bush man went on, the governor
might be willing to incorporate some major Forbes political ideas
into the Bush campaign message.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes folks didn't bite. Still not going to happen, they
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura Can't Make Perot Say `Uncle'
</P>
<P>
   The forces of Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota and Ross Perot are
squabbling again over control of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who is the party's highest elected official, won the
first round back in late July in Detroit when his candidate, Jack
Gargan of Cedar Key, Fla., was elected national chairman at the
party's annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan immediately announced that the party's headquarters would
be moved to Florida from Texas, and he said its day-to-day
operations would be more openly run. He also called on Perot, the
party's founder and presidential candidate in two elections, to
withdraw from any active participation in party affairs,
particularly presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the Detroit defeat and mounting evidence that the
party's rank-and-file is ready for change, Perot, accustomed to
running things his way, seems bent on retaining as much control
over the party as possible. And, it turns out, he still has some
things going for him _ at least until Jan. 1. That is the date that
Gargan will officially take office. Until then, the man in charge
of the party is the one who has been chairman for the past few
years, Russ Verney, and he is a Perot man, going back almost to the
days when the Texas billionaire founded the party.
</P>
<P>
   So the other day when the party's Executive Committee met to
vote on a site for next year's national convention, set for Aug.
10-13, Verney was able to thwart a move by Ventura supporters to
hold the gathering in Minneapolis. It took several rounds of voting
to head off the governor's forces, but eventually Verney prevailed
and the committee picked Long Beach, Calif., as the site.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan accused Verney of railroading the proceedings by calling
the meeting on too short notice and then taking too many votes to
decide the site issue. He contended that committee members had not
had enough time to canvass party members about where they would
prefer to meet and he said that when the committee could not agree
on a site on the first vote, the matter should have been tabled
until a future meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Now he wants to poll party members to see which site they
prefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with California if that truly is the wish,''
he said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Verney says California is, truly, the favored site, in part
because many party members worry that Ventura, despite his
declaration that he will not run for president, would dominate any
convention held in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the convention eventually is held, the Reform Party's
role in the 2000 presidential race could be important, especially
if the contest is close.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura can always change his mind about running and polls
indicate that he might pick up 10 percent or more of the vote
should he be the Reform nominee. Similarly, if Patrick Buchanan,
the columnist and commentator, bolts the Republican Party and ends
up as the Reform candidate, the polls say that he, too, might
capture a significant number of votes, maybe 15 percent or so.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans worry that a Reform candidate might cost their
nominee more votes than the Democrats' nominee. And adding to that
worry is the fact that on the basis of past election performances,
the Reform Party will have more than $12 million in federal
campaign funds to lavish on its nominee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When $5 Million Doesn't Add Up
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has spent a good part of the past seven
years dropping in on places beset with trouble and announcing
federal money grants. It's all part of the political game, a proven
vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   So when he showed up in Boston the other day and announced a $5
million aid package for New England's troubled fishing industry
(too many boats, not enough fish) he was warmly received.
</P>
<P>
   Initially.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on closer inspection, it became clear that Gore was not
announcing a new program but rather was announcing a program that
had been approved almost a year earlier _ after being pushed
through Congress by New England legislators, led by Sen. John F.
Kerry, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Anger replaced warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides chided Gore aides for glossing over credit
where credit was due. So did fishing industry leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really stinks of cheap, election year politics,'' Paul
Cohane, the head of the Gulf of Main Fisherman's Association,
complained to The Boston Globe. ``Gore had very little to do with
this. Yet he came in an took all the glory. He stole the
limelight.`
</P>
<P>
   Gore's office said he did nothing more than make a ``formal
official announcement'' that the aid was available. But he called
Kerry to apologize, The Globe reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
