<HEADER>
A8507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-SCENE-(TRIMS)-N     09-11 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-SCENE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRY FROM BESIEGED CITY: DON'T FORGET EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-RDP, TIMOR-U.N.) 
(js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ On the steep hillside behind the U.N.
compound, armed men were shooting at refugees who were trying to
flee to safety. In the crowded courtyard below, a police adviser
from New Zealand was teaching little boys to play cricket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in an extraordinary combination of the bizarre
and the obscene,'' Brian Kelly, a U.N. official, said Saturday as
he described that strange recent moment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The fear ebbs and flows, people here said. Sometimes the
gunshots and the blasts of hand grenades are hardly noticed.
Sometimes _ usually late at night _ panic sweeps the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes terrified refugees storm their way into the compound,
tossing their children over its wall and climbing through coils of
razor wire to seek safety. Sometimes the gunfire drives them to
flee again, crawling under the coiled wire at the back of the
compound and scaling the hillside in search of some other place to
hide.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The number of people seeking refuge in the compound rises and
falls. At the moment it is about 1,000. Small cooking fires are
everywhere. People with nothing else to do sleep like vagrants here
and there on the ground. The air is filled with the cries and
whines of hundreds of small, dirty children.
</P>
<P>
   Inside an auditorium, a small table is covered with crucifixes
and statues of the Virgin Mary that the refugees took with them
when they fled their homes. Candles are always burning.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival Saturday of a delegation of high-ranking U.N.
officials caused little stir. Only rumors of an imminent attack, it
seemed, could rouse the people here from a passivity born of dread.
</P>
<P>
   As she watched the officials tour the camp, a woman named Maria
burst into loud tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid, please help us, I beg you,'' she cried in
English, accosting Martin Adjaba, the Namibian representative to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sympathize with you,'' said Adjaba, one of five
representatives from the Security Council who visited this stunned
and bleeding city to test the assurances of the Indonesian military
that everything was under control.
</P>
<P>
   The woman named Maria raised her voice. ``If we stay here they
will kill us, all of us,'' she said. ``I beg you. Don't leave us
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   If her manner seemed dramatic _ particularly in contrast with
the people who looked on dully from their cots and cooking fires _
it was impossible not to respect her fears.
</P>
<P>
   Adjaba took her hands. ``We will do everything to make sure your
future is secure,'' he said. ``That is the commitment of the United
Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a commitment the delegation was struggling to implement
Saturday as it urged the military here to quell the irregular
militias that have terrorized East Timor since it voted nearly two
weeks ago to become independent of a 24-year Indonesian occupation.
</P>
<P>
   As residents of the compound can testify, in example after
example, the Indonesian security forces _ far from curbing militia
activity _ are acting in concert with them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is that the same people who are supposed to
protect us are the ones who are terrorizing us,'' said Peter Wyatt,
an Australian security officer.
</P>
<P>
   When the military, in what so far seems to have been an
ineffective gesture, declared martial law here four days ago, a
force of fresh soldiers replaced a contingent of police officers in
guarding the U.N. compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police left on two trucks,'' said Nick Birnback, a U.N.
official, ``and when they did, every single one of them emptied
their weapons into the air. That was their goodbye to us.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the picture of East Timor that was presented to
the delegation in a surreal visit to the military headquarters, a
sprawling white building that is one of the few sizable structures
left intact in Dili, and is still festooned with the red-and-white
bunting that marked Indonesia's national day last month.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri presented a slide show of colored
graphs marked: torture, kidnap, arson, killing, looting. The graphs
he said, showed conclusively that martial law was choking off the
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of moment that has tested the patience of the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gen. Wiranto, the armed forces commander, made a
similar presentation in Jakarta. According to an official traveling
with the delegation, Adjaba told the commander, in effect: ``We
don't believe you. You are not convincing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the meeting still under way, the hand phones of the
delegates began to ring. Militia fighters were firing guns and
menacing the compound in Dili, they were told.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto made his own telephone call: No, he said, nothing was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates insisted, and the general _ who speaks English _
made another telephone call to one of his subordinates in Dili.
``I'll call my insubordinate commander,'' he said, in a telling
slip of the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a person traveling with the delegation said, the
general conceded that there was violence, but denied _ incorrectly,
as witnesses here confirmed _ that it was directed at the compound.
</P>
<P>
   As he was waiting for his second reply from Dili, according to
this account, Wiranto made an awkward moment more awkward, offering
light patter about a new golf course he had just built adjacent to
his headquarters in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he wanted us to play golf,'' the person said, ``to which
there was a resounding silence in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Dili Saturday, the U.N. delegation saw enough to convince
them that they were witnessing a major humanitarian disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely appalling,'' one official said. ``I had tended
to think, even in the worst case, that they would not go so far.
They spit in the eye of the United Nations, of the member states
and the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun began to sink, the delegates hurried from the
compound for a well-guarded convoy back to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   As one man rushed down the steps of the auditorium, picking his
way through a crowd of refugees, he heard a quiet voice just behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget East Timor,'' the voice said.
</P>
<P>
   The man stopped and looked. A woman, holding a small child in
her arms, looked back at him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
