<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rematch veteran Holyfield steps up training for Lewis
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Confident, Evander Holyfield moves to Houston this
week to continue intense training for his Nov. 13 heavyweight title
rematch with Lennox Lewis. He's excited for good reason: Holyfield
is the king of the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Five times Holyfield won second bouts against the same opponent:
Dwight Qawi, Alex Stewart, Michael Moorer, Riddick Bowe and Mike
Tyson. Now, it's Lewis, who contends, like many, that he won the
March bout with Holyfield, which ended in a draw by the judges'
scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can surprise Evander once,'' his attorney, Jim Thomas
said, ``but you can't surprise him twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and his team have been perhaps more diligent than ever
in preparation. The three-time champion began preliminary training
in early July without an agreement on a second bout. He has spent
about three weeks with strength and conditioning coach Tim Hallmark
in Atlanta while also doing serious training under Don Turner.
Those efforts will increase in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, Holyfield's trainer, has reviewed the first fight and is
charting a course of action against Lewis' left jab that was so
effective in the first fight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hallmark is ensuring that Holyfield enters the ring
in his typical flawless shape. Holyfield's new diet emphasizes
natural foods and water, while minimizing strength-enhancing
supplements like Creatine. Holyfield experienced cramps in the days
leading up to the first Lewis fight and during the match, and he
and his camp are hopeful the new diet with eliminate those
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Training really is not a burden for me,'' Holyfield said.
``I've been doing it for 15 years. I don't have to go to the woods
to train. A man's going to do what a man wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What Holyfield likes to do while training in Houston is go to
schools or YMCAs and speak to youngsters. He is free with his time,
which is where Thomas steps in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want as few distractions as possible,'' he said. ``I'm going
to take on every task possible to keep it off of Evander. He is
always giving of himself. It's hard to convince him that to give to
other people he has to first take care of himself over the next
nine weeks.... I want him focusing totally on the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
