<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quarterbacking the D: Free safety's job is no snap
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NFL free safety is described as the ``quarterback
of the secondary,'' and Eugene Robinson calls his share of signals
for the Falcons. His job is to position defensive backs and change
coverages based on opposing formations. Robinson describes what
happens in the few seconds before and after the ball is snapped:
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is, where is the tight end lined up? Then, we
can get everybody lined up on defense. (Middle linebacker) Jessie
Tuggle makes the call; I echo the call, sending the strong safety
to that side. From there, I look at the backfield to see if there
are any adjustments, and then if the wide receivers or tight ends
look like they're going to go in motion. After that, I start
thinking what we're going to change if we get motion. I think,
`What do they like to do from this set?' _ based on what I've seen
watching film.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a receiver is split way out, I go, `Do I have to get way
over the top (deep zone) on him, or do I cut down my drop?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have different checks that I yell out that will rotate a
zone to the motion side or rotate away from the motion side. We
have one where a linebacker flares out, which might leave a man
(usually a running back) uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``With motion, the corner will give me a signal by tapping a
hand to a certain spot on the body that lets me know I might need
to change my position. It could indicate whether I need to cover
over the top on my side, whether I'm going to take inside cuts, if
I'm going to give him help or if I can just worry about going to
the other side to help there.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the yelling I do is just confirming that I see the
signals. Sometimes, the signals indicate I'm covering a certain
route, like a corner route or a curl.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a cornerback comes across with a receiver in motion, I
may have to go back on that side. If the strength of the passing
formation is away from me, I'll tell the corner he's normally
isolated, and he has no help. I'll tell him to watch the slant over
the middle because he has no help there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll mess with the quarterback sometimes and try to make it
look like I'm staying in a certain part of the field. Then, when he
turns his head, I'll sprint as fast as I can to another area of the
field, where there might be multiple receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, that's how you get picks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-D.C.-CURFEW-380&AMP;ADD-N     09-11 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D.C.-CURFEW-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON POLICE BEGIN TO ENFORCE 1995 CURFEW
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four years ago, the City Council approved a youth
curfew. Then, after a long court challenge and a recent campaign to
educate parents, children and the police, the District of Columbia
started last week to enforce the ban on unsupervised children on
the streets late at night.
</P>
<P>
   Young people appeared to be obeying. In the first few days of
enforcement, only six teen-agers were caught by police officers and
released to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Moving slowly along the city streets, rarely more than 25 mph,
Sgt. Pamela Wheeler Taylor of the Metropolitan Police Department
monitored night clubs, fast-food restaurants, city parks and
outside college dorms on Thursday night after 11. And from downtown
Washington to quiet, tree-lined residential neighborhoods, the
sidewalks were unusually free of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The curfew is a good idea in principle, but the logistics of
enforcing the law concern police officers,'' Ms. Taylor said. ``Of
course, if we can help one child, it is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for every child detained for a curfew violation, she said,
one officer must be pulled off his beat or away from his work to
supervise the child, who must be kept away from adult criminal
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Once a child is in custody, officers can search him or her and
run background checks. Handcuffs may not be used unless the child
becomes violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``An officer must use some discretion and a little common
sense,'' Ms. Taylor added. ``You know what kids are doing and what
they are not doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits teen-agers under 17 years of age from being in
a public place unaccompanied by a parent, guardian or any person 21
or older between 11 p.m. and 6 a.m. Monday through Thursday, and
midnight to 6 a.m. Friday to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the curfew, which started on Tuesday, could result in
25 hours of community service for young offenders. But the law
tries to reach the teen-agers through their parents, who can be
punished with fines of up to $500 and community service for
permitting their children to roam city streets during restricted
hours. There are exceptions to the law, however, including running
errands for a parent or guardian, traveling to or from work,
attending chaperoned school events and certain emergencies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Terrance W. Gainer, the executive assistant police chief, said
neighborhood patrol officers would contact the parents after
picking up a child. Officers transport the child home, and the
parents must sign a release for custody. If parents or guardians
cannot be reached, the child will be held overnight. The child is
turned over to the Department of Human Services if not picked up by
6 a.m. And the Department of Child and Family Services becomes
involved for any child under 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district's curfew law is part of our overall strategy to
keep our neighborhoods safe _ and we will vigorously enforce the
law,'' Mayor Anthony A. Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The curfew law was adopted in June 1995, a result of increasing
crime rates among young people in many urban areas around the
country, but enforced sporadically. Similar curfew proposals died
in 1993 and 1994 here.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, U.S. District Judge Emmet G. Sullivan ruled
that the curfew violated minors' rights to free movement and
parents' rights to exercise parental discretion. The decision came
in a case brought by the American Civil Liberties Union, which is
critical of curfew laws.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the District of Columbia Circuit Court of Appeals
disagreed, ruling that teen-agers did not have an unrestricted
right to gather in public late at night and that the 1995 law did
not infringe on the rights of children or parents.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur B. Spitzer, legal director for the ACLU office in
Washington, anticipates that enforcement of the curfew law may be
``arbitrary and discriminatory,'' with police officers patrolling
certain neighborhoods more than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is virtually inevitable in a situation like this,'' Spitzer
said. ``Some kids have back yards and automobiles. And kids in
other neighborhoods have no place to go other than neighborhood
streets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
