<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-MEN-I-ART-     09-11 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-MEN-I-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRITTY MARTIN EXTENDS HIMSELF TO FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Martin was the kid in all-whites flailing away
on the remote courts of the National Tennis Center as a junior when
Andre Agassi, in his denim shorts, was bleaching his long locks and
foiling tradition in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was a year removed from scraping up laundry money and
lugging books to class at Northwestern University when the gangly
Pete Sampras barged onto the scene and left the grounds with a cup
lofted in the air after winning the U.S. Open in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Martin has always been the tag-along in American
tennis, always stuck in the line of recognition behind Agassi,
Sampras, Jim Courier and Michael Chang. Not anymore. Over the last
dozen days, Martin has showed it is never too late to reveal your
identity to an American public eager to embrace miracle &UR;  &LR; makers.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting this description, seventh-seeded Martin extended himself
in sickness and in health this past &UR;  &LR; week to secure his place in
the men's final with a meticulous dismantling of Frenchman Cedric
Pioline, 6-4, 6-1, 6-2, Saturday in Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' said Martin, who will play second-seeded
Andre Agassi, the winner over third-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov in
Saturday's 's other semifinal match. ``I didn't expect to be here.
I knew I could, given the right circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't look at the draw. I knew that Pete Sampras was
in my section, but I wasn't aware that Patrick Rafter was on my
half,'' added Martin, who benefited when both withdrew due to
injuries. ``I felt good today. I felt really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a Windex-blue sky, Martin looked as fresh and crisp as a
dry-cleaned shirt compared to the greenish hue he had assumed
during his last two matches, performances that were fortified by a
buffet of intravenous fluids and chanting partisan crowds. Finally,
he looked healthy, as if the cool, breezy air agreed with him in
the face of the stylish but perpetually angst-ridden Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up this morning I was nervous that I wouldn't be
able to play as well on a full tank as I had been on a half, but I
did,'' Martin said. ``Played pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, grit overcame grace once again as Martin snapped
back returns and pulled winners out of a holster with the kind of
consistency that left Pioline crestfallen before the second set was
15 minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after being broken twice in the first set, Pioline
would find the answers harder and harder to come by. Every
brilliant shot was turned against him, as in the sixth game of the
second set.
</P>
<P>
   A well-placed approach shot, sliced behind Martin deep at the
baseline, looked like the prelude to a winner for the Frenchman.
But Martin, circling back in stumbling imperfection, managed to
whip his racket around and slap a crosscourt passing shot that left
Pioline lunging in vain on his way to being broken and slapped down
into a 1-5 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   A game later, as his backhand floated long on Martin's set
point, Pioline flipped his racket into the air, missed the catch
and knocked himself in the head. This was not going to be his day
to make his third Grand Slam final, it was Martin's moment to
achieve his second.
</P>
<P>
   Since his appearance in the 1994 Australian final, Martin has
faded in and out as a threat on the men's tour because of nagging
injuries that seemed to sabotage every rise he made in the
rankings. In 1996, he finished the year ranked 12th. A year later,
after an elbow injury that put his tennis on hold for seven months,
his ranking had plummeted to a dismal No. 81.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he cannot get through a hotel lobby unnoticed after the two
weeks he has had. ``It's nice; you're carrying your bags, and
people stop you,'' Martin said. ``It's not bad; it's OK with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has only himself to thank for this newfound celebrity.
Instead of fitting himself for a cardigan and bingo, Martin decided
it was not time to retire, but the moment to seize a chance and
come back fighting at the age of 29. For a while, during an
exhausting fourth-round match with Greg Rusedski, when Martin was
nearly undone by a stomach virus, he was down two sets to none and
watching his adversary serve for the match.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, through pride or divine intervention, Martin survived
in a five-set match that left him so physically drained that he was
spread out in the training room for two hours receiving fluids
through a tube.
</P>
<P>
   His revival was stunning enough as he advanced through the
semifinals against Slava Dosedel in four sets. But Saturday, Martin
showed what a nice rest and a healthy glow can do to his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he played too good,'' Pioline said. ``He was reading
very well the ball today, catching everything. Very few unforced
errors and serving big,'' said Pioline, who watched 14 Martin aces
go by in a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him play like this,'' Pioline said. ``I think
he has a good chance'' to win in the final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
