<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-MCCAIN-55     09-11 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-MCCAIN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Texas) 
GIULIANI HAS KIND WORDS FOR McCAIN, BUT NO ENDORSEMENT  
(lh) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the sort of highly publicized event featuring
two politicians gearing up for major campaigns that under most
circumstances would reflect their mutual endorsement: Rudolph
Giuliani, the mayor who would be senator, and John McCain of
Arizona, the senator who would be president, chatting over
antipasto and seafood marinara at DaNico in Little Italy and
pretending not to notice the photographers and television cameras
all around them.
</P>
<P>
   But with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas now the far-and-away
front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination with a
record $49 million in campaign contributions, these are not normal
circumstances. So even as Giuliani and McCain have developed a
close friendship, despite their effusive public embrace last week,
close political advisers to the mayor say he has already quietly
committed to endorsing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain himself acknowledged that possibility on Wednesday,
saying it would not dampen his own support for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may make a decision on who he wishes to support for the
presidency of the United States; that matters little to me,''
McCain said after their lunch. ``What's important to me is to have
Mayor Giuliani in the United States Senate.'' He also said he did
not think the mayor's endorsement would matter in New Hampshire or
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, however, continued to dance a fine line between his
good pal from Arizona and Bush, who is expected to visit New York
City early next month to raise money. In recent weeks, Giuliani has
often said he believes Bush will be the Republican nominee, though
he tends to add that McCain would be a great choice, too. And last
week he continued to stress that he had not yet made an
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have said is very, very strong and supportive things
about Governor Bush and about Senator McCain,'' Giuliani said when
asked to clarify where he stood. ``And since Senator McCain is here
now, I think all that you'll find wherever he campaigns are words
of strong admiration for him. I think Senator McCain is an
exceptional senator. I think he is an exceptional American. I think
he is an exceptional man and I think he would make a very fine
president. But I haven't made an endorsement yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the mayor said they were in touch with the Bush
campaign and expressed confidence that the Texas governor was not
offended by the mayor's warm welcome of McCain, who was in New York
to promote his new book and attend the MTV Video Music Awards with
his wife and two daughters. In Austin, Texas, a spokesman for
Bush's campaign, Scott McClellan, said, ``Governor Bush thinks it's
great that Republican leaders are meeting with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Republican leaders are not likely to forget that
Giuliani in the past has proved unpredictable in his political
endorsements. Most notably, of course, he crossed party lines to
endorse Mario Cuomo, the Democratic incumbent, over George Pataki
in the 1994 gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they know Giuliani has every reason to step in
line because he will need strong support from national Republican
leaders if he runs for Senate next year against Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who is expected to seek the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But if Giuliani, who is not known for being self-conscious, felt
any pressure to be less vocal about his warm friendship with
McCain, he did not show it last week. He put the DaNico lunch date
on his public schedule, thereby inviting the New York press corps,
helped McCain promote his book, and even expressed strong support
for the senator's bill on campaign finance reform, saying he would
vote in favor of it if he were a senator.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the last two years, Giuliani and McCain have helped each
other raise money in New York, Arizona and Washington and even
attended the Fiesta Bowl college football game together this year
in Phoenix. They disagree on a number of policy points _ the mayor,
for example, supports abortion rights, while McCain does not _ but
they said their friendship transcended politics, and McCain even
tried to make light of the mayor's probable support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not asked for his endorsement,'' McCain said. ``In fact
I have specifically not asked for it, because I don't think that
friends ask friends to do things that may not be beneficial to them
politically. My first priority is to have Mayor Giuliani in the
United States Senate, and I will do everything in my power.'' He
paused. ``And if that means that he endorses Al Gore, that's OK
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to the mayor suggested that the timing of an
endorsement would depend on the wishes of Bush's campaign and would
almost certainly be orchestrated to make the best use of New York's
huge media market. Giuliani visited the Governor's Mansion in
Austin in April, and Bush has a standing invitation to come to New
York. But Giuliani himself said last week that he did not know when
he would make an endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who was a prisoner of war in Vietnam, said he was in New
York primarily to promote his new book, ``Faith of My Fathers,''
about his family's three generations of service in the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am on a book tour,'' McCain said, holding up a copy that he
had given to the mayor, even as he clearly anticipated that most of
the attention would be on politics. ``I came primarily to hype this
book rather than see my friend Rudy, who I get to see most any
time. So I hope that you understand what this is really all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
