<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-WHITMAN-FUTURE-900     09-11 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-FUTURE-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN REVELS IN REFOCUSING ON THE JOB SHE HAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ As her abridged run for the U.S. Senate fades
into memory, Gov. Christie Whitman is beginning to sound like
someone enjoying a second honeymoon with her job in the New Jersey
Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman stunned the political world on Tuesday when she withdrew
from the race to replace Sen. Frank Lautenberg, saying that the
demands of raising $100,000 a week made it impossible to focus on
the daily issues facing the state. And while the governor conceded
that she had not fully decided what agenda she would pursue during
her final 28 months in office, she warned that it was far too early
to write her political obituary.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits will force Whitman to step down on Jan. 1, 2002, and
because she is no longer constrained by the need to court potential
voters, she suggested that she might use that freedom to tackle
some unexpectedly ambitious issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge relief,'' the governor said. ``It will be fun to
think about policy issues without having to factor in the possible
political consequences. It allows you to do what you think is right
and take on some of the sacred cows.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who bristled in recent months whenever her
decisions were interpreted as a tactical maneuver for the Senate
race, seemed buoyant as she discussed plans to fine-tune policies
like her effort to preserve one million acres of open space or
improve the quality of preschool education.
</P>
<P>
   Although she might one day be interested in working for a
Republican administration in Washington, Whitman scoffed at
suggestions that she had abandoned the Senate bid because she had
been offered a Cabinet post by George W. Bush, a candidate for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The governor even joked about the New Jersey Republicans who
have publicly criticized her for throwing the state party into
disarray by backing out of the Senate race seven months after
entering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better that I did it now rather than seven months from
now,'' she said with a laugh. ``It's still a long, long way until
Election Day. And there's plenty of time to decide on a qualified
candidate, put out a message and win that seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's lightheartedness was a stark contrast with her
description of the expected drudgery of the Senate campaign. She
said she agreed to run for the Senate after scores of Republicans
convinced her that she would be the party's strongest candidate.
The seat being vacated by Lautenberg, a Democrat, simply presented
too tempting a political opportunity to pass up. But even when she
announced her candidacy, Whitman seemed more regretful about ending
her second gubernatorial term early than excited about the prospect
of becoming a senator. That ambivalence was magnified, the governor
said, by the relentless need to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Under any circumstance, New Jersey is an expensive state in
which to run a statewide race, because its candidates have to pay
for advertisements in two of the nation's most expensive markets,
New York and Philadelphia. For the Senate race next year,
Republicans also faced the daunting prospect that one of the
leading Democratic contenders, Jon Corzine, a former chairman of
Goldman, Sachs, is willing to tap into his $300 million personal
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's advisers said she expected former Gov. Jim Florio to
win the Democratic nomination. She nonetheless undertook a
withering schedule in hope of raising at least $10 million. ``It
just seemed never-ending,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the governor said, she was growing increasingly weary
of seeing her every move as governor viewed through the prism of
the race. The speculation reached comic proportions last month, she
said, when she declared a drought emergency and heard assorted
suggestions that she was trying to placate some bloc of voters or
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd forgotten how much I hated it, the second-guessing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Whitman family took a week of vacation in Nova
Scotia in late August, Whitman began discussing her plans with her
husband, John, and their two children. At first, her husband urged
her to press on with the Senate bid, but she eventually convinced
him that her heart just was not in the race.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Whitman said, the soul-searching helped her accept
that her personality and management style were far better suited to
supervising than to legislating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do enjoy the role of executive,'' she said. ``It's wonderful
to be able to see a problem, identify a solution and watch things
happen. It's hard to get that kind of direct job satisfaction
elsewhere. It would have been different in the Senate, frustrating
at times, but that doesn't mean you don't do it. You'd have to find
your satisfaction by helping to shape the debate instead of taking
direct action.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in Trenton have occasionally made that same
observation about Whitman, and said her imperial style of governing
has caused unnecessarily rocky relations. So it is questionable
whether she can push any landmark proposals through as a lame duck
_ especially because the state's two legislative leaders, Assembly
Speaker Jack Collins and Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, are
believed to be positioning themselves to try to succeed her as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Whitman, New Jersey gives more power to its governor
than almost any other state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After weathering opposition in the state Senate, Whitman and her
appointed attorney general will soon be free to press ahead with
their plans to overhaul the New Jersey State Police, a force beset
by charges of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The governor plans to push for several ``smart growth''
restrictions to control suburban sprawl. If she chooses, Whitman
can also champion any number of proposals she has advocated in the
past, perhaps expanded programs for the elderly or school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said she planned to push to hold school board
elections at the same time as existing political primaries, to
increase voter turnout and make school boards more accountable to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she would consult with Cabinet members next week.
``There are going to be new things,'' she said. ``I just don't know
what they are yet, but no, I don't have a surprise 35th tax cut to
unveil today.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Shaw, a lobbyist who was Whitman's chief of staff in 1994
and 1995, said: ``There is still time to be bold. She has talked
about privatizing the Meadowlands, she could be very aggressive in
promoting Jersey City and Bayonne as a deep-water port, and she
needs to follow through on the plan to repair the state's schools
and build new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   If Whitman completes her term, she will also be able to deepen
her effect on the state Supreme Court. She has already appointed
four of the seven justices, and since two more members of the bench
are scheduled to retire in the next two years, she can strengthen
her effort to rein in a court once known for its judicial daring.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts have criticized Whitman for diluting the
highly scholarly composition of the bench, but the governor insists
that she is merely restoring the court to its proper role as a body
that interprets law without making new law.
</P>
<P>
   Like all elected officials approaching the end of a final term,
Whitman will also have the opportunity to put the finishing touches
on her record. Perhaps she will even be able to reconcile the
paradox of her public perception.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the state, Whitman has built a distinct national
reputation as a fiscal conservative who is moderate on social
issues like abortion and gay rights. Among New Jersey residents,
however, Whitman's image is surprisingly ill-defined, even after
nearly six years in office.
</P>
<P>
   She was first elected in 1993 as a tax cutter, and even today
Whitman passes up few opportunities to mention the 34 tax cuts
enacted during her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey's property taxes are still among the highest in
the nation, so most public opinion polls show that less than a
quarter of all voters have a high opinion of her tax policies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a recent poll by the Eagleton Institute of Politics at
Rutgers University found that fewer than 30 percent of New Jersey
voters believe that her record includes any major achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's seen as sort of a George Bush Republican,'' said Cliff
Zukin, public policy professor and director of the
Star-Ledger-Eagleton poll. ``She wants to steer the ship safely and
responsibly. But she doesn't want to go any place particularly
exotic or get there very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor disputes that characterization, and contends that
she has been as effective a policy trailblazer as she is a civic
caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already made some very bold moves on taxes, auto reform,
open space preservation, school standards and other issues,'' she
said. ``And I intend to continue running an activist
administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
