<HEADER>
A8541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HEALTH-INSURANCE     09-11 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEALTH-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AMERICA'S UNMET OBLIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Sept. 12:
</P>
<P>
   Though rivals for the Democratic presidential nomination, Al
Gore and Bill Bradley are both trying to restore a shamefully
neglected issue to its rightful place at the forefront of public
debate. The issue is health insurance _ specifically, this
country's grievous failure to provide coverage for nearly one-sixth
of its population.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians have turned from this issue ever since
President Clinton's proposal for universal health coverage crashed
in 1993, a victim of political mismanagement. But the problem has
not gone away, and remains a vivid and embarrassing rebuke to
American democracy. As Bradley observed last week in announcing his
candidacy, ``While kings and dictators come to this country for the
best health care treatment in the world, you and I both know that
this care is not available to the 45 million citizens who have no
health insurance at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Congress bickers over regulating health maintenance
organizations and otherwise seeks to improve the system for people
who do have health insurance, the plight of those who do not have
insurance gets worse by the day. Despite an extraordinary economic
boom and an unemployment rate that is at the lowest level in more
than 25 years, the number of uninsured Americans has steadily risen
by about 1 million a year over the past decade. This number will
probably continue to rise as more children are born, more Americans
switch from manufacturing jobs that provide insurance to service
jobs that do not, and more people leave the welfare system, which
provides health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has yet to propose a specific program, although he is
expected to soon. Gore is further down the programmatic road,
having last week unveiled a plan to provide health insurance for 11
million to 15 million uncovered Americans, mostly children. The
proposal is modest compared with Clinton's original plan to
guarantee health insurance for everyone. Gore's rationale for not
being more ambitious is that ``we have all learned that we cannot
overhaul the system in one fell swoop.'' He also notes that his
program seeks to cover one of the most vulnerable segments of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the plan would expand the Children's Health
Insurance Program, a federally subsidized state-run program created
in 1997 that helps insure children in families earning up to about
$33,000 a year for four people. Gore would raise that income
ceiling so that families earning 2.5 times the official poverty
level, or about $41,000, could qualify. The program would also
allow uninsured parents of children who are eligible for Medicaid
or CHIP to buy subsidized insurance for themselves, and in various
ways would encourage states to seek out and enroll every child who
may be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Constructive as they are, Gore's ideas will still leave some 30
million Americans without any real help. Most of these are working
poor adults, including a disproportionate number of minorities.
Gore may be right when he suggests that after the Clinton debacle
in 1993, only an incremental approach will pass muster with
Congress and the country. It may also be true that if he and
Bradley continue to push health care to the front of their
campaigns, the opportunity may come around again to force Congress
to take a more sweeping approach. But for now, these Democratic
rivals have helped put the question of universal health care back
on the national agenda and, in so doing, have reminded everyone of
America's unmet obligation to 45 million people for whom a medical
setback could mean financial ruin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
