<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-FORD-POLLUTION-FIGH     09-11 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FORD-POLLUTION-FIGHT-ART-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TOBACCO DEFENSE LAWYER TAKES ON FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note.)  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ill., Mich., Ohio, Ky.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ When C. Mark Pickrell was an associate at a big New
York law firm three years ago, helping to defend a large cigarette
company against anti-smoking lawsuits filed by Mississippi and New
Jersey, a colleague nicknamed him Brimstone, joking that he would
surely go to hell for having represented Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pickrell is in another courtroom struggle. But this time he
is fighting a big corporation, not defending one.
</P>
<P>
   He is representing a one-man Internet newsletter against a
lawsuit filed by Ford Motor Co., the world's second-largest
corporation. And using skills developed in legal battles over
smoking, he is trying to start a legal war over whether Detroit
automakers colluded to avoid the expense of manufacturing sport
utility vehicles that might produce less air pollution while
getting better fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   Pickrell insists that he sees many parallels between his former
legal work and the current lawsuit. ``As I look at it, I keep
saying, `It's like tobacco.''' Pickrell said. ``The similarities
that I've seen are unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials declined to comment on any issue regarding the
litigation with Lane, any antitrust issues or any comparisons
between smoking and sport utility vehicle issues. Auto industry
officials have dismissed suggestions of collusion in the past,
saying that the auto market is too competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Pickrell has already won the first round in his fight. Ford had
sought a preliminary injunction against Pickrell's client, Robert
Lane, who operates the Internet site, www.blueovalnews.com, which
provides news on Ford vehicles for auto enthusiasts. The injunction
would have prevented Lane from using, copying or discussing boxes
full of internal Ford documents that someone had mailed him
anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal judge turned down most of Ford's request last
Tuesday, saying that the free-speech provision of the First
Amendment protected Lane even though the documents might be trade
secrets and might be copyrighted.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ruling, Pickrell had engaged in a helter-skelter
legal dash worthy of the recent genre of lawyer novels. Pickrell,
who is the sole lawyer in his law office in Nashville, Tenn., heard
about the lawsuit from a friend on Aug. 27, a Friday. He sent Lane
a fax that afternoon, offering his legal services for a nominal
fee. Lane called back that evening to say that he was due in
federal court in Detroit for a hearing the following Monday morning
and did not have a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, a 33-year-old nursing student who lives several blocks
from Ford's headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., could not afford to
pay for a last-minute, full-fare airline ticket to Detroit for
Pickrell. But Lane is married to a flight attendant for Northwest
Airlines, who sent Pickrell a so-called ``buddy pass'' to allow him
to buy a very cheap ticket at a rate available only to friends of
airline personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Detroit on Sunday morning, Pickrell, who is also 33,
spent all day and night looking up legal precedents on CD-ROMs and
electronic databases on his laptop computer, drafting a legal brief
and making photocopies at a Kinko's store. Lane said that the two
men were able to talk for only 15 minutes about what he would say
on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Whatever you do, don't lie,''' Lane recalled.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Ford lawyers mentioned in the hearing that what had
really upset Ford was Lane's posting on his Internet site of
internal Ford documents relating to the Environmental Protection
Agency. One of these documents, for example, discussed problems
that Ford will face in meeting air pollution standards as it moves
to install diesel engines in more of its full-sized sport utility
vehicles and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Pickrell contended that the lawyer's comment showed that Lane
should be treated legally not as someone who recklessly disregarded
trade secrets and copyrights, as Ford alleged, but rather as a
journalist who had been gathering news about a public policy issue
involving the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the judge ruled in Lane's favor, Ford's lawyers had
demanded from Pickrell extensive information about the content and
source of the documents in Lane's possession. Pickrell has
responded by asking Ford for extensive documents regarding its
discussions with competitors and the Environmental Protection
Agency regarding air-pollution technologies and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   While representing Brown &AMP; Williamson, a large cigarette
company, Pickrell had learned a lot about the issue of whether
tobacco companies deliberately avoided selling cigarettes that
would emit fewer carcinogens.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds broke ranks with other tobacco companies in 1988
when it began marketing the Premier as a ``safer'' cigarette. While
the Premier was a failure in the marketplace, plaintiff lawyers
responded to it by saying the product showed that less dangerous
cigarettes had long been possible.
</P>
<P>
   With this legal background, Pickrell said that during the
current lawsuit he immediately became interested in Ford's decision
21 months ago to break ranks with other automakers and redesign all
of its sport utility vehicles to emit as little air pollution as
cars. Federal regulations allow sport utility vehicles to emit two
to three times as much pollution per mile as cars.
</P>
<P>
   Some top auto executives have suggested that Ford broke a
``gentleman's agreement'' among Detroit automakers not to compete
on who could build the least polluting vehicles. While Japanese
automakers have done well in the U.S. car market, Detroit
completely dominated the sport utility vehicle market until the
last couple of years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate, read a news
report in May mentioning auto industry cooperation and wrote a
letter to the Justice Department urging an antitrust investigation
into whether automakers had conspired to not install
pollution-control equipment, particularly on sport utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Nader became famous in the 1960s partly for persuading the
Johnson administration to file an identical antitrust lawsuit and
then accusing Detroit automakers of conspiring to not develop or
install pollution-control gear; the consent decree from that case
expired during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Rose, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said that the
agency was preparing a response to Nader's letter, but she declined
to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Ford documents briefly posted this summer on Lane's Internet
site show that the automaker is working on improvements in
pollution and fuel economy. One document, for example, projected
that the fuel economy of Ford Explorer and Mercury Mountaineer
sport utility vehicles could be improved by 26 percent over the
next decade. But the documents gave no indication of the cost or
feasibility of such a change.
</P>
<P>
   Pickrell's tobacco experience may not be his only special
expertise for the case. He left New York and returned to his home
state of Tennessee two years ago because of temporary health
problems and a desire to be his own boss. His law practice in
Nashville now specializes in appeals to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Cincinnati; he is a former clerk of the court's chief
judge, Boyce Martin Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The court handles federal appeals from Michigan, Ohio, Kentucky
and Tennessee, and will receive any appeals from Ford's lawsuit in
Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
