<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS _ ATLANTA _ When they returned from the Super Bowl
in January, the Falcons were greeted by thousands of fans who
jammed Centennial Park for the lovely celebration. They celebrated
the team of destiny; a franchise oft labeled as the worst in sports
had made it to the big game on the crest of a team chemistry that
was unsual in pro sports. Then there were changes. Cornelius
Bennett was cut. Tony Martin was cut. And Jamal Anderson, trying
hard to be a national celebrity before his time, went through an
extended holdout that distracted the team during training camp.
Team chemistry took a big hit, and that might not bode well for a
team that begins the season against Minnesota, then Dallas.
(Winkeljohn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/FBN-TECH _ ATLANTA _ Talking Xs and Os: Falcons defensive back
Eugene Robinson describes what happens in the secondary when the
ball is snapped and receivers like Randy Moss and Cris Carter head
into their pass patterns. (Winklejohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
