<HEADLINE>
NYC GIRDS FOR WEEKEND OF SPRAYING TO COMBAT ENCEPHALITIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As residents of the five boroughs geared up for a
weekend of pesticide spraying, the number of possible cases of St.
Louis encephalitis, the mosquito-borne viral disease, rose to 89 in
the city Saturday, with 31 added since Friday, city officials said.
The number of confirmed cases remained at nine.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the 31 cases is considered ``probable,'' in which
the likelihood of infection is greater than 50 percent, said Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani in a news conference at City Hall on Saturday. All
the other new cases fall under either the city's ``suspected''
category, in which the chances of infection are about 1 in 10, or
``low probability'' category, in which there is almost no chance of
finding encephalitis, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the situation as it existed yesterday is pretty
much the same,'' Giuliani said. ``We don't have any more definite
cases. We do have one more probable case.''
</P>
<P>
   Three people have died of the disease since last week, when city
officials first became aware of the outbreak. Eight of the nine
confirmed cases of encephalitis, a swelling of the brain that can
be fatal, especially in babies and the elderly, were in Queens. One
case was found in the Borough Park section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   To fight the spread of the disease, the city began a
weekend-long land and air insecticide bombardment of mosquitoes
Saturday evening in sections of all five boroughs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Airplanes and helicopters sprayed the insecticide malathion over
the eastern half of the Bronx, southwestern Queens and a section of
Staten Island between 5 and 9:30 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks roaming through sections of Brooklyn, including the
downtown area and Brooklyn Heights, were scheduled to spray a
different insecticide, resmethrine, between 11 p.m. Saturday and 6
a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 5 p.m. Sunday, aircraft will spray over northern and
eastern Queens, Roosevelt Island, Wards Island and Randalls Island,
and northern Staten Island. Trucks will spray throughout Central
Park between 11 p.m. Sunday night and 6 a.m. Monday, according to
the city's schedule. Midtown and lower Manhattan will be sprayed by
trucks starting at 11 p.m. Monday, although Times Square may be
spared until Tuesday, officials said. In all, the city's Office of
Emergency Management is using 11 trucks, 5 helicopters and one
airplane, which will be used solely over Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, according to maps distributed to reporters Saturday,
every inch of New York City will have been treated. But the mayor
and city health officials stressed that neither spray is dangerous
to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very unlikely that anyone would have any health
effects of any concern, even if they were directly under the
spray,'' said Dr. Bob Hoffman, the director of the New York City
Poison Center, speaking at the news conference. ``People should
really feel comfortable with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani hammered home his own reassurances, pointing out that
very few mosquitoes actually are thought to carry the encephalitis
disease, and reassuring the public about the sprays, which he noted
were being used in small concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was reassured. Manhattan Borough President
Virginia Fields went to 125th Street and Lexington Avenue on
Saturday afternoon to respond to what she said was a flood of calls
to her office from residents worried about plans for the nighttime
spraying of all of Manhattan north of 110th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of shoppers at the Pathmark store on that corner came by
to pick up fliers detailing precautions to take during the spraying
and how to avoid being bitten by mosquitoes. Most said they were
more concerned about the pesticides than about the mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fields said that she had been assured by city officials and
toxicology experts that the pesticide would not hurt anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course this is an issue in question that has been
raised and continues to be raised by people in the community,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
