u s BC-BBO-GILES-680&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-11 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GILES-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVEN A CHANCE, SOME PLAYERS HAVING BREAKTHROUGH SEASONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early last season, Brian Giles became part of the plan that has
helped make the Cleveland Indians the perennial division champions
they are. With less than two years of major-league service, he
enrolled in the club's long-term signing strategy, agreeing to a
three-year contract worth a minimum of $5.45 million. Seven months
later, however, the Indians traded Giles to the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to trade in winning,'' he said. ``Everybody wants
to do that in their career. Over there I had that opportunity for
three years. But it was getting to the point in my career where if
I didn't get out of there and get a chance to play every day and
show what I can do, I'd be a role player the rest of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing center field on a regular basis, Giles has had a
breakthrough season. He entered the weekend with a .315 batting
average, 36 home runs and 108 runs batted in. Not since Dave Parker
in 1978 have the Pirates had a player lead them in those Triple
Crown categories with a .300 average, 30 home runs and 100 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   But Giles is only one of a group of players who are having
breakthrough seasons, seasons in which they either get the chance
to be regulars or play themselves into the everyday lineup and
respond with productive performances.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno, for example, never played more than 105 games in a
season, never hit .300 and had a total of 23 stolen bases in 311
games over four seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers. With the Mets
this season, he has been a regular outfielder, a .300 hitter and a
base-stealing threat with, at last count, 61 steals.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Mike Sweeney is having a similar experience,
though minus the stolen bases. In four seasons, he had not played
more than 92 games and had career highs of .279, eight homers and
35 RBI. In 128 games before the weekend, the first
baseman/designated hitter was hitting .313 with 20 home runs and 94
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett has received the playing time the past two seasons,
but this season with Houston he has taken greater advantage of it.
He is reaching career highs with 21 home runs and 93 RBI and, with
a .331 batting average, positioning himself to hit .300 for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vidro has emerged so dramatically in Montreal that he has
knocked Wilton Guerrero from second base to left field. After
splitting the previous two seasons between the Expos and the minor
leagues, Vidro has blossomed with an average hovering around .320.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Owens has not produced flashy numbers for San Diego, but
after failing the past three seasons to establish major league
credentials with Cincinnati and Milwaukee, he has become a
versatile starter with the Padres. Playing five different
positions, three outfield, two infield, Owens has hit in the .270s.
</P>
<P>
   Among these and other players who are having breakthrough years,
Giles has broken through most substantially. The Indians would miss
him if they did not already have the best hitting team in the
American League, although they would like to have received more
effective relief pitching from Ricardo Rincon, whom they acquired
for Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really know what to expect,'' the 28-year-old Giles
said. ``Obviously, playing part-time in Cleveland and putting up
the numbers I did, people project what you can do over 500 at-bats,
but I didn't know what to expect and I didn't have any
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two seasons, Giles averaged one home run every 22
at-bats. This season Giles has averaged one homer every 13.4
at-bats. He attributed his improvement to playing every day.
``That's the biggest difference, knowing you're in the lineup every
day,'' he said. ``It takes the pressure off you. After an 0-for-4
game you know you're going to be out there the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   When he missed games, it was by design. ``Geno's been pretty
good with me,'' Giles said, referring to manager Gene Lamont. ``We
kind of have an understanding. If he thinks I need a day, he'll
tell me the day before. Or if I feel I need a day, if I feel tired,
I'll tell him. That approach has taken a lot of pressure off me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Giles signed his contract, for three years plus an option
year, he was a part-time player. Does he regret having done that
considering that now he is a starter?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Giles said. ``I signed the contract for my own
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Security perhaps? ``That's the first thing you look at,'' he
said. ``When my wife and I sat down and talked about it and made
the decision, I knew what I was getting into. When I signed the
deal, I was happy with it. I'm still happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the possibility of more playing time, the contract
has bonuses for number of plate appearances and a clause that will
raise Giles' salary by $200,000 for any season after he has 600
plate appearances, which he is nearing now.
</P>
<P>
   Giles' departure from Cleveland created additional playing time
for Richie Sexson, who despite his production is not an everyday
starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here in Pittsburgh we'd love to throw him out for 550
at-bats and see what kind of numbers he can put up,'' Giles said.
``I hope Richie gets that opportunity; he deserves it. But I looked
at a box score the other day, and he wasn't in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Already at the 100-RBI plateau, Sexson doesn't need a
breakthrough offensively, but a full-time job could take him to
another level.
</P>
</TEXT>
