<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 ROGERS' REALITY  
 BELLE VS. BELL  
 BRAINLOCK ON 3 OUTS  
 SCHISM AFFECTS GRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isn't it time to bury the fairy tale about how Kenny Rogers came
to New York in 1996 and became Ed Whitson, unable to pitch under
the pressure of the city where fans eat losers for lunch?
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who struggled for two seasons with the Yankees, has
started eight games for the Mets and won four, and the Mets have
won seven of the games Rogers has started. The team has won all
five of his starts at Shea Stadium, where he has compiled a 1.95
earned run average. Yet stories about his days with the Yankees
continue to be dredged up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a good story at the time,'' Rogers said in his
soft-spoken way that his critics construe as indifference. ``I
never thought it was a problem where I was pitching. I always knew
exactly what it was. I knew it was how I was pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers acknowledged distractions exist in New York that do not
exist elsewhere. But he said: ``I wasn't able to compete well by
then. Nobody knew about it or really cared about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, whom the Yankees had signed as an expensive free agent,
created his own problems by not disclosing that he had been injured
late in spring training. The bruised left shoulder affected the
team's pitching plans, and Rogers' secrecy soured Manager Joe Torre
on his new left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Rogers said: ``I was so happy my first year in New
York it was unbelievable. That's the best year I've ever had
because of everything I went through. Nobody wants to know that,
and nobody knew it at the time. I was so proud of that year.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for his abbreviated start in the playoffs. ``The
playoffs, yeah, I didn't do very well,'' he said, ``but I got 12
wins when everything was terrible. At the time, it wasn't good
enough for everybody else. I never really cared what everybody
said. If they wanted to blame me, that's fine. I could take it,
whether it was true or not. But I know I can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has proved that in Texas, he has proved it in Oakland and
now he is proving it in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Belle vs. Bell
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since opening day, Albert Belle passed Jay
Bell in a ding-dong of a home run race that has not caught the
fans' fancy as much as the one between guys named Sosa and McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last Tuesday when Belle struck his 33rd home run in
Baltimore's fourth inning. But just as happened on opening day,
Bell did not let the Belle lead stand. The Arizona second baseman,
who in the previous four seasons hit 67 home runs to Belle's 177,
connected for his 33rd in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   In another, even more intriguing race, Sammy Sosa took a 59-56
lead into the Cubs' weekend series in Houston. That was 59 home
runs for Sosa, 56 victories for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Brainlock on 3 Outs
</P>
<P>
   Phil Nevin suggested that because the Montreal Expos were in
town, ``it might have been the Canadian exchange rate, four outs
for three.'' The San Diego third baseman was talking about the
collective brainlock that occurred in the seventh inning of the
game Thursday. Reggie Sanders struck out for the Padres' third out,
but the umpires didn't realize there were three outs and neither
did the Expos. So Nevin went to the plate and Ted Lilly threw him
three pitches before the Expos alerted Jerry Layne, the plate
umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Layne's out counter said three, but when no one started in from
or out to the field, he figured his indicator must be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The National League office did not take a stern view of the
incident. ``It wasn't that only one person wasn't paying
attention,'' Katy Feeney, the league's senior vice president, said.
``No one ran off the field. From what I understand it was an honest
mistake and fortunately it was caught before anything happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Schism Affects Grief
</P>
<P>
   That the schism between two groups of umpires will not ease soon
was evident last week at the funeral for Kim Coble, wife of Drew
Coble, one of the 22 umpires who lost their jobs in a backfired
labor strategy. The funeral in Graham, N.C., was attended by 10
umpires from the pro-Richie Phillips faction and four from the
insurgent group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very awkward; there's no other way to describe it,''
Steve Rippley, a National League umpire, said. ``You're there
grieving for Kim's sake and you have other issues that are still
active.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
