u a BC-N.Y.-PUMPKIN-CROP-NYT     09-11 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-PUMPKIN-CROP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLIGHT PAUCITY OF PUMPKINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, N.Y. _ The news from the pumpkin fields of Orange
County is a bit unsettling. Thanks to the hot, dry days of July,
this fall's pumpkin crop will come in shy of bumper. Farmers say
the outlook is not all that bleak. But it is not bountiful, either.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, farmers say, a summer of scant rainfall, below
normal pollination (blame balky bees) and the growing popularity of
the pumpkin will lead to a mild shortage. When the farmers say
``mild,'' they mean that farms and wholesalers will get enough
locally grown and imported pumpkins to roadside stands,
pick-your-own fields and green markets to satisfy everybody. But in
a classic case of demand exceeding supply, pumpkins will cost a few
cents more a pound this Halloween season, they say, than last.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hoeffner, 61 and a fifth-generation farmer, grows 40 acres
of pumpkins on his 400-acre produce farm here. ``At best, we have
half a crop of pumpkins, and that's stretching it,'' he said. Some
of Hoeffner's pumpkin acreage had no irrigation pipes. Irrigated
acres suffered from poor pollination, either because pumpkin
blossoms closed prematurely or bees performed poorly in July's
heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like it too cold or too hot,'' Maire Ullrich, an
agent with the Cornell Cooperative Extension Association in Orange
County, said of bees. ``They work best between 70 and 85 degrees
and they get cranky on either end of that spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Shuback also had some pollination problems on the 90
acres of pumpkins he had squeezed onto his 700-acre sod farm in the
fabled black dirt of Florida, down the road from Montgomery. But
his biggest woe was the 10 acres of pumpkins he had planted in
sandy soil next to the black dirt, which sits a few inches above
the water table and is very fertile. Those 10 acres foundered in
the drought, he said. ``It looks like I'll have a decent crop; not
big, but decent,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Shuback's customers are garden centers within a 100-mile
radius of his farm. Last year, he said, he sold his pumpkins to the
centers for 12 to 14 cents a pound, and they in turn sold them for
29 to 35 cents a pound. This fall, Shuback's wholesale price will
be 15 to 20 cents a pound. He expects the centers to raise their
prices by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffner is playing it cagey for now. He said he was not quoting
his wholesale price yet and would wait until he saw what the market
would bear. Traditionally, he has sold most of his pumpkins to
suburban garden centers on Long Island and in Connecticut and
northern New Jersey. Some then sell the pumpkins at their roadside
stands. At others, Hoeffner or his helpers leave the pumpkins in
small fields that cater to schoolchildren on pumpkin-buying outings
and families on weekend pumpkin-picking excursions. ``We call them
instant pumpkins,'' Hoeffner said. ``At night, the fields are
empty. In the morning they're full of pumpkins.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he said, his customers farthest from Manhattan sold
pumpkins for 29 to 30 cents a pound. Those closer charged 45 to 55
cents a pound, and in some cases 60 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I figure those near New York will be looking for 75
cents a pound,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That means that a nice 10-pound Howden, the broad-faced,
thick-skinned pumpkin ideal for carving jack-o'-lanterns, will
command $7.50 in the more expensive centers.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Hoeffner and Shuback said, they did not bother
with pumpkins because demand was skimpy. But the '90s has brought a
steady increase in the popularity of Halloween and the willingness
of people to spend for pumpkins and Halloween's other trappings,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to entertainment and it comes to fun _ and
that's what pumpkins are _ people seem to have enough money,''
Hoeffner said. ``They squawk about food every time they walk out of
our stand. They'll buy three ears of corn for $1 and ask, `When is
the price coming down?' But they'll pay 60 cents a pound for
pumpkins and laugh when they take them out. Price is no problem.
People do it for their children. If the cash market is worth the
while this year, pumpkins will find their way to New York City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
