<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-SOHO-COMMERCE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ART-DRIVEN SOHO, DISPUTE BETWEEN RESIDENTS AND TRUCKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's 7 in the morning and the heavens are cerulean. A
gentle breeze whispers through SoHo's southeastern end. But this
artsy precinct of prosperity is not meekly yawning awake. Commerce
is already zipping ahead full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   A forklift on Broome Street ferries stacked crates of garlic and
watermelons from a truck to a warehouse several feet away. A few
doors down, another forklift carts a truckload of broccoli and bok
choy to a warehouse around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   With little notice beyond its borders, SoHo, a community best
known for chichi galleries, restaurants, boutiques, boites and
bars, has also become home to fruit and vegetable wholesalers and
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   It is an uneasy mix. In one corner are the wholesalers and
distributors, whose defenders describe them as honest businessmen
who have toiled in the district for years _ longer than many of the
residents now complaining. In the other are the loft-dwelling
artists, restaurateurs and gallery owners who complain that the
four companies are a bullying presence that are heedless of their
neighbors in ways that range from the annoying to the outright
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   A civic group called the SoHo Alliance has sued Harry Tran, the
owner of a produce company, World Farm, accusing his employees of
operating forklifts dangerously on the sidewalks, blocking
crosswalks and fire hydrants with their trucks, leaving trucks
idling ``loudly and obnoxiously'' before dawn and using the streets
and sidewalks to store and unload produce.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Rosenstein, a community advocate who is a co-owner of a
loft building down the street from World Farm, is the most vocal
opponent of the wholesalers and distributors. ``This is an assault
on our community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the alliance have encouraged city officials to move
the businesses elsewhere. And they routinely call on the police and
fire departments to issue summonses to law-breaking truckers and
warehouse owners.
</P>
<P>
   Most owners of wholesale and distribution companies either
refused to be interviewed or directed questions to their spokesman,
Abraham Tan, the president of the Chinese Wholesalers and Retailers
Association of Greater New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tan, who is also the owner of Valley View Farms, a produce
wholesale and distribution company in Chinatown, suggested that the
produce proprietors had as much right to be in the area as the
artists. He pointed out that Ban Produce, a wholesale operation,
had been in business for 15 years on Broome Street, longer than
some loft residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was SoHo?'' he asked. ``Nobody wanted it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Community advocates in Little Italy have joined in the SoHo
Alliance lawsuit. John Fratta, a Democratic district leader who was
born and raised in Little Italy, said the wholesalers were clearly
violating the rules of a special zoning district known as the
Mulberry Street Spine, which forbids warehousing. Little Italy,
which is a mere skeleton of its former size because of Chinatown's
expansion, has seen eight wholesalers and distributors move into
the neighborhood, Fratta said.
</P>
<P>
   Some produce wholesalers and distributors _ all of them Chinese
_ have suggested that bigotry is at the core of the objections to
their operations. At a community meeting, one Chinese man rose and
said: ``They're not only ignoring the ideas or opinions of the
Chinese people, they practice racial discrimination against them.
They dislike them because of racial prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the people thought it was racism,'' said a reporter
for a Chinese-language newspaper. ``I don't think it's racism. What
it is, is the SoHo people don't like the produce. They don't like
the traffic and the noise. They don't like businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for SoHo residents said charges of racism were
unfounded. ``It's not their ethnicity we're complaining about; it's
their conduct,'' said Jack Lester, the lawyer for the wholesalers'
adversaries. ``Their conduct would be odious whatever their
ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner of World Farm has girded himself for a fight. ``I'm
sure things will go well for my client and he will be fully
vindicated,'' said Stephen Goldman, the company's lawyer. ``There's
a witch hunt going on down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
