<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ECOLI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND DEATH FROM E. COLI IS CONFIRMED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York state and local health officials confirmed Saturday
that a 79-year-old Gansevoort man was the second person to die in
an outbreak of E. coli bacteria infections in the Albany area.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities also raised the number of people hospitalized
with the illness Saturday to 60, two more than on Friday, according
to the state Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although almost all of the cases have been linked to the
contamination of a well at the Washington County Fair in Greenwich.
The authorities said that four people had become ill since Friday
after attending the Schaghticoke Fair in Rensselaer County, and E.
coli infections were suspected.
</P>
<P>
   John Signor, a spokesman for the State Health Department, said
investigators had determined that two food vendors had moved their
booths from the fair in Washington County to the one in Rensselaer
County, and may have carried contaminated well water with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have not had symptoms of the infection yet, you
probably are not going to get them,'' Signor said. ``The peak has
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the main threat of infection had been from well water
drawn at the Washington County Fair on Sept. 1, and since the
strain of E. coli involved, O157:H7, has an incubation period of
nine days, few more infections were expected.
</P>
<P>
   With health officials on high alert in much of upstate New York,
residents of Phoenix, an Oswego County village 135 miles east of
Albany, were advised Saturday to boil drinking water after
inspectors found E. coli in a test of school water fountains. No
illness was reported.
</P>
<P>
   Signor said state officials believed that the contamination in
Phoenix was unrelated to the outbreak around Albany because the two
were separated by great distances, and because isolated cases of E.
coli contamination are common across the nation, with about 20,000
reported annually.
</P>
<P>
   Still, state health officials, assisted by several local
agencies, continued to monitor the outbreak near Albany Saturday
and to warn people of the symptoms of E. coli infection, which
include diarrhea and abdominal pains.
</P>
<P>
   Signor said the initial cause had been identified as a
combination of heavy rain on Aug. 26 and the proximity of the
Washington County well to a farmyard containing cows, manure and an
area being excavated.
</P>
<P>
   He said the well, which had been tested by health inspectors as
recently as June, had been contaminated by runoff from the rain,
which carried bacteria from the manure into the well water.
</P>
<P>
   He said the two vendors who may have transported some of the
contaminated water to the Schaghticoke Fair ``would not have done
so intentionally.'' Nonetheless, he said people who suffer symptoms
of E. coli after having attended the fair in Rensselaer County
should consult their doctors, particularly if they consumed food or
drinks from either of the two vendors _ O'Sullivan Crows Enterprise
Taco Stand or S&AMP;W Caterers, which sells lemonade, coffee and ice
cream.
</P>
<P>
   But Signor said the four people in Rensselaer County might not
have contacted E. coli infections at all, but ``just happened to
get diarrhea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MORTGAGE-RATE-REAL-96     09-11 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE-RATE-REAL-960(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF THE ADJUSTABLE-RATE MORTGAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Hocheiser, a loan officer at Bank of America Mortgage in
Fairfield, N.J., is struck by how much the mortgage market has
changed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 27 loans in my pipeline right now, but only two of them
are 30-year fixed-rate loans, while the rest are adjustables,''
Hocheiser said. ``We're coming into a whole different kind of
mortgage market.''
</P>
<P>
   By many accounts, that is not an understatement. While rates for
conventional 30-year fixed-rate mortgages had sunk to less than 7
percent as recently as April, they have been mounting rapidly and
hit 8.31 percent in mid-August, according to HSH Associates, a
financial publisher in Butler, N.J., that tracks the market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the difference in cost between fixed-rate loans and
adjustables has widened enough since the beginning of the year to
make fixed-rate mortgages no longer look like ``virtual
no-brainers,'' said Keith Gumbinger, an HSH vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The result?
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the pattern of the last two years, in which
historically low rates have made fixed-rate mortgages _ which carry
the same annual rate over the term of the loan _ the
all-but-automatic choice of most consumers, ``we're seeing a
shift,'' said Neil Bader, chief executive of Skyscraper Mortgage, a
mortgage broker based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing people lock in at shorter-term adjustables,
usually where the rates are adjusted every three or five years,''
Bader said. Rates on such mortgages are recalculated after an
initial period, and often yearly thereafter, to reflect changes in
such interest indexes as the one-year Treasury bill rate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in a real estate market where houses often seem to be
mercilessly scarce and home prices are still skipping upward,
mortgage rates are not necessarily a top concern for all consumers.
</P>
<P>
   At White Horse Financial Services in Bronxville, N.Y., Edna
Haber, a mortgage broker, reports that most of her customers _ in a
market where ``20 people seem to be chasing every house'' _ are
more concerned with simply getting the property they want.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates have softened a bit since mid-August, averaging
7.88 percent as of midday last Thursday. And by historic standards
_ as well as the standards of the 1990s _ such rates are still low,
Gumbinger said. Still, the recent rate increase seems to have
already spurred many consumers to look hard at adjustable-rate
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing a huge change in thinking,'' Hocheiser said. ``Even
when the rate for a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was 8 percent some
two years ago, we were still putting people into 30-year fixed-rate
loans. But now people are asking more for adjustables.''
</P>
<P>
   One consumer who recently decided to opt for an adjustable-rate
mortgage over a fixed-rate product is Robert Maina, who works for
an investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Maina and his wife, Claire, who now live in Bayside, N.Y, are
buying a three-bedroom colonial-style home in Rockville Centre,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   When Maina began looking into mortgages in early July, he
discovered that the rate for a 30-year fixed-rate loan would have
been roughly 8.25 percent. He subsequently decided to go with a
30-year adjustable-rate mortgage on which the rate will be fixed at
7.75 percent for the first seven years, and adjusted annually after
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``As first-time home owners we wanted to be as conservative as
possible,'' said Maina. ``Besides, we view this home as a starter
home and I don't plan on being in the house more than seven years.
After that, if we're still there, we can always adjust our payment
after we refinance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rate changes and a renewal in the popularity of adjustable-rate
mortgages are not the only recent developments in the mortgage
market. There has been a dramatic increase in the amount of
mortgage-related information available on the Internet and the
number of lenders participating. New mortgage products include
loans whose rates can only go down, as well as those that can be
used to pay off other debts, like credit-card loans.
</P>
<P>
   A new federal law has been enacted that gives homeowners the
right to cancel private mortgage insurance once their equity
reaches 20 percent. Borrowers who have less than terrific credit
are finding it easier to obtain mortgages than they once might
have. And finally, there has been a dramatic shift by consumers
away from refinancings, which accounted for a whopping 70 percent
of all mortgage volume a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Bank now offers its customers a home equity line
of credit that carries none of the expenses usually associated with
mortgages _ like closing costs or appraisal fees _ yet still lets
them take a tax deduction on their interest payments, as well as
consolidate outstanding bills, like credit card payments, often at
lower total monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   And some companies, including City Line Mortgage, a small
mortgage banker in San Diego, now offer mortgages whose rates
automatically go down when prevailing rates decrease, as a way of
hanging onto customers who might otherwise go elsewhere to
refinance. City Line is licensed to do business in 26 states.
</P>
<P>
   On the mortgage insurance front, the Homeowners Protection Act,
which took effect on July 29, gives consumers who are getting
mortgages the right to cancel their private mortgage insurance once
their equity reaches 20 percent. Such private mortgage insurance _
known as PMI _ is usually required when down payments are less than
20 percent; its costs are added to the monthly payments on the
mortgage itself. Under the new federal law, cancellation is
supposed to become automatic at 22 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who have less than exemplary credit have benefited
lately from lenders who are willing to overlook bad credit
histories. In August, these mortgage shoppers found that they were
in a better position when using the Internet as well. That is when
Mortgage.com, an online lending site, announced a partnership with
Intuit Inc. to provide ``subprime'' mortgages at Intuit's
QuickenMortgage.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recent changes in the mortgage market have had
widespread effects. The rise in interest rates, for example, has
reduced the number of homeowners who are refinancing their
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Refinancings have just about completely dried up,'' said
Sterling Edmunds, president of Crestar Mortgage. ``Consumers feel
that because rates have gone up, they've probably missed the boat,
and they're probably right.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Lange, president of the Mortgage Bankers Association of
America, agreed. ``Refinancings are the first casualty when rates
rise,'' Lange said, ``and we've seen our refinancings drop from
about 50 percent to about 20 percent'' since the beginning of the
year for the industry as a whole. Lange is also president and chief
executive of Pacific Financial Services in Torrance, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the Internet by mortgage shoppers, either to look up
mortgage-related information or to get actual loans, has been
rising, and is expected to increase even more.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research, a market research firm in Cambridge, Mass.,
projects that online mortgage lending will grow from $18 billion in
1999 to over $91 billion in 2003, a figure representing 10 percent
of the value of all mortgages. James Punishill, an analyst at
Forrester, points out that compared with a year ago, consumers now
have a veritable bonanza of choices on line.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates are not necessarily lower online, he cautioned.
But instead of automatically going to a mortgage broker, consumers
can save money by quickly comparing rates from dozens, if not
hundreds, of lenders at sites like QuickenMortgage.com,
LendingTree.com and RealEstate.com, which provides rates from more
than 220 lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago the choices were still pretty limited; we had a
handful of lenders, and none had their own products,'' Punishill
said. ``But now consumers have the pricing transparency that can
help them save.''
</P>
<P>
   Punishill has noticed another significant change online: Instead
of encouraging consumers to bypass mortgage brokers, a growing
number of Internet firms, like LoanCity.com, are offering consumers
access to brokers as part of their services.
</P>
<P>
   LoanCity.com offers a ``personalized service'' feature that the
company claims lets consumers work with brokers to complete all the
paperwork and still saves them about a third of the fees involved
in a traditional loan. ``A lot of consumers don't want to eliminate
brokers entirely,'' Punishill said. ``As a result, these firms are
now offering what might be described as `lite' advisory services.''
</P>
<P>
   While most mortgages being issued in recent weeks continue to be
the traditional fixed-rate types, the increase in interest rates in
recent months has changed the focus of many consumers.
Adjustable-rate mortgages are ``the hottest product right now,''
said Lange of the Mortgage Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The borrower has become much more sophisticated than even two
or three years ago,'' he said. ``They're looking at mortgages and
are asking themselves how long they really intend to live in their
new home.''
</P>
<P>
   The result?
</P>
<P>
   ``Borrowers now may decide to go for a mortgage where the first
five years are fixed, and the next 25 years are adjusted,'' Lange
said. ``They've decided that such a product works just fine for
them, and also that they can save between three-quarters and one
percentage point in interest to go from a fixed product to an
adjustable.
</P>
<P>
   Also, by moving from a fixed rate to an adjustable, they can
effectively negate the fact that rates have gone up between one and
one-and-a-quarter percentage points lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Lange added that relatively attractive terms are helping ease
the risks of adjustable-rate mortgages. For example, he pointed out
that the interest rates on most adjustable mortgages can increase
by only one to two percentage points per year, as well as a
lifetime cap of about six percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cap may seem high,'' Lange said, ``but the perception now
among consumers is that the Federal Reserve has a good handle on
inflation, so there is now a higher comfort level switching over to
an adjustable than there was in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The switch to adjustable-rate mortgages has not been a
landslide. Margaret Scott, a senior mortgage consultant at New York
Mortgage Corp., a mortgage broker, said most of her customers
choose 30-year fixed-rate mortgages, like the couple who came to
her in late August. They were thinking of either buying a $1.2
million home or having one built for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started talking to them about other mortgage products, but
they quickly rejected them,'' Ms. Scott said. ``From their
perspective there were so many other things to think about other
than rates, like whether they should put a lot of money down to
reduce the overall cost. Like many people today, they were looking
at their home as a long-term investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, real estate experts say adjustable-rate mortgages
are more popular than they have been in years. Last fall, for
example, adjustable-rate mortgages accounted for just 2 percent to
3 percent of the mortgage business at Crestar, but that number has
now swollen to 25 percent to 30 percent, with most customers
interested in one-, three- and five-year adjustable-rate products,
said Edmunds, the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   Like many mortgage lenders, many of whom have seen their
business volume shrink as interest rates have climbed, drying up
their refinancing business, Crestar has been busy rolling out more
options for adjustable-rate customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come up with numerous mortgages that have all sorts of
features,'' said Susan Huber, a senior vice president of secondary
marketing. Last spring, for example, Crestar began offering a
30-year annually adjusted mortgage that lets consumers pay interest
for only the first 10 years, and whose rates, Ms. Huber said, are
far less than those of similar products.
</P>
<P>
   Crestar's product, she added, is pegged to carry an interest
rate that is just 1.5 percentage points higher than the Treasury
security to which such loans are generally pegged. By contrast, she
said, similar loans now run 2.75 or 2.875 percentage points higher.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing appeal of shorter-term adjustable-rate
mortgages, experts urge consumers to look before they leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so used to lower rates, but they should be careful
not to lock in too short a period, perhaps with a one- or
three-year product,'' said Bader, the chief executive at Skyscraper
Mortgage. He pointed out that on a five-year adjustable-rate
mortgage, consumers can still get a rate in the range of ``the low
sevens,'' and if they are willing to pay points _ the up-front fee
of a percentage of the total loan, with one point being 1 percent
of the mortgage _ they can get a rate in the ``high sixes.''
</P>
<P>
   He recommends that consumers pay a few extra points and buy down
their interest rate. Each point paid will lower the interest rate
by roughly 0.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have all but forgotten about points, but remember that
each point is one percentage point of a loan and two points is
effectively a half-percent of interest-rate reduction,'' he said.
``By paying two points on your mortgage, you can bring rates down
to where they were five months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bader also advises consumers to ask their banks about a
longer ``lock-in'' period _ the time for which a lender promises to
hold a certain interest rate while a loan is being processed _ in
case interest rates keep going up.
</P>
<P>
   While banks usually lock in rates for 60 days, some banks are
starting to tout 90-day locks, he said. He emphasized that the
longer lock-in periods are especially critical in fierce housing
markets like that of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so tight now that sellers can't find new houses
to move into, so they're asking for longer closing periods,'' he
said. At Bank of America, Hocheiser said he has noticed that while
mortgage loans used to close within 35 to 60 days as recently as a
few months ago, they now tend to close within 60 to 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers, however, may find that it pays to speed up the
closing process. Gumbinger said one way consumers can soothe some
of the sting of the recent rate hikes is to ask for a shorter
commitment period, which is the time between when a lender promises
to make a loan _ generally after it has already been approved _ and
the time the loan is actually made.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who have good credit, as well as having their
paperwork in order, may be able to close their loan in just 30
days, he said, allowing them to get a slightly lower interest rate,
perhaps in the range of an eighth of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   What about other defense strategies?
</P>
<P>
   Gumbinger advises consumers to consider offsetting the recent
increase in interest rates with a larger down payment, as well as
getting a ``float-down'' option in case rates might actually be
lower by the time the buyer closes on the loan. While a float-down
option usually entails paying a small fee _ such as one-eighth or a
quarter of 1 percent _ they give consumers access to lower rates if
they fall during the closing process.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gumbinger urges consumers not to panic. ``When rates
are higher and rising, it's more important to sit down and really
try to decide how long you plan on staying in a home so that you
can find the best mortgage,'' he said. ``With a 30-year fixed-rate
loan, you're buying stability, but it's expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scott also urges consumers to shoot for the future. ``Today,
it's more about a home being a long-term investment,'' she said.
``It's not so much about rates as it is about a good buy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
