<SLUG> BC-NJ-ANTISUBURBIA-SUBURB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: HOLD THE FRANCHISE, A WEALTHY ENCLAVE TELLS FAST-FOOD
 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST WINDSOR, N.J. _ It can be tough, being new in the area, and
rich, and a little uncertain about which fork to use, as it were.
You spend a lot of time worrying about your looks, for one thing.
That goes for people, and it goes for places.
</P>
<P>
   Take West Windsor. Until a little over a generation ago, it was
little more than the open farmland that separated Princeton from
the New Jersey Turnpike. But since the 1970s, it has grown into a
sprawl of expensive houses in carefully groomed developments, and
home to nearly 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   And like any new place, West Windsor invented itself each step
of the way as it grew, keeping its concern with appearances in
mind. But there have been tensions. Though it was created by the
automobile, the town is intent on keeping car culture at bay. The
effects of this conflict are visible everywhere: in the houses that
turn their backs on highways, in the serpentine writhing and dead
ends _ pardon, cul-de-sacs _ of its residential streets, and above
all in the town leaders' abhorrence of those emblems of suburbia,
the strip shopping center and the fast-food joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Windsor residents have always, for as long as I can
remember, prided themselves with living in a place that is
different from all the other towns in the area,'' said Sam Surtees,
West Windsor's community development director and chief planner.
``They see the commercial development and the strip malls that
other towns have along their major roadways, and they don't want
that stigma here.''
</P>
<P>
   So West Windsor prohibits funeral homes, self-storage places and
commercial gyms, among other things. At its meeting Wednesday, the
planning board considered allowing veterinary hospitals, provided
the animals were kept indoors at all times. But one member asked
about tigers _ after all, a 431-pound one escaped from a private
preserve in Ocean County in January _ and other members could not
agree on whether dogs could be made to do their business inside,
and the matter was tabled.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the town to do about fast food? A burger franchise's
``garish corporate architecture and signage'' conflicts with the
township's ``appearance goals,'' a planning board report put it
last month. But an outright ban on just one kind of restaurant
would probably be illegal. So far, only a McDonald's has crept into
town, but it has no drive-through window. A Wendy's tried to get
in, but its application was ``nit-picked to death,'' by the board,
Surtees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those meetings about the Wendy's went to 2:30 in the
morning,'' said Drewe Schoenholtz, a landscaper who sits on the
planning board and would like to see more restaurants of any kind
in town. ``It was a snob thing, that's what I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Windsor is the wealthiest town in Mercer County,'' he
said, ``and it's the place where everybody wants to be now.'' What
about Princeton, right next door, and traditionally one of the
state's best addresses? ``Forget Princeton,'' Schoenholtz snapped.
``Princeton's over.''
</P>
<P>
   At first the town planners considered simply outlawing
drive-through windows, for what fast-food restaurant could live
without one? But when town lawyers realized such a ban might not
stand up in court, the focus turned to forbidding free-standing
fast-food places in residential areas, allowing them only in
planned commercial developments, where signs and design have to be
uniform. A fast-food joint without its own garish sign, the
thinking goes, may turn into no joint at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what people are saying is,'' Surtees said, ``if you
don't want fast food, what can we do to make it so they don't want
to come here on their own?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
