<P>
   BUSING _ CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ In this city were busing for
desegregation began three decade ago, the color of school
children's skin has mattered most. Now the Charlotte-Mecklenburg
schools have less than a year to wipe clean the black-and-white
slate. A ruling Friday by U.S. District Judge Robert Potter gives
the nation's 23rd largest school district until the next school
year to institute color-blind policies in classroom assignments.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Consitution)
</P>
