<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNST-PITT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE HOLDS ON TO EDGE PITT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ What's with Penn State? What's the deal
with LaVar Arrington? And who's the real quarterback for the
Nittany Lions?
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 2 and still unbeaten, the Nittany Lions left a few
worried fans among their 96,127 customers on Saturday when they
survived Pittsburgh, 20-17, in Beaver Stadium. Penn State lost a
fourth-quarter lead and needed a 24-yard field goal by Travis
Forney with 1 minute 20 seconds left to make its record 3-0. Coming
into the game, the Panthers (1-1) were big underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the lead, the Nittany Lions were reeling at the end.
Pittsburgh ran the ensuing kickoff back to the 50-yard line and
passed on first down to the Penn State 25. But the drive stalled
and a Penn State sack put the Panthers back to the 35. From there,
Nick Lotz of Pittsburgh tried a 52-yard field goal that was blocked
by a leaping Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, an outside linebacker touted by some as a Heisman
Trophy candidate, gave another inconsistent performance that
included a loss of composure. That will probably not impress the
people who vote for various awards.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Penn State used two quarterbacks. The backup Rashard
Casey, a junior, was the most fun to watch, but left the game after
fumbling a first-down snap in the second half. Kevin Thompson, the
senior starter, directed the offense on the winning drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions broke a 10-10 tie with 14:15 left in the
fourth quarter on a 7-yard touchdown run by Eric McCoo, who swept
left behind strong blocking after taking a handoff from Thompson.
But their 17-10 lead lasted only until 4:34 showed on the clock,
when Pittsburgh tied the score on a 42-yard touchdown pass from
John Turman to Julius Dixon. On this play, and on the one before
that, the Penn State defenders were victimized while trying for an
interception. On the previous play, the victim was Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State had won the previous six games between these
Pennsylvania rivals, who first met in 1893. Although it was the
95th meeting between the Nittany Lions and the Panthers, next
season's game is the final one scheduled in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State fans were looking for an improved performance from
Arrington, a 6-foot-3-inch, 242-pound junior. In the previous game,
a 70-26 victory over Akron last week, Arrington made only one
tackle and was victimized at least twice on a Zips scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   After being knocked over by a blocker on an Akron touchdown run,
Arrington could be seen in animated conversation on the sideline
with at least one teammate and Jerry Sandusky, the defensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Akron game, Arrington said: ``I wait for a play to
come my way. When they don't come, I get a little restless. I just
have to learn to be a little more patient.'' He may have been
reacting to some observations that he was over-committing too early
to the initial motion of plays, thereby putting himself out of
position.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's game, Arrington stood out on a first-half play
that cost his team two penalties and could have resulted in his
ejection.
</P>
<P>
   With Pittsburgh punting from the Penn State 46, Arrington fought
off a block and tackled punter Greg DeBolt after DeBolt had kicked
the ball. When Arrington persisted in roughing DeBolt, refusing to
let him up, D.J. Dinkins of the Panthers came to his punter's aid
and Arrington jostled him as well amid the yellow flags.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington went to the bench and sat by himself during the next
Penn State drive, but returned to the field with his teammates for
their next defensive shift. When Arrington knocked down Turman
after a pass, he helped Turman to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams used two quarterbacks in the first half, which ended
with the Nittany Lions holding a 10-7 lead. Penn State's touchdown
drive was led by Casey, who completed four of four attempts for 88
yards in the half, including an 11-yard scoring play to Mike
Cerimele with 4:18 remaining in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In relief of Thompson, Casey often scrambled out of the pocket
to throw on the run, sometimes directing blockers and receivers
with hand motions between pump fakes. He also lost 20 yards on a
second-quarter scramble that put his team out of field goal range.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State's other three points came on a 43-yard field goal by
Forney with 7:23 remaining in the half. The Panthers' first-half
touchdown came with 11:59 left in the second quarter on Turman's
16-yard pass play to Antonio Bryant, over Arrington. Early in the
second half, the Panthers gained 33 yards on another pass over
Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third quarter, Pittsburgh successfully
executed a strategic oddity: a quick kick on third down by Turman
that carried 47 yards to the Penn State 4-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   On the sixth play of the Lions' drive, linebacker Bryan Knight
of Pittsburgh intercepted Thompson's pass and returned it to the
Penn State 17. But the opportunity evaporated with an incompletion,
a false-start penalty and another incompletion. The Panthers
settled for a 35-yard field goal by Lotz to tie the score at 10-10
with 5:55 remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another tough test for Penn State should come next Saturday when
it plays its first game on the road, at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions begin their eight-game Big Ten schedule Sept.
25 against Indiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
