<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-UNION-6     09-11 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-UNION-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH-CARE UNION PREPARES TO SHOW ITS MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York's labor leaders have long had a vision of
creating a single, powerful union for the city's health-care
workers. Until now, such a plan was dashed by fierce competition
among the region's rival unions to recruit members.
</P>
<P>
   But the dream of establishing one giant health-care union is
finally becoming a reality now that two medium-size unions are
merging with the city's largest health-care labor grouping _ 1199,
the National Health and Human Service Employees Union.
</P>
<P>
   Those mergers, as well as 1199's recent success in several
organizing drives, will swell 1199's ranks to about 200,000
members, making it far larger than any other union in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rivera, 1199's president, said this growth spurt _ the
union now has 150,000 members _ would increase the union's clout in
bargaining, lobbying and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will increase our ability in the political world,'' said
Rivera, who has often thrown his union's considerable weight behind
Democratic candidates. ``It will increase our ability and our
resources to organize new workers. And it will help us in case we
have a strike or a massive mobilization.''
</P>
<P>
   The union's increased power is sure to upset some Republican
officials who fear 1199's muscle in political campaigns and often
dislike its hardball lobbying in Albany. Twice since Gov. George
Pataki came to power, 1199 has spent hundreds of thousands of
dollars to broadcast attacks on the governor over planned Medicaid
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In one major move to increase 1199's size, the union will merge
with Local 1115 of the Service Employees International Union, a
-unit based in Westbury, Long Island that represents 15,000
nursing-home workers. Service Employees International is also the
parent of 1199.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's union will gain an additional 22,500 members by
absorbing the home-care unit of Service Employees Local 32B-32J,
which represents janitors and has a large affiliate representing
workers who go to the homes of aging or ailing people to help with
cooking, cleaning and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 1199 has recently succeeded in organizing 4,000
home-care workers with Partners in Care, a subsidiary of the
Visiting Nurse Service, a nonprofit agency that provides nurses,
rehabilitation therapists and home-care aides to thousands of New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said his union expected to gain at least 15,000 more
members by organizing thousands of home-care workers employed by
subcontractors of the Visiting Nurse Service.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, 1199 had 105,000 members and was the city's
second-largest union, behind District Council 37 of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, which
represents 120,000 workers. But it leapfrogged District Council 37
two years ago when Service Employees Local 144 and its 30,000
hospital and nursing-home workers voted to join 1199, after Local
144's president was ousted for extravagant spending.
</P>
<P>
   The union's steady growth has showcased Rivera's knack at
persuading other unions to merge with 1199 as well as his unusual
ability to persuade many hospitals, health-care companies and
health-care agencies not to oppose organizing drives.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald McKelvey, a spokesman for the Visiting Nurse Service,
said the agency agreed to work with 1199, rather than fight a
unionization drive, because it believed that 1199's political clout
could help win expanded home-care funding from Albany.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the mergers and rapid growth, 1199 is realigning
itself into divisions: hospital, with nearly 100,000 workers; home
care, with almost 50,000 workers, and nursing home, with 43,000
workers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jay Sachman, the president of Local 1115, will be the head of
the nursing-home division. ``This organization is going to
represent 75 percent of the nursing home workers in the New York
metropolitan area, which is unprecedented,'' he said. ``With the
power this gives us, we will work to increase staffing ratios and
reimbursement levels for New York's nursing homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Health-care experts said these mergers would not only lead to
more industrywide bargaining, instead of negotiating institution by
institution, but also could lead to far larger strikes than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   With unions seeking to reverse their membership losses in recent
decades, Rivera has vowed to make 1199 one of New York's busiest
union organizers. In August, 500 workers at St. Agnes Hospital in
White Plains voted to join 1199. Also last month, the union got
nearly 200 workers at Catholic Medical Center in Queens to sign
cards saying that they wanted to join.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 2, close to 300 workers at Doctors Hospital in Staten
Island voted to join 1199. Last week, nearly 150 workers at Hebrew
Hospital Home, a nursing home in Valhalla, voted for membership.
Also this month, clerical workers at Lenox Hill Hospital in
Manhattan voted 126-124 to join 1199, although the final results
remain up in the air because of challenged ballots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
