<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-935(2TAK     09-11 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-935(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: UPGRADING A BUILDING'S ELEVATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks ago, this column contained advice for co-op
and condominium boards negotiating elevator-maintenance contracts
for their buildings. As pointed out then, a carefully drafted
contract with a carefully chosen elevator company is essential for
the safety and convenience of residents.
</P>
<P>
   But even an excellent contract with an excellent company may not
be enough to prevent an elevator from succumbing to the ravages of
time, friction and physics. That means that at some point near the
end of an elevator's life span _ often around the 35-year mark,
experts say _ the time will come to take the expensive step of
elevator modernization.
</P>
<P>
   ``When dealing with elevators, you really have to plan years
ahead,'' said Herb Rose, a co-op consultant based in Manhattan.
``You can't just wait for the elevator to fall apart and then
replace it. If you have a 16-story building, you have 16 floors of
responsibility. And whenever you're waiting for something to break,
you're courting disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose pointed out that it is not uncommon for modernization
projects to cost hundreds of thousands of dollars and put cars
being upgraded out of commission for months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for a building to spend a quarter of a
million dollars upgrading its elevators,'' Rose said, adding that
with numbers so large, it usually pays for a co-op or condominium
board to seek expert advice. And one way to do that is to hire an
elevator consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consultants keep everybody honest,'' said Tom Corsale,
director of sales and marketing for Central Elevator, an elevator
maintenance and installation company in Manhattan. ``Let's face it,
we're not talking about buying a box of doughnuts here.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things a consultant will do, Corsale said, is to
provide an independent assessment of the current condition of the
elevator and the projected life span of its major components.
Another, he said, will be to draw up detailed specifications for
whatever work the board determines is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   James Samson, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that the primary
concern for boards contemplating an elevator-modernization project
_ once the issue of how to pay for the project has been addressed _
is how to deal with having one or more elevators out of service for
an extended time.
</P>
<P>
   In a building with one passenger elevator and a service elevator
it generally makes sense to upgrade the service elevator first so
that residents can at least use the freshly renovated unit when the
passenger car is taken out of service. In buildings with just one
elevator, Samson said, the stakes are higher and the solutions more
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a client with four seven-story buildings with one
elevator per building and lots of senior citizens,'' Samson said.
``You take one of those elevators out of service and you've got a
real problem on your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   One way way to address such a problem, he said, is to provide
residents with as much advance notice as possible of the dates the
elevator is expected to be out of service. Another is to keep the
down time to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a contractor will be able to shorten the time the
elevators will be out of service,'' he said, adding that such an
accommodation is likely to result in higher costs because an
accelerated schedule requires contractors to work through the night
and on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also possible that with enough advance notice, some
residents will be able to find somewhere else to stay while the
elevators are out of service,'' Samson said, adding that those who
are not able to do so must also be accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may end up having to put them up in hotel rooms or ease
their burden by hiring extra staff,'' he said. ``It's just one of
those things you're going to have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every modernization project requires the immediate gut
renovation of the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Walsh, president of Walsh Associates Ltd., an elevator
consulting company in Manhattan, said that many elevator
modernization jobs can be done in phases. That means that a total
modernization project that might take anywhere from 12 to 15 weeks
could be broken down into separate five- or six-week stages with
the different stages spread out over time.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of such a project, Walsh said, would generally
be to replace the parts of the elevator that get the most wear and
tear _ the elevator door and the mechanism that moves it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A door package usually includes a new car door, new hangers
and tracks, and new closures,'' Walsh said, explaining that hangers
and tracks in an elevator are a heavy-duty version of the plastic
rollers and aluminum channels that are used to secure hanging
closet doors in their frames while allowing them to move freely
back and forth. And closures, he said, are the intricate gears,
levers and motors that open and close the door.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of a typical modernization project, Walsh said,
would be an aesthetic upgrade of the interior of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we redo the cab, put in a new panel and install
new hall buttons on each floor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the final phase of a three-phase modernization project,
Walsh said, would be to replace the electrical and mechanical
equipment that controls the movement of the elevator itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 95 percent of cases we can retain the hoist machine,'' he
said, referring to the motor and pulley assembly used in most
high-rise buildings in the city. ``We'll usually have to replace
the generator, though, and we'll always replace the controller.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The controller, Walsh said, is a sophisticated electronic device
that functions as the brain of the elevator. Choosing which type of
controller to use, he said, is one of the most significant
decisions a property owner or board will be required to make when
upgrading an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh explained that controllers can be either proprietary
devices made by elevator manufacturers for use in that
manufacturer's elevators, or generic devices that can be
retrofitted into almost any elevator, including those made by
manufacturers that use proprietary equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the complexity of modern controllers, however,
sophisticated electronic tools are typically needed to diagnose
equipment malfunctions. And while generic controllers can be
diagnosed and repaired by any qualified elevator contractor using
generic controller diagnostic tools, proprietary controllers
require the use of proprietary tools for diagnosis and repair.
</P>
<P>
   And that, Walsh said, often makes it necessary for those who
have proprietary controllers installed in their elevators to hire
the elevator manufacturer that made the controller to service and
repair it _ a requirement that limits a board's ability to
negotiate a service contract on the most favorable terms.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the experts say, boards that hire a company to perform
an elevator upgrade should probably use the same company to
maintain and service the new elevator, at least for the first few
years. In fact, the service contract should provide for a period of
free service in its early stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the company that upgraded the elevator did the job right,
there shouldn't be any service necessary for at least the first
year or so,'' said Samson, the lawyer. ``So you should be able to
get at least one year free service without even breathing hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
