<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HIRSCHLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLEN HIRSCHLAND, 80, COLLECTOR AND A FRIEND OF MODERN MASTERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (rk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ellen B. Hirschland, an art collector, teacher and a
great-niece of Baltimore collectors Claribel and Etta Cone, died on
Sept. 3 while traveling near St. Moritz, Switzerland. She was 80
and lived in Great Neck, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pneumonia, said her son Edward.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hirschland was born in Baltimore, the daughter of Sidney
Berney, a vice president at Isaac Hamburger, a clothing store in
Baltimore, and Dorothy Long Berney, a niece of Etta and Claribel
Cone, who amassed a world-class collection of 19th and 20th century
art, including 42 Matisse oil paintings, which they bequeathed to
the Baltimore Museum of Art in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 17, Mrs. Hirschland traveled with Etta Cone to
Paris, where she met Matisse, who became one of her lifelong
friends. She also came to know other modern masters, including
Chagall, Albers, Miro and Louise Nevelson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, the year she graduated from Wheaton College, she
married Paul M. Hirschland, who became a Manhattan investment
banker. Hirschland died in 1988. During their marriage, the couple
collected modern art and put together a group of works by artists
ranging from Cezanne to Frank Stella. Mrs. Hirschland was also a
trustee of the Baltimore Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 years, Mrs. Hirschland taught art history in the adult
education program in the Great Neck public schools. She also
lectured widely on the Cone sisters and, with her daughter, Nancy
H. Ramage, recently completed a biography about them, which is to
be published by Harry N. Abrams next year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her son Edward, of Chicago, and daughter, Nancy,
of Ithaca, N.Y., she is survived by another son, Roger, of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
