<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-PERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ERROR LETS WOMAN SEARCH YEARS FOR DEAD SON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After her son, a sophomore at Queens College,
disappeared in October 1995, Arnita Fowler sold everything she
owned, gave up her job in California and moved to New York City so
she could search for him. And so she did for four years, posting
thousands of fliers and making hundreds of calls to the police.
</P>
<P>
   But her son's body had been found floating in the East River
near 38th Street six days after he disappeared, and he was buried
at Potters Field on Hart Island, in an unidentified pauper's grave.
And, in what police officials called a mistake, a fingerprint check
by the FBI had long ago determined the body's identity, but Ms.
Fowler had not been notified.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, La-Mont Dottin, was 21 when he disappeared on Oct. 18,
1995, after a trip to the post office in Hollis, Queens, where he
lived. Investigators and William H. Allee Jr., the chief of
detectives for the New York police, described the incident as a
simple miscommunication.
</P>
<P>
   Fingerprint checks on the body taken from the river returned no
hits from the New York state police database, and Allee blamed the
FBI for never calling to alert missing persons detectives that they
had found fingerprints on file with the police in Sacramento, where
Dottin had been arrested on a gun possession charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to indicate that the FBI sent us anything
back,'' Allee said, blaming the FBI for the miscommunication and
defending his detectives, even though they did not follow up with
the federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, after determining that missing persons
investigations in the past were lacking, the Police Department
created the squad to reinvestigate old, unresolved cases, Allee
said. In March, the case was given to the squad.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, Ms. Fowler, who now lives and works in Queens,
said she believed that the detectives discovered that her son had
been found only because of a routine call she made to the Missing
Persons Squad to set up a meeting last week. That was the day she
was told that her son had been found. Ms. Fowler said a detective
told her that investigators realized the error when a supervisor
asked him to make the follow-up calls to the FBI that should have
been done years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was an error,'' Ms. Fowler said Saturday. ``He
calls four years of pain an error?''
</P>
<P>
   Police believe Dottin's death was accidental, but they plan to
exhume the body to re-examine it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fowler said she planned to attend law school and become a
lawyer to help others with missing loved ones work the system
better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
