u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ATTENDANCE-     09-11 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ATTENDANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE MILLION FANS' MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourteen months ago, George Steinbrenner said that if
attendance at Yankee games reached 3 million this season, he would
discuss keeping the team in the Bronx. The Yankees barely missed
that mark last year, but they will surpass it on Sunday against the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   After drawing more than 55,000 fans on Saturday, the Yankees
eclipsed their attendance record of 2.95 million, set in 1998. With
more than 55,000 tickets sold for Sunday, the team will exceed 3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, lauded the fans for
their support, but he dodged questions on Saturday about what the
attendance milestone might mean.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was reluctant to discuss his team's future, because
he wants the Yankees' priorities to be on winning a second straight
World Series title. He is also awaiting the National Basketball
Association's approval of the proposed Yankees-Nets deal, a
business merger between the baseball and basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a telephone interview if the attendance record had
proved to him that fans would flock to the Bronx, he responded:
``We will be making up our minds soon. We're waiting to get the
approval on the Yankee-Nets. Then we'll make a decision on where
we're playing, whether it be in the Bronx, Manhattan or New Jersey.
I just can't talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's lease at Yankee Stadium expires in 2002, but
speculation about the Yankees' moving to the Upper West Side of
Manhattan or to New Jersey has waned. Some baseball officials have
said that upgrading the current stadium may be the only option for
Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   With seven home games left in the regular season, the Yankees
will also shatter the New York attendance record that the Mets set
with 3.047 million in 1988. ``It's a wonderful achievement and a
wonderful tribute to New York,'' Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner has complained for the past decade about traffic
and safety concerns in the Bronx and about the lack of luxury boxes
at the Stadium, saying these deficiencies cost him millions of
dollars and do not allow him to fairly compete with teams that have
modern facilities. While Steinbrenner has refused to reveal what
changes he wants if the team remains in the Bronx, they will
include more parking, ways to minimize traffic congestion, luxury
boxes and 3 million or more fans a year on a consistent basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-ENGINEERS-NYT &LR;      09-11 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ENGINEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO HEADS, THINKING AS ONE, IN THE CAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The relationship between a race car driver and his engineer
during a Formula One weekend is similar to that in a good marriage.
``You need a lot of trust and a lot of respect between the two of
you for it to work,'' said Steve Clark, the race engineer for Pedro
Diniz of the Sauber team.
</P>
<P>
   A white lie by the driver about the reason for a spinout may be
balm for good relations between a driver and his team owner or the
news media. But the race engineer must know the truth, or it could
be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often you find that half of the race engineer's job is as a
psychologist,'' said Clark, who was the engineer for Alex Zanardi
last year in the CART series, which they won. The idea, he said, is
``to try to cocoon, to make a little team within the team to
protect the driver, because his performance is an emotional one. If
he loses confidence, he might as well not get in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 22 Formula One drivers who will make up the
grid at the Italian Grand Prix in Monza Sunday, there will also be
the 22 engineers who work throughout the season with their
individual drivers and share much of the responsibility for their
success or failure.
</P>
<P>
   The senior race car engineer is constantly by the driver's side
in the garage or as a voice in his ear through the radio during the
race. When not racing, the engineer and the driver try to develop
the car or find the ideal setup for a specific track. To do this,
the engineer collects and interprets both the computer data from
the car and the human data of the driver's impressions, which he
must translate into deft technical changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver will say, `I have understeer, or I have oversteer,
or I'm bottoming too much,''' said Heinz-Harald Frentzen, the
German driver who is in fourth place in the championship standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this information from the driver is also accessible to the
engineer through the computer sensors. So I say to him, for
example, `I don't want my car to understeer so much in this or that
corner.' We talk about what we can do. We can lower the right tire,
we can do softer springs, we can do a softer tire on the front, or
softer damping, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Race engineers often follow drivers to other teams, as Ross
Brawn followed Michael Schumacher from Benetton to Ferrari in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Brawn is also Ferrari's technical director and the mastermind of
its race strategy. Last July, Schumacher broke his leg at the
British Grand Prix. To maintain equilibrium at Ferrari for Eddie
Irvine and his technical team, Irvine kept his own race engineer
rather than switching to Brawn. But Brawn has worked closely with
Irvine and his engineer while Irvine has taken on the role as
Ferrari's No. 1 driver.
</P>
<P>
   Jock Clear followed Jacques Villeneuve, the former IndyCar and
Formula One champion, from Williams to the new British American
Racing team this year. He did so, he said, because ``ultimately my
job is very much dependent on the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Clear added, ``He makes me look good or bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
