<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-ASSAULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATING TRIAL HAS 2 VIEWS OF AN INCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a Brooklyn courtroom this week, prosecutors will
continue to claim that two New York City police detectives acted
like ``common thugs,'' viciously beating a man who was later struck
and killed by a train in a nearby subway station.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers will continue to insist that the detectives
did not assault the man. They are depicting him as a quarrelsome
drunk who argued with many people before committing suicide in the
subway.
</P>
<P>
   The two accounts are being offered as the trial of the two
detectives _ and of two other detectives accused of helping in a
cover-up _ begins its second week Monday in state Supreme Court in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The man who died, Reginald Bannerman, 36, worked as a porter at
BBB Soul and Seafood Restaurant at Bedford Avenue and Crown Street
in Crown Heights. Early on Dec. 19, 1997, prosecutors say, he was
savagely beaten on the street outside, after he argued with a group
of off-duty detectives who were drinking at a birthday party at the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant is six blocks from the Sterling Street subway
station, where Bannerman died about 45 minutes later. The City
Medical Examiner's office says his death was a suicide. But a
lawyer for Bannerman's family says he was dazed by severe head and
eye injuries from the beating and fell in front of the train.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the prosecutors, from the Brooklyn district attorney's
office, told the jury that two of the defendants, Lloyd Barnaby,
38, and Mark Cooper, 29, were among a group of assailants who beat,
kicked and stomped Bannerman, with Barnaby also using a bottle on
him. When he broke away from his attackers to flee, a prosecutor
said, Barnaby and Cooper were among the detectives who fired their
guns wildly over his head.
</P>
<P>
   One witness told reporters before the trial that Bannerman had
apparently angered the detectives by telling the hard-drinking
group to quiet down.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the defendants, Detective Edward Howard, 31, helped
Barnaby and Cooper pick up and hide the spent shell casings, ``to
avoid evidence being found,'' a prosecutor, Charles M. Guria, said
during opening statements. And Guria said the fourth defendant,
Detective Orice Connor, 30, committed official misconduct by not
reporting the violent events to the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``These defendants reverted to common thugs,'' said Guria, an
executive assistant district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnaby's lawyer, Dino J. Lombardi, told the jury that there
had been a ``general confused melee'' in which his client ``never
endangered anyone's health or caused physical injury to Reginald
Bannerman,'' whom he said had been drinking heavily, was
argumentative and was flashing a light in people's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's lawyer, Alan I. Friess, told the jury that his client
had nothing to do with any assault on Bannerman and that his death
was not related to whatever happened outside the restaurant nearly
an hour before. Saying that Bannerman had not been chased by
anybody to the subway station, he told the jury, ``For reasons
unknown, Reginald Bannerman jumped in front of a train.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said before the trial that there was no evidence
of a chase. In any event, the judge, Albert Tomei, told the jury
that the cause of Bannerman's death ``is not an issue at this
trial, and you are not to speculate or guess at what caused his
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing both Howard and Connor, Marvyn M.
Kornberg, said the two men had done nothing to warrant the
evidence-tampering charge against the former and the official
misconduct charge against the latter.
</P>
<P>
   The only witness so far has been Bannerman's brother-in-law,
Michael Knight, a part-owner of the restaurant. He described a
sidewalk scene in which about a half-dozen men, including Barnaby,
were stomping and kicking Bannerman ``in the head, the face, all
over his body.'' He said Barnaby used a bottle or a glass.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, the detectives' lawyers sought to convince
the jurors that Knight's testimony was unreliable. Using written
reports by police investigators who had interviewed Knight at
different times, the lawyers stressed discrepancies in details the
reports said he had given.
</P>
<P>
   Bannerman had also worked as a recreation specialist in an
after-school youth program. The detectives, with the Brooklyn South
Narcotics Unit at the time of the incident, are on restricted duty
until the case is resolved. Barnaby and Cooper face the most
serious charges, second-degree assault, punishable by up to seven
years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
