<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSING12-COX     09-11 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. city grapples with deadline to end race-based busing
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ In this city where busing for desegregation
began three decades ago, the color of schoolchildren's skin has
mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Charlotte-Mecklenburg schools have less than a year to
wipe clean the black-and-white slate.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling Friday by U.S. District Judge Robert Potter gives the
nation's 23rd-largest school district until the next school year to
institute colorblind policies in classroom assignments.
</P>
<P>
   In dissolving the desegregation order stemming from the landmark
Swann vs. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education case, Potter
concluded that the district has acted in ``good faith for almost 30
years'' to eliminate ``vestiges of past discrimination to the
extent practicable ...''
</P>
<P>
   School officials in Charlotte said the ruling by the Reagan
appointee will bring a historic end to forced busing, the city's
primary tool for achieving racial balance among the district's
101,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   The nation is watching, again, as Charlotte-Mecklenburg suddenly
finds itself reluctantly freed from federal court supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next problem is going to be how they are going to handle
it,'' said Gary Sams, attorney for the DeKalb County, Ga., school
district, which was under a federal desegregation order from 1968
through 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Charlotte, they lived under one set rule for 30 years. It
is going to be very difficult to change a mind-set over one year,
especially when the rule they had to follow is now against the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Although school officials had anticipated Potter's ruling,
Superintendent Eric Smith said, ``These are very difficult issues.
It is going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter agreed, comparing the Charlotte-Mecklenburg district to
the Sisyphus, a mythological figure whose eternal punishment in the
Greek underworld was to roll a stone up a steep hill only to see it
roll back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of remedial necessity, the Court will not add
to that conundrum by requiring additional affirmative obligations
that address socioeconomic concerns or societal discrimination,''
Potter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It's a landmark ruling in North Carolina's largest school
district, where public education was so segregated in the 1960s
that a federal judge ordered busing of students beyond their
neighborhood schools to achieve racial balance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the 1969 Swann case,
which ushered in urban busing across America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the granddaddy,'' said James Hallford, superintendent of
the DeKalb County schools. ``Nationwide, everybody knows Swann vs.
Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the growing national movement to dismantle desegregation
plans _ in DeKalb County and Nashville, Tenn., among other cities _
Charlotte-Mecklenburg finds itself back in the pack. But it is not
without unique challenges that illustrate the intensifying debate
over race in education.
</P>
<P>
   For Charlotte-Mecklenburg officials, the ruling causes practical
problems. The district doesn't have enough money to build enough
inner-city schools to accommodate the estimated 7,000 black
students who no longer will be bused to primarily white suburban
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run about 1,000 buses right now in Mecklenburg County.
After the judge's ruling, I don't care how we wind up with student
reassignment, we are still going to run about 1,000 buses,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some black parents fear building more inner-city schools could
take several years, a likelihood conceded by school officials.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that the school district, the NAACP or black
parents who joined the case will appeal Potter's ruling. Parties in
the case have 30 days to decide whether to file an appeal to the
4th Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal could delay school improvements and prolong
uncertainty among parents seeking stable school assignments for
their children, said Lee Parks, an Atlanta lawyer who was the lead
plaintiffs' lawyer in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The original plaintiff, Bill Capacchione, sued in 1997 after his
daughter waited two years trying to enroll in one of the county's
magnet schools. At the time of the lottery for seats, spots
reserved for black children had gone unfilled. A group of white
parents argued that busing and other race-based policies violated
their constitutional guarantee of equal protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlotte is right on the edge,'' Parks said. ``If they do not
fix it this year, it will be too late. They have to create programs
to get parents to recommit to public education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want more turmoil and diversity,'' said Smith, the
district's superintendent. ``But we do not want to sacrifice the
quality of education of large groups of students for a year or two
of stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke Largess, a lawyer for two black families in that case who
joined the school district in the lawsuit, said his clients would
appeal if the school district doesn't. He said Potter overstepped
his authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's saying is you cannot use race in any aspect of
operating the educational system,'' Largess said. ``It's an
interesting legal question whether he can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is how do you justify doing away with busing when
all vestiges of a dual system have not been removed?'' Charlotte
NAACP President Dwayne Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-month trial that ended in June, the
Charlotte-Mecklenburg district asked Potter to extend court
supervision. School officials argued that the district needed
several more years to bring about desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   The district's racial makeup is 60 percent white and 40 percent
black, a level that school officials said they had not achieved in
all of the district's 138 schools.
</P>
<P>
   Potter wrote that he found the board's position to be
``bizarre'' since it put it at odds with its late-1960s predecessor
which ``strongly resisted federal supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the judge noted, the school board is aligned with the
black children's parents who originally sued the board in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Potter concluded that ``quite some time ago''
Charlotte-Mecklenburg had achieved an acceptable level of
desegregation among its students.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Potter declared that Charlotte-Mecklenburg's
schools are ``enjoined from assigning children to schools or
allocating educational opportunities and benefits through
race-based lotteries, preferences, set-asides, or other means that
deny students an equal footing based on race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a decision that says Charlotte won't be permitted to
have any desegregated schools unless it happens by accident,'' said
William Taylor, a Washington, D.C., lawyer who is vice chairman of
the Citizens Commission on Civil Rights and teaches at Georgetown
University.
</P>
<P>
   But citing trial testimony, Potter said, ``One (school)
official's unsubstantiated fear that discrimination might reappear
in the absence of a court order is no grounds for prolonged court
supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted that ``Charlotte has become one of the most
racially integrated cities in America,'' resulting partly from
``the dispersion of blacks into the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
