<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-TEAM-RACING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOCKING IS THE RULE IN INTERCLUB CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't come easy for racers when a regatta calls for the
greater good of sailing. But team racing _ where one boat's
first-place finish may keep the team from winning _ calls for
tactics that bend the rules in uncommon ways.
</P>
<P>
   It may mean that you have to waive a basic principle in yacht
racing: allowing a fellow team on port tack to take right-of-way
over your sailboat on starboard tack if it helps the team win.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycle riders use similar tricks, like drafting to allow a bike
behind to benefit from a teammate's position ahead. But in a
yachting competition, racing chicanery often creates daring moves
on the straightaway and logjams rounding the marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole other layer of thinking,'' Steven Wolff, chairman
of Team Racing for the New York Yacht Club, said in a recent
telephone interview. ``Your boat handling has to be top-notch, and
you have to have your speed up. But you also have to be able to
maneuver your boat in tiny, tiny spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran group of Long Island Sound sailors representing nine
yacht clubs in the New York-Connecticut area is scheduled to
compete next weekend in the New York Yacht Club Interclub Team
Race, two days of round-robin competition off Larchmont, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It is the team-race scoring system that encourages gamesmanship
on the water. In any one round-robin race, which pits four boats of
one team against four boats of another, the low point scorer wins.
At the end of eight races, for example, a team that finished 2, 3,
4 and 8 would beat a team that finished 1, 2, 7 and 8. The winning
team would have 18 points as low point scorer, compared with 18\
points for the second team.
</P>
<P>
   The crews soon learn to make the scoring system work in their
favor. Teammates try to block competing team boats from catching up
to a fellow boat. By allowing a teammate to waive the starboard
right-of-way, a team player may give fellow sailors an advantage
over a competing boat just ahead or behind.
</P>
<P>
   Juggling positions at a mark calls for even more calculation. By
trying to allow a teammate to gain the inside advantage, a sailboat
may have to maintain its position in a strong current or rough
seas.
</P>
<P>
   The event marks the annual team championship for the Yacht
Racing Association of Long Island Sound. It also represents a
chance for local bastions of yacht racing to mix it up on the water
without attracting undue attention to any one sailor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of any one boat finishing first,'' Brad
Dellenbaugh, a team-race expert and offshore sailing coach at the
U.S. Naval Academy, said last week from his office in Annapolis,
Md. ``It's how members of your team help each other to gain better
positioning along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the New York Yacht Club, the competing teams include the
Larchmont Yacht Club, the American Yacht Club, the Sea Cliff Yacht
Club, and the Seawanhaka Corinthian Yacht Club, of New York state;
and the Indian Harbor Yacht Club, the Pequot Yacht Club, the
Noroton Yacht Club and the Riverside Yacht Club, of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   In the interclub championship, each association sends 16 sailors
to compete. They race for the Glencairn Trophy, a prize donated two
years ago by the Long Island Sound Yacht Racing Association. Club
teams sail on identical Ideal 18s, 18-foot keelboats that require
two-person crews.
</P>
<P>
   Regatta organizers have planned racing on Friday in the varsity
team division, for skippers 50 and older; there is a similar format
on Saturday for the mixed team division, where age is not a factor.
A series of semifinals and finals is scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Team racing is not altogether new in yachting. Collegiate
sailors thrive on it. But once out of school, most sailors
gravitate to fleet racing under handicap or one-design rules, which
forces competitors to develop a personal approach to sailing rather
than collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about how well you do,'' Wolff said. ``It's
about making an individual sport into a team sport. You have to
communicate with team members on the water, and you have to figure
out how to use the sailing rules to each other's advantage.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
