<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LAWYERS-BIAS-REAL-2TA     09-11 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-BIAS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A DEVELOPER BALKS AT SELLING TO A LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ Timothy B. Liebaert, a lawyer, thought
nothing of mentioning his occupation to a saleswoman at the Fairway
Oaks housing development in this Central Valley farm and oil town.
</P>
<P>
   The saleswoman reacted to the news by grimacing and warning
Liebaert that the developer, Burlington Homes, sometimes refused to
sell houses to lawyers, he recalled. In the developer's opinion,
Liebaert was told, lawyers are particularly litigious about
defects, real and imagined, in their houses, and are therefore not
good customers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a day later, the saleswoman called Liebaert to tell him
that the company would not sell him a house. Unconcerned that he
would be demonstrating the very characteristic the developer had
deplored, Liebaert responded by filing a lawsuit claiming
discrimination based on his profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to exclude people who have any level of
sophistication,'' said Liebaert, 32, who has been an environmental
lawyer for four years. ``Since I'm an attorney, they think I might
try to make them uphold their end of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Liebaert's case illuminates what real estate experts say is an
unusual practice among developers. By limiting the number of
lawyers it sells houses to, Burlington Homes hopes to reduce legal
fees connected with litigation by homeowners who claim that their
houses have defects, like leaky roofs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of two or three similar situations with rentals,''
said Sara Pratt, director of enforcement and compliance for the
National Fair Housing Alliance, a consumer advocacy group based in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not aware of any other case involving the sale of
property,'' she added, referring both to lawsuits filed by
disgruntled lawyers and to developers who are reluctant to sell to
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal statutes protect buyers and tenants from housing
discrimination on the basis of race, color, national origin,
religion, sex, family status and disability, but do not mention
profession. Most state laws are similar, though some also include
sexual orientation as a protected category.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of cities and counties nationwide have laws that
protect buyers and tenants based on their profession. One is New
York City, which passed a law in 1986 prohibiting discrimination
based on profession after lawyers, among others, complained that
landlords had refused to rent them apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Portland, Ore., where in 1991 the City Council passed
an ordinance that prohibits housing discrimination based on
``source of income.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance makes it illegal to discriminate against people
because of their occupation or because their source of income is
government welfare or Social Security checks. People whose source
of income is criminal activity are not covered, nor are those who
have federal rent subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Liebaert's troubles started in February, when he tried to buy a
five-bedroom, four-bath home for $145,900 for himself, his wife,
Kelly, and their two infant daughters. When told that he could not
buy a house at Fairway Oaks, and after his $3,000 deposit on a lot
was returned with the word ``void'' marked across the check, he
filed a suit in state Superior Court in Kern County.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, Liebaert claimed that Burlington Homes had violated
the state's civil rights law by refusing to sell him a home because
of his profession. The law is typically used to protect people from
discrimination based on factors including race, sex and religion.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan Judkins, president of Burlington Homes, acknowledged
that his company was indeed wary of selling houses to lawyers. Such
precautions are necessary, he said in an interview, to keep the
company profitable and prices low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need to do business with everyone who walks in the
door,'' Judkins said, ``just like a lawyer doesn't have to take on
everyone who walks in the door as a client. Being an attorney in
our eyes says, `Open your eyes wider.'''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But Judkins said his company, which is based in Bakersfield, a
city of 174,000 110 miles north of Los Angeles, did not have an
absolute policy against selling houses to lawyers. In fact, he
said, the company ``consciously'' sold a house to one ``classy''
lawyer who has yet to cause the company any problems.
</P>
<P>
   However, Judkins said, the company once sold a house to another
customer without realizing that he was a lawyer. That lawyer,
Judkins said, ``made our life miserable'' with ``threats and
intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Judkins would not specify what the buyer's complaints were or
how they were resolved. But in court documents filed in response to
Liebaert's lawsuit, Burlington Homes said it had not suffered any
legal costs as a result of selling houses to the two lawyers with
whom it says it has done business.
</P>
<P>
   Liebaert points to that admission as proof that Burlington Homes
has no legitimate fear of lawyers. But Judkins is unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Liebaert has not had much success with his lawsuit. In
May, Judge Sidney P. Chapin of Superior Court dismissed Liebaert's
claims of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the state's civil rights law does not include
discrimination based on profession as grounds for a complaint.
Developers can legally refuse to sell houses to lawyers, the judge
said, as long as the refusal is made for business reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Liebaert filed an emergency appeal with the state's Fifth
District Court in Fresno. The court denied the appeal, but Liebaert
can file a regular appeal later if he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   When not dealing with a protected category of consumer,
developers and landlords have some latitude in choosing whom to
sell or rent to, and their rights have been upheld in court on a
number of occasions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, developers can use age restrictions to keep younger
people out of senior citizen communities. And landlords can refuse
to rent apartments to unmarried couples based on religious
concerns. In commercial buildings, they can keep out businesses
they consider incompatible with other tenants.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Liebaert, who is renting a house in Bakersfield and is
still looking to buy one, has revised his lawsuit to claim that
Burlington Homes violated his wife's civil rights. He contends that
the company refused to sell her a house because she is married to a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Employment and Fair Housing is also
investigating Liebaert's claim of discrimination. If the agency
finds enough evidence, it could convene a hearing before an
administrative judge.
</P>
<P>
   Liebaert is also trying to force Burlington Homes to include
what he calls its policy against lawyers in its sales brochures.
</P>
<P>
   June Barlow, vice president and general counsel of the
California Association of Realtors, said people in some
occupations, especially those dominated by members of minorities,
may have recourse against sellers who refuse to do business with
them even if there are no specific ``source of income'' laws in the
buyer's jurisdiction. For example, she said, migrant farm workers,
most of whom are Hispanic, could claim that policies prohibiting
them from buying a house are really a smokescreen for racial
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a difficult situation for the seller,'' Ms. Barlow
said. ``I'm not saying that they would lose. But it's an obvious
connection for the jury. The seller would have to show some kind of
legitimate business reason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
