<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLOMBIAN-GANG-560&AMP;AD     09-11 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIAN-GANG-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLING OF EX-DETECTIVE IS LINKED TO GANG ON NATIONWIDE ROBBERY
SPREE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., N.J.. Mass., Calif., Ohio)  (js) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The gunmen who ambushed and killed a retired police
detective outside a Bronx meatpacking company two weeks ago are
members of Colombian gang linked to more than 50 brazen armed
robberies of jewelers and other businesses in six states,
investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   The key to linking the cases was an address book found in the
pocket of one of the men, Fernando Colorado, 28, who was killed in
the Bronx attack, investigators said. The addresses led the
investigators to the homes of Colorado's partners in Brooklyn and
Queens, where detectives seized evidence that linked the group to
at least four years of violent cross-country crime sprees,
according to a racketeering indictment. The indictment of 11
suspected members of the group was unsealed Friday in U.S. Court in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects are the subjects of a manhunt coordinated by dozens
of New York detectives, agents of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration and local law enforcement officials in Miami, where
the gunmen are believed to have fled immediately after the killing
of the retired detective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will pursue these people wherever they go,'' Howard Safir,
the New York City police commissioner, said in an interview on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The seized evidence includes handguns, fake passports and
drivers' licenses, fake police gear, bulletproof vests, police
scanners, walkie-talkies, surveillance cameras and other
communications equipment, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sophisticated robbery group,'' Safir said.
Federal investigators said that some members traveled to Colombia
for plastic surgery to alter their fingerprints and their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the gang was responsible for armed robberies
in New York, New Jersey, Massachusetts, California, Florida and
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   One of the crimes occurred on a late afternoon in midtown
Manhattan in February 1996, when several men wearing knit caps and
carrying guns ambushed and wounded a Hong Kong jeweler outside the
Hilton New York, shooting him in the chest and stealing a duffel
bag containing $1.2 million worth of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   The police found the robbers' abandoned car nearby on West 51st
Street, but then the trail went cold.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial clue turned up on Aug. 27, when the police say at
least eight heavily armed men surrounded a car in the Bronx. The
gunmen held up the retired detective, Donald E. Pagani Sr., and his
cousin, who were headed to a local bank with $52,000 from the
company, which is owned by the Pagani family.
</P>
<P>
   But the robbery was thwarted when Pagani opened fire with his
.38-caliber revolver and killed Colorado as the others fled.
</P>
<P>
   Pagani, 69, of Peekskill, N.Y., was killed in the shootout. But
investigators said the fatal shot he fired at Colorado helped to
break the case. The notebook found on Colorado listed the aliases
and telephone numbers of people whom the authorities suspect are
gang members.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they are looking for six people in connection
with the killing of Pagani: Alex Restrepo, 25; Nelson Baez, 25;
Jorge Garcia, 34; Carlos Gonzalez, 39; Nicholas Coronel, 17, and
Paola Restrepo, 25.
</P>
<P>
   Five other suspected gang members _ Julian Tamayo, Edison
Santiago Cordova, Wilson Izasa, Pepe Mirand and Carlos Torres _
were also named in the indictment. Except for Mirand, who is 36,
their ages were not given.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mabel Restrepo, 23, the sister of Alex and Paola, was arrested
by detectives on Sept. 1 in New York. She is being held without
bail on second-degree murder charges in the killing of Pagani, but
was not named in the racketeering indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian gang had caught the attention of Federal law
enforcement authorities long before the killing of Pagani.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group have been able to escape capture by using
fake passports and expensive technology, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group have used fake passports to travel to
regions of Colombia and other South American countries that are in
chaos because of government corruption, making it easier for them
to avoid detection by the authorities in the United States,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   According to interviews with law enforcement officials and the
criminal complaint filed in U.S. Court on Sept. 3, investigators
believe that the group's usual tactic was to case a location
anywhere from a couple of hours to a couple of weeks before a
well-choreographed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, a group of armed gunmen, wearing ski masks and
bulletproof vests, would surround their victims, as backup gunmen,
armed with high-powered automatic weapons, waited in getaway
vehicles, the authorities said. The group is also suspected in
robberies of drug suppliers and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   In May, two members of the group were arrested on charges of
stealing more than $500,000 in jewels from a Kay Jewelers store in
Union County, N.J. They used false identification to get released
on $50,000 in bail. They failed to appear in court, then fled,
according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they suspect that Alex Restrepo, who grew up
in New York, is the leader of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Sean O'Toole, the commanding officer of the Bronx Homicide
Task Force and coordinator of the investigation, said that ``when
they saw news broadcasts that they had killed a retired police
detective, they knew it was time to flee.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, Interpol and the federal Immigration and Naturalization
Service are also involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that if the suspects make it overseas he will seek
assistance from federal officials to extradite them, although doing
so might be difficult in Colombia and other similar countries.
Safir added that under federal law, ``we, as law enforcement, could
certainly go to other countries and forcibly return these
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they were confident that they were close to
capturing them because of informers who have turned on gang members
and information that has been obtained about their contacts in the
United States and overseas. In more than one way, officials said,
the killing of Pagani was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Pagani, who had been on the police force for 27
years, struck a particularly sharp chord in the New York Police
Department, where his son is a lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Pagani's family have offered a
$50,000 reward for information leading to the capture and
successful prosecution of the suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NY-VIEQUES-HNS &LR;      09-11 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY POLITICIANS RALLY TO END TARGET PRACTICE ON VIEQUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in the ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York city council member Adolpho Carrion Jr. on
Saturday urged New York City's 900,000 Puerto Ricans to build on
their success winning presidential clemency for imprisoned Puerto
Rican nationalists to press for the withdrawal of the U.S. Navy's
``occupying force'' from the island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real fundamental issue that the leader of the free
world has fought colonialism and marched around the world to free
societies and create democracies but still has a little colony in
Vieques,'' Carrion, D-Bronx, told an informal hearing in City Hall.
``This must be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrion spoke as part of a campaign by some New York City
political leaders to persuade President Clinton that the U.S. Navy
and the Marines should permanently end their use of the Puerto
Rican island of Vieques for target practice.
</P>
<P>
   Five Democratic members of the 51-member New York City Council,
two Democrats in the state legislature and Deputy New York Mayor
Ninfa Segarra, a Democrat serving Republican New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, spoke at the City Hall hearing on the future of military
training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military's target range has been a long-term political
issue in Puerto Rico but became an emotional focal point last April
when a Marine Corps' bombing mishap killed a Puerto Rican contract
security guard and injured four others. Since then, the range has
been occupied by protesters and the Navy has suspended target
practice pending a top level review.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of New York's Puerto Rican community said they are
hoping to persuade both First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Giuliani, her most likely election rival, to join their cause. Both
Mrs. Clinton and the mayor are weighing possible campaigns to
succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Giuliani nor Mrs. Clinton has taken a public position on
the future military use of Vieques, pending the outcome of a review
by a Pentagon panel appointed at the request of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Segarra, Giuliani's deputy mayor for education and human
services, said the mayor has discussed the issue with Defense
Secretary William Cohen. Segarra said the City Hall hearing and
other steps to mobilize public opinion behind demands that the Navy
leave Vieques is ``a way for all of us to put down the mark that we
are a growing political force in this city and state,'' adding:
``We intend to be listened to and we intend to have our issues
debated.''
</P>
<P>
   Political pressure on the White House is likely to mount in
coming days. City Council member Victor Robles, majority whip on
the Democratic-controlled council, said the 51-member council will
approve a resolution Monday calling for the phased Navy withdrawal
from the island bombing range that has been used by the Pentagon
since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Nine city councilors plan to travel to Vieques next week to
conduct public hearings with some of the island's 9,300 civilian
residents.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilor Jose Rivera, wearing a T-shirt proclaiming in
Spanish, that ``All Puerto Ricans are with Vieques,'' said some
members of the city council delegation may temporarily join
demonstrators who are acting as ``human shields'' on the 899-acre
bombing range to prevent resumption of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has suspended target practice and military maneuvers on
the island pending a decision by the president that is expected
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican political leaders are making headway in their
efforts to broaden political support for their campaign to get the
Navy to withdraw from Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilor Walter L. McCaffrey, D-Queens, gratefully
recalled at the hearing that Puerto Rican members of the city
council supported Irish-American politicians' efforts to win
freedom for Irish nationalists imprisoned in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand with you,'' McCaffrey declared. ``With you, we are
one.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilor John D. Sabini, whose district includes the
Jackson Heights and Elmhurst neighborhoods of Queens, said his
district has far more residents who are not American citizens than
does Puerto Rico, where the 3.8 million residents are U.S. citizens
by birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet the concept of the military doing target practice in my
district would be laughable,'' Sabini said. ``We don't use our land
and our people as fodder for practicing our bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the political leaders later traveled to a community
college in the South Bronx to watch a videotaped presentation of
Navy bomb damage on Vieques and a performance by Choco Orota, a
prominent female singer from Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leader Jesse Jackson and Puerto Rico's Catholic
archbishop, Roberto Gonzalez, planned to conduct an ecumenical
prayer service on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Efrain Gonzalez Jr., D-Bronx, said he expected the
end of the month-long controversy over presidential clemency for
the Puerto Rican nationalists would help raise the profile of the
dispute over Vieques, a 33,000-acre island that was seized along
with Puerto Rico by the United States in the Spanish-American War
in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can all focus on the issue we all agree on _ getting
the Navy out of Vieques,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of 16 Puerto Rican nationalists offered clemency by the
president on Aug. 11 were freed earlier this week. Mrs. Clinton
called for the White House offer of clemency to be rescinded three
weeks after the prisoners had not responded to the gesture,
angering many in the Puerto Rican community.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0191 </DOCNO>
