during his semifinal victory over No. 3 seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia at the U.S. Open on Saturday. Agassi shook off a miserable
first-set performance to win, 1-6, 6-3, 6-3, 6-3 and reach the
championship round here for the fourth time in his career; he will
play for the title Sunday against Todd Martin, who defeated Cedric
Pioline in the other semifinal. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MIAMI -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- AFTER-MAS-CANOSA, 09-11 --
Almost two years after the death of the undisputed head of Miami's
Cuban exile community, Jorge Mas Canosa, a void in leadership
remains. The most obvious successor, Mas' American-born son, Jorge
Mas Santos, is seen by many as too young, at 36, and he has the
all-but-impossible job of living up to his father's legacy as
foundation chairman. ``My goal is not to walk in my father's
footsteps, but to extend those footsteps,'' he says. (Bill
Cooke/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MURFREESBORO, Tenn. -- Sept. 11, 1999 --
