<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 09/11/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-12, 09-11 -- A
jubilant Serena Williams of the United States holds aloft the
trophy signifying her first Grand Slam singles title after having
defeated top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland at the U.S. Open on
Saturday. Williams, the No. 7 seed, avenged sister Venus' semifinal
loss to Hingis with a straight set win, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4). (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-11, 09-11 --
No. 7 seed Serena Williams of the United States can hardly believe
that she has won the women's singles final against top seed Martina
Hingis of Switzerland at the U.S. Open on Saturday. Williams
avenged sister Venus' semifinal loss to Hingis with a straight set
win, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), to capture her first Grand Slam singles title.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-10, 09-11 --
Top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland lunges for a backhand
against against No. 7 seed Serena Williams of the United States
during the women's singles final at the U.S. Open on Saturday.
Williams avenged sister Venus' semifinal loss with a straight set
win, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), to capture her first Grand Slam singles title.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-9, 09-11 -- No.
7 seed Serena Williams of the United States during the women's
singles final against top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland at the
U.S. Open on Saturday. Hingis had beaten Serena's sister, Venus,
the previous day to set up the championship match. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- GUN-OWNERS-REVIEW-4,
09-11 -- Usha, of Los Angeles, bought a gun five years ago ``for my
protection.'' She goes to a range for target practice. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- GUN-OWNERS-REVIEW-3,
09-11 -- Jim and Elise of the Washington area with shotguns in the
living room of their home. The debate over gun rights continues in
Congress, in statehouses and in the federal courts. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DENVER -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- GUN-OWNERS-REVIEW-2, 09-11
-- Jayme of Denver recently won two gold medals at the Pan American
Games in Winnipeg. She became interested in target shooting at a
summer camp when she was 14. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MIDDLETOWN, N.Y. -- Sept. 11, 1999 --
GUN-OWNERS-REVIEW-1, 09-11 -- Tyrone, top left, a Middletown
grocer, owns 20 guns ``because of the fun they can bring.'' His
uncle, Jerome, top right, Jerome's son, Devin, bottom right, and
Tyrone's son, Alex, enjoy guns too. There are about 240 million
guns in the United States, according to federal estimates, a total
that gives the nation one of the highest per-capita rates of gun
ownership in the world. (Lonnie Schlein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) MENDOZA, Argentina -- Sept. 11, 1999 --
ARGENTINA-POLITICS, 09-11 -- Domingo Cavallo posing in a stereo
store in Mendoza, apparently with the youth vote in mind. If
economics is the dismal science, then Cavallo, the former economy
minister credited with whipping Argentina's hyperinflation in the
early 1990s, is the dismal third-party candidate in the
presidential election here next month. (Horacio Paone/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. -- Sept. 11, 1999 --
WILDERNESS-REVIEW, 09-11 -- As the population expands, people and
animals are more likely to cross paths. At Yellowstone National
Park, visitors pose for a photograph near a bison. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- CLEMENCY-REVIEW, 09-11
-- Presidential pens are regularly used to sign bills into law.
Rarely for pardons. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-8, 09-11 -- No.
2 seed Andre Agassi of the United States leaps into a forehand
during his semifinal victory over No. 3 seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia at the U.S. Open on Saturday. Agassi shook off a miserable
first-set performance to win, 1-6, 6-3, 6-3, 6-3 and reach the
championship round here for the fourth time in his career; he will
play for the title Sunday against Todd Martin, who defeated Cedric
Pioline in the other semifinal. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MIAMI -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- AFTER-MAS-CANOSA, 09-11 --
Almost two years after the death of the undisputed head of Miami's
Cuban exile community, Jorge Mas Canosa, a void in leadership
remains. The most obvious successor, Mas' American-born son, Jorge
Mas Santos, is seen by many as too young, at 36, and he has the
all-but-impossible job of living up to his father's legacy as
foundation chairman. ``My goal is not to walk in my father's
footsteps, but to extend those footsteps,'' he says. (Bill
Cooke/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MURFREESBORO, Tenn. -- Sept. 11, 1999 --
FORD-POLLUTION-FIGHT, 09-11 -- C. Mark Pickrell insists that he
sees many parallels between his former legal work defending a large
cigarette company against anti-smoking lawsuits and his current
legal situation, where he is is representing a one-man Internet
newsletter against a lawsuit filed by Ford Motor Co. ``As I look at
it, I keep saying, 'It's like tobacco.' `` says Pickrell, 33.
(Chris Berkey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 1999 --
GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-REVIEW-B&AMP;W, 09-11 -- Hitler, in a well-guarded
motorcade, reviewing his troops and his public in 1935. ``The
current instrumentalization and trivialization of the Holocaust in
the United States are a terrible mistake,'' says historian Fritz
Stern. ``Details do matter.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-7, 09-11 -- No.
2 seed Andre Agassi of the United States reacts to his semifinal
victory over No. 3 seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia at the U.S.
Open on Saturday. Agassi shook off a miserable first-set
performance and rallied to win, 1-6, 6-3, 6-3, 6-3 to reach the
championship round here for the fourth time in his career; he will
play for the title Sunday against Todd Martin, who defeated Cedric
Pioline in the other semifinal. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ABUJA, Nigeria -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- NIGERIA-CAPITAL-2,
09-11 -- The balcony of Suleiman Isyaku's house in Abuja will be
his study as he tackles an unexpected workload as a House of
Representatives member. Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation, has
ended nearly 16 years of military rule, and its politicians have
plunged into the new system with typical Nigerian spirit: headlong,
combatively and with a reserve of jaw-dropping surprises.
(Norimitsu Onishi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ABUJA, Nigeria -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- NIGERIA-CAPITAL-1,
09-11 -- Nigeria's House of Representatives is unfinished but
Suleiman Isyaku, a new member, is on the job, three months after
the military left power. Once the dormant capital of a nation ruled
by decrees quietly issued and then rigidly enforced by Nigeria's
military rulers, Abuja is abuzz with the noisy workings of
representative government. (Norimitsu Onishi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- CONGRESS-2000-B&AMP;W, 09-11
-- Sherrod Brown is among the representatives House leaders have
pressured to seek re-election. Brown recalls how he was wooed by
Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Senate Democratic leader, and
Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.: ``Torricelli and Daschle were very
persuasive. They made the case of everything from quality of life
in the Senate to that I would be one of 100'' members instead of
one of 435 in the House. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SEATTLE -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- GATES-SENIOR-PROFILE-2,
09-11 -- William H. Gates Jr., co-chairman of the Gates Foundation,
with family photos at his home in Seattle. With more donations
expected, the Gates Foundation is virtually certain soon to surpass
the Wellcome Trust in Britain as the largest philanthropic
organization in the world. (Dan Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SEATTLE -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- GATES-SENIOR-PROFILE-1,
09-11 -- William H. Gates Jr., 73, oversees the Gates Foundation,
his son's $17 billion philanthropy. Gates' philanthropic duties
with the foundation, for which he receives an annual salary of
$90,000, grew out of a conversation a few years ago with his son
and daughter-in-law during a night out at the movies. (Dan
Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-6, 09-11 -- No.
