<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8647 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-PIAZZA-LADN     09-11 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PIAZZA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REGRETS FOR PIAZZA, PLENTY FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Piazza is attempting to focus on the road ahead, on driving
the promising Mets to the postseason. But there is Los Angeles
honking in his rear-view mirror, tailgating and swerving, its
headlights blaring.
</P>
<P>
   He's forced to look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be a professional and turn the page,'' Piazza
said, opting for another analogy. ``I don't think anybody goes
through life without any regrets. Things happen for a reason. But
I'm a Met now, and that's what I'm thinking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and their fans, meanwhile, are left to contemplate a
meaningless season _ and wonder about what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will end the decade without so much as a playoff
victory. By their standards, it was a decade of mediocrity. But
with Piazza, at least they were close. They made the playoffs, even
though they were swept by the Reds and Braves. They contended for
the division, even if they were a player or two short and faded in
the final two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 16 months after trading Piazza to Florida for Gary
Sheffield and four other players, the Dodgers are much more than a
player or two away from contending. The Piazza trade began a period
of organizational flux that has yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's impact with the Dodgers was as deep as a meteor crater,
and it hasn't been filled.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had their star in Piazza. Sure, he wasn't the
rah-rah clubhouse leader. He wasn't the greatest defensive catcher.
He fought with the club over his contract.
</P>
<P>
   But he was the ultimate Dodger. The grandson of Tommy Lasorda.
And he had the legendary origins too, drafted in the 62nd round as
a personal favor to Piazza's father, Vince.
</P>
<P>
   He became their handsome icon, their magnetic star, the focus of
their lineup _ and their marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They built this team around him,'' said Sheffield, ``and when
he left, the team didn't know how to react.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tried to replace him with Kevin Brown. They tried
with Todd Hundley and Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   All they got were F-bombs and cold stares.
</P>
<P>
   How many fans honestly feel they identify with Brown? If you
don't dislike him for his $105 million contract, then his cold and
colorless personality does plenty to turn you off.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sheffield, he's an explosive player, and not a bad guy
either. But he doesn't have Piazza's charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield wasn't witness to the Piazza era. He was one of five
players the Dodgers acquired from Florida in a salary-dumping deal
for Piazza and Todd Zeile on May 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield has seen the team maneuver wildly since that
trade, changing thr front office, casting off players and signing
new ones, only careening all the more out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, what I've experienced in this clubhouse, I can
understand some of the reasons why he left,'' Sheffield said,
declining to elaborate on those reasons. ``If he wanted to be a
Dodger, he'd be a Dodger. But he couldn't find what he wanted here,
so he went somewhere else to find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it looks like he's found it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the money, Piazza turned down $87 million from the
Dodgers and signed with the Mets for $91 million _ a negligible
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves one thing to me,'' Sheffield said. ``It proves he
didn't want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his reasons for leaving, Piazza is having a blast
in New York. After a rocky introduction, he has them poised to make
the playoffs, dethroning the Atlanta Braves in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Even playing in front of the most ravenous media contingent in
the country, Piazza feels less pressure with the Mets' ensemble
cast. The Mets infield _ Olerud, Ventura, Alfonzo and Rey Ordonez _
was on the cover of last week's Sports Illustrated. Not Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let that one go,'' he said, flashing that poster-boy
smile. ``I've had four SI covers already.''
</P>
<P>
   It's painfully obvious that many Dodgers fans still haven't
absolved themselves of Piazza worship. There have been more jerseys
with his old No.31 in the Chavez Ravine stands this weekend than
for any current Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   He was ruefully booed by many fans, who loathe him for turning
down $87 million. But he was gleefully cheered by a good portion of
the rest, who remember only the opposite-field homers and the
shampoo commercials.
</P>
<P>
   They clearly think more about him than he does of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my time here,'' Piazza said. ``But I've moved on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
