<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEION, PRIMETIME FORGE UNIQUE REPORTING APPROACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEION SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders' column, as told to staff
writer Clarence E. Hill Jr., will appear in the ''Fort Worth
Star-Telegram ``every Sunday during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   As I sit contemplating about which subject I should speak on, so
many issues come to mind that I want to tackle immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I did say tackle. I can do that.
</P>
<P>
   The media and its ways are things I personally don't totally
understand. And the media doesn't totally understand the athlete in
some cases either.
</P>
<P>
   But we need each other to achieve certain things, so why can't
we just get along. Though there are many reasons, I'll elaborate on
just a few.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the athlete nor the media spend enough time trying to
truly understand and walk in each other's shoes, which could enable
both parties to see issues through the others' perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Culture and background also play major roles in this
misunderstanding. Being from different backgrounds sometimes makes
us susceptible to both stereotyping and generalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes must also understand that the media is under pressure
to meet a deadline to report or write a story. There is no time for
mood swings, sudden shyness or amnesia when push comes to shove.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the media and I have had sort of a use-use type
of relationship. I used them and they used me. Talk about
dysfunction. We dissed each other, but we both went on to function
well.
</P>
<P>
   Since I'm now part of the media, I've come up with a solution
for a wonderful working relationship between me and the media.
</P>
<P>
   I'll interview myself. This way both parties can be satisfied
without the unnecessary pressures of the obstacles stated above.
</P>
<P>
   I was deemed so controversial and misunderstood because there
was 2 in 1 _ Deion and Primetime all in one body (No. 21, get it).
There is Deion whom you see everyday, but when the whistle blows,
it's Primetime showing up on game day.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the next few months, I will discuss a variety
of issues in my column. I will talk about stuff people don't like
to talk about. I want people to understand the athlete and also
give you a clearer view of who Deion/Primetime is.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Deion will interview Primetime, and sometimes
Primetime will interview Deion. But it's always going to be real.
</P>
<P>
   We are going to start with Deion interviewing Primetime and shed
some light on the surgically repaired great left toe.
</P>
<P>
   DS: So what's up with the toe?
</P>
<P>
   PT: It's healing fine, maybe even ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   DS: When you initially injured it in the game against Arizona
last year, did you ever imagine it would warrant surgery?
</P>
<P>
   PT: Not in a million years. I've never had an injury this
serious in my 10-year career. I thought the pain would just go away
or that it would heal on its own. It was just a toe, and like most
people, I didn't think it was that big of a deal. But each day when
I woke up and stepped out of bed, the pain was still there and
growing more intense every day.
</P>
<P>
   DS: Were you ever frustrated?
</P>
<P>
   PT: There were times I wanted to play during my injury last
season, and I wanted the trainers to inject my toe \Rto numb it\S
so I would be able to play. But they refused to do so because the
risk factor of further damage to the toe was so great.
</P>
<P>
   DS: But in the playoff game you injected it. What was the
difference?
</P>
<P>
   PT: I was healing to the point that doctors cleared me to have
the shot. Besides, it was the playoffs and the purpose for the
whole season is the playoffs and the Super Bowl. It's all or
nothing at that point. However, that didn't happen and as a result
of injecting my toe I had to be rushed to hospital at 4 a.m. due to
excessive swelling and pain. I thought to myself, ``you are so
stupid, who really cares besides your family.''
</P>
<P>
   DS: Surgery _ why did you wait so long?
</P>
<P>
   PT: We, the Cowboys, doctors and myself, wanted to give it every
chance to heal and we did. Actually, I was in the complex doing
aerobics in the off-season when I realized that this thing wasn't
healing. I knew I needed to do something and that's when I took it
to the trainers and said maybe we should explore the possibility of
going to see a doctor. Two days later we went to a specialist in
Carolina. The specialist looked me in my eye and said this is so
rare you may never play again. Then we went to New York to see the
main guy \R Dr. Bill Hamilton\S, who ended up doing the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   DS: Were you nervous or scared?
</P>
<P>
   PT: Not at all. I understood the risk involved. The doctors said
that I might not play gain. I said, ``I understand, but God said
that no weapon formed against me shall prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   DS: Did you worry that the injury might have prevented you from
getting a contract extension from the Cowboys and force you to play
somewhere else, especially considering that you love the North
Texas area so much that you are building a new home in Prosper?
</P>
<P>
   PT: No, because I can play. Not only can I play, but I can play
this game real good. So why would I worry when 30 other teams would
want me? Besides, if I would have had to leave, it would have been
the Lord's will. He would have made it wonderful somewhere else.
But this is going to be my home no matter where I play.
</P>
<P>
   DS: Does it bother you to hear the constant skepticism from
people who say, ``It's just a toe, you aren't really hurt, you're
faking, you didn't really need surgery, you're not tough, why did
they pay you so much when they don't know you can play?''
</P>
<P>
   PT: No, because success comes with that. I could answer every
accusation like, ``Oh sure, I planned my wedding with surgery in
mind. I really wanted to limp down the aisle with a cane and drop
my beautiful bride trying to carry her over the threshold, and I
really wanted to take five weeks off during one of the best seasons
of my career while a long-term contract was at risk.'' I could go
on but why? What people think of me doesn't confuse me with what I
think of myself. I know who, what, where and why I am and I know
where I'm going and how to get there. I know it's not possible to
please God and man, so I chose to please God and pray for man.
</P>
<P>
   DS: Will you play today against the Redskins?
</P>
<P>
   PT: I want to but...
</P>
<P>
   DS: But what? Don't you feel an obligation to your team and the
fans?
</P>
<P>
   PT: Yes, that's why there's a but. Fans, along with my
teammates, want and deserve to see the best product a team has to
offer. But right now, I can't give them that. Though it still may
be good, it's not the best. I can't imagine you buying a can of
Pepsi half full or a cake with two slices missing and be satisfied.
You all deserve that can and cake dish to be full and I want to be
able to give you the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   DS: Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   PT: Yes, I'd like to answer questions from the fans. Beginning
next week, e-mail your questions to chill\nstar-telegram.com and I
will answer at least one each week.
</P>
<P>
   DS: Jesus loves you!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
