<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARMY-WAKE-FOREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE FOREST FINDS ITS LEGS AT ARMY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Army and Wake Forest, the teams with the best
and worst rushing attacks in Division I-A last season, met Saturday
at Michie Stadium, and the one with 1998's least potent ground game
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest, which averaged only 65.4 yards a game rushing last
season, Saturday had a much bigger and more experienced offensive
line, and the best runner in Morgan Kane, to give the Deacons a
34-15 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Kane _ a senior fullback from Ottawa and the only returning
backfield starter from last season's 3-8 team _ gained 211 yards on
32 carries, including two touchdown runs of 10 and 46 yards. Wake
Forest managed something few teams do, outgaining the Cadets on the
ground, 320 to 282 yards. Army averaged 293.8 yards a game in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Army kept it close through the first three quarters before a
crowd of 29,646. The Cadets drew within 10-9 at the end of the
first half when Matt Parker kicked his third field goal, a
48-yarder. Then, with Wake Forest ahead, 17-9, the Cadets scored
their lone touchdown, a 9-yard pass from quarterback Joe Gerena to
Grady Jett, with 4 minutes 52 seconds left in the third quarter.
But Gerena's pass for a 2-point conversion was knocked down in the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   That ended the Cadets' scoring. On Wake Forest's next two
possessions Army proved vulnerable on big plays, as it had so often
last season when the Cadets were 3-8, losing three games by a total
of nine points.
</P>
<P>
   First, Kane bolted up the middle for a 46-yard touchdown 2:47
into the fourth quarter. On the Deacons' next possession,
quarterback Ben Sankey raced 20 yards for Wake Forest's final
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some great opportunities, but didn't take advantage,''
Army coach Bob Sutton said after the game. In the first half, the
Cadets got inside the Wake Forest 20-yard line three times but
scored only two field goals. The Cadets also failed to take
advantage of a fumble recovery at the Wake Forest 37-yard line in
the third quarter. And early in the fourth quarter the Cadets drove
to the Deacons' 39 but a Gerena pass was intercepted at the 5-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't convert when we could have,'' Sutton said. ``And we
let a team that doesn't run well run the ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
