<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES GO WITH THE FLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Braves' remarkable success despite critical
injuries can be traced to their ability to make adjustments in
difficult situations.
</P>
<P>
   For four months, they used either Walt Weiss or Ozzie Guillen as
leadoff men, with dismal results.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, they switched to left fielder Gerald Williams , and
the results have been astounding. In the first 31 games, they went
24-7 and Williams had 19 RBI, 25 runs and nine steals.
</P>
<P>
   He has become the first true leadoff hitter for the Braves since
Marquis Grissom was traded in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' getting on base has helped Chipper Jones develop into
a very strong MVP candidate. He has more than 100 RBI for the
fourth consecutive year and has reached 40 homers for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the key piece that we have needed all year,''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan said. ``We needed a boost in the second half and he
gave it to us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big numbers
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which appears to have withstood the Giants' final
charge, has a good chance to have four players with 100 RBI and
four with 100 runs. Matt Williams is already there in RBI and Luis
Gonzalez and Jay Bell could reach it by the weekend. Steve Finley,
who had to cut his own free-agent deal last winter, has 29 homers
and 91 RBI. Bell, Gonzalez and Tony Womack already have scored 100
runs, with Williams closing in. The National League record for
having players reach those numbers is six, by the Dodgers in 1953.
This year's team still does not have anyone with 100 RBI or runs
scored. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red-hot Reds
</P>
<P>
   With nine homers last Saturday and five more the next day,
Cincinnati set a major-league record and kept alive its hopes in
the wild-card race. But the Reds' best hitter all year, Sean Casey,
has not joined in the fun. Reds manager Jack McKeon benched him
twice this past week, hoping to take off some of the pressure. When
McKeon did it in August, Casey responded by hitting .528 (19 for
36) during the next nine games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A little history
</P>
<P>
   An upside to the Cubs being so bad is that they now are battling
Florida and Montreal for the No. 1 pick in next year's draft. The
last time the Cubs had the first overall pick was in 1982 when they
took their former longtime shortstop
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Dunston. While it is too soon to know about 1999 pick Ben
Christensen, the 1998 draft was good for the Cubs. They took high
school outfielder Corey Patterson,
</P>
<P>
   who batted .320 with 20 homers, 35 doubles, 72 extra-base hits
and 31 stolen bases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life after Leyland
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jim Leyland has decided to step down to spend more time
with his family, the Colorado Rockies are looking for a manager and
general manager. The candidates are lining up. The interviews for
GM have begun with Rockies exec Gary Hughes believed to be the
early front-runner. Cleveland assistant GM Dan O'Dowd also has been
in, but the Yankees denied Colorado permission to talk to Mark
Newman. As for manager, Phil Garner has a good chance. But a
sleeper candidate is Oakland's Art Howe, who has the A's in an
unlikely wild-card race. Howe was a hitting instructor in Colorado
under Don Baylor and is a personal favorite of owner Jerry
McMorris'. Howe was the runner-up last year when Leyland took the
job. By the way, Leyland walks away from $4.5 million remaining on
his three-year, $6 million contract. Leyland also had $500,000
deferred from each year of the contract. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
