</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTSTEPS GROW LOUDER AS RED SOX EDGE YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideki Irabu glanced toward right field to watch a
ball zooming into the seats Saturday for a home run and then
quickly turned away and gazed at the grass. Irabu trudged behind
the mound, raised his arms up high as if he was doing jumping jacks
and then arched his back. It was only the second inning and Irabu
looked like the poster pitcher for exasperation. He was not alone.
</P>
<P>
   The day started and finished in exasperating fashion for the New
York Yankees, who mixed in some exhilarating moments to counter
their frustration before tumbling to the Boston Red Sox, 11-10, at
Yankee Stadium. The Yankees can see, feel and hear the Red Sox
creeping up on them after another loss, a loss in which the Yankees
staged three teasing comebacks only to end up lamenting a sloppy
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When is the last time the Yankees felt this uncertain? Maybe
earlier this season there were stray doubts, but the Yankees have
been in first place for 96 straight days, and things are never as
serious in April as they are in September. The Red Sox, who have
sounded content to try for the wild-card berth, have made the
Yankees nervous after chiseling the Yankees' lead in the American
League East to 4 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's erratic pitching put the Yankees in a perilous position
and caused Joe Torre to replace him after two innings, Nomar
Garciaparra slugged two of the Red Sox' five homers, and Chuck
Knoblauch was booed after he committed another critical error which
led to Garciaparra's three-run homer. General manager Brian Cashman
spoke with a concerned George Steinbrenner by telephone on Friday
night and surely fielded another call Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always alarmed and I'm always looking over my shoulder to
see who is there,'' Steinbrenner said by telephone. ``People say
all you have to do is one of the next two and you're still up by
five and a half, but I don't think that way. We've got to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   It is premature for the Yankees to panic because they would have
to collapse totally in the last 21 games to miss the postseason,
but they do need to end a streak in which they have lost 7 of 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   For better or for worse, Roger Clemens, once an icon in Boston,
will try to prevent a massacre of sorts in the Bronx Sunday as the
Red Sox push for the three-game sweep. It will be up to Clemens to
quiet the brash Red Sox fans who have shocked some Yankees with
their rising decibel level and even by unveiling a derogatory
Yankee banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sense any tension or panic mode,'' David Cone said.
``I do sense there is a little bit of urgency in tomorrow's game.
Doing the math is pretty easy. It's five and a half or three and a
half. It's a big swing game.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees had won one of the first two games against the
Red Sox, they could relax a bit Sunday. No one is relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to come out and win tomorrow's game,'' Darryl
Strawberry said. ``We put ourselves in a tough situation. It's been
comfortable most of the year for this club. Now it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are uncomfortable despite comebacks Saturday from a
5-0 hole anda 9-4 deficit and almost from an 11-8 disadvantage.
Paul O'Neill's three-run homer highlighted a four-run outburst in
the fourth inning, but it came off Mark Portugal. Portugal is 0-6
with a 7.18 earned run average against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Another four-run splurge, in the seventh, was boosted by three
Boston errors. Finally, after Butch Huskey's two-run, pinch-hit
homer off Mike Stanton in the eighth increased the Red Sox' lead to
11-8, Tino Martinez hit a towering two-run shot that nearly scraped
the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Rod Beck retired Bernie Williams with the potential
tying run on first to end the game, Irabu had failed the Yankees
and angered Torre. Irabu walked the first two batters (both
scored), and he allowed four runs in two innings. Torre did not let
Irabu see the third, and the Yankees never recovered as their
bullpen also fizzled. The Yankees gave up nine walks and 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need our starter to give us a chance to win every time we
send him out there,'' Torre said. ``Walking the first two guys is
not the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu, who has allowed 29 earned runs in his last 35 innings,
would not address Torre's decision. When Irabu was asked if he
would have pitched better if he had stayed in the game, he simply
said, ``I wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   But the concern for the Yankees goes beyond Irabu. They must
regroup and survive September before they can thrive in October.
The postseason looms, but the Yankees were exasperated Saturday.
The Red Sox are within four and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's pressure, so what?'' Torre said. ``We have to deal
with pressure every day here anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
