<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS OFFENSE HAS THE MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a slow-go kind of summer for the Cowboys. Missing
football pieces were scattered from here to Wichita Falls. For a
while, it appeared Chan Gailey was impersonating a shade-tree
mechanic, with engine parts strewed across his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, meaning an assortment of injuries, The Theatre
of the Toe, and that one ongoing suspension, Gailey kept saying,
``we aren't where we need to be, but we've still got time to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Chan. Time's up.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Cowboys kick off their 40th NFL season today in
Washington, there is basically no excuse for this team not to have
its motor running.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, all pieces are in place, particularly on
offense. And since the NFL of today is a league based on offense,
and since Gailey was originally hired as head coach to bring back
offensive RPMs, well ...
</P>
<P>
   Show us what you've got, Mr. Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   The no-longer-hated Redskins remain a suspect defensive club,
still void of run-stoppers _ as they were last season; plus there's
a lot of single coverage in the secondary _ just what receivers and
quarterbacks love to see.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, the Cowboys died last December because of offensive
meltdown. But Gailey and owner Jerry Jones addressed all that, and
offensive revival is expected to come in several areas. Up front,
the Cowboys had a makeover from tackle to tackle. Only Erik
Williams remains at the same line position he played in '98.
</P>
<P>
   But the largest hole was at receiver, and this could now be the
deepest, most talented area on the team. Beyond a healthy Ernie
Mills and new speed in Rocket Ismail, an unexpected bonus surfaced
at receiver. This rookie, Wane McGarity, is a ready-to-go-now
surprise, while second-year man Jeff Ogden has made the necessary
elevation from his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around the country have forgotten us; the Cowboys are
yesterday's news,'' said Michael Irvin, the senior member of the
receivers. ``But we've got a chance with this offense to be
remembered again, and feared again.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, of course, could have also been talking about himself _
remembered again, feared again. This is a pivotal season in the
long football life of Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch him,'' said quarterback Troy Aikman. ``Michael is going
to be Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Old-school football ... dynasty-days football, those are a
distant memory for the Cowboys. But the names haven't changed. It's
still The Trio. What Aikman does, what Emmitt Smith does, and to a
certain extent, what Irvin does, will determine how good the
offense can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling, and I think it's shared league-wide, is the two
ingredients you have to have are a great offensive mind as coach,
and a great quarterback,'' said owner Jones. ``In Chan, and in
Troy, I see us with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a Jerry dream, or reality?
</P>
<P>
   Also watch for one other offensive development _ tight end David
LaFleur. Privately, Valley Ranch optimism runneth over on LaFleur
becoming an impact offensive force. He's different from Jay
Novacek, with LaFleur being a strong blocker. But the Cowboys feel
LaFleur can become the receiving alternative missing since
Novacek's retirement.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, did anyone mention defense?
</P>
<P>
   I'v got three words for you:
</P>
<P>
   Trust in Campo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strength will be a group of hungry guys who like to run,''
defensive coordinator Dave Campo said Friday. ``We are missing some
veterans we hoped to have. But I don't make excuses. We can win
with what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Through training camp and the exhibition season, Campo mixed and
matched. He had a setback when Quentin Coryatt's physical problems
prevented the free agent from taking over at strong-side
linebacker. There was another minus when veteran cornerback Kevin
Smith went down with a still ailing back. Smith is not what he once
was, but was valuable for the secondary rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Than again, Campo wasn't planning on Leon Lett being around for
today _ and the suspended one won't be. Replacing Lett in the
defensive line isn't easy, but it's not the first time Campo has
had to move on indefinitely without Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the case of Nine-Toed Deion, who might or might not
appear today, at least on the field. More important, Deion did make
deadline as our new esteemed fellow columnist. He will be in charge
of the toe beat.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, however, now knows Deion is close _ if not today, then
next week. ``And for a long time, no one was sure how long it would
be,'' said Campo.
</P>
<P>
   While the defense needs Campo magic, the offense is ready. Just
how ready is what this season-opening intrigue is all about.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8669 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-RANDY-MOSS-TEX     09-11 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RANDY-MOSS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS' RANDY MOSS PLANS TO `WORK HARDER' FOR ENCORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, the hands. Randy Moss has hands so big that when he
extends them for a greeting you wonder if he's going to shake your
hand or just palm you altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the legs. Long, even for a guy who is 6-foot-4.
Kindergarteners drawing stick-figures don't scribble legs that
long.
</P>
<P>
   Big hands. Long legs. And what do you get ... man's best friend?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like throwing a Frisbee to a dog,'' Moss said of how he
uses his million-dollar talents. ``You throw a Frisbee to a dog,
and he's going to go get it. Like me. When you throw me the ball,
I'm going to react, and if I have to jump over a guy to get the
ball, I'm going to jump over a guy to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   After a rookie-of-the year season in which Moss made NFL
defensive backs dog-tired chasing him while he caught a
rookie-record 17 touchdowns, just one question remains: What can
Moss, the cocky, talented, opinionated Minnesota Vikings wide
receiver, do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I have to work harder to show that last year was no
fluke,'' Moss said as he sat on a bed in a lobby at the Vikings
training camp headquarters last month. ``The things I did were all
really expected from myself. I mean, 17 touchdowns! Heck, I did
that in college. ... Football is easy. The only difference between
the NFL and college is that in the NFL, you have grown men trying
to feed families and your job is to go out and make the other guy
look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons' secondary, which Moss and the Vikings face
today in the season opener, gets the first look at Year 2 of the
Randy Moss story. Moss has supplanted Jake Reed as the starter
opposite Cris Carter and will get more looks on first and second
down. Vikings coaches expect opponents to double-team Moss much
more in 1999 and put more of an emphasis on jamming the lanky
receiver at the line of scrimmage in order to keep him from running
free into the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Moss acknowledged that that kind of coverage frustrated him at
times last season but not enough to keep him from becoming a
first-team All Pro selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have problems with press coverage every now and
then,'' he said. ``But I wouldn't recommend for a coach to put his
cornerback on me one-on-one with no help, either. It's either a
catch, pass interference or a touchdown. Sometimes, it'll be a
drop. But probably about 95 percent of the time, it'll go to my
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   With Vikings quarterback Randall Cunningham's ability to throw
long, Moss did most of his damage running deep routes in 1998. He
averaged an NFC-leading 19 yards per catch and had a team-record 10
touchdown receptions of 40 yards or longer. Yet despite his success
the knock on him became: ``Yeah, but can he catch a pass over the
middle?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't ask him to run a lot of underneath things or catch a
lot of balls across the middle last year _ we felt the best thing
for him at that stage was to give him things he could do really
well to build confidence,'' Carter said. ``What he could do was
run, and he could play the ball well with his tremendous height and
speed advantage against most defensive backs. So he wasn't asked to
do more than that, and he didn't need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss contends he can run any pass route. He claims, in fact,
that he was run ragged by all the deep balls, and that an ankle
injury he suffered early in the season never completely healed
until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, \Rformer Vikings offensive coordinator Brian\S
Billick had me running too many \Rdeep\S routes,'' Moss said. ``I
ran them in practice, in training camp, and when it came toward the
end of the season, my body was really worn out by all those deep
balls. I was beat. \RNew offensive coordinator\S Ray Sherman came
in and told me, `Man, that's extra running.' So this year there's a
lot less deep balls in practice. Game time, I'll probably run
some.''
</P>
<P>
   The roster of cornerbacks who will try to undo Moss's run into
the record books include Atlanta's Ray Buchanan, Oakland's Charles
Woodson, and if healthy, the Cowboys' Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   With Sanders on the bench last Thanksgiving Day in the
Vikings-Cowboys' game, Moss caught three passes for 163 yards and
three touchdowns. Unwilling to talk about what he could have done
if Sanders played him and unwilling to relive his emotions about
the Cowboys' _ and 18 other teams' _ decision to pass him up on the
draft, Moss refused to talk to the media after that game. But on a
breezy day in Mankato, Minn., last month, Moss had no problems
opening up about playing against Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't look forward to playing Deion because I
practiced against him in the Pro Bowl,'' Moss said. ``I look
forward to playing anybody on Sunday, and the fact that it's Deion
Sanders makes no difference. I know how good he is, his style, how
quick he is, how fast he is. I know that. But I don't want to look
at him in that way because that'll probably get me carried away
from what I'm trying to do. If I know I've got a guy one-on-one,
that's going to get me excited because I've only got one man to
worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball is thrown, I plan on catching it _ no matter
who's on me.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
