A8670 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-JERRY-JONES-Q&AMP;A-T     09-11 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JERRY-JONES-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF OFFENSE ROLLS, JONES SEES SHOT AT SUPER BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Jones' second decade as Cowboys owner begins in earnest
today when the Cowboys play the Redskins in the season opener. He
remains unwavering in his optimism about his franchise. Jones
recently sat down with Star-Telegram reporter Clarence E. Hill Jr.
to discuss his first 10 years with the Cowboys, his outlook for the
coming season and his hopes for the future: S-T: What is the key to
the Cowboys success in 1999? JJ: ``We must move the football. If
that happens, that means we've developed the continuity we wanted
in the offensive line. That means that our tight end situation with
David LaFleur is sound. That means that quarterback Troy Aikman is
healthy and that backup running back Chris Warren is healthy.''
S-T: Are the Cowboys legitimate Super Bowl contenders? JJ: ``I
believe so. If we can sustain all the way through and have a good
December, we can definitely contend for the Super Bowl.'' S-T: You
were more active in the free-agent market this year than ever
before, signing three front-line players in center Mark Stepnoski,
receiver Raghib Ismail and linebacker Quentin Coryatt. Have you
changed your past philosophy of placing a higher premium on
re-signing your own free agents rather than outside free agents?
JJ: ``There was no philosophy change. These weren't hard calls. We
needed help at center. We wanted to improve our speed. I've always
addressed needs. ... Another significant free-agent year was when
we got Deion Sanders. Obviously, we wouldn't have done that in 1989
or 1990. But I thought it would help make a difference in a Super
Bowl.'' S-T: Are the Cowboys still the team to beat in the NFC
East? JJ: ``Considering how we played last year and we are
significantly better team this year, I like our chances.'' S-T:
What about the Cardinals, considering they beat you in the
playoffs? JJ: ``There is a perception Arizona is a young team on
the way up, and there is a perception that we are an older team
than we are. But I'm just looking at how we played last year,
looking at where we were in the games we played and looking at the
personnel. I like our quarterback. Arizona has a good quarterback.
But I like our quarterback. I like our running back and our
offensive and defensive lines. Where I feel pretty good about
things on a competitive basis is that I don't see us as a team on
the beginning of a down turn. And if you buy into the fact that we
are improved and we did beat them two out of three times. Where
does that put us?'' S-T: What player will break out the most this
season? JJ:''Greg Ellis is playing right now at the level like the
eighth pick in the draft. And that's from everybody's perspective.
And he was there last year from my perspective. People were too
critical of what he did last year as a rookie. I understand the
criticism by criteria of sacks. But I don't buy into it, especially
when you compare him to the other defensive line prospects that
were drafted.'' S-T: Looking back on the past 10 years, what are
your biggest regrets about your tenure? JJ:'' Not spending more
time on education and counseling and not doing more to have
thwarted the criticism of our teams' off-the-field activities. I
could have done a better job. I should have done a better job. I
was so focused on having the best players and so focused to doing
the things on and off the field to win that I could have done more
when we had issues.'' S-T: How do you improve on what has been a
great decade? JJ: ``I don't know. But I do have the luxury of the
total 10 years. In 1989 I didn't know how it was going to be
because I didn't know what I was in for. I think I know better how
to do it for the next 10 years than I did in 1989. The rules are
different but we are set to compete because I think the staffs
around us got a lot experience of the last 10 years. I certainly
like where we are starting from today better than where we started
from in 1989 and '90. The future is brighter than it was then.
Besides, I'm better fit to be an owner. I'm better fit to be a
general manager and president. I know I'm better to manage on a
day-to-day basis. I was criticized for not hiring an NFL person
when I came in. In essence when I start the next 10, I'm hiring an
NFL person. I feel pretty good about the experience that's here.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
