<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-TEN-U.S.-OPEN-MEN-TEX     09-11 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.-OPEN-MEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI TAKES NO. 1, SETS SIGHTS ON OPEN TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Andre Agassi left no doubt yesterday
about who's No. 1 in men's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   In a match to determine the top spot, Agassi recovered from a
nervous, slow start to rout Yevgeny Kafelnikov, 1-6, 6-3, 6-3, 6-3,
in the U.S. Open semifinals. Agassi, ranked No. 2 to start the
tournament, climbed to the top of the rankings, a spot Kafelnikov
would have claimed with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a goal that I have,'' said Agassi, who has the
best chance of his career to finish the season No. 1. ``It's not
just a number. It's a big accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Agassi wants to celebrate by winning the U.S. Open
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi plays Todd Martin today in an all-American final. Martin
made it to the title match with an impressive 6-4, 6-1, 6-2 victory
against Cedric Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man has to have his priorities,'' Agassi said. ``Winning the
U.S. Open is most important right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi ascended to the top for the second time this year. He had
gotten there earlier after he won his semifinal match at Wimbledon,
completing a remarkable comeback from a career free-fall that took
him all the way down to No. 141 late in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, he lost the Wimbledon championship to Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he intends to justify the No. 1 ranking with a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Open is what I want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Wimbledon, he enters today's final as a heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little easier going to sleep thinking about Todd Martin
than Pete,'' he admitted. ``But you still have a job to do, and the
job can be brutally difficult if you don't take care of the things
that you need to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not playing Sampras because Sampras isn't in the U.S. Open.
Agassi's rival was ranked No. 1, and would have retained the top
spot with a good showing in the Open. But Sampras had to withdraw
with a back injury that's expected to keep him out for at least a
month, opening the door for Agassi to finish the year on top.
</P>
<P>
   It also opens the door to the debate of, no matter what the
rankings say, who's really the best player. Sampras' victory in the
Wimbledon final was one of three over Agassi this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov, though, has no doubts after Agassi dissected him in
the final three sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely this year, belongs to him,'' Kafelnikov said.
``There's no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi certainly has a good case. He's in the final of his third
consecutive Grand Slam, winning the French and losing to Sampras at
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be better if he defeats Martin today. Although
Agassi is the favorite, Martin is capable of an upset if he plays
as he did in yesterday's semifinal. Martin, the stealth contender,
advanced to a Grand Slam final for the second time in his career _
the 1994 Australian Open was the other _ with a surprisingly quick,
easy victory against Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played good,'' Pioline said. ``He was hitting very well,
very few unforced errors and serving big. He was playing much
better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, despite being the seventh seed, was a huge long shot to
make it to the final before the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something a couple of weeks ago I didn't expect to
happen,'' Martin said. ``I knew I could, given the right
circumstances and playing well. ''
</P>
<P>
   The right circumstances came along when Sampras and defending
champion Patrick Rafter pulled out with injuries. Then Martin took
care of the playing well part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a couple of times against Todd, and I've never
seen him play like this,'' said Pioline, who held a 5-3 edge before
yesterday. ``If he plays this way tomorrow I think he has a good
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin remains a long shot against a higher ranked, more
physically talented opponent. Still, he isn't conceding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to play great,'' Martin said. ``You only have
to play better than the other guy, and that's what I'll try to do.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
