<HEADLINE>
HOW USC RECRUITS ARE PROGRESSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A look at how some of the players who have orally
committed to USC did on the first weekend of high school football:
</P>
<P>
   _Strong safety Jason Leach of Bishop Amat had two sacks and a
fumble recovery to lead the Lancers past Dominguez 21-0.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note that although Leach said he has orally
committed to the Trojans, he still intends to visit other colleges,
including Arizona State and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``USC's my No. 1 right now,'' Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   _Chatsworth quarterback Matt Cassel completed 17 of 23 passes
for 320 yards and four touchdowns in a 61-28 victory over Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   _Taft tight end Gregg Guenther had four catches for 36 yards in
a 49-19 loss to Banning.
</P>
<P>
   _A wide receiver being heavily recruited by USC, Hueneme's Keary
Colbert had a 56-yard touchdown reception in his team's loss to
Alemany.
</P>
<P>
   _Banning tailback Chris Howard, who says he strongly favors the
Trojans, had 22 carries for 241 yards and scored four touchdowns
against Taft.
</P>
<P>
   _Another recruit, tailback Mike Lemon of La Mirada, broke his
leg on the fourth play from scrimmage against West Torrance and
will miss the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wide receiver Craig Mitchell of West Los Angeles
College, who did not qualify academically last month, is being
recruited by Oregon and Hawaii. Mitchell has received his
junior-college degree but did not meet USC's requirements. He will
enroll at a Division I school in the spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
