u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TRINIDAD     09-11 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TRINIDAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD IS DUG IN FOR DE LA HOYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAJARDO, Puerto Rico _ Felix Trinidad could not appear more
confident going into his fight with Oscar De La Hoya next weekend
in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to be confident here, far from the confrontation. The
sun is shining on Trinidad's training camp at the base of a
five-star Wyndham resort hotel an hour from San Juan. The sea slaps
against the rocks with a rhythm not unlike a fighter's hands
spinning a speed bag, and not 10 yards from where a heavy bag hangs
on a metal hook, solitary and silent.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out the window of his stucco villa, Trinidad doesn't see
the fierce figure of De La Hoya waiting for him; he sees a private
island with a nude beach just a free boat ride away.
</P>
<P>
   Safe in this harbor of family and supporters, the International
Boxing Federation welterweight champion smiles freely when talking
of De La Hoya. Can a man living in such a place know anything about
pain and loss?
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad promises the fight will not go six rounds, something he
has said before, quickly assuring anyone listening that he is ready
to go all 12 rounds if he must. Either way, though, the fight can
end only one way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring the victory home to Puerto Rico,'' Trinidad says
without a second thought. ``Let Oscar come out however he wants.
Aggressor, not aggressor. What does it matter? He is the least of
my worries.''
</P>
<P>
   They are brave words considering that De La Hoya is as
undefeated as he is and has faced stiffer competition on the road
to this inevitable confrontation. It is a fight many are comparing
to the first Ray Leonard-Thomas Hearns meeting, a welterweight
clash that made more than noise. It made history, and promoters Don
King and Bob Arum are confident these two young Hispanic boxers
will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Each man's promoter promises more than a million pay-per-view
sales, which would be a first for any weight class other than
heavyweight. Each promoter and each fighter also promises victory.
That is the nature of their business.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a difference in their statements. While De La Hoya
exhibits his usual self-control during a phone conversation from
California, saying he is ready for anything and believing in the
end he will survive it all, Trinidad and his father are not as
diplomatic. If they are to be believed, this is not going to be a
fight at all. It will be a drum solo, a beating pounded out to a
Latin tempo by the grand champion of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as Oscar is, we will show he is not the best boxer in
the world,'' Don Felix, Trinidad's father/trainer, says as he sits
on his safe island, more than 3,000 miles from where De La Hoya
lies waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not be a great fight like Leonard-Hearns. No! It
will be a one-sided fight. It will be like a lion against a monkey
when the monkey's hands are tied. Who's going to win that? The lion
or the monkey? Keep that saying in mind and after the fight let me
know if it is the truth or a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, sitting by the sea, it is all a joke, but on Saturday,
the monkey's hands will not be tied and the Trinidads and the rest
of the world will find out whether there is one lion in that ring
or two.
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   When the Nov. 13 Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield rematch was
officially announced in Las Vegas, Lewis refused to have his
picture taken with King, whom he blames for manipulating the judges
in the first fight so that it ended in a controversial draw.
``You're biased against me,'' Lewis said to King. ``I don't want to
stand there so he can put his arm around me and pretend he's with
me.'' Several days later, King said, ``Imagine that! I done paid
him nearly $40 million and he don't want to have his picture taken
with me. The rematch will do more pay-per-view than any fight has
done because of the alleged scandal. That took this fight to areas
it would never be seen or heard. Now in places where they have no
interest in boxing the people want to know (who is the best
heavyweight). Places where they go to sheep-shearing contests or
corn-raising contests want the fight. We got a shot at 2 million
buys because nobody believed Lennox Lewis was no kind of fighter
until that fight. The fact is this: By him getting that draw, it
put him on the big screen in England. In America they had headlines
and bylines and sitting grand juries speaking his name.'' . . .
Only months after the FBI raided King's offices in Florida with 74
agents, a helicopter, and a crew of computer experts who left with
every machine and file in his office, he stands to make millions
with Lewis-Holyfield and Trinidad-De La Hoya. For the short term,
at least, King seems to have gotten the last laugh. ``I'm so
happy,'' King said. ``I got no accounts receivable. I got no
accounts payable. They got all my records and files. But I got the
gators (Trinidad and Holyfield) to the pond. Now they just gotta
swim through the sharks. Wouldn't it be something if Don King had
Felix Trinidad knock out Oscar De La Hoya and Holyfield knock out
Lennox Lewis with nobody having no futures on either guy?'' King
also has yet to be indicted by a sitting federal grand jury in New
Jersey, which reportedly is looking into boxing's murky business
practices. A host of minority groups have begun to inundate
Attorney General Janet Reno's office with howls of protest,
demanding to know why only King's operation has been so
consistently investigated. ``It's not a prosecution, it's a
persecution,'' said King. ``Why is it only me they're investigating
in boxing? They launch an all-out investigation of boxing and all
they can find is the black guy? The Boston Strangler didn't get
this much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, World Boxing Association super
welterweight champion David Reid made his second successful title
defense in six weeks when he won a one-sided decision from former
champion Keith Mullings, yet the victory left many unsatisfied
because Reid (14-0) was taken the distance for the fourth straight
time. A small crowd at the Hard Rock Casino in Las Vegas booed Reid
for boxing an intelligent but uninspired fight and occasionally
taunting Mullings more than hitting him. Despite that, the 1996
Olympic gold medalist did what he knew needed to be done. He kept
alive big-money matches in 2000 with IBF champion Fernando Vargas,
his Olympic teammate, and possibly 1992 gold medalist De La Hoya.
``We love the matchup of the two gold medalists,'' said Dan
Goossen, Reid's promoter. ``The two gold medalists would generate
tremendous interest. But if Vargas is out there and it makes sense,
that's where we will go. But the two gold medalists is the fight
everyone really wants to see.'' . . . Undefeated World Boxing
Organization light heavyweight champion Darius Michalczewski kept
the pressure on Roy Jones Jr. when he stopped Montell Griffin cold
in four rounds for the 16th successful defense of his 175-pound
title. Minutes after it was over, Michalczewski (41-0, 34 KO's)
once again called Jones out. ``I want to fight Jones because he's
one of the best _ after me.'' No reply from Jones, who couldn't
care less about a Polish fighter who never boxes outside of
Germany, where his promoter lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
