<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `OTHER' MARTINEZ IS STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although Pedro Martinez is sailing toward another
Cy Young Award, brother Ramon is having trouble returning to form.
</P>
<P>
   After signing with the Red Sox last spring, the former Dodgers
right-hander finally returned to the mound in late August after
missing more than a season with a torn rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox acquired closer Rod Beck from the Chicago Cubs,
Manager Jimy Williams put Tim Wakefield back in the rotation and
put Martinez in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance Williams will try Martinez out of the bullpen,
but Ramon's shaky mechanics make that a scary proposition. The Red
Sox originally planned to get him back in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   But they are in a pennant race now, and it's not the time to let
a struggling pitcher try to get back his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez signed with the Red Sox because he didn't think the
Dodgers were offering enough guaranteed money. He was more than
their ace for 10 years. He was the conscience of the club's Latin
community.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Red Sox are on the hook for $5.25 million next year.
Martinez had a base salary of $750,000 this year with a $1 million
signing bonus. &QL; 
More pain
</P>
<P>
   Delino DeShields was injured and ineffective throughout most of
his time with the Dodgers, making the trade for Pedro Martinez all
the more painful. He revived his career in Cincinnati and St. Louis
to earn a three-year, $12 million contract with Baltimore. The
result? He broke his thumb during the first intrasquad game in
spring training, missed April with a bad back and went on the DL in
June with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he has been out with a bruised groin. Fortunately for
Baltimore, second base is one position where the club has a future.
Jerry Hairston has stepped up in DeShields' absence and taken over
the position. &QL; 
Showdown
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers went 7-3 against the Cleveland Indians this
year, winning the season series for the fourth consecutive season.
Although the Rangers acquired left-hander Jeff Fassero to balance
their rotation for the playoffs, the pitcher Cleveland really
doesn't want to see is struggling right-hander John Burkett.
Against the rest of the league Burkett has an ERA of over 6. But
against the Indians, he is 2-0 with an 0.61 ERA. ``His ball moves
so much you think he's cheating,'' said Cleveland's Richie Sexson.
``But he doesn't. He just can't throw a ball straight.'' &QL; 
Cal countdown
</P>
<P>
   Oft-injured Cal Ripken has returned to the lineup, and he has
been moved up in the order to get more at-bats. But it is unlikely
that he'll reach 3,000 hits this season. Ripken, who figured to
reach 3,000 in late August, has been sidelined much of the second
half with a bad back. He needs 27 hits in the last 23 games, an
average of 1.3 per game. Even when he was at his best this season,
he did not average that many. &QL; 
Poor Frank
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing saga of Frank Thomas, the two-time White Sox MVP who
has slumped badly the past two seasons, might be over for the
season. Thomas, who has ditched first base for a designated-hitter
job, is done for the year with a bone spur in his right ankle. If
Thomas is done, he'll end the year hitting .305 with 15 homers and
77 RBI. It will mark the first time in nine full seasons that
Thomas has failed to drive in 100 runs in the big leagues. He had a
streak of five consecutive, 30-home run seasons end last year when
he hit 24. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
