<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SINDENPA     09-11 1763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SINDENPACTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN MANEUVER A BONUS OF CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a hot topic in the fall of 1997 when Bruins
president/general manager Harry Sinden signed rookies Joe Thornton
and Sergei Samsonov to three-year contracts. The deals had
complicated bonus structures that shaped all subsequent bonus
structures for entry-level players. They covered everything _ ice
time, goals, assists, points, plus-minus, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Neil Smith was critical because the
deals posed a giant hurdle for him when attempting to negotiate
with first-round pick Manny Malhotra, No. 7 overall in 1998.
Chances are, they have meant headaches for other teams as well in
negotiating the twists and turns of bonuses to get players signed.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said it was probably the first time in his long career
that he felt he had to veer from the straight and narrow to ensure
the competitive future of the Bruins. He knows there are those who
disagree with his philosophy, and that's fine, but Sinden also has
been an outspoken and sometimes lone voice with regard to keeping
salaries in check. In this case, he had to make an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't care about them with Joe and Sergei,'' said Sinden,
referring to his GM brethren. ``I didn't care about anyone, for a
change. I had no interest in any other team in the league when I
signed Joe Thornton. He was not going to be the sacrificial lamb in
that situation, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden admits the potential for hefty payouts wasn't his first
choice, but it was his only choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of setting a bonus structure for a first pick, it was
lousy but I didn't care how bad it was,'' said Sinden. ``I didn't.
But I get the impression that's the way a lot of people operate
with every single player. They don't care at all. I admit with Joe
and Sergei, I had no interest in any other team. I didn't care what
effect it had on them. What they wanted us to do is not sign him, I
guess. Anything I could've done, I would've done. Anything within
reach, especially for Joe. He was the No. 1 pick. We just finished
the worst season in 30 years, so I didn't care about it at all. If
I was going to hurt everybody, I couldn't have cared less.
(Commissioner Gary) Bettman probably didn't like it; nobody liked
it, but I didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   With Samsonov and Thornton due for new contracts at the end of
this year, it will be interesting to see how that bonus structure
affects future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Smith responds
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Smith, the Rangers' boss politely took issue with
this writer's assertion last week that his club routinely chucks
aside the rules of the collective bargaining agreement while
spending a fortune on some stars and some less-than-marquee
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done that has gotten people upset, which is not a
CBA issue, is we've spent a lot of money,'' said Smith, referring
to shopping for unrestricted free agents. ``That is a
how-you-want-to-use-revenue-and-how-much-of-it-you-choose-to-spend
issue and how much of it you want to make or lose depending upon
your business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   One area in which Smith agreed with this space was how
ridiculous it is that the Players' Association refuses to use the
system despite the fact the players agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the clubs that are saying, `We refuse to use the
system,' it's the players,'' said Smith. ``The player membership by
and large does not understand the intricacies of the CBA; never
mind the intricacies, they don't even understand the basics, but
the agents do. You sit down with a player and tell them about the
CBA and they look at you with puzzlement. When the club has rights,
the cry is, `The club should be fair.' What happened to dealing in
good faith? When the player has the rights, there's no mention of
that anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person decides they no longer want to be a journalist,
they don't have to be a journalist, and if a person decides they no
longer want to be an executive, they don't have to be an executive.
If a person wants to be a hockey player, live under the rules you
agreed to, or else quit being a hockey player, go be a piano player
or an accountant or go do something under another system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nilan Rule
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of bonuses, when trying to figure out a fair package
for goalie Byron Dafoe, Sinden said one bonus he'll never pay any
player is for participation in the All-Star Game. ``We don't give
any bonuses for that,'' Sinden said, ``ever since Mike Milbury
picked Chris Nilan. We wouldn't give five cents for being selected
to the All-Star Game. The fans vote for it, the coaches fool around
with it, and all of a sudden he picks some guy on your team and he
gets a $50,000 bonus but he's really (only deserving of a 10
percent raise in his contract).'' . . . Bruins coach Pat Burns said
that although the offseason was shorter this past summer, he's
happy this year is going to begin earlier than last because it
means the end will be earlier, too. ``I think it got carried away
when people are watching hockey in late June, and Gary Bettman is
probably making a good move here in trying to get things up a
little bit quicker and maybe get it over,'' said Burns. ``Interest
gets lost if you're not in the city that's still in it by the start
of July and the interest gets lost along the way. I think this is
probably a good move.'' There seems to be wide acceptance of the
new rule about referees calling goals rather than relying on
replay. ``Leaving the discretion to the referee on the call instead
of going to the video puts a little more onus on the referee to
make a decision,'' said Burns. ``When we didn't have that, there
was no onus on the referee so it was a passing-the-buck affair.
Now, the referee has to make his decision and live with his
decision and come over and explain to me his decision. I think
that's probably going to be a little bit better there.'' . . .
Pittsburgh coach Kevin Constantine's contract is up for renewal at
the end of the year and GM Craig Patrick isn't planning an
extension any time soon, although he said Constantine is doing a
good job. Patrick said the ownership transition to Mario Lemieux
and attempts to sign Darius Kasparaitis outweigh the urgency of the
coaching situation . . . Despite the acquisition of 36-year-old
goalie Grant Fuhr for a third-round pick, things are tough in
Calgary. The team used to have a season-ticket base of 16,000, with
7,000 more waiting in the wings. Now that base is only 9,000. Part
of the problem is that the club has missed the postseason the last
three years and hasn't won a playoff series since capturing the
Stanley Cup in 1989. GM Al Coates was honest to say part of the
attrition is also due to the renovation the Saddledome underwent in
1995. ``We had to relocate roughly 6,000 season ticket-holders from
the lower bowl to the second tier. Well, a lot of groups who had
been coming together, having dinner together for years, they were
split up and put all over the building. I think it's fair to say,
in my own opinion, that we lost 4,000 season ticket-holders
directly as a result of the renovation. We haven't been able to get
those people back.'' . . . Former Bruin Greg Hawgood is attending
the Vancouver Canucks' training camp on a tryout. Hawgood, who was
the IHL's best defenseman last season with 74 points in 76 games
for the champion Houston Aeros, could help the Canucks on the power
play. ``That game is changing, and skill is more important than
brawn was,'' said coach Marc Crawford, referring to Hawgood's
less-than-imposing 5-foot-10-inch, 190-pound frame. ``He's here
because we all feel he has the opportunity to play here. He was one
of the top defensemen not playing in the NHL last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagr takes short cut
</P>
<P>
   His on-ice brilliance certainly won't change, but Penguins star
and NHL MVP Jaromir Jagr is sporting a new look. He chopped off his
long hair during a vacation in Italy. He joked that he told the
hairdresser to make him look like an Italian, though he confessed
he wasn't sure exactly what that meant. ``I just decided I was
going to cut my hair,'' Jagr said. ``It's just a new look. I think
I'm old enough to have short hair now, no more of that girl
stuff.'' What's funny is that Jagr didn't do it in one haircut. It
took several trips, with the stylist clipping it a little shorter
each time. Jagr said he's going to keep his new 'do. ``It's gone
for good,'' he said. ``New image.'' . . . Meanwhile, down South,
don't be looking for new Florida goalie Trevor Kidd to trim his
trademark locks anytime soon. He did dye his hair blond, however.
``With my long hair and a goatee, everybody thinks I'm a little
crazy,'' said Kidd, who is also a heavy metal fan. ``Coming from
Calgary to Carolina just allowed me to be myself. It didn't matter
what color my hair was or my pads were.'' . . . Sad to see it, but
it was inevitable: Maple Leaf Gardens is for sale. ``We're going to
explore, develop, or sell,'' said Richard Peddie, president and CEO
of Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment. ``All we know is that it
can't exist in its present form.'' Little has taken place inside
the building since the Maple Leafs moved to the Air Canada Centre.
About 40 events have been held, not nearly enough to support the
building. Word is that it could be a shopping mall, a condo
complex, or a theater . . . A Ranger payroll of some $54 million
apparently doesn't include a second-line center. The candidates
seem to be former Bruin Tim Taylor, the 19-year-old Malhotra,
18-year-old Jamie Lundmark, rookie Michael York, or wings Adam
Graves and Todd Harvey. ``We're all thinking about the second
slot,'' said coach John Muckler. ``As of yet, I don't think we've
found a second center-ice man in this training camp. Whether we
will or not, I don't know. He's obviously not going to be a
playmaker if he is. He's going to be a good, solid, checking
center.'' . . . Senators star Alexei Yashin, who is refusing to
honor the final year of his $3.6 million contract, is headed for
Switzerland and plans to skate with a European club. The Senators
suspended him and threatened to sue. The player and his agent, Mark
Gandler, made a laughable proposal to the Senators that would have
kept the salary at $3.6 million this year, with a total of $23
million to follow in the next two years. Yeah, right. That proposal
is actually supposed to fool someone? . . . 20 days to opening
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
