<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITES ARE ATTRACTING ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe they'll slump, and Oakland will make a charge,
and we can resurrect those annual Red Sox stories about choking,
folding, and Calvinist clouds of doubt covering New England.
</P>
<P>
   But not now. There were several dicey moments in Saturday's
11-10 win, but your Red Sox are surging through their ``crucial''
road trip like Rod Rutledge barreling north on I-95.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when George Costanza of ``Seinfeld'' had success doing
the opposite of everything he usually does? That is the Red Sox in
September 1999. They are winning after Labor Day, and now it's the
haughty Yankees who are hearing footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Strange days indeed. New York's lead of 8 1/2 games (Aug. 30) is
down to 4 1/2. And only Roger Clemens stands in the way of a Boston
sweep in New York. How's that for role reversal? What must Don
Zimmer be thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams downplayed the surge, saying, ``We
know where we are and they know where they are. We just have to
take care of our own the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   But across the hall, Yankee manager Joe Torre was being asked
about ``holding off Boston'' and ``letting somebody back in the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about letting somebody back in the race,'' said
Torre. ``We're 30 games over .500. You have to give Boston credit
for the way they've played. They won't go away, and I give them
credit for their resilience. We've played some tough series with
them (the Sox are 7-4 vs. New York). They keep coming at us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of Jimy went national with their message  &UR; yesterday &LR; ,
hitting five homers and beating the world champs in a Fox-televised
game that no doubt caught the attention of the Cleveland Indians
and Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Life is beautiful in Red Sox Nation. The once-reclusive,
ever-pilloried Dan Duquette is doing live standups with TV types,
Williams is keeping a lucky Baby Ruth candy bar on his desk, and
MVP candidate Pedro Martinez has served notice that the Sox will be
a serious opponent in any potential/proverbial short series.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro downplayed the great Yankee chase. ``We're just worrying
about keeping ahead of Oakland,'' said the Cy Young designee. ``A
short series is all we want.''
</P>
<P>
   How well are the Sox going? They couldn't even lose on a day
when they made four errors and handled the baseball like it was a
live grenade. They couldn't even lose with the combustible Mark
Portugal pitching in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal went into the game with a career record of 0-6 and ERA
of 6.96 against the Pinstripers. Moreover, he was 0-4 with a 6.15
ERA in his last six Sox starts. He hasn't won since Aug. 4 and he
didn't get the win  &UR; yesterday &LR; , but he got five runs of support
before giving up four in his fourth and final inning.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is 6-2 since leaving Fenway, and the wild card lead over
Oakland has grown. By the time the Tuna is finished with the
Patriots in Jersey  &UR; today &LR; , the Red Sox could be 3 1/2 behind these
Yankees with 19 to play.
</P>
<P>
   The surge has not gone unnoticed in New York, where another
55,422 (many of them New Englanders) filled the Stadium
 &UR; yesterday &LR; . Torre admitted that he thought the Sox were finished a
month and a half ago, but he and his players are impressed with a
Boston team that has cut New York's lead almost in half since Aug.
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still pretty confident we'll win the thing,'' said Jim
Leyritz, an ex-Sox. ``But the Red Sox are a good-hitting ball
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Costanza, these Sox are the opposite of every Boston
baseball team you have ever known. They did not hit a home run in
their last Fenway homestand yet won six of the seven games. They
play defense ( &UR; yesterday &LR;  being an exception), move runners over,
and occasionally go from first to third on soft singles. Duquette
has assembled a National League pitching staff. To paraphrase Pete
Carroll, the Sox are a little dangerous right now. Sometimes they
aren't pretty, but they're effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a road trip that could have been hazardous, but we've
played well so far,'' said Mike Stanley, an ex-Yankee. ``But those
guys over there know what it takes to win and they're going to come
out  &UR; tomorrow &LR;  like gangbusters.''
</P>
<P>
   Weird. Suddenly, there's a mini-pennant race and we never saw it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been feeling like a pennant race to me for a while,''
said Sox outfielder Darren Lewis. ``I'm not sure what the Yankees
are thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   They are thinking about Boston. In September. The Sox are
charging and the Yanks are vulnerable and it's a bizarro baseball
world in the Bronx  &UR; today &LR; . For Sox fans, it's the opposite of
everything they've been trained to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990911.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PARCELLS-JETS-BOS     09-11 2354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PARCELLS-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS AS DRIVEN AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The bedroom closet in his dream house at Sea
Girt, N.J., contains more than one ensemble. It's just that he
chose to wear the bulky green Jets sweatshirt, green shorts, white
ankle socks, and white sneakers to work last week. Three days in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a fashion statement of allegiance or a hygienic
protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' said Bill Parcells in mock indignation, ``I showered.''
</P>
<P>
   But the man reeks of compulsiveness. Right down to the clothes
that might have been sticking to his back by the time he changed
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear them home,'' he explained, ``because then I don't have
to worry about what I'm going to wear to work the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Because work is all the Jets coach/football ruler wants to think
about. Ever. Especially this past week while he approached his 15th
_ and perhaps last _ season opener as an NFL head coach, Sunday at
Giants Stadium against his old chums, the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I wear the same thing all the time,'' he said.
``But the week of the opener is always hectic with all the
preparation involved. And I've had this Chrebet thing to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the loss of trusty wide receiver Wayne Chrebet,
sidelined at least six weeks with a broken foot suffered in last
week's exhibition finale. That gives Parcells one more thing to
obsess about, one more reason that he can't dwell on such
incidentals as outfits.
</P>
<P>
   As his fabled career that has produced two Super Bowl champions
with the Giants and another Super Bowl visit with the Patriots
heads toward a horizon, the 58-year-old Parcells is still consumed
by the process. Football is never on his mind more than 24 hours a
day. ``I have no idea what's going on in the outside world,'' he
said. And anything that diverts him from thinking about his team
and what he needs to do to make it better is his enemy.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he'll often leave his car parked outside the Jets'
Hofstra University practice complex, ``so I don't have to wait for
the guy to bring it out'' for the 1 1/2-hour commute home after 13
hours at the office. If he's particularly preoccupied, he'll take a
helicopter at his disposal that lands on the Jets' practice field
and transports him to a helipad near his home.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for these shortcuts around real life's nagging
essentials is perfectly logical to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate balance,'' he said. ``In this business, if you
go to the bathroom, you're 20 minutes behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by competition
</P>
<P>
   And Parcells always has tried to stay ahead of the game. That is
his sole purpose in life, and it has been ever since he started out
coaching the defensive line at a football nowhere, Hastings College
in Nebraska, 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember my first game, against Colorado School of
Mines,'' he said. ``We won, 24-0. I thought it was the Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been that way ever since. Every game is as significant as
the one before it, the one after it. Even now that he is on the
threshold of NFL history, in line to become the first man to lead
three franchises to the Super Bowl, his resurrected Jets having
missed by one game last year and favored in many circles to take
the final step this time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to him, the outsiders just don't get it. They think it's the
quest for the rings and dictatorial control that keep him going,
that brought him back from a two-year hiatus forced on him by poor
health resulting in coronary bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready for a heart attack even though I fooled the
doctors for six months because I was still exercising,'' he said.
``I was smoking. I was fat. Leaving coaching wasn't of my own
volition. I felt I had more to do when I came back.
Retrospectively, it gave me a better perspective. I was a windmill
fighter. For a long time, I chased windmills. I still look at
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   But his priorities are not the ones that others impose on him,
the external demands that cause him to shake his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the New York papers saying that if we don't win the
Super Bowl, the Jets are a failure, Parcells is a failure,'' he
said. ``I mean, come on, give me a break.''
</P>
<P>
   The ones who get it, who know what makes this supposed
autocratic mythic figure go without a change of clothes for days at
a time, realize what catalyzes the mechanism. The job titles and
demands for authority _ which triggered his toxic departure from
the Patriots and owner Bob Kraft three seasons ago _ are only a
means.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, I've been portrayed as a guy who's
power-hungry, ego-driven,'' said Parcells. ``If that's what it
takes to win . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Then consider him guilty. He's told his current team, ``I'm too
old to lose,'' but he has fit that description from the day he was
born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the competition,'' he said. ``That's what it's all
about. It's the same thing as when I was down at the gym as a kid
and I'd get my guys and you'd get your guys and we'd find out who's
the best. It doesn't matter who's watching, who's covering, what
the teams are.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter if it's the second Sunday of September or
the last Sunday in January. Parcells wants his guys to beat your
guys. More important, he wants to do everything in his power, use
every shred of his energy, to make sure that his guys are at least
at their best, if not the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want my legacy to be,'' he said, ``is that, `He tried
to get his teams ready to win. Maybe he was tough. Maybe we didn't
like it. But he did what he could to give us the best chance to
win.' My goal is to get my team to play to its potential as I see
it. Maybe that's not good enough to win, but I have to know that at
least I had them ready.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he was taken aback for probably one of the few times
in his career last week. The Jets were preparing for their
exhibition windup against the Vikings, and defensive back Jimmy
Hitchcock _ a Parcells whipping post in New England, now a star in
Minnesota _ approached him on the Giants Stadium turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I didn't like it, but you made me mentally tough and
I want to thank you,' '' recalled Parcells. ``Here's a young man I
hadn't seen since I left New England and he came and sought me out.
It was nice. I was touched.''
</P>
<P>
   So overcome by sentiment was Parcells that his team merely
thrashed the Vikings, 38-17, completing a 3-1 exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   No hidden agendas
</P>
<P>
   These Jets are his latest work in progress, his latest
reclamation project. Just as he did with the Giants and Patriots,
he took over a team that was the dregs of the NFL _ 1-15 in the
calamitous final days of the Rich Kotite regime _ and turned it
around. The Jets jumped to 9-7 the season after Parcells bolted New
England. Last year they overcame an 0-2 start, captured the
division title in the vaunted AFC East, and led the eventual Super
Bowl champion Denver Broncos in the second half of the AFC
Championship game before succumbing.
</P>
<P>
   A nice run, Parcells figured. And thoroughly irrelevant now.
That's why the Jets were greeted on the first day of training camp
with a uniform addendum that established the theme of 1999:
T-shirts with ``START OVER'' emblazoned on the back. It's why just
outside the trainer's room is a green frame with ``NEW YORK JETS''
on the top, ``SUPER BOWL CHAMPIONS 19??'' on the bottom, and
scrawled across the blank space reserved for a group photo the
challenge: ``Are you in this picture? When will it be taken? It's a
team picture only.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is you have to try at least the best you can to
create a mind-set with the players that you aren't going to be
successful if you don't do the things you're supposed to do,''
Parcells said. ``You can't hopscotch fundamentals. They don't stay
in place. It's not like we pick right up 20 minutes from the Super
Bowl. Any team I've had to tell to play hard hasn't been worth a
(expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   The players get the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how Bill is,'' said wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
``It's `yeah, yeah, yeah, you did it last year but don't think it's
going to be a cakewalk this year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And they buy it. They really don't have a choice. Parcells's pro
pedigree is his calling card, his acidic wit both goads and
disarms, his divine right authority to hire and fire is his
ultimate weapon, and his devotion to detail is infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing the players tend to focus on is week to week,
practice to practice,'' said offensive tackle Jumbo Elliott, a
veteran of both Parcells New York regimes. ``It's sort of like his
personality filters down to the players.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no ulterior nuances to that personality, no hidden
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is Bill,'' said running back Curtis Martin, who followed
Parcells's trail from New England to New York last year. ``He's
going to say exactly what's on his mind. He's going to be up front
with you. He's very fair, but at the same time, he's very
demanding.''
</P>
<P>
   And consistent. Parcells will adjust to his personnel
strategically, but he won't budge psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's exactly the same as he was in New England,'' said former
Patriot and current Jet center Mike Gisler. ``I guarantee you the
players in New England could tell you exactly what he's going to do
and say if they were here today.''
</P>
<P>
   But how many more days does he have left in this job? Parcells
says he feels no particular sense of urgency this year, and he
certainly isn't conveying it to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I know, his career is winding down,'' said Johnson,
eyebrows raised in skepticism. ``His career is not winding down.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Parcells acknowledges ``this is a young man's game,''
and he knows his future no longer is measured in indefinite terms.
Yet if this is indeed his last hurrah, he's not betraying any misty
nostalgia. That would detract from the job, the process, and then
there'd be no reason to be doing this, championships be damned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the practice, the preparation,'' said Parcells. ``I
like it when my (salary) cap man, Mike Tannenbaum, comes into my
office at 6 o'clock and I can say, `Where has the day gone?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The AFC East challenge
</P>
<P>
   After 32 years of coaching, 14 years of coaching at the top, he
still finds something new to keep him occupied as those days
disappear, to keep him fresh, to consume his mind and his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any comfort level; I never do,'' said Parcells.
``It's tough to explain even what I was thinking this morning. I
was going over the list of draft choices who've been cut and the
unsigned free agents. Now I know that. It's a very narrow thought
process. I'm thinking about one thing _ getting my team prepared
for this week, this practice. It's so narrow it's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is irresistible to him. Football just happens to be the
forum. If he were trying to meet a sales quota or teach kids
algebra or deliver newspapers, it would be no different. There
would still be the competition, the process, to drive him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I have the right personality or the wrong personality,
I can't say,'' he said. ``It's the way I am. It's been formed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he's a finished product, but each of his teams is a
blank canvas, a new challenge. This one is highly regarded by the
prognosticators, but Parcells scorns them because they never
consider the pitfalls. He knows the Jets could be good. He also
knows they face 10 teams that made the playoffs last season,
starting with the Patriots; that their ownership situation is
unsettled since the death in May of Leon Hess, who gave Parcells
unbridled control of the football operation; that they're working
in five new starters on offense and four on defense; that they're
in a division where the shared wealth is such that the teams may
knock the stuffing out of each other, rendering the survivor
mincemeat by January.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never have a real good gauge of what your team is going to
do at this point,'' he said. ``I really don't have any idea whether
my team is going to be any good or competitive or what they're
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an exercise in anxiety, he'll tell you, and he isn't
expressing false modesty. He has acquired a reputation for bullying
and blustering, and he certainly is capable of such behavior. But a
Parcells press conference features as much soul-searching as
sparring. It's as if he's honestly trying to sort things out,
convince himself that he's on the right track after all these
years, even as he provides definitive answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in my ability that I can prepare my team,''
he said. ``I have confidence that I have enough experience that I'm
not going to screw it up too badly. But I still could screw it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent that, he likes to surround himself with a certain
type of player, and one of the qualities he's looking for often is
experience. Fifteen of his current Jets are at least 30, and three
more will reach that age during the season. Loyalty is another big
item. Those versed in the Parcells Way, those he trusts, tend to
follow him from stop to stop, as evidenced by the presence of
Elliott and five former Patriots on today's Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you've got to do when you come to a team _ and
I don't think the media understands because you get criticized for
doing it _ is you've got to get guys to hold the fort,'' said
Parcells, launching into a soliloquy without prompting. ``If you
don't get some guys to hold the fort, then they storm the gates and
you don't have a fort. Once you do that, you can start building,
but if you don't get it stabilized . . . and that's why it never
stops. And that's the same thing that's happened here. It hasn't
blown down yet. We're going to be under attack here soon, so we'll
find out. We've been under attack the last month. So far, we've
held 'em off. But you never know when they've got too much for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's survival of the fittest, my guys against your guys. Just
like down at the gym. Just the thing that keeps Bill Parcells
ticking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
