<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-RYDERCU     09-11 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-RYDERCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYDER WILL BE A CROWDED CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With no tickets to the 33d Ryder Cup matches available except
through exorbitant package deals, the best advice to golf fans is
to save your money, avoid the traffic headaches and the difficulty
of trying to watch golf in surroundings not designed for
spectators, and watch the action from Brookline on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the Ryder Cup setting will be chaotic,'' said
Dick Haskell, who recently resigned after more than a
quarter-century as executive director of the Massachusetts Golf
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell, who has seen competitions ranging from the 1968 US
Juniors to the 1988 US Open at The Country Club, where he is a
member, is concerned that the event ``is taking on a party
appearance already.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hordes of people, the pavilions, and the hospitality tents
are the ingredients for the `World's Largest Lawn Party,' '' said
Haskell. ``The only people at the Ryder Cup that will be able to
move will be the players on the course. It will be next to
impossible to walk the course with a particular match. You would
have to be 6-2, 225 and very, very aggressive. Pushy. The problem
is simple. The Ryder Cup has been oversold. I think that the PGA of
America has sold 10,000 more tickets than they should have.''
</P>
<P>
   While the matches are being contested Sept. 24-26, the
surrounding streets will be closed to vehicular traffic, off limit
even to taxis. The MBTA has canceled weekend days off in order to
provide maximum service.
</P>
<P>
   There will be seven Jumbotrons scattered about the course and
15,000 bleacher seats. Some of the fairways are bordered by rocky
terrain on which only mountain goats could tread. This isn't the
Tournament Players Club at River Highlands in Cromwell, Conn., a
stadium course built for spectators. This is The Country Club,
which was built for golf.
</P>
<P>
   The area for corporate tents at the 1988 US Open was 40,000
square feet. It is 250,000 square feet for this Ryder Cup, and
$15.2 million worth of on-site corporate tents were sold nearly
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add up the volunteers, the officials, the press, the
PGA professionals, and the service people, you could have close to
40,000 people on the property,'' said Haskell. ``That could be
spectacular gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   On a scale of 0 to 10, The Country Club would rank about a 2 as
a spectator course. It is an old-fashioned layout. It does not have
spectator flow. There is limited fairway viewing access on a number
of holes, and should there be heavy rains in this season of
tropical storms, parking would be nightmarish. Mandatory reading is
the spectator guide currently available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The green locations do not offer good viewing,'' said Haskell.
``Big crowds will further impede getting close enough to see. They
are small greens to start with. Hole No. 5 and No. 10 have some
viewing elevation. The grandstands present an opportunity to see
each match with a degree of comfort on that hole. You can probably
see more watching one of the Jumbotrons located around the course.
If you have any aversion to a throng, stay away from The Country
Club during the Ryder Cup matches.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the US Golf Association opened the floodgates on Monday
of US Open week when it sold an extra 5,000 practice-round tickets
for that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost sunk the club on the first day,'' said Haskell.
There was a move afoot to keep media outside the ropes for Monday's
playoff, but a compromise was worked out. There were 400
credentialed media in 1988, more than 1,300 for the Ryder Cup
matches, where armbands will be extremely limited. It's going to be
survival of the fittest.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA has already sold out Pebble Beach at 32,500 for next
year's US Open, and there was a reported head count of 50,000 on
hand for a given day at this year's tournament at Pinehurst No. 2.
But there was plenty of land at Pinehurst; there is limited acreage
at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it'll be so hard to get there, people will get
discouraged,'' said Haskell. ``I think most of the golfers I know
are going to take a look at this place and end up watching it on
TV. We had a guy on our committee who went to Oak Hill (for the
1995 matches) and watched it all in the men's grille.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Golf writer and broadcaster Ben Wright, whose public and
professional world came crumbling apart after his remarks about
lesbianism on the LPGA Tour in 1995, tells his full story in a new
book, ``Good Bounces &AMP; Bad Lies,'' which is published by the
Sleeping Bear Press and reportedly is selling briskly.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's life certainly has not been uneventful since his
dismissal by CBS early in 1996. He checked into the Betty Ford
Clinic in an attempt to control his drinking problem; he had a
court appearance Friday near his home in North Carolina to face
contempt of court charges for nonpayment; and he is currently
guiding a golf group to Ireland. He has designed a course, Cliffs
Valley GC in Traveler's Rest, S.C., and the beat goes on. Wright
started up a business, The Wright Group, and started receiving
orders for plumbing supplies. Through it all, Wright says, ``I'm
getting on with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright has also launched Wrightway Productions, and he says he
has Gary Player and Jack Nicklaus on board for his broadcasting
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been struggling along trying to make a breakthrough,''
he said. ``We're going to do a lengthy documentary, and that's a
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much of a breakthrough he has made in ``Good Bounces &AMP;
Bad Lies'' remains to be seen, but there are extensive Ryder Cup
stories and a chapter titled, ``If you ever go across the sea to
Ireland,'' in which he takes the reader through his adopted home
golfing turf. It's an easy, pleasant read and maybe, just maybe, a
moment of triumph is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Maine event
</P>
<P>
   The 26th New England Open, a fixture for the past 19 years at
The Quechee Club in Quechee, Vt., sets up for its three-day run
Monday in Maine at Portland CC and The Woodlands. It's the first
time the competition will be contested in the Pine Tree State, but
defender John Hickson out of the Bethel Inn &AMP; CC lends some
home-state flavor. The field of 173 pros and 10 amateurs will split
between the two courses the first two rounds, and Wednesday's final
round, involving the low 60 and ties, will be contested at Portland
CC. There is a record purse of $55,000, with $9,000 first-prize
money. The field includes former champions Paul Barkhouse (1975,
Indian Ridge) of Woburn, Lee Danielian (1980) of Framingham, Jeff
Bailey (1988) of Norwood, Jeff Lewis (1989, 1991, 1993) of Cape Cod
and South Florida, Rich Parker (1992) of the Vermont/New Hampshire
region, and Hickson, who beat Joe Cioe with a birdie on the first
hole of a playoff a year ago. The field also includes stalwarts Tim
Angis of Biddeford-Saco CC and mini-tourists Rod Butcher of North
Kingston, R.I., who won the Massachusetts Open a year ago at Oak
Hill CC, and Pete Morgan of Cape Cod . . . The countdown to the
47th Wogan Award, presented to the NEPGA's top player, is in its
final stages. Entering the New England Open, the top five in points
are Paul Parajeckas (60.5) of Woburn, section champion Mike San
Filippo (54.5) of Nashawtuc, Kirk Hanefeld (49.5) of the Ridge
Club, Nickson (45.6), and Frank Dully (45) of Kernwood. There are
20 points available for a victory in the New England Open and 10
for qualifying for the National Club Pro Sept. 29-Oct. 2. Hickson
(1995, 1998) and Parajeckas (1989, 1997) have won the Wogan twice,
San Filippo (1990) once . . . The phenomenal interest in
mid-amateur competition is reflected by the record 442 who have
entered the 16th Massachusetts tournament (Oct. 4-5) at Longmeadow
CC. They will be split among five venues Monday and one Thursday to
fill 94 spots. There are 26 who are exempt. ``This is right up
there with the State Amateur in terms of interest,'' said MGA
executive director Tom Landry . . . It's perhaps scary to note that
had Scituate club champion Fordie Pitts, who started his round with
a double-bogey 6, shot two strokes lower in the Boston Globe/MGA
Tournament of Club Champions, he would have shot his age (69) and
won a tournament he has played in 46 out of 47 years. He settled
for a 71, as Jim Tyrrell of Weston GC won by a shot. Pitts is an
organizer/founder of the Cape Cod Senior Open, to be held Sept.
20-21 at Hyannis GC, which he and Joe Keller own. Also upcoming is
the 39th State Seniors (Sept. 27-28 at Hatherly CC), an event Pitts
won in 1985 at Wellesley and in 1989 at Pocasset, and the New
England Seniors (Sept. 23-24) at Tumble Brook CC in Bloomfield,
Conn. . . . The latest bulletin from Augusta National GC indicates
changes will be in place for the Masters next April on holes 10,
12, 13, 14, 16, and 17. The 10th and 16th greens have been rebuilt,
and new pin placement options have been established on the 12th and
13th with the recovery of green edges lost to encroachment. Four
trees have been planted to the right of the 14th fairway, two trees
to the right have been removed on the 17th, and three trees have
been added between the 15th and 17th fairways. ``The changes on the
17th will continue to place a premium on accuracy off the tee,''
according to tournament chairman Hootie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The last round
</P>
<P>
   Billy Max, who was one of the Boys of Winter in the days of his
restless youth in the late 1960s, would journey to the West Palm
Beach area in the company of Barkhouse, Bob Menne, and Bruce Dobie
and they would try to scrape by on the course. ``We were all single
and freewheeling,'' Max recalled in 1974 when Menne won the Kemper
Open and fulfilled their dream of dreams. ``We'd just get by. The
four of us would go to the Bahamas for a tournament. If one of us
made money, then we'd all get off the island. We'd eat steaks that
week. If nobody made any money, it'd be hamburgers.'' So they all
toasted Menne's triumph; and now it is time to sing a song of
sorrow for Max, a former assistant pro at Pine Valley in Pelham,
N.H., who died Friday in a hospital in Hanover. He was one of the
good ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
