<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX A PERSISTENT THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette spoke for just
about everyone in and out of uniform Saturday in Yankee Stadium as
he boarded the elevator for the clubhouse following Boston's 11-10
win over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going into our fifth hour until Rod Beck mercifully
ended it,'' Duquette said, ``and I mean mercifully.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was watch this game, and I'm drained.''
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon in which seven home runs were hit, five errors
were made, and 349 pitches were thrown by 11 pitchers who walked 16
batters, the Sox were not assured of victory, despite twice holding
five-run leads, until first baseman Mike Stanley squeezed his glove
around a throw from Jose Offerman on Bernie Williams's game-ending
one-hopper to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, I'm tired,'' Stanley said. ``I'm tired mentally,
physically, emotionally. (Bret) Saberhagen said he was worn out and
he wasn't even playing. He said during the seventh inning he had to
go up to the clubhouse. I wish I could have gone up there with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they have this place packed (55,422) and they get this
place as loud as they get it, the fans getting on their feet, for
an opposing team this is a very difficult place to play. Safe? No,
not in this ballpark, not against that lineup. Even when we were
up, 9-4, I thought there was still quite a bit of game left. You're
never comfortable against those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you just take the bottom line. You don't take anything
else. You take the bottom line, be thankful, go out to dinner, and
be ready to go out there again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for the Sox, who hit five home runs _ including
two by Nomar Garciaparra and one foul-pole banger by Troy O'Leary _
but also made four errors, including two on one play by Offerman,
is this: With a two-run, pinch-hit home run by Butch Huskey in the
eighth inning providing the ultimate margin of victory that Beck
preserved in the ninth, they won for the ninth time in 11 games and
sixth time in eight games on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   They're within 4 1/2 games of the first-place Yankees, the
closest they've been to the top spot in the American League East
since they were four out on July 20.
</P>
<P>
   All that stands between the Sox and a three-game sweep of the
Bombers, who already have lost 7 of 11 to Boston in dropping a
season series to the Olde Towne Team for the first time since 1996,
is Roger Clemens. And the Rocket has misfired more often than not
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're thinking over there,'' said
Garciaparra, who hit a bases-empty home run in the third to give
the Sox a 5-0 lead, then hit a three-run homer with first base open
in the sixth to give the Sox a 9-4 advantage. ``All we're thinking
about is playing hard every day.''
</P>
<P>
   With just 20 games to be played, the Sox assured themselves of
having no worse than a three-game lead over Oakland in the
wild-card race this morning. If they break even the rest of the
way, they will finish with 91 wins, one fewer than the '98
wild-card entrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things happened, I'm not sure what happened,'' said
Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, whose bullpen was doubly taxed by
the short stint of starter Mark Portugal, gone after four innings
after Paul O'Neill's three-run home run cut the Sox lead to 5-4,
and the bellyache of reliever Rich Garces, who was limited to one
inning after losing his lunch because of what he suspects was food
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long game,'' Williams said of a nine-inning exercise
completed in an untidy 3 hours 50 minutes. ``A lot of things
happened to both teams. Good plays. Not-so-good plays. Good
pitching. Walks. Home runs. Everything. But it was a good victory
for us. We hung in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the way this series began _ Pedro
Martinez's one-hit, no-walk, 17-strikeout masterpiece Friday night
_ and the sprawling mishmash that followed couldn't have been
greater.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``Jimy, last night you said you never saw pitching
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams: ``Today I saw pitching I've never seen. But
fortunately, it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee starter Hideki Irabu lasted just two innings, his
shortest start of the season. O'Leary singled home a run and
Stanley knocked in two more in the first, and rookie Trot Nixon hit
a bases-empty home run, his 11th homer of the season, in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's successor, Allen Watson, gave up two home runs, to
Garciaparra and O'Leary, who hit one no more than 5 feet from the
top of the right-field foul pole in the fifth. Yankees second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch kicked away a ground ball for an error that
led to three runs off reliever Ramiro Mendoza in the sixth, as
Garciaparra hit the first pitch he saw from Mendoza into the
left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees picked themselves up once more, scoring four
times in the seventh despite hitting just one ball out of the
infield, Tino Martinez's solid single to center. Garciaparra
backhanded a ball in the hole, but the ball fell out of his glove
for an infield hit. Offerman dropped Knoblauch's grounder, then
threw wildly to first for a double dip on which two runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like I was out there forever,'' said reliever Derek
Lowe. ``It seemed like an eternity. Guys were fighting pitches off,
crazy things were going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's day grew even longer in the eighth, when Martinez's high
fly to right just dropped over the fence for a two-run home run
that made it 11-10. With Lowe crouched behind the mound in
disbelief, Jimy Williams paid a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if I knew what the score was,'' Lowe said. ``He
said we were still winning. He was laughing when he said it. He
said, `Go back out there and throw strikes.' I was able to go back
and get three outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled back, they battled back, but fortunately we
squeezed by.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck needed just two pitches to get the first two outs in the
ninth. Knoblauch rolled to Garciaparra, and Derek Jeter popped to
Offerman. O'Neill then drove an opposite-field single to left, but
Offerman gathered Williams's soft one-hopper on the edge of the
grass and delivered the last out to Stanley's grateful hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a hitter's day,'' Beck said after his second save in two
tries for the Sox. ``I'm just glad they swung at the first pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennant race, anybody?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to get in,'' Stanley said. ``Anything can
happen after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys don't know a whole lot about pressure. You know
they're going to come out tomorrow like gangbusters, and make sure
we don't sweep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
