<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SAIL-SAILING-AMERICAS     09-11 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-SAILING-AMERICASCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOOD GUY IN CUP CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In five weeks, competition begins in New Zealand in the first
series of challenger round-robins for the Louis Vuitton Cup,
leading to the America's Cup in February.
</P>
<P>
   Here in New England, the betting, by heart anyway, is firmly on
the New York Yacht Club's campaign, Young America, led by Cup
veteran John Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   But the New Yorkers are just one of five US challengers, with
another seven non-US challengers, not to mention the one big
defender, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   If the New Yorkers, whom we can loosely adopt as New England's
Team (after all, they are not the Yankees), can prevail against
fairly good odds, the Cup could be back in the Northeast by March.
</P>
<P>
   But, putting aside our dream of seeing the Cup return for one
more of those crazy Newport summers, what do cooler heads and
rational minds have to say about New York's chance to beat New
Zealand?
</P>
<P>
   We turn to one of the steadiest and most learned eyes on the Cup
waterfront, Gary Jobson. As ESPN yachting analyst since 1986,
Jobson has a deep background and is a professional student of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really three tiers,'' said Jobson by phone from his
office on the Annapolis waterfront recently. ``In the first is New
York, Italy, Paul Cayard (San Francisco), and Japan. These groups
have money, two boats, good teams, and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second tier is Dennis Conner (San Diego), France,
Spain, and (John) Kolius (Hawaii).
</P>
<P>
   ``Third tier are the Swiss, the Russians, and Young Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobson's criteria begins with the two-boat programs. It's hard
to imagine a program that can get one boat up to speed without a
benchmark boat newer than the 1995 generation, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jobson says his four top-tier syndicates are ``by themselves,
ahead of everyone else.'' Even the New Zealanders? The ultimate
question, of course. Answer below.
</P>
<P>
   New York has Marshall, head of the design team that helped
produce the 1986 Cup winner, Stars &AMP; Stripes, and a man very long
on experience, including the Young America campaign in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Fox/ESPN mini-debacle last winter, the New Yorkers
will have plenty of money to launch their full plan. But if money
alone were the key, Italy would have to be the odds-on favorite,
says Jobson, since it is awash in cash. The Italians also have
German Frers, Bill Koch's armada, and they've been at it for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's America One challenge has money, a strong team, a Bruce
Farr boat, and Cayard himself.
</P>
<P>
   Conner has just one boat, but a very strong and experienced
team, including such heavyweights as Ken Read, Mike Toppa, Peter
Isler, and Peter Holmberg.
</P>
<P>
   With six boats in the semifinals, rather than the usual four, a
US presence is all but guaranteed, and 2-4 US boats probably will
be there.
</P>
<P>
   As for The Question, whether anyone can beat the Kiwis in their
home waters, Jobson has two scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   --With plenty of money, racing in the waters they grew up in,
armed with the extensive local knowledge needed in tricky Auckland
conditions, and starting with the fastest IACC benchmark in
existence (Black Magic), the Kiwis win in a walk and retain the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   --With no defense trials to toughen them, with the pressure of
sailing at home, having lost a winning designer (Doug Peterson) to
Italy, and considering the fact that challengers have won three of
the past four Cups (not counting the looney-tunes catamaran show),
New Zealand gets beaten by one of the four big defenders if (a huge
if) none of them defects to tune up the Kiwis in the end.
</P>
<P>
   If, as tradition holds, the challengers stick together even
after they get eliminated, Jobson believes it will be difficult for
New Zealand to tune up enough to compete with the challenger that
survives five months of tough competition.
</P>
<P>
   But if some challenger agrees to sail with the Kiwis, all bets
are off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US groups may all hate each other,'' says Jobson, ``but in
the end they ought to close ranks against the defender. It's an
extremely important question.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
