</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JETSADV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE THREE FOR THE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The central story line is still Tuna,
the Jets, and the opener of the 1999 season, for better or for
worse, but it is also the debut of three Patriots rookies whose
performances _ good, bad, or ugly _ could significantly affect
Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   With center Damien Woody, middle linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer,
and running back Kevin Faulk all in key positions, this marks the
first time since 1991 that the Patriots have had three rookies
(offensive tackle Pat Harlow, running back Leonard Russell, and
strong safety Harry Colon) in the starting lineup on Opening Day.
The 1991 Patriots went 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   Woody will have to concern himself not only with the snaps to
Drew Bledsoe but also with making the blocking calls at the line of
scrimmage _ he needs to match up his mates on the line against the
Jets defensive front, look for potential blitzes, and make sure
that every pass rusher is accounted for, so Bledsoe doesn't suffer
another injury.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer must be effective in stopping Curtis Martin, which
means shedding blockers, mainly All-Pro center Kevin Mawae, and
must be able to defend against the pass as well.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk, the running back du jour, must hold on to the football,
first and foremost _ he mustn't do anything frivolous that would
give the Jets good field position. The Patriots are looking for a
sustained, patient running game. The goal of 4 yards per carry is
lofty, but necessary if New England is to grind away at a 3-4
defense that rarely allows big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go out there, I'll see something different,''
said Faulk. ``One of the biggest adjustments (from college) is the
speed of the game. And now they're telling me that the speed of the
regular-season games is faster than the preseason games. So that
part will take getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't fear it. I'm looking forward to it. I think I can
run the football. I don't think there's too much difference in
running it: You still have to find your holes and make the most of
every opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk will split time with veteran Terry Allen, who likely will
be used on third down in a short-yardage situations because he has
a history of getting tough yards. And the rookie also will be used
in tandem with Tebucky Jones on kickoff returns. The question is,
will the Jets' John Hall, who had 24 touchbacks in 84 kickoffs last
year, give Faulk a chance to show his return skills?
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make some plays,'' said Faulk, ``whether it's on
the kickoffs or running it.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jets' 3-4, Woody will line up face to face with
Jason Ferguson, a 6-foot-3-inch, 305-pound third-year nose tackle.
The rookie will have his hands full, for Ferguson is one of the
most underrated guys at his position. In 16 games last season, he
had 63 tackles and four sacks. But Dave Wohlabaugh did a nice job
against him in both 1998 games, and Woody is quicker than his
predecessor at center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been prepared pretty well for the game,'' said
Woody. ``I haven't gone up against this defense yet, so that will
be new, but they've prepared me for different situations and what
to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' scout team, which mimics the next week's
opposition in practice, has thrown everything possible at Woody.
All week the center has had to make blitz reads, and the coaching
staff thinks he's done a good job.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, who missed some practice during the week after
sprained his right ankle in the Carolina game, has been cleared to
play but will have to be at full strength to handle what the Jets
will be throwing at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand when you're a rookie you're going to be tested,''
said Katzenmoyer. ``I've never shied away from that or been awed by
that. I've been tested a lot, and I'll handle whatever they throw
at me. I'm just looking forward to my first pro game, to get one
under my belt and truly understand what it takes to make it in this
league. The adrenaline is going to be flowing, but I just have to
make sure I keep my cool and composure so I know what I'm doing out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll agrees, saying Katzenmoyer and his fellow rookies
will have to show ``great poise'' on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to trust our preparation,'' said the coach, ``and if
we do that, everything should take care of itself. I think we've
prepared these guys to play at a high level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
