<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BROWNS-B     09-11 2427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BROWNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNS IN GOOD HANDS WITH PALMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He wasn't supposed to be a tough guy, and most of the time, he's
not. At least not in the classic, growling Vince Lombardi sense.
But Chris Palmer has proven one thing to the satisfaction of the
new Cleveland Browns: He is tough when he needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you one thing, you do not want to cross him,'' says
offensive tackle Lomas Brown of the bespectacled ex-Patriots
quarterback coach who will lead the Browns into battle for the
first time Sunday night against the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off the field, he's more like a father figure, but he's like a
typical football player on the field. He's a gentle giant off the
field but on the field he's a bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer would never advertise himself as any kind of giant or
even a bear (unless he moved to Chicago). Nor would he try to make
the case that he's a tough guy in the mold of his former employers,
Bill Parcells and Tom Coughlin. But he wouldn't disagree with
Brown's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always agree with the players, I say,'' Palmer joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I don't think I've changed from the days I was at BU
or New Haven. Just because you say hello in the hallway and you're
nice to them doesn't mean you don't know how to do this job
properly. We want certain things done or there will be discipline.
That's part of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a daunting job, to be sure. After being named head coach
of the expansion version of the Browns on Jan. 21, Palmer set out
to build from scratch a team that can compete against franchises
that have been in existence in some cases for more than 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is an optimist, Palmer is also a realist. The job,
he understands, is all uphill in a town that is wild-eyed about the
return of the Browns after the hated Art Modell took the original
team to Baltimore under cover of darkness three years ago, trading
long tradition for long green.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tradition born of years of success dating back to Paul
Brown's days in the 1950s and of a knowledge of the game that runs
deep throughout the state. Ohio is football country, and Cleveland
is the capital of that country.
</P>
<P>
   Yet just how deep this tradition and understanding of the game
runs Palmer didn't begin to understand until one of his first trips
to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been more than I expected,'' Palmer said. ``Fans
here have such a passion for the team that until you're part of it,
it's difficult to comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my wife and I first flew in to look for a house, we're
waiting at the airport and a Hertz bus pulls up. The guy opens the
door and says, `Coach, get the quarterback (Tim Couch). Get what
you know.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What Palmer certainly knows is quarterbacks, having tutored two
of the game's best young ones in Drew Bledsoe and Mark Brunell. But
more impressive is that he found ways to win with other players,
men with considerably less going for them than Bledsoe and Brunell,
men like Jonathan Quinn last year and Rob Johnson a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer won in Jacksonville with both after Brunell was injured
and then he won some more when Brunell returned. In New England,
Bledsoe's improvement after Palmer took over as quarterback coach
in 1996 was equally impressive.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmer's effect on an offense doesn't stop there. When he
tutored the Houston Oilers' receivers, the team led the league in
passing each season, and when he handled New England's receivers,
they became the first group in league history to have five players
with 50 receptions or more. You see production long enough and you
conclude that it's a trend, not an accident.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that Palmer knows how to run an offense, and he's
shown this summer, at least to Lomas Brown's satisfaction, that he
also knows how to run a team. Of course, he's had a little help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been so busy I think I've only been out one time with my
family since we got here,'' Palmer said. ``I took my wife and kids
to dinner and I went to the men's room and there were a couple of
guys in there who'd had a few drinks. One of them says, `Hey,
you're the coach,' and I say I am and nice to meet them and go into
a stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing I hear is a guy tapping on the stall saying, `Hey,
coach, throw the ball more.' When I got back to our table I told my
wife, `The bathroom wants me to pass more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer may actually pass less than people expect this season, at
least as long as veteran Ty Detmer is in the lineup ahead of Couch.
It had been Palmer's plan all along to start Detmer and bring Couch
along slowly, but he also promised both that the best player would
start.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear now that the starter will be Detmer, but not solely
to protect young Couch from bewildering NFL defenses and his own
team's shortcomings. Detmer will be the starter because that's the
way Palmer said it would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim would be the starting quarterback in a lot of
situations,'' Palmer said. ``He played well this summer. But so did
Ty. I told them the best guy would play at every position. Ty
started the summer as our No. 1 quarterback and he played well
enough to hold Tim off.
</P>
<P>
   ``At New England, when Drew arrived, he was so clearly the best
player he had to play. Tim is closing the gap, but it's not the
same situation at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, on the eve of his first game, Cleveland's new tough guy
is just as glad it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the situation we're in,'' Palmer said. ``We
understand we have to play as a team to win because we don't have a
game-breaker. In New England, Drew could turn to Terry (Glenn) or
Shawn (Jefferson) and say, `Run deep,' and they can run deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've told our players this. You can believe what you hear
and read or you can go out and do more. We don't have guys who
strike fear in a defense, but that doesn't mean we can't execute.''
</P>
<P>
   If they do, these new Browns could make an old town proud before
this night is over. If they don't, they could make a tough guy
angry.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion deadline nears
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move, Expansion Committee co-chairmen Bob Kraft
and Jerry Richardson have been added to the list of people who will
meet with prospective franchise owners from Los Angeles and Houston
Monday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting of the Expansion Committee and commissioner Paul
Tagliabue last week in Washington that one owner described as
filled ``with a lot of divergent opinions,'' Kraft and Richardson
were asked to the meeting, which was called to study the state of
the LA stadium proposals before Wednesday's deadline to either go
forward with a vote that gave the expansion team to Los Angeles or
withdraw that approval and go back to either Houston or the drawing
board.
</P>
<P>
   A full owners meeting is set for Oct. 6 in Atlanta, and there
will be an Expansion Committee meeting Oct. 5 to formulate a final
recommendation on a situation that has become a mess.
</P>
<P>
   LA's Coliseum group is clearly in retreat, with little or no
public money behind it. Meanwhile, Marvin Davis, the oilman and
failed baseball team owner, has waded in and convinced some owners
that he's ready to put a ton of money up for a franchise fee if his
Hollywood Park stadium plan is accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Davis holds an option on the Hollywood Park property and some
believe he and Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis may be conspiring to
allow Davis to move his franchise back to Los Angeles. Davis's
group and the Coliseum group will appear in New York Monday, as
will Bob McNair, who is spearheading the Houston bid.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners like McNair's plan, which is believed to be the best
financing and stadium plan ever presented to the league. Others
want him to pay a higher franchise fee than the $500 million under
discussion. Problem is, they cannot even begin to talk to him about
that until after Wednesday. Otherwise they risk a lawsuit from the
Los Angeles representatives, who hold the exclusive rights to the
franchise until then.
</P>
<P>
   It was written here several weeks ago that the league is likely
to tell McNair to go ahead with his stadium construction, though he
will not know for another 18 months whether he's getting an
expansion team or an existing team. There are two problems with
such a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   First, the league has been told privately that some, possibly
all, of the public financing now on the table that makes the
Houston plan so compelling could disappear if McNair is not the
owner of the team because local politicians know him and trust him
and have based their strong support on his being involved.
</P>
<P>
   Second, McNair is not interested in being told by the NFL which
team would come to Houston if he doesn't get the expansion
franchise. If he is not going to be awarded that 32d franchise,
McNair would just as soon negotiate his own deal to buy one of the
current teams, rather than have the league decide who's coming. He
does not want to get the stadium built only to see another owner
move into his house.
</P>
<P>
   McNair has said little publicly and continues to maintain that
he understands the league's reasoning for wanting a team in Los
Angeles, the nation's second-biggest TV market. He has been well
schooled by Richardson, the Panthers owner and a friend dating back
to their college days.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Richardson cautioned McNair to stay focused on
getting a team and not engage in public complaints or controversy.
But if Oct. 6 comes and the LA proposal remains muddled while his
continues to be ignored, he may run out of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Out of malignment
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells was asked what he thought of the ``much maligned''
Bledsoe. He reacted in typical Parcellsian fashion. `` `Much
maligned?' '' Parcells shot back. ``Put him on the free agent
market and see how much maligned he is. They didn't win many before
he got there and they've won many since he arrived.'' . . .
Whenever the Tuna Bowl approaches, old Parcells stories surface.
This past week, Patriot cornerback Ty Law recalled his first
encounter with the irascible coach. It was during the initial
minicamp after Parcells had drafted Law on the first round in 1995,
a move considered surprising by some. Law had worked out diligently
all winter and spring after deciding to leave Michigan early but he
finally tired and took some time off as the draft approached. By
the time of that minicamp, he had ballooned to 205 pounds and ran a
poor 40 time, which led Parcells to bellow at him. ``He says, `Law,
you look like you got the mumps! You're going to be the first
first-rounder cut,' '' Law recalled with a grin. Despite a new
contract that carries a $14.5 million signing bonus, Law continues
to motivate himself with memories of such slights. ``After I signed
my new contract, people started asking how it would affect me,''
Law said. ``It won't. I can't see anything changing for me. People
don't know why I train like I train and do what I do. I never
played for money. I still remember the only time I made the cover
of Sports Illustrated was when Michael Westbrook caught that Hail
Mary pass (over Law and half the secondary to beat Michigan on the
final play in 1994). I'm going to make the cover for doing
something good. People still want me to sign that Sports
Illustrated cover. At first I didn't want to do it, but then I
started thinking, `OK, that's me. I'll sign.' I don't dwell on the
past _ good or bad. I look to the future. Money didn't change
anything.'' . . . Parcells had a tough day when he had to release
old favorites Corwin Brown and Keith Byars, but he again retained
special teams anchor and backup quarterback Ray Lucas, a move
looked upon with surprise by some in New York. ``I just feel he's a
better player than you guys thought,'' Parcells explained to
reporters. ``Ray brings something to the game and I wanted to have
him around.'' Still, it was an emotional moment for Parcells,
because he has grown so close to Brown that last winter he brought
him to the annual combine workouts in Indianapolis because Brown
one day hopes to become a coach himself. ``One of the most
difficult cuts I've had in many years,'' Parcells said. ``He's one
of those guys who have been in the foxhole with me for a long time.
He wants to coach and I told him I'd be interested.'' . . . Both
the Patriots and Jets will have a rookie starting on the offensive
line Sunday. New England has center Damien Woody (as well as
relatively untested guard Heath Irwin), while the Jets have
second-round pick Randy Thomas at guard. Parcells chose to cut Ian
Beckles, who had started 122 of 127 games in his career, including
16 last year for the Eagles, to keep three rookies and converted
tackle Kerry Jenkins at the guard position . . . Speaking for the
first time since his 45-day holdout began, Seattle wide receiver
Joey Galloway said that while he is loyal to the Seahawks, he's
more loyal to his family and to good sense. ``I can't accept
playing for something that's way below market value,'' said
Galloway, who was asked to be the key man in the Seattle offense
this fall for $1.6 million. He has turned down a seven-year, $35
million extension that includes a $7 million signing bonus and is
seeking a shorter deal (five years) for less money ($25 million)
but more up-front cash ($10 million signing bonus). New head
coach/GM Mike Holmgren appears to be making a stand with Galloway,
one of the league's most productive receivers the past four years,
saying he had made his final offer and would begin reducing it each
week he believes Galloway will be unable to play. The major
sticking point, Galloway said, is that Green Bay receiver Antonio
Freeman just signed a bigger contract than what Galloway is being
offered, yet ``everyone has had a chance to see my numbers have
been better than his.'' Holmgren, who coached Freeman in Green Bay,
says it depends on how you look at things. Each entered the NFL in
1995, and over that four-year span, Galloway has 261 receptions for
4,122 yards and 36 touchdowns while Freeman has 229 receptions for
3,706 yards and 36 touchdowns. But if you throw out their rookie
season, when Freeman didn't start a game and had only eight
receptions while Galloway started 16 and had 67, the numbers look
different. Over the past three years, Freeman has 221 catches to
Galloway's 194, for 3,600 yards to 3,083, and has 35 touchdowns to
Galloway's 29. Holmgren reiterated that he will not trade Galloway,
even though at least 15 teams have contacted the Seahawks about
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
