<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-WOMENFINAL?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENA TAKES VICTORY OVER HINGIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Serena did what her big sister could not.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams turns 18 in a couple of weeks. Saturday, she
helped her family get a little revenge and enjoyed an early
birthday celebration as she beat Martina Hingis, the world's No. 1
player, in a scintillating performance.
</P>
<P>
   Williams prevailed, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) to win her first major title.
Hingis had beaten Venus Williams in Friday's semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Serena had never reached the quarterfinals of a major
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   She had never faced this kind of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Nerves? Never.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe a little. Serena did falter a bit in closing out the
match.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis wriggled free of a couple of match points in the ninth
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very upset with myself,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   It was 4-4 in the second-set tiebreaker and Hingis was serving.
</P>
<P>
   First serve: fault. Second serve: Williams whacked a forehand
winner and it was 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Williams served and moved to the net. She drilled a couple of
backhands deep and Hingis tried a desperate lob to get Williams off
the net. It fell just long and Williams was a point away.
</P>
<P>
   Williams turned her back to the net and caught her breath. She
kicked a serve wide. After a short volley, Hingis hit a backhand
long and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Williams staggered back behind the baseline for several seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `should I scream? Should I yell? Should I
cry?' '' Williams said. ``What should I do? I guess I did them all.
It was so exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a glorious moment.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, the first African-American woman to win the US
Open since Althea Gibson won a pair in 1957 and '58.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, avenger of her sister's semifinal loss.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, collector of $750,000 for her win.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, US Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, she was at the net to accept congratulations from Hingis.
Then she headed into a corner of Arthur Ashe Stadium and pulled
herself up into a box of seats to kiss her mother, Oracene. Her
father, Richard, who long has predicted championships for his
girls, came down to meet her on the court.
</P>
<P>
   A little later, President Clinton called from New Zealand to
congratulate her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure my day couldn't get any better,'' Williams
said. ``Next thing I knew, someone was telling me, `The President
of the United States wants to talk to you.' I was thinking, `wow.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in control most of the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always a step late,'' Hingis said. ``She was always
leading. I felt like I was always behind. I was always being
defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, down a break in the second set and serving at 3-5, was
in deep trouble at 15-40. Williams had two match points. But could
not convert them.
</P>
<P>
   On the first, Williams hit a backhand wide and long. On the
next, a backhand into the net. Hingis held on but faced more
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Williams served for the match. And Hingis broke her at love.
Hingis held serve and then had a break point in a long Game 12, but
could not get it and it went to the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Williams dictated play throughout. In the first set, she had 25
unforced errors, but 19 winners. The totals for Hingis: five
unforced errors, one winner.
</P>
<P>
   For the match, Williams had 57 unforced errors and 36 winners.
Hingis had 24 and seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' she said of the 57 errors. ``I mean, imagine if I stop
making those errors?''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up finish put a bookend finish on this year's majors
for Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   She won the Australian, lost in the finals of the French to
Steffi Graf (she was so upset she had to be led back to the awards
ceremony by her mother and coach, Melanie Molitor). At Wimbledon,
she asked her mother to stay away and lost in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's back and smiling again.
</P>
<P>
   Informed that Richard Williams had said she was scared at the
end of the match, she replied that Serena seemed more scared and
had trouble finishing her off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my chances and I didn't take them,'' Hingis said.
``There are many more years to come against the Williams sisters.
It didn't happen today, but there are many more Grand Slams and
finals to come. Hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   And Serena?
</P>
<P>
   She did a round of interviews and then headed out to play a
doubles semifinal match with her big sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
