<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-MENSEMIFIN     09-11 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-MENSEMIFINALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI, MARTIN WIN IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is an all-American final for the 1999 US Open
men's tennis title. It's just not the all-American final
anticipated when this tournament began nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi was expected to be there. Todd Martin was not.
</P>
<P>
   In the semifinals Saturday, second-seeded Agassi survived a
rough start to beat No. 3 seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov, 1-6, 6-3, 6-3,
6-3. No. 7 Martin survived a rough two weeks and then cruised past
unseeded Cedric Pioline, 6-4, 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   It is a matchup of not-so-young Americans. Both finalists turned
29 earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi is 9-5 against Martin and they have split the last four
matches. But Agassi has the edge on hard courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he can play great tennis really on any surface, because he
has the ability to play aggressively and to hit through any court,
even clay,'' Agassi said. ``I mean, if he's really on his game, he
can take returns early and hit them hard, deep and low, get behind
it. He's 6 foot 6. It's hard to get the ball behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was certainly on his game Saturday, and Agassi expects to
see the best of him Sunday. He may have anticipated facing Pete
Sampras (before the No. 1 seed was forced to withdraw with a bad
back), but he's not about to take Martin lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done some incredible things to get here,'' Agassi said.
``It's been great watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Agassi completed his latest comeback when he won
the French Open for the first time. It was his fourth major title
and gave him the cycle: He has won each of them once. This will be
Agassi's fourth US Open final. He beat Michael Stich in 1994 _ in
his first comeback _ and lost to Sampras in both '90 and '95.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the second time Martin has made a major final. He
lost to Sampras in the '94 Australian.
</P>
<P>
   Upsets helped clear the way for both players; Kafelnikov was the
first seed Agassi faced.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi and Kafelnikov split two uninspiring sets. Agassi, who
was not serving well at the start, broke serve in the opening game
of the third set and began to take control of the match.
</P>
<P>
   He was rolling in the fourth set _ recording nine of his 11 aces
_ but he had a little trouble closing out Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov was serving at 2-5 and Agassi squandered one match
point. Ahead, 5-3, Agassi served for the match and fell into a
15-40 hole. He dug his way out, missed another match point, and
then put it away with a service winner followed by a Kafelnikov
forehand into the net.
</P>
<P>
   While Agassi was making his way through the bottom half of the
draw, the top half opened up for Martin. No Pete. No Patrick
Rafter. And Martin had to face only one seeded player on his way to
the semis _ no one rated higher than his No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But he faced plenty of drama, even after Sampras pulled out and
Rafter was taken out by Pioline, retiring in the fifth set of their
first-round match.
</P>
<P>
   There was a first-round match when he was up two sets on
qualifier Stephane Huet and then had to rally to win in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fourth-round test, when he was out on his feet
against Greg Rusedski (down two sets) and somehow pulled it out.
</P>
<P>
   There was little drama in his semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Martin just crushed Pioline and in the process livened up the
finale. Maybe it won't be automatic for Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Martin played great, but he isn't necessarily counting on doing
that Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to play great,'' he said. ``You only have to play
better than the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly did Saturday. This was no contest. He picked
Pioline apart.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ripped returns. He hit groundstrokes deep. Angled
volleys. Tickled the lines.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Pioline was talking to himself, shaking his head,
and kicking balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played too good,'' Pioline said. ``He was reading the ball
very well today, catching everything, very few unforced errors,
serving big.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioline peaked in the very first game. And that had Martin a
little concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline had four break points on Martin's serve. But Martin
served out of trouble each time, saving serve with a pair of
service games.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Martin had his first service break. Pioline got that one
back late in the first set. But in the next game Martin broke right
back, ripping a return that Pioline could not handle, and he rolled
from there.
</P>
<P>
   The first set took 42 minutes. The rest of the match took 54.
And by the way, Martin never disagreed with Kafelnikov's statement
after his third-round match that either he, Agassi, or Richard
Krajicek was going to win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to be here myself,'' Martin said. ``Given the
right circumstances and playing well, I thought I had a great
chance to be in the final. When somebody speaks in the
quarterfinal, it's going out on a limb, regardless of who you pick.
I told CBS the other day I agreed with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
