<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-EWING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING'S ANKLE A SORE SPOT FOR KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, wouldn't you like to have been the proverbial fly on the
wall in those Madison Square Garden boardrooms last week? Franchise
center Patrick Ewing, who is in the breakdown lane of his NBA
career, says not only that he is still sore, but, well, sayonara to
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The partially torn Achilles' tendon has mended, he said. But the
tendinitis in the area (left ankle) is still there and Ewing won't
put on a uniform until it's not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be ready for camp. Hopefully, the regular
season,'' he said at the Wheelchair All-Star Game in New York.
``I'm in the mindset to get healthy and that's it. I'm not going to
play on it, then sit out. I'm not going to go through what I went
through last year. I'm not going to play until I'm sure I'm healthy
and won't reinjure it. I did the same with my wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. After missing most of the 1997-98 season with
a shattered wrist, he returned in the second round of the playoffs
and the Knicks went out and lost just fine with him. He was there
and his wrist was so-so and he didn't make much of a difference.
This past season, after being in and out of the lineup, he finally
pulled up lame in the conference finals against the Pacers. He
watched the NBA Finals in an expensive suit.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, of course, is doing the right thing. At 37, the body
doesn't heal or respond the way it did when he was 27. (Wait till
he hits 40.) Using standard sports logic, it'll be more beneficial
to have him healthy for the playoffs. It makes sense for him to be
completely healthy assuming, of course, that such a blissful state
exists for him at this point.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that Ewing is being indefinite about any
timetable (``when the swelling goes away, I'll be ready''), and
that's not a situation anyone likes. It's also New York and we all
saw what happened last year when he sat out. Jeff Van Gundy found
out he had a bench and a fast team that played differently _
sometimes better _ without Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Van Gundy has to know now what he has. (Hint:
Marcus Camby is No. 23, the big guy with the Chinese scrawl on his
arm.) He has to know what's in store. (Hint: Latrell Sprewell likes
to get up and down the floor.) And, yes, Charlie Ward and Chris
Childs are still the point guards. (Two out of three isn't bad.)
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Ewing's revelation was probably some news that the
Y2Knicks could have done without. The Knicks feel a healthy,
contributing Ewing is essential to claiming a championship flag.
But the only flag we saw this past week was a red one, with Ewing
carrying it. He has every right to wait until everything feels
fine. The two questions he can't answer are how long that will take
and how he will know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't even run on the ankle yet _ and training camp starts
in a month. His backup is also hurt. Allan Houston is even
volunteering to man the middle, adding, ``Believe me, we've been
through worse.'' And most of those times have been when Ewing has
been on the sideline, as he is now.
</P>
<P>
   Cross off Kris
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 NBA draft may go down now as an official Waste of Time
for the Celtics. The player they drafted, Kris Clack, the Texas
guard that they ``couldn't believe'' slipped all the way to 55,
won't even be invited to training camp. ``We feel Kris needs more
time and seasoning to get to the NBA level,'' GM Chris Wallace
said. ``He's not going to get that with us.'' Clack played for the
Celtics in their summer league, but not well enough to warrant an
invitation. ``He really needs to work on getting his body in shape
and learning what his game is,'' Wallace said. The Celtics would
like Clack to play in the new International Basketball League,
whose Baltimore franchise has his rights. Another option is the
Continental Basketball Association. As of now, the Celtics have 15
players on scholarship and Rick Pitino may decide to leave it at
that. ``He's not a big believer in bringing in players just to be
in camp,'' Wallace said. Of those 15, however, two (Greg Minor,
Pervis Ellison) are potential injury-list candidates . . . Kenny
Anderson also showed up at the Wheelchair Games and didn't seem all
that upset about the loss of Ron Mercer. (Maybe because it means
more shots for him?) ``I like our team right now,'' said Anderson.
``What it does for me is put more responsibility on me in the
backcourt. And I like that, because I didn't feel I had that last
year.'' (What planet was he living on?) Anderson also said Mercer
``was asking for X amount of money and didn't do, you know, X
amount of work. It's kind of strange.'' Did he think Mercer wanted
out of Boston? ``I think so. But you know, sometimes the grass
isn't greener on the other side. He's in Denver now. What's the
difference there? It's a business thing, but did he re-sign with
them? No. Now you've got to play out a season to get his money?
It's a rough situation. Now you've got him on a Nick Van
Exel-(Antonio) McDyess team. I hope it works out for him. I've got
no gripes or bad things to say about him. But sometimes, being in
the league long enough, you learn the grass ain't greener on the
other side.'' . . . As for former Pitino favorite Bruce Bowen, he
was in Las Vegas working out with the Milwaukee Bucks. He's been
getting some one-on-one attention and Milwaukee did lose Michael
Curry via free agency. Bowen also has drawn interest from Seattle,
Miami, New York, and San Antonio, but agent Steve Kauffman has yet
to hear those magic words: ``guaranteed contract.'' The Spurs may
decide to opt for Chucky Brown and then there's a drought at small
forward (Shandon Anderson excepted). However, teams like Orlando
will be forced to make cuts, further flooding the market. ``As far
as the supply/demand goes, the numbers look bad,'' Kauffman said.
``It's really out of whack. And it's not fun relating this to my
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing channels
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fiorentino, who has been a part of the Miami Heat's
basketball operation since Day One and is the last holdover from
the pre-Pat Riley days, has been moved over to the television side.
Riley has brought in Marc Iavaroni from Cleveland to join Bob
McAdoo and Stan Van Gundy on the bench . . . Speaking of the
Cavaliers, center Zydrunas Ilgauskas has been cleared to play after
missing most of last year with a broken foot. That came as welcome
news to new coach Randy Wittman . . . Television viewers in San
Antonio are seeing the first wave of commercials promoting the
construction of a new ``Save The Spurs'' arena. Voters will decide
Nov. 2 whether to approve increases in both rental car and
hotel/motel taxes to pay for the $175 million building. While the
ads suggest that San Antonio will still have low hotel taxes, those
in the biz think the spots are misleading. In addition, city
officials are still upset that the Spurs wouldn't back an arena
proposal that would have been funded by an increase in the sales
tax. The Spurs say they cannot compete in the Alamodome and will
have to move if a new arena is not built . . . The Houston Rockets
are the latest NBA team to take a flyer on former Celtic Thomas
``Big Ham'' Hamilton. No word on how much he weighs . . . Agent
Bill Duffy is heading to China, which could well be the next great
frontier for the NBA. The Mavericks drafted Chinese center Wang
Zhi-Zhi in the second round (No. 36) in June and may well have him
for the 2000-01 season. (He's in the People's Army right now.)
Duffy also is high on 19-year-old Yao Ming, who happens to be 7
feet 5 inches. ``He'll probably be in the draft not next year but
the following year,'' Duffy said. Duffy represents Bateer Menk, a
23-year-old, 6-11 Chinese player who appeared in the Desert Classic
last spring and may end up in the IBL in Las Vegas. ``These players
all have ability,'' Duffy said. ``The problem is that they play a
completely different game, almost genteel. You don't have anyone
like Anthony Mason over there. It's not a very physical game. They
don't get into your face.'' . . . Speaking of Mason, he also was at
the Wheelchair Game and didn't mince words about the rule changes
that will attempt to eliminate gratuitious roughness, a Mason
trademark. ``I thought it was garbage,'' Mason sniffed. ``Every
year, you're going to have people changing something. You've got a
bunch of people on the (rules committee) who don't play anymore.
When they played, it was basically wrestling. Now, they're trying
to make the game more sissified. In the WNBA, the girls are allowed
to play harder than we're allowed to play. The rules will slow the
game down.'' The changes, whatever they are, will be adopted by the
NBA Board of Governors prior to the league meetings two weeks from
now in Vancouver. However, the league will offer a video
presentation to the teams at the meetings and hope the message gets
transmitted down to the common folk . . . Atlanta's new arena opens
this weekend with an exhibition hockey game and then, a bit later,
officially, with an Elton John concert. ``We still need every day
we can get through October to get it ready,'' said Hawks president
Stan Kasten. The Hawks, however, decided to play their ``home''
exhibition game against the Celtics in Biloxi, Miss. Wait until the
players find out there's a casino next door to the arena . . . So
Michael Curry, how hard was it to leave Milwaukee and go back to
Detroit? ``It was an easy decision,'' he said. ``If Milwaukee went
five years, like Detroit did, it would have been a tough decision.
But when you're a year and $2 million off, it's an easy decision.''
Curry said he had six or seven legitimate offers of three or more
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
