<HEADER>
A8867 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARTER-B     09-11 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER A SECONDARY TARGET OF JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde will be on the other side of the line, sure to
be looking for him even if he might not be looking at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our slogan this year is, `Start over,' '' said Testaverde, the
New York Jets quarterback. ``Last year means nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' Chris Carter will not be starting over, but
starting out, New England's last line of defense at safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be nervous,'' said Carter. ``Just a little
something called anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   This, anxiety and all, is a role he relishes. The anxiety will
disappear, he's sure, once he hits his first Jet. After that, it
will be football, Testaverde ``starting over'' by going after
Carter, and Carter hoping to keep his cool, hoping to keep his
wits. He will be a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a general rule, go after the new guy, or if somebody goes
down, they go after the guy who comes in, that's the general
rule,'' said Carter. ``But I'm not looking forward to their going
away from me; I'm looking forward to their coming after me. And
when I see that, my eyes get bright, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Other defenders can make mistakes and teammates can help. But
when the free safety makes a mistake, only white lines are between
the opponent and the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's words are sure and his analogy quick when talking about
this do-or-die role of his. He reaches for his other love in life
beyond football to make his point. Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm planning on going to med school and studying cardiology,''
said New England's new free safety. ``As a cardiologist, you're
pretty much the last line of defense. If you mess up there, it's
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   One cannot be faint of heart as a cardiologist or a free safety.
</P>
<P>
   Carry on the analogy. Patriot fans have palpitations heading
into the new season Sunday, palpitations over their team's defense.
New faces and new bodies are on that defense, Carter's being one of
the more prominent. Hearts flutter and questions leap out; how good
will these new players be?
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde openly stated what Patriot fans fear, that teams will
try to run the ball against New England's defense until the
Patriots show they can stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked on our running game very hard this training
camp,'' said Testaverde, ``and that will help us keep teams
off-balance. Hopefully, it will keep New England off-balance this
week. We really want our running game to work for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But, take this to heart; the Jets will also throw the football.
And then will come the battle between the wily veteran and the
young safety who, admittedly, will be feeling some anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a better quarterback than I was even a year ago,''
said Testaverde. ``That's because I understand this offense better.
And, most of all, I'm trying to go to the right spot with the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Football may be the ultimate team game, but there are 11
one-on-one battles each and every play that decide the trend of the
game. One of the more significant battles will be Testaverde versus
Carter. The Jets' game plan surely will be to try to confuse the
new safety.
</P>
<P>
   And Testaverde is the wily veteran, the veteran who prides
himself ``on staying very calm when the lawnmower starts.'' The
lawnmower? That was Baltimore coach Ted Marchibroda's phrase when
Testaverde played there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there's all this noise around you but you have to
stay cool,'' said Testaverde. ``And I think I've gotten better at
that since last year because this system we have here allows me to
stay focused on my job and my job alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Carter will try to stay cool when that lawnmower revs
up and Giants Stadium grows very loud. The game _ and the Patriots'
season, to be blunt _ could well swing to a large degree on how
well Carter does his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get out there, mentally I'll be going over what I'm
supposed to do and I'll try to get relaxed and be focused,'' said
Carter. ``I'll be anxious but by game time I'll be ready to play.
This is the greatest game in the world, the NFL. You can't get any
higher than this. `Exciting' is an understatement for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is very bright (National Honor Society in high school,
national academic honors at Texas), and his pre-med focus was in
kinesiology. Yet his job in football is that fine blend of hitting
other players very hard while at the same time being a defensive
quarterback who must instantly recognize what formations the other
team lines up in and what untold number of moves the offensive
players can make from those formations. Sometimes, Carter conceded,
there can be too much thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Patriots' persistent problems last year in giving up
first downs when they went into nickel and dime packages on
third-and-long situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we tried to overplay a lot of teams on third down,''
said Carter. ``We tried to outthink them and we tried to do things
to take away their best thing, and teams adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this year, we're planning on just doing our basic things
and winning our one-on-one matchups. Everybody has their matchups
on third down, one of our tackles on their guard, Willie (McGinest)
coming off the end, one of our linebackers on their backs. We all
have one-on-one matchups we have to win and that's what it comes
down to on third down.''
</P>
<P>
   If enough spotlights are not on Carter already, the brightest
one is still being warmed up. Carter, after all, replaces wily
veteran Willie Clay, who was dumped two days before camp opened.
Comparisons between Clay and Carter will be made all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't add any pressure on me at all,'' argued Carter.
``I'm a different player from Willie. All players are different.
Maybe Willie makes a tackle by grabbing the right leg and I grab
the left leg. We're just different people. I'm not thinking about
Willie because the cohesiveness of the defense is the main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   All he can do, said Carter, ``is work hard. Anytime you're
stagnant, you're falling back. It's always a constant effort to go
forward, to push forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bill Parcells and Testaverde will be coming at him Sunday
afternoon. Work has gotten Carter this far, but the next step?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' he said. ``They can come at me any way they want to.
I'm prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
