<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DOWNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNEY LOOKING FOR A FIGHTING CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ The numbers tumble from Aaron Downey's tongue
with unabashed enthusiasm. He knows them by heart. No need to
consult hockey's official guide and record book or pull a tattered,
yellowed newspaper clipping from his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   A fighter's hands aren't made for carrying resumes. He's got all
the vitals memorized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got good numbers,'' declared Downey, not quoting his
goals and assists, but rather his total penalty minutes each of the
past five seasons. ``I've got 320, 358, 338, 407, and 401. And the
best part about 'em, I never cost my team, not once. I've always
taken a guy with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is not yet so politically correct that contenders such as
Downey must pretend their greatest attribute is something that it's
not. He's a fighter, an enforcer, a man for hire. As a member of
the Baby Bruins the last two years, the 25-year-old right wing has
led the American Hockey League in PIMs both seasons. If he's going
to make it to Boston this year, or anytime soon, he'll be delivered
there by the strength of his steeled knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an optimistic guy,'' said Downey, who grew up on his
parents' farm in Shelburne, Ontario, some 90 minutes north of
Toronto. ``I come from a good family farm, and I just do the best I
can every day, and if it doesn't work out, it doesn't work out _
but it won't be because I didn't try. I just put myself in a
scenario where I want to do the best I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario, in Downey's mind, would find him on a line with
Ken Belanger, his former teammate in Guelph (Ontario), two tough
wingers paired with a pivot that could form a formidable crash line
_ like the Bobby Holik-Mike Peluso-Randy McKay combination that
helped the Devils to the Stanley Cup in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd make a heck of a line,'' said Downey. ``I think
we could bring some real energy to the FleetCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless things change dramatically in the two-plus weeks leading
to the season opener, Belanger will be Downey's greatest obstacle.
There are only so many jobs on the police force and Belanger is the
returning beat cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what he does in the exhibtion games,'' said
ex-cop Pat Burns, the Bruins' coach, whose club took on the Sabres
here Saturday night in each team's exhibition opener. ``I think
Belanger is your legitimate tough guy. The question is: how many do
you need? Now, if (Downey) could do something else, maybe beat
someone out for a different job _ who knows? _ we might need a
fourth-line type of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons, there are open jobs on Boston's front
line. Tim Taylor is now a Ranger. P.J. Axelsson hasn't come to
contract terms. Dmitri Khristich won big in arbitration and then
lost bigger when the Bruins cut him loose as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   If Downey can mix in some unexpected skill over the next
fortnight, as he believes he can, then he could be reciting some
new numbers _ NHL games played _ after the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's like being on the farm,'' said Downey.
``They don't tell me much, but I've got a job, and I know how to do
it. Back on the farm, if I've got a $100,000 piece of equipment out
there, then I'm out there cultivating potatoes. That's the job, and
you've got a lot at stake with that machine and with what's in the
ground. And here I am now, in the NHL, playing with the elite
players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What all that shows me is, I've got a job, right now, and I've
got to make the most of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
