<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.-OPEN-WOMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS PROVES FATHER KNOWS BEST IN WINNING U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Richard Williams turned out to be a
prophet after all.
</P>
<P>
   Not two weeks ago, when he predicted a U.S. Open final between
daughters Venus and Serena, but last year, when he was asked which
sister would be the better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena is the best one,'' he said then. ``What makes me think
she will be better is she had years to sit around and watch Venus
and see what Venus' mistakes were. She always was a better athlete
than Venus to start off with. She hits the ball harder. She returns
serve better. She places the ball better.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena succeeded yesterday where her big sister failed. Venus
lost to top-ranked Martina Hingis in the semifinals, but Serena
struck a blow for family pride with a 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) upset victory
in the U.S. Open women's final before a raucous crowd at the
National Tennis Center. She became the second African-American
woman to win a Grand Slam singles title, joining Althea Gibson, who
won the last of her five singles titles in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, the 17-year-old who wasn't considered mentally
tough enough, who never before had advanced past the quarterfinal
of a Grand Slam tournament, became the first member of the family
to win a major singles event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty exciting,'' she said. ``I was thinking should I
scream, or yell, or cry, what should I do? I think I ended up doing
them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as she did when they were growing up, Serena learned from
her older sister. After watching Hingis win in the semifinals on
Friday, she immediately headed to a practice court.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I saw Martina had won, I thought I had to go out and
improve also,'' she said. ``I hit some groundstrokes and serves.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the serve that proved to be the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Serena's serve remained a weapon all during her match. She
continued to hit her first serve in on the big points and managed
to keep pressure on Hingis even with her second serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can serve it,'' she said. ``Even if I miss my first
serve I'm still going for it, because I feel I can make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis' serve, on the other hand, was ineffective. Williams
picked on her soft second serve, stepping well into the court to
crank winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't push the ball over the net,'' Hingis said. ``She
just kills it. I didn't serve very well. That's the biggest thing I
have to improve in my game. I have to put more of those first
serves in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis entered the match as the favorite. She is the top-ranked
player in the world, and owns five Grand Slam singles titles. But
after needing three sets and two hours to beat Venus, she was a
step slow yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't stay focused and concentrated,'' she said. ``I
usually react better. Today I was moving in slow motion.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the prevailing pre-match theory, it shouldn't have
mattered. Her first Grand Slam final was supposed to reduce
Williams to a quivering mass of nerves. The butterfly that Venus
wears around her neck was supposed to be in Serena's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she came out firing. She broke Hingis the first time
she served and, despite facing break points in each of her service
games, she didn't fold.
</P>
<P>
   She made mistakes _ 25 unforced errors _ but made up for it with
19 winners on her way to winning the first set.
</P>
<P>
   Williams appeared to be on her way to an easy victory when she
broke in the seventh game of the second set, held for a 5-3 lead
and, with Hingis serving again, earned two match points with a
forehand winner.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when the nerves arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The match points disappeared on a wild backhand and a forehand
into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I lost those two match points I was very upset with
myself,'' she said. ``I was like Serena, this can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis held, but Williams still was serving for the match. She
didn't win a point, though, committing four unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something went dreadfully wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It continued to go wrong the next time she served, and Hingis
held a set point. Williams, though, gave herself a pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time when you have to stop caving,'' she said. ``I
said you're going to have to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams held to force the tiebreaker and won the match when
Hingis made the final mistake, hitting a backhand long.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
