<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping rare chemistry tough for team on rise
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The game will be played today in front of a sold-out
Georgia Dome crowd of 70,000, with millions more watching on
national television. But the Falcons began building for this
showdown with the Vikings, building for this season, halfway
through 1997 _ when they were 1-7.
</P>
<P>
   That's when, even after winning just a single game in the first
half of the season, character was most apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at two years ago,'' quarterback Chris Chandler said. ``A
lot of the same guys still in this locker room were here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in so many situations where, at that point, guys
tank,'' said Chandler, who has played for five other NFL teams.
``They're done. They want to get the season over with. And they
have a tendency to clash with guys who are true professionals, who
want to keep playing hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, two years ago, it never happened. There were very few,
if any, guys who stopped caring.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons won six of their last eight in the '97 season and
then went 16-2 last season before losing to the Broncos in Super
Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a cliche. But as the Falcons try to put together
consecutive winning seasons for the first time in their 34 years,
it bears repeating: Chemistry matters. The cohesion in the Falcons'
locker room is rare at the pro level, and it appears to be there
again for this season.
</P>
<P>
   A dining-hall scene in training camp illustrates the team's
chemistry. Sitting at a table were defensive linemen Travis Hall
and Ed Jasper, one a starter and one a reserve, one black and one
white. With them were star running back Jamal Anderson and a cast
of rookies and since-released players; several were white and
several were black.
</P>
<P>
   All were laughing as Anderson ripped them.
</P>
<P>
   Another example, from two nights ago: Dozens of players, coaches
and their wives _ white and black _ showed up at the home of Bob
Whitfield's mother for some of Eartha's chow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we don't have disagreements,'' defensive end
Chuck Smith said. ``But we're cool. Heck, I hang out with (kicker)
Morten Andersen. We live on the lake together'' at Lake Lanier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare in Atlanta, since I've been here,'' said Smith, who
joined the team in 1992. ``We always had guys who had underlying
beefs. It was pretty bad until (coach) Dan (Reeves) got here'' two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing he said early is, `We're going to need everybody if
we're going to win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday nights throughout the season, players gather at a
different teammate's house to watch the NFL game on TV. Golf
outings include offensive and defensive players. Many players took
vacations together in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   After playing for the Colts 1993-96, cornerback Ray Buchanan has
a sense of how special the Falcons' atmosphere is. He and his wife,
Sheree, are close with Chandler and his wife, Diane. One family is
black, the other white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it the other way, where people break off into
groups,'' Buchanan said. ``Here, it's mostly a matter of ... good
people, and Dan not going out and picking up peanut-heads from
other teams who will cause distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves and his staff are not unique in trying to sign free
agents and draft players with solid character. But circumstances
have changed. With success comes expectations. For the Falcons,
nine starters can become unrestricted free agents after the season,
and two more can become restricted free agents. As some re-sign,
jealousies could emerge.
</P>
<P>
   With Anderson having held out to get a five-year contract for
$32million, the Falcons' chemistry might be more fragile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know about the attitude of your football team until
you face adversity,'' Reeves said. ``It's easy when you're
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler sees the possibility for problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the unspoken things have a chance to come out,'' he
said. ``Hopefully, it never happens, but yeah, there are different
pressures this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves concedes that any team's relationships always are
tenuous. At practice Friday, for example, he had to pull aside
Smith and tight end O.J. Santiago and mediate a disagreement
between two players whose lockers are next to each other. ``It's
been surprising to me,'' first-round draft choice Patrick Kerney
said. ``You do research on draft picks and free agents, but
everybody has got skeletons in their closet. They've been pretty
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's not arguing and he's not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the exact definition of chemistry,'' he said.
``But a big part of it is liking each other. If you don't, it
probably ain't going to happen. It's a lot easier to play hard when
you care about guys who are going to be affected by how you play.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
