<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin tests Agassi in all-American final
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andre Agassi and Todd Martin do have this in common:
Their tennis careers were feared kaput two years ago, and today,
the 29-year-old Americans will play for the U.S. Open singles
title, both claiming they're playing the best tennis of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, a four-time champion in the Grand Slams, wasn't sharp
until the end Saturday but defeated Yevgeny Kafelnikov 1-6, 6-3,
6-3, 6-3 to claim the No. 1 ranking. Martin, advancing to his first
major final in five years, has rarely played better than his 6-4,
6-1, 6-2 rout of Cedric Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the tournament started, I said that if I was in the
finals, I would like to be playing Pete Sampras, assuming he's the
best playing on the other side of the draw,'' Agassi said. ``When
he pulled out, I still wanted to play the best player on the other
side and it's Todd Martin. He's done some incredible things.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt who the favorite will be.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi played in his first U.S. Open semifinal in 1988, the same
year Martin was in the semifinals of the U.S. Open boys division.
In 1986, when Agassi played his first U.S. Open, Martin didn't even
qualify for the national 16-and-unders.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin isn't surprised to reach his first Grand Slam final
since the 1994 Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations and belief are two different things,'' Martin
said. ``I believed it from the beginning; I just didn't expect
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A wrist injury in 1997 kept Martin off the tour for seven months
as his ranking fell out of the top 75. Now, he's headed for a
career-high No. 4 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, whose ranking bottomed out at No. 141 in 1997, is in his
third straight major final. Kafelnikov yanked Agassi around in the
first set while Agassi struggled with his serve in the wind, making
just 27 percent of first serves. But Agassi lost only nine points
on serve in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year belongs to him,'' Kafelnikov said of Agassi, ``no
question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first all-American final here since Sampras
defeated Michael Chang in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
