<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-WOMEN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Serena Williams: A new power in tennis
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Too much power, too much speed, too much serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, making the strong case that she's the world's
best hardcourt player if she can just get a hold of her nerves, had
a hard time swallowing her first U.S. Open championship Saturday
but finally washed it down in a 6-3, 7-6 (4) victory against world
No. 1 Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is the first African-American woman to win the U.S.
Open since Althea Gibson in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   ``You totally prepare for this all your life, and I was always
the one to say, `I won the U.S. Open, I won the U.S. Open,'''
Williams said. ``With (sister) Venus, it was Wimbledon. With me, it
was always the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' 26-3 hardcourt record this year is the best on the WTA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the start that Williams' first appearance in a
major final was hers to win or lose. She struck 36 winners to
Hingis' seven but also had 57 errors against Hingis' 24. It was
Williams' serve, and Hingis' lack thereof, that gave Williams her
biggest edge. Williams had 62 aces in the tournament, 40 more than
anyone else. In the first set, Williams faced break points six
times, at least one in every service game, but Hingis could get
only one of the bullets back in play.
</P>
<P>
   Williams didn't face any break points in the second set until it
came time to win it, at 5-4. Having mismanaged two match points in
the previous game, Williams then sprayed four errors and lost her
service at love.
</P>
<P>
   Serving at 5-6, Williams missed another easy cross-court
backhand that would've forced the tiebreaker but still got there
after withstanding two set points and a 20-point game. Williams
turned the deciding game with a forehand return winner up the line
to lead 5-4. Hingis missed a top-spin lob, then hit a forehand long
for the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when you have to stop caving,'' Williams
said. ``You get so tired of having to go down because of one simple
problem. I told myself I have to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
