<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giants extend Glavine slump
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Braves have lost only four times in their
past 21 games, and the latest was a 3-2 loss to the Giants on
Saturday, their third loss in Tom Glavine's past three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine gave up six hits in the third and fourth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back singles by Rich Aurilia and Scott Servais to start
the third inning gave the Giants a 1-0 lead when F.P. Santangelo
drove Aurilia in with a ground-out. Back-to-back singles by Aurilia
and Servais in the fourth inning stretched that lead to 3-0 after
Glavine had loaded the bases on a Barry Bonds double, an Ellis
Burks walk and a J.T. Snow single.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is not let it get me frustrated or dejected,''
Glavine said. ``I've got to keep working hard and know if I
continue to pitch like I did today we're going to win most of those
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' double in the fourth was the 2,000th hit of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good because it was off one of the best left-handers in
baseball,'' Bonds said. ``He's beat me up so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves rallied to score a run on closer Robb Nen in the
ninth inning but watched a rusty Randall Simon strike out on three
pitches to end the game with Otis Nixon at second.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, 11-11, is back to .500 for the first time since Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were lulled to sleep offensively by left-hander Kirk
Rueter, who beat them for the second time in five weeks. Especially
telling was the sixth inning when the Braves had Gerald Williams at
third base with one out. Chipper Jones bounced a fielder's choice
grounder to the mound, and Rueter threw to third to get Williams
trying for home.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams was tagged out at home by Servais in a rundown,
Jones was caught leading off first base toward second, ending the
inning on a double play to keep Rueter's shutout intact through six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter broke it up with an RBI double to follow a Jose
Hernandez single in the seventh to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a bad day,'' Chipper Jones said. ``We got lucky last
night, they got lucky today. We gave it right back to them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
