u a BC-WACO-EVIDENCE12-COX     09-11 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-EVIDENCE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Military-style tear gas grenades focus of a still-secret
document
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a battle across two courtrooms Saturday to
keep from having to immediately make public a Texas Rangers' report
on the Branch Davidian evidence, state officials revealed what will
be a focus of the still-secret document: the military-style tear
gas grenades used by federal agents that were capable of starting a
fire.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure came during a running legal battle Saturday in
which the 3rd Court of Appeals in Austin, in a rare Saturday
decision, ordered the report released just as state District Judge
Paul Davis had done Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin American-Statesman filed a lawsuit Friday seeking to
have the report immediately made public, after Texas Department of
Public Safety officials decided to withhold it until noon Monday _
a delay they said would allow federal officials time to possibly
block its release.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, DPS Commission Chairman James B. Francis Jr.
had publicly discussed new disclosures in the ongoing investigation
and argued for a full public accounting, much to the chagrin of
federal officials who had turned over the Davidian evidence to the
Rangers years ago to complete a criminal investigation of the
51-day Davidian siege and fatal fire.
</P>
<P>
   One thing missing from the inventory was any mention of the
``classified'' military secrets that DPS officials, in arguing why
the report should not be fully made public, had said repeatedly
Friday was included.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to a court filing Saturday was a DPS memo from Ranger
Sgt. Joey Gordon, the report's author, stating that a ``technical
data packet'' for the M651 E1 tear-gas cartridge was considered
``proprietary'' by the Pentagon and ``should not be released to the
public because it fully explains how to build this military
munition.''
</P>
<P>
   DPS Commission Chairman James B. Francis Jr. and other DPS
officials did not return phone calls Saturday night to explain what
the earlier-cited ``classified'' material included.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon Saturday, Texas Assistant Attorney General
Don Walker appealed Davis' order, arguing that the report should
remain under wraps for now because DPS lawyers had not yet
determined what could be made public and what could not. Statesman
attorney Randall D. Terrell countered that DPS had already decided
to make the report public, and that any delay would allow DPS ``to
delay the release of public information to suit its own purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Within about three hours, on a day when courts are normally
closed, 3rd Court Chief Justice Marilyn Aboussie and Justices B.A.
Smith and Lee Yeakel agreed the report should be made public now.
</P>
<P>
   DPS immediately asked the Texas Supreme Court to block the
release. And the court _ also ruling on a day when it normally is
closed _ quickly did so, saying it would review the issues Monday
just hours before DPS' scheduled release.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Davis had ordered DPS to make public by 5 p.m.
Saturday whatever sections of the report it had deemed were public.
Nothing was.
</P>
<P>
   But in its court filings, the agency offered a first glimpse of
what will be in the report: The narrative plus 15 attachments that
include photographs, specifications, manuals and other information
about the M651 tear-gas grenades used by federal agents during the
51-day siege _ and during the final day when a fire erupted and
leveled the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The M651 E1 round is a military-issue grenade loaded with CS
riot gas, a type of tear gas. The 4.5-inch round, made to be fired
by a single-shot grenade launcher attached to an M-16 rifle, is a
green cartridge shell topped by a gray round with a red band, an
Army manual states.
</P>
<P>
   The military projectiles are slightly larger than those used by
many law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike tear-gas projectiles used by civilian police forces, the
M651 can cause a fire, a fact mentioned several times in the U.S.
Army's manuals for urban warfare and the grenade launcher.
</P>
<P>
   A 1979 Army manual states: ``Effective in driving the enemy from
bunkers, buildings, subways or sewers using a tactical agent (CS),
the round has some incendiary characteristics. It could be a fire
hazard when used in buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI documents have stated the agents fired so-called ``Ferret''
rounds _ also noted as an attachment in the Ranger report inventory
_ into the Davidian compound during the final hours of the siege.
Those tear gas shells, which also spew CS gas, use a liquid form of
CS gas that reacts with a chemical to produce a nonburning cloud of
tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Four federal agents were among the 88 adults and children who
died during the 51-day siege at the compound east of Waco, with
most of them killed in the April 19, 1993 fire. Sect leader David
Koresh, the target of a federal firearms investigation that
triggered the standoff, was among those who died.
</P>
<P>
   Other items to be in the Rangers' report: An Aug. 30 letter from
Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Johnston of Waco to U.S. Attorney
General Janet Reno, presumably the one warning her ``individuals or
components within the Department of Justice'' may have long
withheld evidence from her and the public about the FBI's use of
pyrotechnic grenades on the day the Davidian compound burned.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials had repeatedly insisted previously that no
such fire-starting devices were used in the final assault.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's letter and other disclosures about pyrotechnic shell
casings found at the scene after the fire _ ones apparently
discussed in the Ranger report _ have prompted the House Committee
on Government Reform to launch a new investigation into the
Davidian case. Reno last week appointed former U.S. Sen. John
Danforth of Missouri to head an independent inquiry into the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' report was forwarded Thursday to the House
committee, and DPS officials said in court Friday they also plan to
forward a copy to Danforth.
</P>
<P>
   The report, completed Thursday with 13 pages of narrative and
about 200 pages of attachments, was ordered in June by Francis
after he learned that pyrotechnic tear gas canisters may have been
fired by federal agents in the waning hours of the siege.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego military affairs writer James Crawley contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
