<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley campaign finds encouragement in Iowa
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX CITY, Iowa _ Amid the parched cornfields that have
devastated the farming economy here, presidential candidate Bill
Bradley is finding some fertile soil for his uphill battle against
Vice President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley completed a three-day swing through Iowa on Saturday,
his 16th visit since announcing his campaign last year, and
everywhere he went he found Democrats eager to greet him and lend
their support.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds were sometimes small. But many who came shared a
common refrain. After seven years in President Clinton's shadow,
Gore is too tainted by the Clinton scandals to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need some new leadership,'' said Mike Perry, a
social worker from Drakesville, Iowa, who came to meet Bradley at a
stop in Ottumwa, Iowa. ``The Clinton administration has some
negative baggage to carry. Mr. Clinton's vice president, no matter
who, is not going to be our next president.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry's concerns about Gore, in different variations, greeted
Bradley everywhere he went, from the Mississippi town of Keokuk in
southeast Iowa, to the western reaches of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Iowa public television Saturday, Bradley
said he had no deliberate plan to tap into ``Clinton fatigue,'' a
trend some recent polls are finding in voter attitudes toward the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really understand what that word means,'' Bradley
said. ``I do think that many people in this country want a fresh
start. I do think that more people are looking to the future and
who's got a program for the future. So there is no calculation to
take advantage of how the people may or may not feel about
President Clinton. This is an attempt to turn the page and move on
to a new time in our politics and to a new presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley may be building a loose coalition of disaffected
Democrats, it remains to be seen how well he will do in peeling
away those voters who are content with the Clinton presidency and
see Gore as the appointed heir.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that he needs to do ``better than expected'' in the
Iowa caucuses on Jan. 31 in order to build some momentum heading
into the New Hampshire primary a week later. A recent poll showed
Bradley about even with Gore in New Hampshire, but Bradley is less
well known in Iowa and Gore has done a better job lining up the
Democratic establishment here.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin (D-Iowa), a popular figure in Iowa and a former
presidential candidate himself, endorsed Gore last week and has
already campaigned for Gore at several high-profile events,
including a party fund-raiser Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has sought to counter the advantage by portraying
himself as the underdog against a better-financed and better-
connected rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up against establishment power,'' Bradley said. ``I'm up
against resources, and all I have is reaching out to people.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Johnie Hammond, a Democrat, said she was initially
concerned about Gore's electability, and considered Bradley
carefully. But said she believed Gore's problems would fade. But
Bradley is also picking up some support from Iowa Democrats who
said they believe that Gore has steered the party too far to the
middle. These voters said they liked Bradley's positions on gun
control and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley favors national licensing of all handguns and supports
public financing for congressional elections to take ``special
interest money'' out of politics. Throughout his stops in Iowa,
Bradley repeatedly held up those positions as a way to contrast
himself with the vice president, who favors new gun control
legislation and more limited campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, they are similar, but Bradley seems open to new
ideas,'' said Phil Zaring, a retired college professor at Iowa
State. ``I think Gore is moving too close to the center of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
