<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-11 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS HAVEN'T LET VALENTINE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The questions didn't have much pace. They were
lobs, really, so Bobby Valentine could reflexively return them
without diverting his gaze from the television mounted on the wall
in the manager's office in the visiting clubhouse at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Some two hours before Friday's game between Valentine's Mets and
the Dodgers, a herd of reporters shuffled into Valentine's office
to find the former Dodger and Angel player sitting with Dodgers
executive Tom Lasorda, both entranced by an unfolding drama.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't watching an L.A. car chase, though regular
television programming had been interrupted earlier in the day to
show one. What Lasorda and his protege were watching was the New
York version of a spin-out and crash ending.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, it wasn't a replay of the Mets' 1998 finish.
</P>
<P>
   This was live theater, Venus Williams frittering away a 3-2 lead
in the decisive third set of her U.S. Open semifinal against
Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   If Valentine simply had to watch, well, managers these days are
nothing if not masochistic. Look what Terry Collins kept going back
to every day for two solid months in Anaheim before finally
resigning earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Mets moved into position for their first postseason
berth of the darkening decade, Valentine was a beleaguered manager
looking to make some kind of statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had a $70 million payroll and 27 wins in their first 55
games, not exactly a resonant return on the dollar. When three of
his assistant coaches were axed the first Saturday in June,
Valentine was astute enough to know the bloody blade would
henceforth be pointed at him.
</P>
<P>
   He won himself a reprieve by stepping close enough to the cold,
steel tip to be grazed by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I am not doing my job as good as I should be,''
Valentine volunteered. He then vowed to use the next 55 games as a
self-evaluation period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put the rope around his own neck,'' said Mets pitcher Orel
Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Californians inured to the impertinence of their pro
athletes may be surprised to hear Valentine's ballplayers didn't
hurry to hang him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, going into Saturday's game against the Dodgers the Mets
were 59-28 since Valentine put his future on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what inspired the turnaround,'' Valentine said,
sounding oh-so-bored to be asked. ``I don't remember what I said
yesterday, (much less) on June 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Further efforts to jog his memory produced this: ``I thought we
were a good team from the first day of the season. I think we're a
better one now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have so many weapons, it doesn't take an arrogant
streak the size of Manhattan's (or Richard Williams') to suggest
the World Series could be an All-in-the-New-York-family affair.
</P>
<P>
   The defending world champion Yankees sit atop the AL East.
Meantime, the Mets have arguably the best defense in the league.
They've allowed just 18 unearned runs (the Dodgers, by comparison,
have yielded 54).
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' lineup is harder for opposing managers to solve than
The New York Times puzzle, given the first seven batters (and eight
on the roster) are hitting over .300. Add to the mix the speed of
Roger Cedeno and relic Rickey Henderson and a starting rotation
that goes six deep, and the Mets' three-game cushion over
Cincinnati in the National League wild-card race seemed on Saturday
very firm indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, it would appear, is on the verge of shedding his
label as the best manager never to have led a team to the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's no unrestrained joy in Metsville. To the contrary,
ask Valentine anything about the playoffs and his expression grows
as taut as a hamstring on the verge of snapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The postseason is not an inevitable situation on this team,''
he said, flinching.
</P>
<P>
   A little while later he would wince as he watched a U.S. Open
trainer tend to Williams' cramping thigh muscles shortly before
Hingis closed out the match.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows Valentine could feel Williams' pain, having
watched his own team knot up horribly at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Mets took a one-game lead in the NL wild-card race
into the final week and squandered it. They lost their final five
games _ two to Montreal and three at Atlanta _ by a combined score
of 25-10.
</P>
<P>
   Like Williams' double-fault-itis in the final four games Friday,
the Mets' collapse was a breathtaking implosion. Consider: They
stranded 32 runners over the final three days.
</P>
<P>
   So far the 1999 Mets haven't left Valentine stranded. He called
a suicide squeeze play and his Mets are running for home. In 19
games, we'll know whether or not they are safe. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
