<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-11 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8938 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CORN-MAZE-KAN &LR;      09-11 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORN-MAZE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZE OF CORN IN A KANSAS FIELD IS A MAGICAL MAGNET FOR FUN-LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIN FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUHLER, Kan. _ A 4 1/2-acre field two miles east of here _ even
in the sunshine of hot September afternoon _ can be eerie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cornfield planted for silage, which, in this age of
hybrids, still grows even higher than an elephant's eye. But it's
more _ a prime example of what's becoming a popular attraction from
Washington to Pennsylvania, Wisconsin to California.
</P>
<P>
   What's on Leon and Ruth Gaeddert's farm is a corn maze.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow passages lead through the 10-foot-high khaki-colored
stalks. Some lead to other paths, some to frustrating dead ends. To
walk is to puzzle. There are few straight lines. The corn blocks
out everything, even part of the blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow what was just a humdrum patch of land alters itself into
a labyrinth, a confining mesh, an impenetrable web. Those ears are
more than just corn on the cob. They're Cary Grant huddled between
the corn stalks in ``North by Northwest.'' They're James Earl Jones
disappearing amid the ripening stalks of corn in ``Field of
Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   And mazes? Who can forget Jack Nicholson lost among the
intricate evergreen hedges in ``The Shining''?
</P>
<P>
   Here at the Gaeddert farm, seeds were planted, a plan was drawn,
markers were laid out, and then Ruth's trusty 54-inch, zero-radius
riding mower created what can not only be a little eerie in the
afternoon but downright spooky as darkness falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come with flashlights,'' she said. ``Now that's
something to see, lights bobbing around in the corn. People love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far 500 to 600 people have plunked down five bucks ($3 for
youngsters) to walk the mile or so of paths that wind through the
maze. And 1,000 to 1,500 more visitors are expected this week with
the Kansas State Fair running in nearby Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get lost in there,'' said Sandra Kopaev of Wichita,
who walked the maze with her 7-year-old daughter, Maria, and a
friend, Carol Truex. ``It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth said corn-maze enthusiasts are diverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had big groups,'' she said. ``We've had people in
wheelchairs. We've had exchange students. Everybody seems to have
just the best time. You know, it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   That difference, said Andrea Hughes, who helped create the 1998
Wisconsin Sesquicentennial Corn Maze that drew 50,000 visitors, is
that such a simple attraction stands in stark contrast to much of
today's high-tech tourist entertainment _ the zooming roller
coasters, virtual-reality video stations and what's usually passive
participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A corn maze is something most people have no prior experience
with,'' said Hughes. ``It's simple. It's low-tech. It's out in the
open. And it's a puzzle the whole family can work on together to
solve. Who's to say which way to go _ this way or that? The
parents? The kids?''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, who runs Event Management Co. of Madison, Wis., said she
is already getting reservations for a seminar Feb. 5-6 in Madison
that will focus not only on creating a corn maze but increasing
attendance and profits. The seminar price isn't cheap _ $325 a
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``With commodity prices and the way we're losing farmers, the
agricultural community is looking for any way to survive,'' Hughes
said. ``What we call agritourism is one way. And people love mazes.
They're coast to coast anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Including two in Kansas. The other one, designed by artist Stan
Herd, whose work has appeared on television and in magazines,
opened this summer on the Jack and Karen Pendleton farm east of
Lawrence, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The Herd/Pendleton maze, on a 5-acre plot, took the form of a
turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth said her family, unaware of the Lawrence area maze until
recently, chose Noah's Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya Gaeddert Martisko, one of the Gaedderts' daughters, had
visited Eden Prairie, Minn., last year where, of all things, there
was a corn maze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it,'' said Tonya. ``And I got to thinking about
home. We grow corn.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The Gaedderts are big farmers _ cattle, corn and
soybeans. Their farm sits on the western edge of the Equus Beds, a
huge aquifer that allows irrigation in this part of Kansas. Plant
it here and it will grow.
</P>
<P>
   But more than being big farmers, the Gaedderts haven't stood pat
as livestock and grain prices tanked over the past few years. If
you can grow feed corn, said Ruth, you can surely grow sweet corn,
that delicacy a lot of people consider one of the best parts of
summer.
</P>
<P>
   For the Gaedderts, sweet corn is their ``value-added'' crop,
meaning they get their price plus the middleman's, too. Or $2.50
for a dozen ears at the farm, $3.50 in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a premium product,'' said Ruth. ``That's what we
sell. It's picked the day you buy it. You know what you're getting
and who you're getting it from.''
</P>
<P>
   With Leon working with his brother John and his family, Gaeddert
Farms has eschewed the traditional selling out of the back of a
pickup or one of those weathered roadside stands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at seven off-farm locations, people in south-central
Kansas have only to look for the neat kiosks with big yellow and
green canopies that declare ``Gaeddert Farms Sweet Corn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have changed,'' said Ruth. ``They like things to look
nice. They see our stands and know what they'll be buying isn't
some corn that who knows is how fresh and maybe was shipped in from
out of state days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   So the corn maze was a small leap for the Gaedderts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it'd be fun,'' said Tonya.
</P>
<P>
   Plus it would get their name out and sell some sweet corn.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya designed the maze so that keel of the ark parallels the
east side of the Gaeddert driveway. The sails and the wind are on
the east. Corn has even been used to replicate ocean waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tricky,'' said Tonya. ``The problem with making a corn
maze is that you only get one chance. You plant the whole field to
corn. But then when you cut in your design, you better not get it
wrong or you'll ruin it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth said cutting the paths was a nervous time, especially this
year as the corn took hold and grew rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used silage corn,'' she said. ``That grows real nice and
tall. Not like feed corn. But it grew so fast. When we started
laying out the design it was only knee high. By the time we were
finished, it was up to your waist.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the paths were made, a garden tractor with a disc was used
to smooth them. Cut-out animals representing what Noah took aboard
the ark were placed to lead visitors in, a concession stand was
installed, and then the Gaedderts watched the corn grow.
</P>
<P>
   The maze opened in late August. Visitors started showing up from
the first. It will remain open until next Sunday. Then it will be
cut for silage, stored or sold.
</P>
<P>
   And next year?
</P>
<P>
   Tonya and Ruth said there will be another maze, maybe even
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about the design yet,'' said Ruth. ``That's
a surprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
